\t\t</table>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/making-potions.webp\" />\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div>\n</div></div></div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_xadnq2n2oe8","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.NJzLnOSKUn1jq0Uj"}}}
{"_id":"0lSq3KH2QDfGZ0Ls","name":"Mass Battles","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Mass battles</h1>\n  <p>\n    Many adventures feature heroes traveling about the land, gathering @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Allies]{allies} to\n    thwart some inevitable foe or ravaging horde. They build coalitions, train\n    armies, discover powerful artifacts, and finally stand against the enemy in\n    desperate and glorious battle.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The rules presented here allow the Game Master to handle a small warband\n    holding a fort against an undead horde, a siege against a walled city, or\n    even full divisions of troops fighting across a massive battlefield. The\n    process is abstract, but it provides a narrative base for heroes to plan,\n    get involved, and take part in the carnage!\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Use the Mass Battle rules when you\n    need to resolve a large conflict that can go either way, and also allow the\n    player characters to have a role in its outcome. The culmination of these\n    tales is not always a foregone conclusion, and failure can be just as\n    interesting as victory!\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>The Basics:</strong> Each side has a number of “Force Tokens” equal\n    to its relative strength and size. Commanders roll their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Battle]{Battle} skill each\n    turn. The winner reduces his rival’s force until one side or the other\n    breaks.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Setup</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    To start, give the larger or more powerful army 10 Force Tokens. Give the\n    opposing army a proportional number of tokens. If one army has 10,000\n    warriors, for example, and the other has 7,000, give the smaller army seven\n    tokens. These represent the troops, ships, and other assets in each side’s\n    army.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Adjust the ratio as makes sense to account for special or elite troops,\n    better equipment, and so on. If one army is half as powerful as another, for\n    example, give one side 10 Force Tokens and the other five. Get close enough\n    to give a reasonable approximation of relative strength. The dice and the\n    players’ actions will handle the rest.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Battle</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    At the start of each round, the player characters discuss and decide on\n    their plan. Then the attackers make an opposed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Battle]{Battle} roll against the\n    defender. Add the modifiers below as appropriate to each roll.\n  </p>\n  <table style=\"width:75%\">\n    <colgroup>\n      <col></col>\n      <col></col>\n    </colgroup>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Battle Modifiers</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">Modifier</th>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">Circumstance</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>+1 per<br />point of<br />advantage</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p>\n            <strong>Force Bonus:</strong> The side with the most Force Tokens\n            adds +1 for each point of difference. If the larger army has 10\n            tokens and the smaller one has 7, for example, the commander of the\n            more powerful army adds +3.\n          </p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>+1 to +4</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p>\n            <strong>Tactical Advantage:</strong> Grant a +1 to +4 bonus for any\n            special circumstances that might help that army, such as\n            fortifications, weather, terrain, or other conditions not otherwise\n            factored into the army’s strength.\n          </p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>+1 to +4</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p>\n            <strong>Battle Plan:</strong> Add +1 to +4 if one side has a\n            particularly effective or clever plan over the other.\n          </p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <h3>Results</h3>\n  <p>\n    The winner of the opposed roll consults the Battle Results. Casualties are\n    generally distributed evenly throughout the army or however the GM feels is\n    most appropriate for the narrative.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Time:</strong> A standard battle round is two hours of hard\n    fighting. The Game Master should change this as suits her needs or the\n    story. A more reserved fight might have four- or even eight-hour rounds,\n    while a siege might be a battle round per day.\n  </p>\n  <table style=\"width:75%\">\n    <colgroup>\n      <col></col>\n      <col></col>\n    </colgroup>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Battle Results</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">Modifier</th>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">Result</th>\n      </tr>\n      \n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>Tie</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p><strong>Draw:</strong> Both sides lose one Force Token.</p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>Success</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p>\n            <strong>Marginal Victory:</strong> The victor loses one Force Token, the defeated loses two.\n          </p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>Raise</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p>\n            <strong>Victory:</strong> The defeated army loses two Force Tokens.\n          </p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <h3>Morale</h3>\n  <p>\n    After an army loses one or more Force Tokens, its leader makes a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Spirit} check modified by these circumstances:\n  </p>\n  <table style=\"width:75%\">\n    <colgroup>\n      <col></col>\n      <col></col>\n    </colgroup>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Morale Modifiers</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">Modifier</th>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">Circumstance</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>−1</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p>Each Force Token lost so far.</p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>+2</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p>The army is made up mostly of @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Undead]{undead} or other @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Fearless]{fearless} troops.</p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>+2</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p>The army is within fortifications or prepared positions.</p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p>+2</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p>The army cannot retreat or will be killed if it does.</p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <p>\n    Success means the leader cajoles the army to fight on. The battle continues another round (or as the attacker sees fit).\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Failure means the commander loses control of his force. The army is defeated\n    but conducts an orderly retreat. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means they flee the field\n    in a reckless rout. They may be scattered temporarily or permanently, ridden\n    down by the enemy, or captured as the GM decides.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Aftermath</h3>\n  <p>\n    When one side routs, retreats, or runs out of Force Tokens, the battle ends.\n    If it’s important to determine the fate of named @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extras} or other nonplayer\n    characters, use the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aftermath and Extras]{Aftermath &amp; Extras}</strong> rules.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Characters In Mass Battles</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    Player characters can dramatically affect the results of the battle. Before\n    their commander makes a Battle roll, players who want to enter the fray\n    describe what they’re doing and make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support} roll with whatever skill they\n    feel is most appropriate. (Don’t forget that enemy champions can add to the\n    rival commander’s Battle roll as well!)\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Each hero’s success grants the commander +1 to his Battle roll but the\n    warrior takes @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises} for the effort. With a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise},\n    the character emerges unharmed and rolls on the\n    <strong>Battle Effects</strong> table; the player may choose to use the\n    result rolled or give the commander the usual +2 bonus instead.\n  </p>\n  <table>\n    <colgroup>\n      <col></col>\n      <col></col>\n    </colgroup>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Battle Effects</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">2d6</th>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">Result</th>\n      </tr>\n      \n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          2\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <strong>Inspire:</strong> The warrior battles valiantly, inspiring\n          the troops and urging them to fight on despite their injuries. Her\n          side immediately recovers one Force Token.\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          3–4\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <strong>Terrorize:</strong> The fighter’s fury terrorizes her foes. The enemy commander subtracts 2 from his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Spirit} roll if forced to test morale this round.\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          5–9\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <strong>Valor:</strong> The warrior’s Support adds +2 to the commander’s Battle roll as usual.\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          10–11\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <strong>Slaughter:</strong> The foe reels at the champion’s onslaught. Subtract 2 from the enemy commander’s Battle total.\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          12\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <strong>An Army of One:</strong> Tales will be told and songs sung\n          of the warrior’s epic feats this day. The enemy army loses a Force\n          Token immediately (this doesn’t subtract from his Battle roll but\n          does cause a morale check even if he wins).\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <p>\n    Failure means the warrior fought bravely. He takes a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wound} but doesn’t add\n    to the commander’s Battle roll. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means the character rolls\n    on the <strong>Battle Effects </strong>table but also suffers d4+1 Wounds!\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The Game Master and players should work together to describe each\n    character’s glorious scenes of bravery and carnage once the results are\n    determined.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Ammo &amp; Power Points</h3>\n  <p>\n    If it’s important to track, each round a hero enters the fray and uses @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} or an arcane skill the character expends some ammunition or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points}.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Arcane types and archers use 2d6 Power Points or arrows per round of Mass\n    Battle. The GM should alter these numbers based on the character's\n    chosen tactics, the length of each battle round, weapon types, or how long\n    she thinks the hero has to recover or rearm between rounds.\n  </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7jG5kHamo9emO3Qo"}}}
{"_id":"0sXgmDnR9n2mtmb3","name":"Setting Rules","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Setting Rules</h1>\n<p><cite>Savage Worlds</cite> range from dark and gritty detective tales to cinematic epics to political thrillers. These rules provide a great framework for anything you want to do, but adding the right Setting Rules really brings the world and the action to life!</p>\n<p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Setting Rules accommodate different play styles and help emulate genres or tropes of established settings—like those of a book or movie that’s inspired you. This lets you easily tweak the rules to make a gritty crime drama more bloody, or an adventurous space romp more fun—all without changing the core of the game.</p>\n<p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Each Setting Rule is different. Some apply during @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Character Creation Summary]{character creation} while others tweak @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Combat]{Combat}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{skills}, or even @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny} use in some way.</p>\n<aside class=\"gray-slate\">\n<h2>Setting Rule Checklist</h2>\n<p>Use the following list to choose the Setting Rules for your game, coloring in the dots so everyone in the group knows which rules are in effect.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Born A Hero]{Born A Hero}:</strong> Player characters ignore @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Advancement]{Rank} requirements for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges} during @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Character Creation Summary]{character creation}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Born from War]{Born from War}:</strong> Player characters start with a free @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Background Edge} that must be tied to their backstory experiences during the Last War during @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Character Creation Summary]{character creation}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Conviction]{Conviction}:</strong> Heroes gain Conviction Tokens that can be used to add a d6 to all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Traits} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage]{damage} rolls for one round. Conviction is awarded for triumph (overcoming a great obstacle important to that character), and tragedy (a personal setback, death of a friend or ally, etc). Conviction effects may be extended by spending a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Creative Combat]{Creative Combat}:</strong> A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test} allows the character to roll on a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Creative Combat]{special table} that grants additional effects.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dumb Luck]{Dumb Luck}:</strong> Characters may spend a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny} after a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure}, allowing another chance for success in unusual and unexpected ways.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash}:</strong> A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{arcane} skill roll forces the player to roll on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dynamic Backlash]{special table} with various chaotic results.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fanatics]{Fanatics}:</strong> Enemy thugs take the damage for their masters.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fast Healing]{Fast Healing}:</strong> Characters make natural @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Healing]{Healing} rolls once per day instead of every five days, and recover a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps &amp; Bruises} every four hours instead of every day.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heroes Never Die]{Heroes Never Die}:</strong> Heroes and named villains rarely actually die but return in some way after being defeated.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glory and Infamy]{Glory and Infamy}:</strong> Glory or Infamy track the reputation of the Player Characters. As it increases they are awarded with benefits from those that respect the reputation of the character.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.More Skill Points]{More Skill Points}:</strong> Player characters in advanced or specialized settings start with 15 skill points.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.No Power Points]{No Power Points}:</strong> Those with arcane backgrounds don’t track Power Points but instead subtract half the listed Power Point cost (round up) from their skill roll to activate the ability. Powers may be maintained as desired at a −1 penalty to all further arcane skill rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Skill Specialization]{Skill Specialization}:</strong> Characters choose a specialization for each skill and subtract 2 when using other variations.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Unarmored Hero]{Unarmored Hero}:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} without armor add +2 to their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Soak Rolls]{Soak} rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wound Cap]{Wound Cap}:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} never suffer more than four @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{wounds} from a single hit.</li>\n</ul>\n</aside>\n<img src=\"modules/swade-core-rules/assets/art/pg142_quote_setting_rules.webp\" /></div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.vrgPhQvUqoH4LGcr"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":21},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
