{"_id":"31HiNnBUwJUOdeTJ","name":"Arcane Background (Wizard)","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Wizard)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Wizard)]{Arcane Background (Wizard)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Wizard]{Wizard}</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Smarts})</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Might:</strong> Wizards may take Edges that require Arcane Background (Magic).</li>\n<li><strong>Backlash: </strong>When a wizard rolls a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} roll, the Dungeon Master rolls on the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash} to see what happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers: </strong>3</li>\n<li><strong>Power Points:</strong> 10</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Analyze Foe]{Analyze Foe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Augury]{Augury}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{Burrow}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/Conceal Arcana}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Drain Power Points]{Drain Power Points}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{Entangle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{Environmental Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Gift of Battle]{Gift of Battle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{Glyph}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{Growth/Shrink}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{Invisibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{Locate}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Magic Mark]{Magic Mark}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{Mind Link}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{Mind Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{Mind Wipe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Planar Binding]{Planar Binding}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Plane Shift]{Plane Shift}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Repair]{Repair}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Scrying]{Scrying}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Secret Writing]{Secret Writing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{Shape Change}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{Speak Language}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Beast]{Summon Beast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{Teleport}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Time Stop]{Time Stop}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wish]{Wish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{Zombie}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>Arcane Magic</h2>\n<p>Arcane magic is a form of science. There are predictable rules that shape reality, and with proper study and force of will, anyone could potentially perform arcane magic. This is what makes arcane magic the foundation of civilization in the Five Nations: it can be taught, and once learned, it is entirely reliable. Arcane magic involves channeling ambient magical energy—the powers of the planes, the emanations of the Ring of Siberys—and focusing it to alter reality. The components of a spell—like verbal incantations, somatic gestures, and focus items—help this process, but the most important element of spellcasting is mental focus. Though a fighter could perfectly duplicate the words and gestures of a wizard, nothing would happen. You must cast the spell in your mind, harnessing and shaping mystical energy, and this can dangerous and exhausting.</p>\n<p>Spellcasting using Smarts is grounded in knowledge and logic. For these characters, casting a spell is like solving an equation—harnessing and carefully channeling the precise quantity of mystical energy required to produce the effect you’re looking for. A wizard may use words of power and mystic gestures to generate power, while an artificer instead relies on tools. But either way, you fundamentally know what you’re doing, which is why both artificers and wizards can prepare new spells each day. Arcane magic is a science, and you’re a scientist.</p>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Principles of Arcane Science}</h3>\n<p>Arcane magic involves the manipulation of vast, ambient mystical energies that permeate Eberron. These forces are largely omnipresent and invisible, not unlike gravity; they’re fundamental elements of the world, and in the course of time most cultures find some way to harness and manipulate them. Like most forms of science, there are different theories about how this science works, and specifically what force is being manipulated.</p>\n<p>You should consider what school of Arcane Science your wizard comers from and let that influence the kind of casting that your wizard accomplishes.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Siberyan Theory}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Externalist}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Sympathetic Magic}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Dominion Theory}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Principles of Arcane Science]{Fringe Traditions}</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Schools]{Schools}</h3>\n<p>A wizard's intense studies lead him down two paths—a \"universalist\" who dabbles in all the various \"schools\" of magic, or a \"specialist\" who focuses on a school at the expense of other studies.</p>\n<p><em><strong>Specialists</strong></em> designate one favored @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{school} and two opposition @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{schools} from the list below. They gain one free reroll when casting spells from their favored @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{school}, but spells cast from their opposition @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{school} cost one additional Power Point and suffer a −2 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} penalty.</p>\n<p>Opposition spells should be marked with an asterisk in a character’s power lists, like this: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{banish}*</em>.</p>\n<p><em><strong>Universalists</strong></em> have no favored or opposed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{schools}, and thus gain none of the advantages or disadvantages of specialists.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Abjuration:</strong> The abjurer uses magic against itself, specializing in defensive magic. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{Glyph}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection},  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Conjuration:</strong> Conjurersfocus on spells to summon magical servants or bend reality to their will. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{Burrow}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Gift of Battle]{Gift of Battle}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Planar Binding]{Planar Binding}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Plane Shift]{Plane Shift}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Repair]{Repair}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Beast]{Summon Beast}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{Teleport}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Divination:</strong> Diviners are masters of remote viewing and prophesies; they use their spells to explore the world. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Analyze Foe]{Analyze Foe}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Augury]{Augury}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/Conceal Arcana}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{Locate}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{Mind Link}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{Mind Reading}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Scrying]{Scrying}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{Speak Language}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Enchantment:</strong> The enchanter uses magic to manipulate the minds and perceptions of opponents. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{Mind Wipe}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Evocation:</strong> Evokers revel in the raw power of magic; they use spells to create and destroy with equal ease. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Illusion:</strong> Illusionists use magic to produce confounding sights, sounds and even smells to baffle and vex their opponents. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{Invisibility}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Magic Mark]{Magic Mark}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Secret Writing]{Secret Writing}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>Necromancy:</strong> The necromancer commands undead and uses the power of unlife against their enemies. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Grave Speak]{Grave Speak}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Lower Trait}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{Zombie}</span></li>\n<li><strong>Transmutation:</strong> Transmuters use magic to change themselves and the world around them. <span class=\"list-powers\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost Trait}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{Entangle}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{Environmental Protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{Growth/Shrink}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{Shape Change}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Time Stop]{Time Stop}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Spellbooks]{Spellbooks}</h3>\n<p>Wizard spells are strange, complex things that fade quickly from the minds of even the most accomplished casters. For this reason, each wizard maintains a spellbook with the spells he’s translated and acquired. He studies them daily, transcribing their mystical patterns onto his mind.</p>\n<p>The link to the book is far more than rote memorization—it is an arcane bond with the power and patterns within. If a wizard doesn’t have access to his spellbook, he may continue to cast normally until the next sunset or sunrise (whichever comes first). After that, the magical imprint on his mind fades and he can no longer cast them.</p>\n<p>Wizards may only carry one active spellbook at a time. The mountains of scrolls, magical notations, and research needed to prepare another cannot be carried with the wizard and must be stored safely somewhere. It takes a week of work and 500 gp to create a replacement spellbook once the wizard has access to his magical notes.</p>\n<p>When a wizard finds a new spellbook or scroll, the spells it contains become available as choices to the wizard when he next chooses the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.New Powers]{New Powers} Edge. Moreover, a wizard taking the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.New Powers]{New Powers} Edge can learn a third new power, if all the new powers are learned from scrolls and spellbooks.</p>\n<h2>Casting</h2>\n<p>Mages must make gestures with at least one free hand and speak aloud various magical words at least at a whisper. If either their hands are bound or they are prevented from speaking, they cannot cast their spells.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>Wizards are some of the most versatile casters in Eberron. There are no limitations on the kinds of trappings that can be utilized by a wizard.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yqngxv6403a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.3. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":3}}}
{"_id":"3ecUSTKJMhi7L9xu","name":"Using Bennies","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Using Bennies</h2>\n    <p>Bennies may be spent at any appropriate time and don’t incur any sort of penalty. They may only be used for your own character.</p>\n    <p>Here are the ways players can use Bennies.</p>\n    <ul>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Reroll a Trait:</span> Bennies grant a hero a reroll on <em>any</em> Trait (see <strong>Rerolls,</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{here}).</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Recover from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}:</span> This is instant and may be done at any time, even interrupting another’s actions if desired.</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Recover Power Points:</span> A character with an Arcane Background, Mystic Powers, or any other ability that grants @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} can \n            spend a Benny as a free action to recover five Power Points.</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Soak Rolls:</span> Bennies can be used to prevent @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds} or recover from being Shaken.\n        </li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Draw a New @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Card}:</span> When the game is in rounds, a character can spend a Benny to get a new \n            <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Cards}</strong>. \n            This occurs after all cards are dealt and Edges or Hindrances like @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Quick]{Quick}, \n            @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Level Headed]{Level Headed}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Hesitant]{Hesitant} are resolved. <em>Then</em> players or \n            the GM may spend Bennies for an additional card as many times as they like and take their choice of all their draws. Edges like Quick or Level Headed <em>do not</em> apply to \n            these additional cards drawn with Bennies. This continues until everyone (including the GM) passes. Then the round begins and no further cards may be drawn.</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Reroll <span>Damage:</span></span> You may spend a Benny to reroll damage. Include any additional dice you may have gained for a raise on the attack roll.</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Influence the Story:</span> This one is entirely up to the Game Master, who may allow a character to spend a Benny to find an additional clue if you’re stuck, \n            come up with some mundane but needed item, or push a nonplayer character into being a bit more agreeable.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <blockquote class=\"flavor\">\n        <em><strong>Example:</strong></em> The party is adrift on a storm-tossed sea. None of the characters purchased navigational equipment, \n        but Harsk the ranger had been aiding their doomed captain through the previous encounters. Harsk's player asks the Game Master if he might have been given his\n         own compass and maps while aiding the captain, and might still have them in his bag. The GM agrees—for a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny}. \n         Harsk suddenly remembers the tools in his pack and turns the boat toward shore.</blockquote>\n\n    <aside class=\"sidebar\">\n        <h2>Awarding Bennies</h2>\n        <p>It takes a few games to figure out how many @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Bennies} you should award players during a session. In general, we recommend you be fairly free with them, \n            especially early in the game. If someone makes everyone laugh (and isn’t distracting the flow of the game), toss the player a Benny. \n            When players roleplay a Hindrance, reward them. When someone does something clever or heroic or imaginative, acknowledge it with a Benny.</p>\n        <p>Some GMs worry the game will become too easy if Bennies are too common, but we find the opposite is true. When Bennies are plentiful, \n            players often spend them on trivial things that are important to <em>them</em>. Maybe the rogue <em>really</em> wants to pick the lock on a chest. \n            There’s nothing particularly valuable inside and the player probably knows it, but the character is the <em>rogue</em> and wants to prove it to the rest of the party.\n        </p>\n        <p>When Bennies are scarce, however, players tend to save them for injuries, death, or taking out the big bads. That’s fine, but takes away from the fun and heroics that \n            got them to this point. <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> is about big action and players should be encouraged to take chances. The “currency” of these chances are \n            those Bennies.\n        </p>\n        <p>Veteran <cite>Savage Worlds</cite> GMs might also notice Bennies tend to flow fairly fast early on in a session. The group is settling in, laughing, and are rewarded \n            for roleplaying their Hindrances the first time or two. In the mid-to-late game, Bennies tend to be spent faster than they’re gained. That’s a fantastic pace. \n            It gives the heroes opportunities to do big things in the early and mid-game then forces some critical resource management for the final showdown.\n        </p>\n        <p>If you find yourself being stingy, go the other way the next time you run and see how it affects your group. Then you’ll know what’s right for you and your friends.</p>\n    </aside>\n\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0urjihl2ptj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Rules keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.ei1JpxVf1ihgn6Cm"}}}
{"_id":"3fOVBjv9kg1d573f","name":"Siege Engines Table","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<table class=\"table gear-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Siege Engines</h2>\n<div class=\"table-summary\">\n<p>Catapults and trebuchets are mechanical devices that hurl large stones at enemy defenses or ranks of troops. They normally require a crew of eight to load the projectile, crank down the lever that propels it, then sight and aim it. Firing can be done by a single person (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}), but loading the projectile takes at least four.</p>\n<p>A ballista is a mechanical engine designed to fire a massive crossbow bolt. One person can fire the device (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}). One person can reload, although it’s faster with two people.</p>\n<p>A ram is a movable scaffold with a heavy wooden pole suspended by rope or chains. A crew of at least two is needed to swing the ram pole to batter another object. Up to eight people can swing the ram, with the leader making the attack roll (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}) and others providing @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}.</p>\n<p>A siege tower is a massive wooden tower on wheels, designed for scaling walls. Moving the structure requires at least a crew of eight, who can push the device at @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} 1 from within the tower on the ground (double that if 16 individuals push the tower, and triple it if 24 push). Those within have complete @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{cover} and solid wooden walls until the ramp drops, usually at the highest level. Some siege towers may have arrow slits on the higher levels as well, allowing archers to fire as they approach the enemy walls.</p>\n</div>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Type</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Range</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Damage</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">AP</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">ROF</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Blast</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Cost</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Ballista]{Ballista}</td>\n<td>15/30/60</td>\n<td>3d6</td>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Special</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>500 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"7\"><strong><em>Notes:</em></strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heavy Weapon (HW)]{Heavy Weapon}, Reload time is 5 minutes for a solo operator, or 2 minutes with a crew of 2.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Catapult]{Catapult}</td>\n<td>24/48/96</td>\n<td>3d6</td>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Special</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{MB}</td>\n<td>800 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"7\"><strong><em>Notes:</em></strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heavy Weapon (HW)]{Heavy Weapon}, Reload time is every 5 minutes with a crew of 4.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Ram]{Ram}</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>2d6</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>1,000 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"7\"><strong><em>Notes:</em></strong> Not a ranged weapon, used to batter objects. See @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Breaking Things}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Seige Tower]{Seige Tower}</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>2,000 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"7\"><strong><em>Notes:</em></strong> Not a ranged weapon, used to scale walls; shooters can fire from upper floors.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Trebuchet]{Trebuchet}</td>\n<td>30/60/120</td>\n<td>3d8</td>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Special</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{MBT}</td>\n<td>1,000 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"table-body-notes\">\n<td colspan=\"7\"><strong><em>Notes:</em></strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heavy Weapon (HW)]{Heavy Weapon}, Reload time is every 5 minutes with a crew of 4.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"striped-row-offset\">\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n<td> </td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_dl21vgq63wq","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear tables","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"3ngNEZFre5UVeg0c","name":"Storms at Sea","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Storms at Sea</h1>\n<p>Storms in the Thunder Sea are legendary. Riding them out is a true test of a captain and crew’s mettle.</p>\n<p>First roll [[/r 1d6+3]]. This determines how the long the ship is under serious distress from the storm, in 30 minute increments. The Game Master then draws a card to determine how rough the storm is that particular half-hour.</p>\n<p>The captain makes a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{Boating} roll each round, subtracting the penalty shown on the table below. Storm damage is applied against the ship’s base @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}, ignoring all but magical armor.</p>\n<p>Every round the roll is missed, each character must make an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Agility} roll (add +2 if tethered). The Game Master can roll for crewmen as well (use groups of 10 for large ships). Those who fail are washed overboard and must make @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} rolls every other round to avoid drowning. A critical failure indicates the character has been hit by driftwood for [[/r 2d6]] damage. </p>\n<table class=\"table value=table\" style=\"width:70%\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Storm Severity</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Card Draw</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Penalty</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Damage</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>–4</td>\n<td>[[/r 5d6]]</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3-10</td>\n<td>–2</td>\n<td>[[/r 4d6]]</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Jack-Ace</td>\n<td>0</td>\n<td>[[/r 3d6]]</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Joker</td>\n<td>+2</td>\n<td>[[/r 3d6]]</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Boarding]{Boarding}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranks of Archers]{Ranks of Archers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Sinking]{Sinking}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6g48t5q06rw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"3pyIPNVJUdcDgShP","name":"Reflecting","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Shield Enchantment</h3>\n<p>The shield’s surface is completely reflective. Once per day, the wielder can reflect any power that affects her by making a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Spirit} roll (at −2 if the casting roll got a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}). If successful the caster suffers the full effects of the power as if he had been the original target.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 4</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 16,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"49KodzYrS0MJxeQ3","name":"Reach","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Reach</h2>\n  <p>Weapons with “Reach” allow their user to make Fighting attacks at the listed range. A Reach of 1, for example, allows a character to strike a target 1″ (2 yards) distant. Weapons without a Reach value can only strike targets at arm’s length (adjacent).</p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.xyQaQ5r4IdqsoiUK"}}}
{"_id":"4FZyw9PdSQ7ZMJW2","name":"Goblin","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Goblin</h1>\n<p>The goblinoid species—goblins, hobgoblins, and bugbears—were once the dominant civilization in Khorvaire, with the goblinoid Empire of Dhakaan ruling the continent for thousands ofyears. It was crippled by a long conflict with the daelkyr and their aberrant armies; even though the daelkyr were defeated, the seeds of madness took root in the empire and tore it apart. Today there are four primary goblinoid cultures in Khorvaire.</p>\n<p>Amongst the most areas of Khorvaire goblins are at best second class citizens that are often nothing more than scavengers. Among the <em>dar</em> or goblinoid races, goblins are known as the <em>golin'dar</em>, the \"quick people\", known as crafters, skilled labor, and excellent scouts. Not knowing any better, when humans came to Khorvaire they named the goblinoid people after the most prolific breeders, goblins.</p>\n<h3>City Goblins</h3>\n<p>Goblins dwell in most o f the major cities of the Five Nations. When humans first came to Khorvaire, they enslaved many goblins and built their cities on the foundations of Dhakaani ruins. Galifar ended the practice of slavery, and these goblins are now citizens of the Five Nations. Gifted goblins can be found in all walks of life, and goblins served in the armies of the Five Nations during the Last War.</p>\n<h3>The Heirs of Dhakaan</h3>\n<p>Though the Dhakaani Empire defeated the alien daelkyr, the war left seeds ofcorruption strewn throughout the empire. As Dhakaan began to fall, a number of generals and governors gathered their forces and retreated into shelters deep within the earth, determined to preserve their civilization until the Empire could finally be restored. After thousands of years, their descendants have finally emerged, competing among themselves to determine which leader deserves the imperial crown. Once this is settled, they will turn to the conquest of Darguun and Khorvaire.</p>\n<p>The Dhakaani are far fewer in number than the <em>ghaal'dar</em>; they had to carefully limit their population in the underground vaults they've dwelled in for the past age. However, they have held onto the martial discipline and techniques that allowed their ancestors to dominate the continent. Their weaponsmiths are superior even to the artificers of House Cannith, and they are experts in the working of adamantine and other exotic metals. Anyone who presumes to look down upon goblinoids should be surprised by the skills of the Dhakaani.</p>\n<p>The Heirs of Dhakaan are an agnostic society and don't have clerics, paladins, or druids. Their focus is on martial excellence, and their spiritual leaders are bards, who tell tales of past glory. Among the Dhakaan, goblinoids work together. Hobgoblins are the strategists and commanders, typically having the skills of fighters, bards, or rangers. Bugbears cultivate a focused battle rage and are typically barbarians. Goblins are largely artisans and laborers, but exceptional goblins join the khesh'dar (\"silent folk\"), learning the skills of rogues, monks, or rangers. The khesh'dar spread agents across the Five Nations, and one can never know when a city goblin might turn out to be an assassin.</p>\n<p>As an adventurer from a Dhakaani clan, consider why are you working with the other player characters? Are you a scout gathering information? Are you searching for allies to defeat a rival clan, or to support your own unlikely bid for the Imperial throne? Are you an exile? If so, do you hope to regain your position, or have you abandoned your ties to the Dhakaani?</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Agile:</strong> Goblins are naturally quick and agile. They start with a d6 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} instead of a d4. This increases their maximum @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Darkvision]{Darkvision}:</strong> Goblin eyes have become accustomed to the darkness in Khyber. Darkvision ignores up to –4 penalties for all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Illumination} up to 10\" away. Beyond 10\" they ignore up to –2 penalties. Such vision is in black and white (monchrome) only.</li>\n<li><strong>Diminutive: </strong>Goblins average only about three and a half feet tall, reducing their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} (and therefore @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}) by 1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Goblins start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Goblin} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n<li><strong>Sneaky:</strong> Goblins are naturally stealthy. They start with a d6 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} skill instead of a d4. This increases their maximum Stealth to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Tricksy Fighter]{Tricksy Fighter}: </strong>Goblins do anything to win a fight. They add +2 to all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Tests} during combat.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/goblin.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/goblin.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.p9Bxarupnmiw6UST"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"4GTRoTLe6ph9AxWK","name":"Alchemical Silver","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2 class=\"wide\">Alchemical Silver</h2>\n<p>A complex process involving metallurgy and alchemy can bond silver to a steel weapon. This allows them to affect creatures with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Weakness]{Weakness} to silver, such as lycanthropes. They cost ten times normal price.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Special Materials]{See Special Materials here}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"4I2lZGJ3HmvUY8EX","name":"Artificer","content":"<p>In Eberron, magic is almost technology. Spellcasters specialize in certain forms of that technology, while artificers tinker with its fundamental workings. Artificers understand magic on a different level from spellcasters, and do not cast spells as wizards and clerics do. They have an amazing facility with imbueing magic into items and constructs. They are the engineers keeping the magical world of Eberron running.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Crafting, Dragonmark Focus, Lore, Magecraft, Repair, Research, Science, Thievery</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Arcane Background (Dragonmark of Making or Magecraft)</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Artificer, Adept Artificer, Master Artificer, Attune Arcane Weapon, Enchant, Improved Enchant, Expert Artificer, Finely Tuned, Imbue Item, Tinkerer</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Jack-of-all-Trades, Mr. Fix It, Scholar</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Homunculus, Scavenger</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.0L51NGzpAsw9Ft2l"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"4JHwjrZBlSAAaXMU","name":"Weapon Size","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Weapon Size</h2>\n  <p>Weapons wielded by some creatures may be larger or smaller than those listed here. A Giant’s battleaxe, for example, is larger than a human’s, while a kobold’s longsword is smaller. The GM can increase or decrease the Minimum Strength and weight as logically needed, but other statistics (Range, damage, etc.) remain as listed.</p>\n  \n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.bZTVyaxcewVOZOB3"}}}
{"_id":"4SOV49e7NaWv93sp","name":"Natural Weapons","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Natural Weapons</h2>\n  <p>Creatures with natural weapons such as fangs, claws, or horns may attack with them using their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} skill. \n\t\tDamage is stated for character @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Ancestries]{ancestries} and beasts in their various descriptions.</p>\n\t<p>Creatures with natural weapons are always considered armed. T\n\t\this means they aren’t <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Unarmed Defender]{Unarmed Defenders}</strong> \n\t\tand foes fighting with <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Two Weapons]{Two Weapons}</strong> gain no advantage against them.\n\t\tHere are a few additional notes for each type of attack:</p>\n\t\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Bite:</strong> The creature may bite a target it’s grappled (most attackers can only crush their prey, \n\t\t\tsee <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Grappling]{Grappling}</strong>. \n\t\t\tThis is a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} attack.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Claws:</strong> \n\t\t\tAdd +2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}(climbing) rolls on any rough or soft surface (not sheer steel, glass, etc.).</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Horns:</strong>  \n\t\t\tAdd +4 damage from a successful attack with a creature's horns if it runs and moves at least 5″(10 yards).</li>\n\t</ul>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.vHhUVBVfp1Q6vLFS"}}}
