{"_id":"52mXxjjbZB1cD3FL","name":"Dynamic Backlash","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Dynamic Backlash</h2>\n<p>A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on an arcane skill check results in <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}</strong>. That works well in traditional fantasy settings or worlds where magic is relatively common. If you feel magic should come with a higher price, however, use the <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash}</strong> table instead.</p>\n<p class=\"embedded-example\"><strong>Example:</strong> Gabe is a techno-sorceror in some far-flung science fiction world. He rolls a Critical Failure when casting lower Trait against an enemy’s Agility. Gabe’s player rolls Backfire on the Dynamic Backlash table so it affects his friend Red instead.<br />Red’s Agility suddenly drops two die types, forcing the warrior to go on the defensive until the power wears off.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.yZtQgdoGVBYvNjKj"}}}
{"_id":"56aroMHcw9HU16xc","name":"Arcane Background (Divine Magic)","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Divine Magic)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Divine Magic)]{Arcane Background (Divine Magic)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Novice}</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Spirit})</li>\n<li><strong>Miracles:</strong> Divine casters may take Edges that require @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Miracles)]{Arcane Background (Miracles)}.</li>\n<li><strong>Domain: </strong>Priests must choose a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Domains]{Domain} to follow on taking this edge.</li>\n<li><strong>Transgressions: </strong>Priests who violate the tenets of their faith can get blocked from thier source of power. Consult each @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Domains]{Domain} for what are considered transgressions and the effects.</li>\n<li><strong>Backlash: </strong>When a member of the clergy rolls a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} roll, the Dungeon Master rolls on the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash} to see what happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers: </strong>3</li>\n<li><strong>Power Points:</strong> 10</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers: </strong>Very depending on the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Domains]{Domain} followed.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>Divine Magic</h2>\n<p>There’s no logic to divine magic, no pure science that can explain exactly how it works. An acolyte might spend years meditating and praying, performing virtuous deeds, and tending their flock, and still never gain the power to cast a spell; meanwhile, a smith who can’t even read might feel @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Onatar]{Onatar’s} guiding hands and cast magecraft. Divine magic requires two things: absolute faith and a connection to a divine power source.</p>\n<p>Faith is about conviction. It can’t be something you approach rationally. You need to know in your heart that the magical effect you seek to produce with your spell should and will happen. Whether you’re smiting an enemy or healing an ally, you know that the enemy will fall and that you will save your friend. This doesn’t mean that you have to be a zealot with no doubts whatsoever; you can question your overall course of action. But you can’t think about your doubts in the moment of casting the spell; in that instant, you must have pure and absolute certainty that the spell will come to pass.</p>\n<h3>Connection to Divine Power</h3>\n<p>But faith alone isn’t enough; you also need a connection to a source of divine power. In Eberron, no one can prove whether the Sovereigns or other deities exist—if @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Onatar]{Onatar} actually guides all artisans or if @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Dorn]{Dol Dorn} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} truly watch over every battlefield. But whether or not @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} exists, when her paladin smites a foe, they draw that power from something. The paladin believes it to be @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} granting her favor, and maybe it is. Or maybe the shared faith of the tens of thousands of people who believe in the Sovereigns has created wells of power in the collective unconscious, and the paladin draws on this powerful force instead. In a practical sense, the truth is irrelevant; regardless of its nature and source, the power exists. And this is where science fails. The Silver Flame is a source of divine power, a force that has held demons at bay for millennia. Those who seek to defend the innocent and fight supernatural evil can draw on its power. But why does one templar become a paladin over another of equal faith? Why does an illiterate farmer gain the gift of divine magic when a religious scholar who’s spent decades studying texts doesn’t? People of faith usually respond that it’s because the farmer was chosen by Arawai, or because one templar was more open than the other to the Voice of the Flame. Maybe that’s true, or maybe it’s all just luck.</p>\n<h2>Casting</h2>\n<p>To the outside observer, divine magic is very different in flavor from arcane magic. A wizard traces glowing sigils and speaks words in a language older than humanity; a priest simply points dramatically at their enemy and calls on the Silver Flame to strike them down. Whether a spell is fueled by arcane or divine power, however, it still requires verbal and somatic components. Practically speaking, this means the spellcaster has to be able to speak and use their hands, and that these are somehow tied to casting a spell. But where a wizard may recite a complex incantation, the verbal component of divine magic could be the simplest of prayers: “@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah} smite my foe!” or “Stand revealed in the light of the Flame!” Or it might be more complex, perhaps singing a hymn or reciting a passage from an ancient text. In both cases, the verbal components are statements of conviction and intent. Just as arcane magic is more than words and gestures, divine magic likewise has a mental component. The caster doesn’t just ask for something; they reach out and take the power from the divine source, and if they draw too heavily on this connection, it can backlash on them.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings} for divine magic vary greatly depending on the faith or diety of the the clergy. A follower of the  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Devourer]{Devourer} <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt} </em>might be a shock of lightning while a <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt} </em>from a disciple of the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Silver Flame]{Silver Flame} might manifest as a silvery flame. View the specific suggestions on the various deities or faiths.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yqngxv6403a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.3. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":5}}}
{"_id":"5eNCd3uJLZnUsnKW","name":"Aberrant Bloodline","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Aberrant</h1>\n<p>A bizarre and alien legacy taints the sorcerer’s blood. Her strange form increases her @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness} by +1. <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{blast}</em>, and <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{burst}</em> spells must be cast with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Lingering Damage (+2)]{Lingering Damage} Power Modifier, but cost the sorcerer only 1 additional Power Point instead of 2.</p>\n<p>Finally, her long limbs give her @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reach]{Reach} +1, which can be used for purposes of determining a spell’s Range or origin.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li class=\"star\"><strong>Advanced Form: </strong>The character is never @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Surprise]{Surprised} and is immune to the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.The Drop]{Drop} unless @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound}. Her alien form grants her another point of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_w2j6cd7pbcs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.4. Bloodlines","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"5ewQ7Vu2LmfWtObA","name":"Fighting Below Deck","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Fighting Below Deck</h1>\n<p>It’s quite cramped below the decks of a ship where boxes, bottles, and kegs are stored in every nook and cranny and the ceiling forces a man to stoop.</p>\n<p>Any weapon longer than a knife, hook, or similar device of less than six inces length suffers a –2 penalty to the user’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls when using it below deck.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Boarding]{Boarding}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranks of Archers]{Ranks of Archers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Sinking]{Sinking}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6g48t5q06rw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"5gU5ye6CoTnHIxad","name":"Common Gear Table","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"4\">Common Gear</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Items</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading center\">Cost</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading center\">Weight</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading center\" style=\"width:50%\">Notes</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"4\"><span class=\"no-class\">Adventuring Gear</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Backpack]{Backpack}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Ballbearings]{Ballbearings}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">One batch covers a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Small Blast Template}, two a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Medium}, and three a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Large}. Counts as Difficult Ground; anyone moving through the area must make an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll or stop moving for one round. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} causes the person to be knocked @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{Prone}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bedroll]{Bedroll}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bell]{Bell}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Blanket]{Blanket}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 sp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Caltrops]{Caltrops}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\"><strong><em>Notes:</em></strong> One batch covers a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Small Blast Template}, two a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Medium}, and three a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Large}. Counts as Difficult Ground; anyone moving through the area must make an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll or be @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{Shaken}. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} causes a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{Wound} to the feet (–2 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} until healed).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Candle]{Candle}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 cp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">one hour, 2\" radius</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Chalk]{Chalk}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 cp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Chest, Huge]{Chest, Huge}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">200</td>\n<td style=\"tex