owers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0bt6afhtf6wi","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.2. Domains","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"BsmS4It9vSMq0KRw","name":"Damaging","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>The weapon’s damage increases by +1</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 1</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"C4LPZJYJ17isZfJD","name":"High Altitude","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>High Altitude</h2>\n  <p>\n    Traversing landscapes at high elevations can cause @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} — and potentially\n    worse — to those who aren’t used to it.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    When traveling at altitudes roughly a mile high or higher, a character must\n    make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Vigor} roll every four hours. Failure means the hero incurs a Fatigue\n    level. The roll is at −2 for elevation greater than 10,000 feet, and −4\n    (maximum) for higher than 15,000 feet.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    At the GM’s discretion, characters who are already acclimated to these elevations don’t need to roll.\n  </p>\n  <p><strong>Death:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} victims @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{die} after 2d6 hours.</p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Recovery:</strong> Victims one level of Fatigue per hour after resting for at least two full hours.\n  </p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4txb7iklyvb","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Hazards keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.NkqPjaIb3hpiKESN"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":5},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"C9emmD5DGLVHJpPE","name":"Prone","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Prone</h2>\n  <p>Ranged attacks suffer a −4 penalty to hit prone characters from a range of 3″ (6 yards) \n\t\tor greater (this does not stack with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover %26 Obstacles]{Cover}) \n\t\tand subtract four points of damage from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Area Effect attacks}.</p>\n\t<p>If a prone defender is caught in melee, his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} is reduced by 2 and he must subtract 2 from his \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls.</p>\n\t<p>Standing from prone is a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}, but costs a character 2″ of movement.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.TsPTxdhNeJrrGTo3"}}}
{"_id":"CBgx1wCRzM150a7w","name":"7 Schools of Magic","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Schools of Magic</h1>\n  <p>\n    On Eberron, spells are categorized based on the effects generated by the\n    power. These specialized groups are called schools. Any power not tied to a\n    school of magic is considered to be a universal spell, such as\n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wish]{wish}. There are eight schools of magic: Abjuration, Conjuration,\n    Divination, Enchantment, Evocation, Illusion, Necromancy, and Transmutation.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    A spell is always considered to be from its school, no matter where it comes\n    from. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost Trait}, for example, is a Transmutation power, whether\n    its cast from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Miracles)]{Arcane Background} (Cleric) or \n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Magic)]{Arcane Background}(Sorcerer).\n    The GM may decide, however, that a caster's specific trappings move the\n    power into a different school for that caster (so a GM might rule that,\n    while a typical barrier belongs to the conjuration school, a purely magical\n    barrier might be an evocation spell instead).\n  </p>\n  <div>\n\t  <img class=\"float-right\" style=\"shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/wizard-list.webp')\" src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/wizard-list.webp\" width=\"300\" height=\"566\" />\n  </div>\n\t  <p>\n    Knowing the schools of magic and their effects can be instrumental in\n    identifying magical traps, weapons, items, or auras surrounding an opponent.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Here are the various schools and the powers that belong to each. Note: these\n    lists do not affect which powers an Arcane Background has access to. These\n    lists simply identify which powers are associated to each particular school\n    and the general focus of the school of magic.\n  </p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Abjuration:</span> This is the school of protective magic.\n      It's used to prevent harm and suppress other spells. \n\t  <em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane protection}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{banish}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{damage field}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{dispel}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{deflection}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection},\n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sanctuary]{sanctuary}.</em>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Conjuration:</span> This school focuses on altering reality by\n      creating, restoring or moving objects and creatures. \n\t   <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{burrow}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{conjure item}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Planar Binding]{planar binding},\n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Plane Shift]{plane shift}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{relief}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Resurrection]{resurrection}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{summon ally},\n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{teleport}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{warrior’s gift}.</em>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Divination:</span> This school focuses on predicting the future\n      and learning the secrets held by others.\n\t  <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/conceal Arcana}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{divination}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{locate}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{mind link},\n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{mind reading}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{object reading}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Scrying]{scrying}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{speak language}.</em>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Enchantment:</span> This school affects the minds of others,\n      influencing or controlling their behavior. \n      <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast friend}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{confusion}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{empathy}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{mind wipe}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{puppet}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{slumber}.</em>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Evocation:</span> Evocation magic taps into the unseen source of\n      power to produce spectacular effects. \n\t  <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{burst}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{havoc},\n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light / Darkness]{light/darkness}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{stun}.</em>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Illusion:</span> This school deceives the senses or minds of\n      others. These spells often cause people to see things that are not there,\n      or not see things that are. \n\t  <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{illusion}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{invisibility}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{sound/silence}.</em>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Necromancy:</span> This school manipulates the power of death,\n      unlife, and the life force. \n\t  <em>\n\t\t  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{curse},\t\n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Drain Power Points]{drain Power Points},\n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{fear}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{lower Trait}, \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{zombie}.\n\t  </em>\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Transmutation:</span> Transmutation changes the properties of\n      some creature, thing, or condition.\n      <em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost Trait}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{darksight}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{elemental manipulation}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{environmental protection}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{farsight}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{fly}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{growth/shrink}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{intangibility}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{shape change}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{sloth/speed}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{telekinesis}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Time Stop]{time stop}, \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{wall walker}.</em>\n\t  \n    </li>\n  </ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_vv8zdhdw0l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.yEgv2Q3WVU980AzX"}}}
{"_id":"CCHyw48bxIoRGVV3","name":"Skill Specialization","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Skill Specialization</h2>\n<p><cite>Savage Worlds</cite> skills are intended to be broad, allowing characters to focus primarily on @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Edges]{Edges} for customization rather than multiple iterations of something like @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} for edged weapons, Fighting for blunt weapons, etc.</p>\n<p>If it’s important to have more detail for some reason, the GM can decide some skills require specialization. A character chooses one particular use of that skill to roll normally, and subtracts 2 from the total when using it in any other way.</p>\n<p>Gaining an additional specialization counts as raising a skill below its linked @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Attribute}. So a character can gain two new specializations with an @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Advance}, or mix and match to gain a specialization and increase a skill below its linked Attribute.</p>\n<p>Below are skills appropriate for this extra detail and some example specializations:</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Boating]: </strong>Powered, Sail, Steam.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Driving]: </strong>Hover, Tracked, Wheeled.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Fighting]: </strong>Axe, Blunt Weapon, Exotic (such as nunchaku; each is separate), Long Blade, Pole Arm, Short Blade.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Piloting]{Piloting}: </strong>Fixed Wing, Rotary, Space.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Riding]{Riding}: </strong>Camel, Horse, Dragon.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Science]{Science}: </strong>Biology, Chemistry, Engineering.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}: </strong>Bows, Pistol, Rifle, Shotgun.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Survival]{Survival}: </strong>Arctic, Desert, Temperate.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.zEfU1gRBdXGyr8B6"}}}
{"_id":"Chvdt2b5TVbrkveK","name":"Energy Resistance","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Armor or Shield Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Grants environmental resistance against a single energy type, determined at creation, to a piece of armor or a shield. Damage from that source is reduced by 4 when the armor is worn, and the hero adds +4 when resisting any effect tied to that element.</p>\n<p>A leather jerkin of energy resistance (Cold), for example, helps its wearer avoid @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from exposure (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards} on page 153) and damage from any attack with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trappings]{Trapping} of cold, ice, frost, etc.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 1</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 2,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Enviromental Protection]{Enviromental protection}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"CzDdVjqGErM01jOV","name":"Fey Bloodline","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Fey</h1>\n<p>The capricious nature of the fey runs in this sorcerer’s family. She ignores @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Difficult Terrain} in the wilderness and has the “laughing touch.” If she successfully touches a target with her hands (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Touch Attack]{Touch Attacks}, page 142), the target is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted}.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>★ Advanced Form: </strong>Victims of a fey’s spell with a lingering effect, such as <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{blind}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{lower Trait}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{stun}</em>, and the like, subtract 2 from any roll made to recover.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_w2j6cd7pbcs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.4. Bloodlines","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"D4rAvjLZ7YB93xRX","name":"Light Domain","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Light Domain</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Aspects:</strong> Light, the sun, nobility, sacrifice, order</li>\n<li><strong>Deities:</strong> Aureon, Dol Arrah, the Path of Light</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Accelerate Healing]{Accelerate Healing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Analyze Foe]{Analyze Foe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Augury]{Augury}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Champion of Faith]{Champion of Faith}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Consecrate/Desecrate Ground]{Consecrate Ground}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/Conceal Arcana}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation} (air and fire only)</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{Environmental Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{Healing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Holy Symbol]{Holy Symbol}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{Locate}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sanctuary]{Sanctuary}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Beast]{Summon Beast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0bt6afhtf6wi","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.2. Domains","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1}}}
{"_id":"D7nRfh7AIcJRwZdK","name":"Shifter","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Shifter</h1>\n<p>Shifters are sometimes called the weretouched, as many believe they are the descendants of humans and lycanthropes. Whatever their origins, shifters have evolved into a unique race. They are humanoids with a bestial aspect; while they can't fully change shape, they can temporarily enhance their animalistic features-a state they call shifting. Each shifter walks on the knife's edge between the wilds and the world around them. Do they embrace their primal instincts or the path of civilization?</p>\n<h3>The Beast Within</h3>\n<p>Early in childhood, a shifter forms a bond with a beast within, a totemic force that shapes their body and mind. Some shifters believe that these spirits are independent entities, and they may speak of Bear or Wolf as ancestors or guides. Most just see the beast within as a formidable expression of their inner nature, something that emerges as the shifter's personality takes shape. The beast within is a pool of powerful instincts, and its influence is revealed by a shifter's personality: a feline shifter may be cool and distant, driven by predatory instincts, while a shifter with a lupine spirit might be drawn to find and protect a pack. When a shifter fully embraces this beast within they physically transform for a short time.</p>\n<p>A shifter's beast within is reflected by its shifting ability. Four kinds are especially common:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Beasthide </strong>often signifies the bear or boar: stoic, stubborn, and thick-skinned.</li>\n<li><strong>Longtooth </strong>shifters typically have lupine traits and prefer to run with a pack.</li>\n<li><strong>Swiftstride </strong>are often predatory and feline, but a swiftstride could also be a cunning rat who darts through the shadows.</li>\n<li><strong>Wildhunt </strong>shifters are born from any creature that tracks its prey.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These other types are also present in the shifter population</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Cliffwalk </strong>often signifies apes, monkeys, or goats: expert climbers and social.</li>\n<li><strong>Dreamsight </strong>don't have a particular beast within, so much as a deep intuitive connection with all beasts.</li>\n<li><strong>Gorebrute </strong>are born from powerful horned beasts.</li>\n<li><strong>Razorclaw </strong>are often clawed predatory animals, often feline in connection.</li>\n<li><strong>Swiftwing </strong>are flight beasts such as flying rodents and bats.</li>\n<li><strong>Truedive </strong>manifest connections to fish.</li>\n<li><strong>Winterhide </strong>are from creatures that dwell in cold mountain passes: stoic, tough, and often loners.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>While the beast within certainly has a physical impact on a shifter, it has a spiritual and psychological effect, as well. Two beasthide shifters share the same special ability, but if one has the aspect of the boar and the other is more like a bear, they'll be quite different in personality. With any shifter, identifying the beast within is a crucial part of understanding the character.</p>\n<h3>Similiar and Diverse</h3>\n<p>Shifters are similar to humans in height and build but are typically more lithe and flexible. Their facial features have a bestial cast, often with large eyes, flat noses, and pointed ears; most shifters also have prominent canine teeth. They grow fur-like hair on nearly every part of their bodies.</p>\n<p>The traits of the beast within affect a shifter's appearance as well. A swiftstride shifter may have catlike eyes and delicate build, while a beasthide shifter might be a massive brute built like a bear. While a shifter's appearance might remind an onlooker of an animal, they remain clearly identifiable as shifters even when at their most feral.</p>\n<h3>The Journey Yet to Come</h3>\n<p>Shifters have a strong presence in the Eldeen Reaches but can be found in rural areas across Khorvaire, where they often live among humans. While they form powerful bonds to friends and kin, shifters place great value on self-reliance and freedom. It's a shifter proverb to \"always be prepared for the journey yet to come,\" and most shifters strive to be ready for change or opportunity.</p>\n<p>Shifters have a natural inclination toward classes with a primal connection. A shifter barbarian draws their rage from the beast within. A shifter ranger indulges their urge to wander and hunt. A shifter rogue harnesses their own predatory instincts. But shifters can pursue any path or faith.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Keen Senses: </strong>Shifters have heighted senses. They begin with a d6 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} skill. This increases their maximum @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Low Light Vision]{Low Light Vision}:</strong> <strong><span style=\"font-weight:400\">Shifters have the sight of their beastial ancestors who have hunted in the night and their eyes amplify light. </span></strong>Low Light Vision ignores up –2 penalties for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination}. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Pitch Darkness} remains unaffected.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Shifting]{Shifting} (Minor Shape Change): </strong>This ability allows a shifter to tap into his lycanthropic heritage. At character creation, the player chooses a shifter ability from the list below. Shifting is a free action and lasts 1 minute or until dismissed as a free action. While in this animal-like form, the shifter can ignore 1 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{wound penalty}. When the shifting ends, the shifter must wait 4 hours before shifting again or suffer a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{fatigue} when the second shifting ends. This level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{fatigue} can only be removed after 4 hours of abstaining from shifting. If the shifter uses this ability again during the recovery time, it inflicts another level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{fatigue} that requires an additional 4 hours of recovery time.</li>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Beasthide]{Beasthide}:</strong> The skin of beasthide shifters harden, providing @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor]{Armor} +4.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Cliffwalk]{Cliffwalk}: </strong>The limbs, hands, and feet of cliffwalk shifters become stronger, allowing cliffwalk shifters to add +2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (climbing) rolls, and climb at their full @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Dreamsight]{Dreamsight}:</strong> Dreamsight shifters' instincts and awareness become heightened, granting them the <em>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-powers.Beast Friend]{beast friend}</em> power. The power affects animals of Size +1 or smaller as well as swarms of Small size. Its effects only last while shifting rather than the power's normal duration.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Gorebrute]{Gorebrute}: </strong>Gorebrute shifters manifest powerful horns that can inflict @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength}+d6 damage (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons} in Savage Worlds Adventure Edition core rules).</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Longtooth]{Longtooth}: </strong>The face of a longtooth shifter distorts, growing a canine muzzle full of sharp teeth that cause @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength}+d4 damage (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons}). Longtooth are also particularly fierce and agressive. They start with a d4 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Razorclaw]{Razorclaw}: </strong>The claws on the hands of razorclaw shifters grow and can be used to make attacks dealing @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength}+d4 damage (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons}). Razorclaw shifters respect little other than physical power. They get a +1 bonus to all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Swiftstride]{Swiftstride}:</strong>The legs of swiftstride shifters elongate and they balance on the balls of their feet. Their base @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} increases by 2 and their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{running die} increases a die type.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Swiftwing]{Swiftwing}: </strong>The arms of swiftwing shifters grow leather flaps of skin similar to a bat's wings, granting the ability to fly at a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} of 6 per round, and \"run\" for extra movement as usual. Maneuvering uses the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} skill. These wings can be targeted, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Entangled} by foes.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Truedive]{Truedive}: </strong>Truedive shifters grow fins and webs of skin between their toes and fingers. They become aquatic creatures that cannot drown in water, can move their full @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} when @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{swimming}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Wildhunt]{Wildhunt}: </strong>Wildhunt shifters' sense of smell becomes more sensitive, providing a +1 bonus to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival} rolls.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Winterhide]{Winterhide}: </strong>A winterhide shifter gains a +8 bonus to resist the negative effects of a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cold]{cold} environment. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cold]{Cold} damage is also reduced by 8.  </li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/shifter.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/shifter.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.P8nuLccu1LyBzOL3"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"DGXfoKM4cOxPVg9f","name":"2 Character Creation Summary","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<div class=\"character-creation\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Character Creation Summary</h1>\n</div>\n<h3>Concept</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Start with a general idea of what you want to play. Your setting book likely provides many ideas.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Races]{Race}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Choose your character’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Races]{race} and apply any bonuses or special abilities it grants.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Select up to four points of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances} (Major Hindrances are worth 2, Minor are worth 1).</li>\n<li>For 2 Hindrance points you can raise an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{attribute} one die type, or choose an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{edge}.</li>\n<li>For 1 Hindrance point you can gain another skill point, or gain additional starting funds equal to twice your setting’s starting amount.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Attributes}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Attributes start at d4. You have 5 points to distribute among them. Each step costs 1 point.</li>\n<li>Attributes may not be raised beyond d12 unless your hero’s racial bonus states otherwise.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Skills]{Skills}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} are core skills and start at d4 for free.</li>\n<li>You have 15 points to put into these or any other skills.</li>\n<li>Each die type costs 1 point up to and equal to the linked attribute; then 2 points per step after that.</li>\n<li>Your character knows @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common} plus a number of starting @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Languages} equal to half your character’s Smarts die type. A Smarts of d6, for example, gives you three additional starting  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{languages}. </li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Characters]{Derived Statistics}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Standard @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace}</strong> is 6″, but may be changed by racial abilities, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Characters]{Parry}</strong> is 2 plus half of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}</strong> is 2 plus half of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Characters]{Vigor}, plus any @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor]{Armor}.</p>\n<p>Note the amount of armor in parentheses like this—Toughness: 11 (2). This means 2 points of the total 11 Toughness comes from Armor. An @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor Piercing (AP)]{Armor Piercing (AP)} attack could bypass those 2 points but not the other 9.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Edges]{Setting Edges}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Every character starts with one free @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Edges]{Class Edge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Background Edge} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Professional Edge}. This edge must be tied to the story of your characters experiences during her life in the Last War.</li>\n<li>Use any leftover Hindrance points to take @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Edges]{Setting Edges} if you like.</li>\n<li>Each @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge} costs 2 Hindrance points.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Gear]{Gear}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Purchase up to 300 galifars (gp) worth of equipment.</li>\n</ul>\n<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_intbwo9s2if","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":7}}}
{"_id":"DVXQAjM9bsnYMqEt","name":"Arcane Background (Druid)","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Druid)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Druid)]{Arcane Background (Druid)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Druid]{Druid}</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Spirit})</li>\n<li><strong>Connected to Eberron:</strong> Druids may take Edges that require @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Miracles)]{Arcane Background (Miracles)}.</li>\n<li><strong>Vow of Protection:</strong> Druids have a major vow to protect nature. Those drawing energy from divine sources must uphold these principles or be cut off from the source of their power.</li>\n<li><strong>Backlash: </strong>When a druid rolls a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} roll, the Dungeon Master rolls on the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash} to see what happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers: </strong>3</li>\n<li><strong>Power Points:</strong> 10</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Accelerate Healing]{Accelerate Healing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Analyze Foe]{Analyze Foe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Animate War Tree]{Animate War Tree}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Augury]{Augury}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{Burrow}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Consecrate/Desecrate Ground]{Consecrate Ground}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/Conceal Arcana}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy} (animals only)</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{Entangle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{Environmental Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{Growth/Shrink}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{Healing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{Locate}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message} (animals only)</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{Mind Link} (animals only)</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Plane Shift]{Plane Shift}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet} (animals only)</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sanctuary]{Sanctuary}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{Shape Change}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Beast]{Summon Beast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>Playing a Druid</h2>\n<p>Druids draw primal magic from the world itself. The process isn’t like the spells of a wizard or the tools of an artificer, nor is it a divine petition to a higher power. Well, not exactly. Legend recounts how the great progenitor dragon Eberron enveloped the jealous evil of Khyber in the living prison that would become the world. If arcane magic comes from the tears of Siberys above, then Druidic magic is the blood and breath of Eberron herself, granting power to those who seek to defend her and the natural order from the threats beyond.</p>\n<p>Most druids are swathed in tradition, usually initiated by a sect that teaches the secrets of this primal magic while also charging the aspirant with specific duties. While some sects are loosely aligned, each one has its own ideas as to the role their kind should play in the world.</p>\n<p>Most druids come from the Eldeen Reaches, where their animistic religion is the dominant faith. Others are found anywhere that nature’s spirit is strong, from the craggy mountains that house the Mror Holds to the fetid swamps of the Shadow Marches. Some druids from the Eldeen Reaches espouse radical philosophies that oppose the use of “unnatural” magic and condemn the building of settlements. Most druids are more moderate in their beliefs about the proper balance of nature, magic, and civilization.</p>\n<h3>Druids and Civilization</h3>\n<p>Most druids come from the Eldeen Reaches, where their animistic religion is the dominant faith. Others are found anywhere that nature’s spirit is strong, from the craggy mountains that house the Mror Holds to the fetid swamps of the Shadow Marches. Some druids from the Eldeen Reaches espouse radical philosophies that oppose the use of “unnatural” magic and condemn the building of settlements. Most druids are more moderate in their beliefs about the proper balance of nature, magic, and civilization.</p>\n<p>You can roll on the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore-tables.Druidic Beliefs]{Druidic Beliefs}</strong> table to see how your druid views civilization.</p>\n<h3>Druids and Sovereign Host</h3>\n<p>Traditionally, the Sovereign Host is a civilized faith with shrines in the great cities of the Five Nations but a number of shrines to deities tied to nature can be found in the wilds. Balinor is the Sovereign of the Hunt, Arawai brings nature’s bounty, and the Devourer embodies its destructive power and the hunger that reclaims its waste. In Eberron, a priest of Balinor isn’t inherently required to follow one trail or the other, but the main differences between the two lay in how command of nature is granted, and the purpose for which they use it. While it’s common for the two paths to recognize one another, such respect isn’t always equal.</p>\n<p>From a philosophical perspective, a druid is an envoy of nature with a connection to the environment itself, not a servant of a higher power. By contrast, the cleric serves a higher power and holds dominion over the natural world. While druids shun such metal armaments, nature clerics usually practice combat in manmade heavy metal armors until proficient. Yet, clerics lack the primal understanding required to communicate in Druidic and to assume Wild Shape, which is a reflection of the druid’s deep connection to the natural world.</p>\n<p>Such differences lead to a deep disconnect between the typical druid and a nature worshiping cleric. The Warden of the Wood might see the priests of Balinor as an arrogant outsider, a city-dweller who believes that humanoids hold some sort of divine right over the planet, which is admittedly often the case. To the priestess of Arawai, nature is something that serves the people and her primary concern is ensuring a bountiful harvest, not driving farmers from their fields.</p>\n<p>While this is the obvious contrast, it’s possible to create a character who uses one class while following the opposite path. Perhaps you want to play a priest of Balinor but you love the idea of hunting in the form of a wolf, or you want to be Ashbound but have no interest in ever assuming a Wild Shape. While there will be the occasional disconnect, like the Ashbound cleric can’t use Wild Shape, the Balinor druid can’t turn undead, look to juxtapose these ideas to best match the story and experience you’re looking for, using backgrounds like the acolyte or outlander to cultivate the option.</p>\n<h2>Casting</h2>\n<p>Druids must make gestures with at least one free hand and speak aloud various magical words at least at a whisper. If either their hands are bound or they are prevented from speaking, they cannot cast their spells.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>Druids interact constantly with nature, drawing all their power from it. They regularly perform various rituals while they rest or pray. They regularly tend to the natural order of things. This opens their conduits of power to the natural energies and allows them to activate powers later without begining the appeal in the moment. </p>\n<p>Druidic powers are cast through chants, talismans, and talking with nature itself. Depending on the spell, the druid may cast bones, sprinkle of ash, rubbing a talisman, beseeching the forces of nature. Trappings for the spells of druids should all include natural components or aspects.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yqngxv6403a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.3. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":3}}}
{"_id":"E0QLtjaYSqo6jQnE","name":"Arcane Backgrounds","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Arcane Backgrounds</h1>\n<p>There are numerous Arcane Backgrounds avilable in the <cite>Eberron Campaign Setting</cite>. Review all the backgrounds below for a summary of what kind of heroes use them. These are the backgrounds that are available to be used and in all cases should be used instead of those presented in the <cite>Savage Worlds</cite> core rules.</p>\n<figure class=\"figure table-figure\">\n<figcaption class=\"figure-heading\">Arcane Background Summaries</figcaption>\n<table class=\"table summary-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Arcane Background</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Arcane Skill</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Summary</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Aberrant Dragonmark)]{Aberrant Dragonmark}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Focus]{Focus} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Spirit)}</td>\n<td>Heroes that has manifested an Aberrant Dragonmark that falls outside the standard marks of the Dragonmarked Houses.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Artificer)]{Artificer}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Smarts)}</td>\n<td>Masters of unlocking magic in everyday objects, artificers are supreme inventors. Creating objects of all kinds that can be used to harness magic.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Bard)]{Bard}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Smarts)}</td>\n<td>Song mages, bards, or skalds work their magic through the power of their voice and musical instruments.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Cleric)]{Cleric}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Spirit)}</td>\n<td>More than mere preachers, clerics serve as emissaries of their gods. These ecclesiastics vow to spread the tenets, knowledge, and truth of their faith.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Divine Magic)]{Divine Magic}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Spirit)}</td>\n<td>From priests to clerics to vassals. Any that draw their power from their faith in any of the Gods of Eberron.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Druid)]{Druid}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Spirit)}</td>\n<td>Druids draw primal magic from the world itself. most druids are swathed in tradition.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Magic)]{Magic}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Smarts)}</td>\n<td>Heroes that are taught to draw on the raw magical energies that are ever present in Eberron. From mages, to wizards, to illusionists, to necromancers.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Psionics)]{Psionics}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Psionics]{Psionics} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Smarts)}</td>\n<td>Psionic powers spring from sentient minds drawing on a reservoir of mental strength to manipulate matter, read minds, and far more. </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Sorcerer)]{Sorcerer}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Spirit)}</td>\n<td>The hero has innate abilities that don't fit in the any of the other magical backgrounds, such as innate racial magic, or sorcerers.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Wizard)]{Wizard}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{(Smarts)}</td>\n<td>These shrewd magic-users research, collect, and covet esoteric knowledge. Some choose to become a master of a particular field of magical study. Others embrace versatility, reveling in the unbounded wonders of all magic.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</figure>\n<p> </p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Magic and Powers</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Using Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Activation]{Activation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers Summary List]{Powers Summary list}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cantrips]{Cantrips}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{Schools of Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3> </h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_fsjso9rnq9","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/4.1. Using Magic","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":7}}}
{"_id":"E4B3M0r8H3bubm5c","name":"Dramatic Tasks","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n\t\t\n\t\t\t<h1 class=\"wide\">Dramatic Tasks</h1>\n  \t\n\t\t\t<p>Heroes often find themselves in tense and dangerous situations such as disabling a complex trap, climbing a rock face while under fire from archers, or rescuing people from a burning building or sinking ship with a definite — and sometimes deadly — time limit.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>This system simulates these events and helps the Game Master insert some drama into what would otherwise be simple skill rolls.</p>\n\t\t\t<p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Dramatic Tasks are great for tense actions that must be performed in a hurry or have disastrous effects if failed.</p>\n\t\t\t<p><strong>The Basics:</strong> The heroes make skill rolls to accumulate \"Task Tokens\" and resolve the event before time runs out.</p>\n\t\t\t\n<h2>Setup</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<p>The GM starts by figuring out what the task is, how long the party has to complete it, and how many tokens they need for success.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Single Person Tasks</h3>\n\t\t\t<p>Use these guidelines when only a single character can attempt the task each turn (others can @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}):</p>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Challenging:</span> Collect four Task Tokens in three rounds. <em>Examples:</em> Disable a trap in the dark, pick a lock before a guard returns, disengage a moving horse-team from its wagon.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Difficult:</span> Collect six Task Tokens in four rounds. <em>Examples:</em> Disable a trap in the middle of combat, cast a ritual, sail a craft to shore during a storm.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Complex:</span> Collect eight Task Tokens in five rounds. <em>Examples:</em> Disable a particularly complicated and/or dangerous trap, Pick a very difficult lock or series of locks before a patrol returns, cast a large and powerful ritual, repair a complicated machine with multiple moving parts.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t<h3>Multi-Person Tasks</h3>\n\t\t\t<p>If more than one person can attempt the task at once, such as crewing a ship, the GM must set the number of rounds and tokens required for victory herself. Here are some guidelines.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Assume each player will average one success per turn. Use that as a guideline if you want the task to be \"fair,\" and set the number of rounds from three to five as appropriate. A party of five given three rounds to save a galleon in a storm, for example, needs to accumulate 15 Task Tokens in three rounds. Increase or decrease the number of tokens to make it more or less challenging.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>If the number of tokens achieved is a measure of success rather than a straight win/fail condition, such as rescuing victims from a fire or hauling up bags of gold from a collapsing mineshaft, simply set the possible number of tokens that may be gathered in the time allowed. Each token gathered represents a person saved, a bag recovered, etc. It’s up to you whether it’s possible to save them all (using the guide above) or not.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Let the party choose how many will attempt the task, especially if there’s something else going on at the same time. Deciding how many heroes will break into the jail to rescue a friend while the others fight off the corrupt city guard allows <em>them</em> to choose their tactics.</p>\n\t\t\t\n<h2>Performing the Task</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<p>Characters are dealt @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Cards} as usual during a Dramatic Task. Those attempting the task make relevant skill checks and get a Task Token for each success and raise. Failure means no progress and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} reduces progress by one (if any has been made).</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The skills that can be used to accumulate tokens depends on the situation. They might be defined, such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} to disable a trap, or they might be open — a heroic paladin might use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} to carry people from a burning building while a mage uses <em>telekinesis</em> (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting}) to do the same.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Multiple Skills</h3>\n\t\t\t<p>The GM can break tasks down into steps if she likes, each of which might require different skills. If disabling a difficult trap in the dark, for example, the heroes might first have to get two tokens to get the feel for their surroundings using @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, then three more tokens using Thievery to cut all three trip wires in the correct order.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Requiring multiple skills throughout the task makes it more difficult since raises from one type of skill check don’t carry over to the other. In the trap example above, for example, the first step requires two Notice successes. Additional successes <em>don’t</em> carry over to the Thievery rolls needed afterward.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Complications</h3>\n\t\t\t<p>If a character’s Action Card is a Club, something has gone wrong. Attempts to resolve the task (or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support} it!) are made at an additional −2. </p>\n\t\t\t<p>Worse, if a roll is failed during a Complication, the Dramatic Task fails — the trap springs, the lock jams, a victim cannot be saved, and so on. The character may choose <em>not</em> to attempt a roll on a turn he has a Complication — it just costs him precious time.</p>\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Support:</strong> Characters assisting (via Support)also suffer the Complication penalty, and an additional −2 if <em>their</em> Action Card is a Club! @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} on their part just subtracts from the lead’s roll as usual, however, it doesn’t cause the entire task to fail.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Death Traps</h3>\n\t\t\t<p>Think carefully before designing Dramatic Tasks that might wipe out the entire party if failed. The threat of catastrophe should be very real but you don’t want a couple of bad die rolls to end the entire game. </p>\n\t\t\t<p>Instead of total disaster, maybe the party has a moment to dive clear before the trap triggers. They don’t perish, but later awake in the care of a local healer or are captured and find themselves about to experience a new type of adventure.</p>\n\t\t\t\n<h2 class=\"example\">Example: Dragon fire!</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<p>An evil red dragon roams the countryside, burning farms and villages throughout the land. @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Seelah]{Seelah} the paladin and @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Harsk]{Harsk} the ranger watch in horror as the dragon breathes fire down on their favorite tavern. The pair rush to aid the choking and gasping patrons attempting to flee the burning building.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The Game Master decides rescuing the survivors is a three-round, Multi-Person Dramatic Task. There are 10 patrons. Each success saves one of them from the inferno.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>On the first round, Seelah and Harsk roll @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} to run into the tavern and drag someone out. Both get a raise, so that's four citizens saved!</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The next round, Harsk gets a Complication. The GM decides he becomes trapped in one of the back rooms and must make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} roll at −2. If he fails, it takes him too long to escape and he won't be able to save any more patrons. Harsk draws his brother's trusty @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Axe, Battle]{battleaxe} and hacks his way free. He decides to go with it and narrates using his Fighting to hack open a hole in the wall for the survivors. He's successful, and Seelah gets a raise this turn with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} — yelling at the locals to help throw water on the fire. That's seven total patrons saved.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>On the third round, Seelah gets a Complication and fails — she's choking on smoke and can't help. Fortunately, after spending a few Bennies, Harsk manages to get two @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raises} and pull the last patrons from the fire.</p>\n\t\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t\t<img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/dragon-fire.webp\" />\n\t\t\t</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.T2GQAJPHkP0TzTNk"}}}
{"_id":"E4sTwgDhOnICfEVT","name":"Darkwood","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2 class=\"wide\">Darkwood</h2>\n<p>This rare wood is much lighter than normal. Items carved from it weigh half as much as typical equivalents and cost 10 gp per pound more than usual. Darkwood items increase @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Hardness} (or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness} if the hull of a vehicle) by 1.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Special Materials]{See Special Materials here}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"E50q3UQHY43xhzdt","name":"#[CF_tempEntity]","content":"","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000","name":"4. The Adventure Toolkit","children":["wZ1Aksns9mqXwzJI","RkQ18cLFRsGUhuaF","t7cEySUJEeGkcuOn","6qE8QcidtDghyi0x","r1TYWhlyGeNUcC8c","E4B3M0r8H3bubm5c","JbDV9v0JyG1xoUIj","MliuyWwR54HWUBmV","E84By6y6JheRfZn0","0lSq3KH2QDfGZ0Ls","68yLEak0FiDyj8Da","oJjFbSjjuIDOeLGV","UeiJs3y8MFrNRv1Z","0sXgmDnR9n2mtmb3","Hn8AGLkO540uPf49","2H7lHiQA5Bl7xgr4","hz2KOH8IaL8kn09K"],"folderPath":["temp_5n9ndtjortv"]}}}
{"_id":"E84By6y6JheRfZn0","name":"Interludes","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Interludes</h1>\n<p>Interludes are tales the players tell in-character to roleplay, enhance a long travel scene, or reveal the secrets and backstories they’ve put so much effort into.</p>\n<p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Interludes give players a way to get to know their characters, reveal some of their backstories, and even add to the world you’re all building together.</p>\n<p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Players tell a story from their character’s point of view and are rewarded with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny}.</p>\n<h2>Running An Interlude</h2>\n<p>When you want to give your players a moment to catch their breath and get into character, allow those who want to take part to draw a card from the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Deck}. The suit of the card gives each player three choices: <strong>Downtime</strong>, <strong>Backstory</strong>, or <strong>Trek</strong>. If a player draws a Joker give <em>everyone</em> an extra @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny} and let <em>them</em> choose the suit and category!</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>DOWNTIME: </strong>What the hero does when left alone. A priest might quietly read a holy text while a warrior constantly sharpens his blades.</li>\n<li><strong>BACKSTORY: </strong>A tale of the character’s past, told through her voice and narration.</li>\n<li><strong>TREK: </strong>The story of an obstacle or challenge the party encountered on the trip.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Reward</h3>\n<p>Those players who participate in the ­Interlude receive a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny}.</p>\n<table class=\"table interlude-table\" style=\"width:66%\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Interludes</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Spades</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Downtime: </strong>The character spends time alone in quiet contemplation. What does she do?</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Backstory: </strong>A great victory or personal triumph.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Trek: </strong>A difficult obstacle the group negotiated along the way.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Hearts</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Downtime: </strong>The hero practices a skill. What is it?</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Backstory: </strong>A tale of the hero’s greatest love—lost, found, present, or waiting on her back home.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Trek: </strong>The party met along the way—merchants, fellow travelers, a renowned bard or hero, etc. Who were they and what happened?</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Diamonds</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Downtime: </strong>The character studies or works on an object of some sort. What is it?</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Backstory: </strong>Something your hero wants or already has. It might be a material possession, recognition, a political goal, or even a trip he wishes to take to some amazing destination.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Trek: </strong>How the group found something that helped them along the way, such as an oasis, minor treasure, food or water, friendly locals, etc.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Clubs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Downtime: </strong>Your hero broods or is angry about something. What is it, and how does she misbehave?</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Backstory: </strong>A tale of misfortune from your hero’s past, perhaps revealing something of his Hindrances or a dark secret.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Trek: </strong>A hardship the party overcame on their trip: the tragic death of a favored Extra, spoiled or lost supplies, a mechanical breakdown, abysmal weather, and so on.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/atmosphere/harpies-attack-an-airship.webp\" /></div>\n<p> </p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.fSBsmuTK9aYdGBsE"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":7},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"EIua6OVfmlKSXvnM","name":"Dancing","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Melee Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>The wielder can command the weapon to dance once per encounter as a free action. It animates immediately, attacking as a character for up to five rounds. It uses its master’s Action Card and attack skill, and rolls two of its normal damage dice for damage. The weapon can fly at @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} 10 and counts as an ally for the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ganging Up]{Gang Up} bonus.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 4</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 20,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"ELS85YQImQwyOIds","name":"Bonus Damage","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Bonus Damage</h2>\n  <p>\n    Well-placed attacks are more likely to hit vital areas and do more damage. If your hero gets a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} \n    on his attack roll (regardless of how many raises), he adds +1d6 to the final total. Bonus dice can also @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aces]{Ace!}</p>\n  <p>\n    Bonus damage applies to all attacks, including spells and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{area effect}\n    weapons.\n  </p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Combat]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aeejh0xnzv6","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Combat keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.g7oyWfLDWqrIRAEQ"}}}
{"_id":"ENgHm8n8s59Iq7Az","name":"Ganging Up","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Ganging Up</h2>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ganging Up]{Ganging Up} allows attackers to flank, exploit openings, and generally harass a foe. \n\t\tEach additional adjacent ally (who isn’t \"@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned}) adds +1 to all the attackers’ Fighting rolls, up to a maximum of +4. \n\t\tIf three goblins attack a single hero, for example, each of the three goblins add +2 to their Fighting rolls.\n\t</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Lbz26MrLopfQYP3j"}}}
{"_id":"ES3HyWlIF51ZM4Xp","name":"Necromancer","content":"<p>Necromancers learn to manipulate the energy that animates all living things. Most people see necromancers as menacing, or even villainous, due to the dose association with death. Not all necromancers are evil, but the forces they manipulate are considered taboo by many societies.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Lore, Religion, Spellcasting or Faith</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Miracles or Magic)</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Familiar, Necromancer, Master Necromancer, Scholar</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.mMBVGTbi74PNwMup"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"EZ8F7XWrX8klsOez","name":"Death Domain","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Death Domain</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Aspects: </strong>Birth, death, fate, prophecy</li>\n<li><strong>Deities:</strong> The Keeper, Blood of Vol</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Augury]{Augury}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{Burrow}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{Curse}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/Conceal Arcana}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Drain Power Points]{Drain Power Points}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Resurrection]{Resurrection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sanctuary]{Sanctuary}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wish]{Wish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{Zombie}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0bt6afhtf6wi","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.2. Domains","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
