{"_id":"FKSQYzprKD08IpBx","name":"Fatigue","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Fatigue</h2>\n  <p>Some hazards, stress, powers, or circum­stances may cause @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} instead of damage. \n\t\tThis represents mental stress or minor but lingering injuries that make a person less effective. \n\t\tFatigue stacks until the victim is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}.\n\t</p>\n  <ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Fatigued:</strong>  The victim subtracts 1 from all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls}. \n\t\t\tIf he takes another level of Fatigue, he’s Exhausted.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Exhausted:</strong> The victim subtracts 2 from all Trait rolls. If he takes another level of Fatigue, he’s Incapacitated.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Incapacitated:</strong>  The victim cannot perform actions and may be unconscious (GM’s call).</li>\n\t</ul>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.RcNTp9yJSlHoJeVH"}}}
{"_id":"FMSFfZFjkN7abo8i","name":"Attacks","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Attacks</h2>\n  <p>\n    The basics of fast, furious combat are discussed in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Melee Attacks]{Melee Attacks} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Attacks]{Ranged Attacks}. Many additional options and situations are covered under <strong>Situational Rules</strong> \n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{here}.\n  </p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Combat]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aeejh0xnzv6","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Combat keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.B4iYmR9ZZVjz1OHN"}}}
{"_id":"Ftz47fWT7f6BbDUV","name":"4 Situational Rules","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n\t<div>\n\t\t<h1 class=\"wide\">Situational rules</h1>\n\t</div>\n    \n\t<p>The core rules for <cite>Pathfinder for Savage Worlds</cite> are very simple— roll a skill die \n\t\t(and a Wild Die if a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card)}. \n\t\tIf the result is 4 or higher after all modifiers, you’re successful.</p>\n\t<p>In the following section are some of the more elaborate maneuvers characters can attempt.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Aim</h2>\n\t\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} rolls assume a character is moving about, dodging attacks, and keeping an eye on the chaos around her. \n\t\t\tIf she focuses her attention and aims, she can make a much more accurate shot.</p>\n\t\t\n\t\t<p>If a character spends her entire turn Aiming a ranged weapon at a particular target or spot (GM's call) and takes no other actions, <em>on her next turn</em> \n\t\t\tshe may ignore up to 4 points of\"@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range}, \n\t\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover}, \n\t\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Called Shots]{Called Shot}, \n\t\t\tor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} penalties; or add +2 to her roll. \n\t\t\tHer attack must be used on the first action of her next turn or the bonus is lost.</p>\n\n\t\t<p>The shooter must be relatively stationary to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aim]{Aim}. \n\t\t\tShe can’t walk, run, ride a horse, or be constantly jostled.</p>\n\t\n\t<h2>Area Effect Attacks</h2>\n\n\t\t<p>Spell effects, breath weapons, and other attacks that cover a large area are “area effect attacks”. \n\t\t\tThe most common are Small, Medium, and Large Blast Templates, and the Cone and Stream Templates. \n\t\t\tThere are copies you can print out on our website.</p>\n\t\t<p>Area effect weapons target a location rather than individuals and so ignore defensive bonuses for targets \n\t\t\tcovered by the template, such as the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Dodge]{Dodge} Edge or speed penalties.</p>\n\t\t<p>Cone and Stream templates are placed with one end (usually the narrow end for the cone template) emanating from \n\t\t\tthe attacker and fired with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} skill \n\t\t\t(or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} for breath weapons and other natural attacks). \n\t\t\tA basic success means those beneath the template are hit. Failure means the attack didn’t occur for some reason— \n\t\t\tthe creature failed to belch up noxious gas, the flamethrower malfunctioned, etc.</p>\n\t\t<p>To attack with a blast template, the player places it on the tabletop (or describes where he wants it to land) \n\t\t\tand rolls Shooting, or Athletics for thrown weapons and breath attacks. If the attack fails and there’s a chance \n\t\t\tthe miss might hit someone else, see Deviation, below.</p>\n\t\t<p>If the roll is successful, any target even partially beneath the template is affected, regardless of any attack penalties to hit such as the Dodge Edge. \n\t\t\tIf the effect causes damage, roll for each victim separately. Attacks that hit with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} \n\t\t\tcause bonus damage as usual.</p>\n\t\t\t\n\t\t<h3>Deviation</h3>\n\t\t\n\t\t<p>Most of the time, the GM can ignore a missed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{area effect attack}. \n\t\t\tIf it's important to know where a missed blast lands, thrown items deviate 1d6″. \n\t\t\tFired projectiles deviate 2d6\". Multiply by 2 if the attack was made at Medium Range, 3 if Long, and 4 for Extreme.</p>\n\t\t<p>Next roll a d12 and read it like a clock facing to determine the direction the missile deviates. A weapon can never deviate more than half the distance \n\t\t\tto the original target (that keeps it from going behind the thrower).</p>\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\n\t\t<table>\n\t\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tTemplate\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tDiameter\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tTargets Affected\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tSmall\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t4 yards\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t2\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tMedium\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t8 yards\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t3\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tLarge\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t12 yards\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t4\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tCone\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t18-yard-long cone\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t3\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tStream\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t24 × 2-yard line\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t3\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t</tbody>\n\t\t</table>\n\n\t<aside>\n\t\t<h1>Templates Without Miniatures</h1>\n\t\t<p>Use the measurements below when you need to figure out how many enemies a template might affect and you aren't using miniatures.</p>\n\t\t<p>The <strong>Targets Affected</strong> column above shows the GM how many enemies are hit in narrative situations, modifying the result if \n\t\t\tthe targets are spread out (like trained assassins) or bunched up (like mindless zombies).</p>\n\t\t<h3>Cover and Area Effect Attacks</h3>\n\t\t<p>Solid obstacles like trees or thick walls protect against @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{area effect attacks} \n\t\t\tif they’re between the center of the blast and a victim and the GM thinks they’d offer protection. \n\t\t\tReduce the damage by half the object's hardness, see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover &amp; Obstacles}.</strong>\n\t\t</p>\n\t</aside>\n\n\n\t<h2>Bound and Entangled</h2>\n\n\t<p>Grappling and powers like <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> \n\t\tcause characters to be Bound and Entangled. Here’s what each of those states means and how to break free from them. \n\t\tCharacters are either @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound or Entangled}— effects don't stack.\n\t</p>\n\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Entangled:</strong>  The victim can’t move and is Distracted as long as he remains Entangled.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Bound:</strong>  The victim may not move, is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted and Vulnerable} \n\t\t\tas long as he remains Bound, and cannot make physical actions other than trying to break free.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t\n\t<p>Breaking free is an action. With success, an Entangled hero is free of one particular entanglement or grappler. \n\t\tA Bound character improves to Entangled with a success; with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, he’s free. \n\t\tSee below for more details:\n\t</p>\n\t\n\t<p>\n\t\t<strong>Breaking Free from a Foe:</strong> \n\t\t Use the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Grappling]{Grappling} rules in reverse to break free. \n\t\t The victim initiates an opposed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} \n\t\t roll with whoever’s holding him (either may roll Strength at −2 instead to maintain or break free of the hold). \n\t\t If the victim’s successful, she improves her status one level, or two with a raise.\n\t</p>\n\t<p>A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} grappler maintains her hold.\n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned} grapplers let go immediately.\n\t</p>\n\t\n\t<p>\n\t\t<strong>Breaking Free from a Device:</strong> \n\t\tEscaping a web, net, or the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> power is a Strength −2 roll <em>or</em> \n\t\tAthletics roll (victim’s choice) minus any penalties noted for the entanglement. The sticky web of a giant spider, for example, \n\t\tmight note that escape attempts are made at −2 or more. This is an action, and success works just like breaking free from a foe \n\t\t(explained above). \n\t</p>\n\n\t<p>Characters and allies may also destroy the entanglement (see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Breaking Things}</strong>. \n\t\tWebs, ropes, nets, and the like are generally Hardness 4 and must be cut with an edged weapon.\n\t</p>\n\n\n\t<h2>Breaking Things</h2>\n\n\t<p>Occasionally a character may want to break a solid object, such as a weapon, lock, or door. \n\t\tUse the wielder’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} if held, or 2 if it’s motionless. \n\t\tIf a damage roll equals or exceeds the object’s Hardness, it’s broken, bent, shattered, or otherwise ruined. \n\t\tThe GM decides the exact effect.\n\t</p>\n\t<p>Most anything can be broken given enough time and effort, so use this system only when attempting \n\t\tto break things in a hurry (such as during combat rounds).\n\t</p>\n\n\n\t<table>\n\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\">\n\t\t\t\t\tObject Hardness\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tHardness\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tObject\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t4\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tRope\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t6\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tBow\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t8\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tPolearm, thin wooden door or wall\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t10\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tShield*, longsword, thick wooden door or wall\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t12\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tIron lock, manacles, shackles\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t</tbody>\n\t\t</table>\n\n\t<p>*A character must specifically state he’s trying to break a shield to do so—don’t check every time the shield-bearer is hit.</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>No Bonus Damage or Aces:</strong> Attacks against solid objects don’t get bonus damage from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raises}, \n\t\tand damage rolls don’t @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aces]{Ace}. \n\t\tUnlike a person or complex device like a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Vehicles]{vehicle}, \n\t\tan attack can’t hit a “vital” area on a lock or a door and thus do more damage.</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>Damage Types:</strong> Certain types of attacks can’t break certain types of objects. A club can’t cut a rope, for example. \n\t\tUse common sense when determining whether or not a particular type of weapon can destroy an object.</p>\n\n    <h2>Called Shots</h2>\n\n\t<p>Targeting a particular part of the body is a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Called Shots]{Called Shot}. \n\t\tThe modifier to the attack roll depends on the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} of the target itself \n\t\t(not the creature it’s part of). Use the <strong>Scale Modifiers</strong> table in the Size and Scale section further down to determine any bonus or penalty \n\t\tfor the target’s Scale. These modifiers are already listed in parentheses for Normal scale creatures, along with any specific game effects:</p>\n\t\t\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Hand (-4)</strong>: Target may be <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Disarm]{Disarmed}</strong>.</li>\n\t\t<li> <strong>Head or Vitals (-4)</strong>: Hitting the head or vital organs of living creatures adds +4 damage to the attacker’s total. \n\t\t\tThe penalty is −5 if attempting to target the face of someone wearing an open-faced helmet (thus bypassing the helmet’s Armor).</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Item</strong>(?) : Use the dimensions on the Scale table for items. Targeting something the size of a dagger, for example, is −4.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Limbs</strong>(-2) Unless attempting to Disarm (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Disarm]{here}), \n\t\t\thitting a limb has no additional special effect since it’s already accounted for by Wound and Pace penalties \n\t\t\t(see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{here}</strong>).</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Unarmored Area</strong> (?) : The attack targets the unprotected area of a target otherwise covered in Armor. \n\t\t\tThe penalty depends on the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} of the area. \n\t\t\tThe eye slit of a helmet is Tiny (−6), for example, while the flesh beneath the missing scale of a Huge dragon might be Very Small (−4).</li>\n\t</ul>\n\n\t<h2>Chases</h2>\n\n\t<p>Whether a daring rooftop chase in the dead of night or a desperate escape through an ill-lit dungeon, a chase can be played out like a regular combat, \n\t\tor using a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Quick Encounters]{Quick Encounter}. Or you can check out our Narrative Chase Deck to resolve the action.</p>\n\n\t<h1 class=\"wide\">Cover and Obstacles</h1>\n\n\t<p>Melee and ranged attacks suffer a penalty when attempting to hit a target behind @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover}. \n\t\tPenalties only apply to the targeted area— a skeleton standing behind a knee-high wall doesn't get Light Cover, \n\t\tbut he does if a quarter of his body is protected by a door frame.\n\t</p>\n\t\n\t\t<table>\n\t\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\tCover Penalties\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tPenalty\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tCover\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t−2\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Light Cover:</strong> A quarter of the target is obscured.\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t−4\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Medium Cover:</strong> Half the target is obscured, or target is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone}.\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t−6\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Heavy Cover:</strong> Three-quarters of the target is obscured.\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t−8\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Near Total Cover:</strong> The target is hidden or barely visible.\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t</tbody>\n\t</table>\n    \n\t<h3>Obstacles</h3>\n\t<p>Sometimes characters have sufficient power to attack their foes <em>through</em> obstacles. \n\t\t(See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Breaking Things}</strong> to actually destroy intervening obstacles.)</p>\n\t<p>When this happens, add an Armor bonus equal to half the obstacle's Hardness to the target beyond (round up if necessary).</p>\n\t<p>If the obstacle is a person or creature, subtract its Toughness from the attack instead.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Defend</h2>\n\n\t<p>A character can choose to focus all her energy and skill into defense against melee attacks with the \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Defend]{Defend} maneuver. \n\t\tThis increases her @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} by +4 and takes her entire turn— \n\t\tshe cannot perform @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Actions}. \n\t\tShe may move normally but may not run. The bonus lasts until the beginning of her next turn.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Desperate Attack</h2>\n\n\t<p>Determined to land a blow, the warrior unleashes a frantic attack, focusing on hitting his target at the expense of damage. \n\t\tHe adds +2 or +4 to any Fighting roll and subtracts a like amount from damage if he hits. \n\t\tThis can be determined per attack (before rolling), and can't be combined with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Attack]{Wild Attack}.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Disarm</h2>\n\n\t<p>A character can try to make an opponent drop a weapon or other object by making an attack against the limb or hand \n\t\t(see <strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Called Shots]{Called Shot}</strong>). \n\t\tIf the attack hits a weapon, the attacker rolls damage normally for an item \n\t\t(no raise effect or Aces, see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Breaking Things}</strong>). \n\t\tThe defender must make a Strength roll equal to the damage or drop the item.</p>\n\n\t<p>If an attack against a target's hand or limb @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shakes} or \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds} him, he must make a Strength roll at −2 if it hit his limb or −4 if it hit his hand. \n\t\tFailure means he drops whatever item is in that hand.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Distracted and Vulnerable</h2>\n\n\t<p>Characters may be @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted or made Vulnerable}\n\t\tby special abilities, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Tests}, or powers. \n\t\tThese states last until the end of the character’s next turn unless otherwise noted. \n\t\tIf a hero becomes Distracted or Vulnerable during her current turn, \n\t\tit lasts until the end of her <em>next</em> turn. \n\t\tLike effects don't stack.</p>\n\t\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Distracted:</strong>  The hero subtracts 2 from all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls} until the end of his next turn.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Vulnerable:</strong>  Actions and attacks against the target are made at +2 until the end of his next turn. \n\t\t\tThis doesn’t stack with <strong>The Drop</strong> (see below).</li>\t\n\t</ul>\n\n\t<h2>The Drop</h2>\n\n\t<p>Sometimes an attacker is able to catch a foe off-guard and gets “The Drop” on him. \n\t\tThe GM decides when this is in effect— usually it’s when the victim is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{bound} \n\t\tor completely unaware of an attack. The Drop usually happens up close but the GM can also allow it in other situations \n\t\tas she sees fit (a sniper attacking an unaware and stationary target).\n\t</p>\n\n\t<p>The Drop adds +4 to a character’s attack and damage rolls against that target for one action.</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>Knockout Blow:</strong> If a character takes enough damage to be @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} \n\t\tor worse from an attacker with The Drop on him, he must make a Vigor roll (at −2 if the attack was to the head) or be knocked unconscious.</p>\n\n\t<p>KO’ed characters stay that way for about half an hour or until the GM decides it’s dramatically appropriate to wake up. \n\t\tNote that Knockout Blows come from any kind of damage, not just blows to the head!</p>\n\n\t<h2>Evasion</h2>\n\n\t<p>Some attacks are slow or require the user to “telegraph” their delivery, like flamethrowers or dragon’s breath. \n\t\tSuch attacks state they may be Evaded. If an attack <em>doesn’t</em> say it can be \n\t\tEvaded, it can’t— victims are simply hit if the attack is successful and take damage.</p>\n\t<p>If an attack can be Evaded and the character is aware of it, he makes an Agility roll at −2. \n\t\tThose who are successful manage to avoid the attack and take no damage.\n\t\tIf this was an area effect attack, the GM should place the figure to the side or rear of the template \n\t\tas makes sense in the situation.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Fatigue</h2>\n\n\t<p>Some hazards, stress, powers, or circum­stances may cause Fatigue instead of damage. \n\t\tThis represents mental stress or minor but lingering injuries that make a person less effective. \n\t\tFatigue stacks until the victim is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}.\n\t</p>\n\t\t\t\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Fatigued:</strong>  The victim subtracts 1 from all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls}. \n\t\t\tIf he takes another level of Fatigue, he’s Exhausted.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Exhausted:</strong> The victim subtracts 2 from all Trait rolls. If he takes another level of Fatigue, he’s Incapacitated.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Incapacitated:</strong>  The victim cannot perform actions and may be unconscious (GM’s call).</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t\t\n\t<h3>Recovery</h3>\n\t<p>Unless otherwise specified by the source, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} and Exhaustion improve one level per hour. \n\t\tCharacters @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} from Fatigue are helpless \n\t\tand may be unconscious (GM’s call) for 2d6 hours. If treatment is possible (food, water, etc.; depending on the source of Fatigue), \n\t\tand a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{Healing} roll is made, the character improves to Exhausted.</p>\n\t\t\n\t<p><strong>Mixed Fatigue:</strong> If a hero suffers Fatigue from different sources with different recovery times, \n\t\tremove one level when the effect with the shortest duration expires, then another level when the longest expires.</p>\n\t\t\n\t<h3>Hazards</h3>\n\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from hunger, thirst, etc., sometimes has different recovery conditions. \n\t\tSee <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</strong>. \n\t</p>\n\n\t<h2>Finishing Move</h2>\n\t<p>A completely helpless victim may be dispatched with a lethal weapon of some sort as an action. \n\t\tThis is automatic unless the GM decides there’s a special situation, such as a particularly tough or naturally armored victim, \n\t\ta chance for escape, and so on.</p>\n\t<p>The killer must usually dispatch his foe up close and personal, but the GM may occasionally let @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Finishing Move]{Finishing Moves}\n\t\tbe performed at range if the situation warrants.</p>\n\t\n\t<h2>Firing Into Melee</h2>\n\n\t<div>\n\t\t<img src=\"/assets/art/PF17.webp\" />\n\t</div>\n\t<p>Occasionally, heroes have to fire into the middle of hand-to-hand fights. \n\t   The trouble is that even though we might see figures standing perfectly still on the tabletop, \n\t   in “reality,” they’re circling each other, wrestling back and forth, and moving erratically. \n\t   For that reason, firing into a tangle of people, such as a melee, is quite dangerous. \n\t   Use the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Innocent Bystandards]{Innocent Bystander}</strong> rules when this occurs.</p>\n\n\n\t<h2>Free Attacks</h2>\n\n\t<p>Some Edges, such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Counterattack]{Counterattack} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.First Strike]{First Strike}, \n\t\tor options such as <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Withdrawing From Melee]{Withdrawing From Melee}</strong>, allow a character to make a free attack.</p>\n\t<p>Free attacks are a single attack unaltered by other Edges or combat options. This is usually a Fighting or grappling attack, but could include Shooting \n\t\tif the attacker is armed with a hand crossbow, wand, or small device \n\t\t(GM's call, see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Weapons in Melee]{Ranged Weapons in Melee}</strong>.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Ganging Up</h2>\n\n\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ganging Up]{Ganging Up} allows attackers to flank, exploit openings, and generally harass a foe. \n\t\tEach additional adjacent ally (who isn’t @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned}) adds +1 to all the attackers’ Fighting rolls, up to a maximum of +4. \n\t\tIf three goblins attack a single hero, for example, each of the three goblins add +2 to their Fighting rolls.\n\t</p>\n\t\n\t<p>Each of the defender's adjacent allies cancels out one point of Gang Up bonus from an attacker adjacent to both. \n\t\tThis means troops in opposing lines, such as a medieval formation where each man has three adjacent foes and two adjacent allies, \n\t\tdon’t get the bonus unless actually flanked.\n\t</p>\n\n\t<h2>Grappling</h2>\n\n\t<p>As an action, an attacker can make an opposed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll to grapple a defender. \n\t\tIf the attacker wins, the foe is Entangled. With a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, he’s Bound. (Success on a foe who was already Entangled makes him Bound.) \n\t\tSee<strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound &amp; Entangled}</strong>.</p>\n\n\t<p>If a foe is Bound, the <em>grappler</em> is also @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Vulnerable} while maintaining his hold.</p>\n\n\t<p>The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ganging Up]{Gang Up} bonus applies when grappling a defender, \n\t\tbut other maneuvers don’t unless the Game Master rules otherwise in a specific situation.</p>\n\n\t<p><strong>Size Matters:</strong> If there’s a difference in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} between the attacker and defender, \n\t\tthe grappler subtracts the difference from his total (the defender doesn't get a bonus or penalty for Scale difference).</p>\n\n\t<p>Creatures may not generally grapple a foe more than two Sizes larger than themselves \n\t\tunless they have exceptional reach or Strength for their Size (GM’s call).</p>\n\n\t<blockquote><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> A dragon (Huge +4) tries to pin a humanoid thief (Normal). \n\t\tThe difference between Huge and Normal Scales is 4, so the dragon must subtract 4 from its @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll. \n\t\tThe rogue doesn't get a bonus or penalty.\n\t</blockquote>\n\n\t<p><strong>Crush:</strong> A grappler may harm someone he’s Entangled or Bound by making an opposed Strength roll as an action on his turn. \n\t\tWith success, his attack does his Strength in damage (gaining bonus damage for a raise as normal).</p>\n\n\n\t<h2>Hold</h2>\n\t<p>A hero may choose to delay her turn by going on \"Hold\". \n\t\tThis allows her to resolve her actions later in the round if she wishes, and lasts until it’s used. \n\t\tIf a character is on Hold when a new round begins, she’s not dealt a new Action Card but can go at any point in the round she chooses. \n\t\t(Discard her current card and mark her as “On Hold” with a counter of some sort.)</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} and </strong><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned}:</strong> \n\t\tIf a character is Shaken or Stunned while on Hold, she immediately loses her Hold status \n\t\tand her turn for the round. (Shaken or Stunned characters can’t go on Hold either.)</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>Interrupting Actions:</strong> If a character on Hold wants to interrupt an action (including a rival who was also on Hold), \n\t\tshe and the opponent make opposed  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} rolls. \n\t\tWhoever rolls highest goes first. In the rare case of a tie, the actions are simultaneous.\n\t</p>\n\n\t<p>If the character interrupting fails, she loses her Hold status but gets a turn after the foe finishes his. \n\t\tShe may take whatever actions she wishes when her turn comes up— she’s not locked into whatever she was trying to do when she failed to interrupt.\n\t</p>\n\n\t<h2>Illumination</h2>\n\t<p>Darkness conceals details and makes it more difficult to detect objects and targets. Subtract the Illumination Penalties \n\t\t(see the <strong>Illumination Penalties</strong> table below) from active @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls} affected by Illumination, \n\t\tsuch as attacks, arcane skill and Notice rolls, etc. </p>\n\t\n\t<p>It’s up to the Game Master exactly what Trait rolls are affected, but here are a few examples of rolls that should <em>not</em> be penalized:</p>\n\t\n\t<ul class=\"bullet\">\n\t\t<li>Resisting powers</li>\n\t\t<li>Resisting grappling attempts</li>\n\t\t<li>Recovering from a negative status, such as being Shaken or Stunned</li>\n\t\t<li>Verbal Support rolls</li><li>Verbal Tests</li>\n\t\t<li>A friendly, cooperative, adjacent character in Pitch Darkness where touch and communication overcome lack of sight</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t\n\t<p>Note that foes may get bonuses for attacking a target that can’t see them (see <strong>Attacking from Stealth</strong> in \n\t\tthe Stealth subsection in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Traits}).\n\t</p>\n\t\n\t<table>\n\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\">\n\t\t\t\t\tILLUMINATION PENALTIES\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tPenalty\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tLighting\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−2\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Dim:</strong> Twilight, light fog, night with a full moon. Visibility is generally limited to 25\" (50 yards).\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−4\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Dark:</strong> Typical night conditions with some ambient light from stars, a clouded or partial moon, \n\t\t\t\t\t\ta few flickering torches in a large space, etc. Targets aren’t visible outside of 10″.\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t−6\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Pitch Darkness:</strong> Complete and total darkness (or the target is hidden or invisible). \n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tPowers that require sight may not be possible.\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t</tbody>\n\t\t\t</table>\n\n\n\t<h2>Improvised Weapons</h2>\n\t\n\t<p>Heroes often fight with objects that aren’t intended for use as weapons. Torches, vases, chairs, tankards, bottles, tools, and other mundane items \n\t\tare frequently pressed into service in combat.</p>\n\t<p>Characters with improvised weapons count as armed but subtract 2 from attack rolls. \n\t\tRange, damage and Minimum Strength are determined by type:</p>\n\t\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Light:</strong>  Beer stein, fist-sized rock, dagger pommel (as a club). Range 3/6/12, Damage Str+d4, Min Str d4.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Medium:</strong> Hammer, pick, wooden chair. Range 2/4/8, Damage Str+d6, Min. Str d6.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Heavy:</strong> Head-size rock, sack of stones, log. Range 1/2/4, Damage Str+d8, Min. Str d8.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t\n\t<p>The GM should adjust the damage and other factors as makes sense for the particular item.</p>\n\t\n\t<div>\n\t\t<img src=\"/assets/art/2 Kobold Ambush_v2.webp\" />\n\t</div>\n\t\n\t<h2>Innocent Bystanders</h2>\n\n\t<p>When an attacker misses a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing) roll, \n\t\tit may sometimes be important to see if any other targets in the line of fire were hit. \n\t\tThe GM should only use this rule when it’s dramatically appropriate— not for every missed shot in a hail of arrows.</p>\n\t<p>Each skill die that’s a 1 hits a random victim adjacent to or directly in the line of fire to the original target.</p>\n\t<p>A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} must miss with his Wild Die for a RoF 1 weapon to hit an Innocent Bystander—  \n\t\twild dice never hit innocent bystanders.</p>\n\t<p>This sometimes means it's easier to hit an adjacent victim than the original target. That may not be entirely realistic, \n\t\tbut is simple, dramatic, and requires some care in tight tactical situations.</p>\n    \n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>\n\t\t\t<strong>RoF 2+:</strong>  Although rare on Eberron, weapons with a Rate of Fire or 2 or more, or that fire in a spread, are much more likely to hit others. \n\t\t\tEach skill die that rolls a 1 <em>or</em> a 2 hits a bystander.\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\n\t<h2>Mounted Combat</h2>\n\t\n\t<p>Characters fighting from horseback (or other beasts) have certain advantages and disadvantages in combat, as described below.</p>\n\t<p>Mounts aren’t dealt Action Cards— they act with their riders. Animals may attack during their rider’s action if desired. </p>\n\t<p><strong>Horsemanship:</strong> Characters who wish to fight from horseback must use the lowest of their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}\n\t\tor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding} skills. This also applies to other more extraordinary mounts.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Falling:</strong> If a character is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}, \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned}, \n\t\tor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounded} while mounted, or his mount is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}, \n\t\the must make a Riding roll. If he fails, he falls. If the mount was running, \n\t\tthe rider suffers 2d4 damage (2d6 with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}). \n\t\tIncrease the damage by an additional die or two if the mount is particularly fast, flies, or the rider falls in particularly rough or dangerous terrain.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Missed Ranged Attacks:</strong> \n\t\tMounts and riders are affected by the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Innocent Bystandards]{Innocent Bystander}</strong> rules. \n\t\tIf a shot intended at a rider rolls a 1, it hits the mount instead.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Wounded Mounts:</strong> When an animal is Shaken or Wounded, it rears or bucks. A rider must make a Riding roll to stay mounted, or falls as above.</p>\n\t\n\t<h3>Charging</h3>\n\t<p>A rider on a charging mount adds +4 to his damage roll with a successful Fighting attack. \n\tTo be considered charging, the rider must have moved at least 5″ (10 yards) or more in a relatively straight line toward his foe.</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>Setting Weapons:</strong> A weapon with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reach]{Reach} of 1 or greater can be “set” against a cavalry attack. \n\t\tTo do so, the attacker must be on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{Hold} and win an opposed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll \n\t\tto interrupt as usual. Whoever has the most Reach adds +2 to his roll.</p>\n\t<p>The winner attacks first. If successful, he adds the +4 charge bonus to his damage (whether he’s the rider or not).</p>\n\t\n\t<h2>Multi-Actions</h2>\n\t\n\t<p>Characters can perform up to three actions on their turn (one of which may be a limited action). \n\t\tEach additional action beyond the first inflicts a −2 penalty to all actions. \n\t\tTaking two actions, for example, incurs a −2 penalty to both, and three actions is a −4 penalty.</p>\n\t\t\n\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} get their Wild Die on each action as usual.</p>\n\t\n\t<p>All actions must be declared at the start of the turn and before any dice are rolled. \n\t   Penalties remain even if a later action doesn’t happen (usually because it was dependent on an earlier success).</p>\n\t<p><strong>Movement and Multiple Actions:</strong> A hero may take her actions at different points of her movement as she wishes.</p>\n\t<p>\n\t\t<strong>Free Actions:</strong> \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Action} penalties do <em>not</em> apply to \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free} (or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Limited Free Actions]{limited free}) actions.\n\t</p>\n\t\n\t<h2>Natural Weapons</h2>\n\t\n\t<p>Creatures with natural weapons such as fangs, claws, or horns may attack with them using their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} skill. \n\t\tDamage is stated for character @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Ancestries]{ancestries} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Bestiary]{beasts} in their various descriptions.</p>\n\t<p>Creatures with natural weapons are always considered armed. This means they aren’t <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Unarmed Defender]{Unarmed Defenders}</strong> \n\t\tand foes fighting with <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Two Weapons]{Two Weapons}</strong> gain no advantage against them.\n\t\tHere are a few additional notes for each type of attack:</p>\n\t\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Bite:</strong> The creature may bite a target it’s grappled (most attackers can only crush their prey, \n\t\t\tsee <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Grappling]{Grappling}</strong>. \n\t\t\tThis is a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} attack.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Claws:</strong> \n\t\t\tAdd +2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (climbing) rolls on any rough or soft surface (not sheer steel, glass, etc.).</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Horns:</strong>  \n\t\t\tAdd +4 damage from a successful attack with a creature's horns if it runs and moves at least 5″(10 yards).</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t\n\t<h2>Nonlethal Damage</h2>\n\t\n\t<p>A character who wants to beat someone up without killing them can choose to do nonlethal damage. \n\t\tThis requires the attacker use only his fists or a blunt weapon of some sort. Edged weapons may be used if they have a flat side, \n\t\tbut this subtracts −1 from the attacker’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls.</p>\n\n\t<p>Nonlethal damage causes Wounds as usual, but if a character is rendered @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}, he cannot Bleed out.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Off-Hand Attacks</h2>\n\n\t<p>Characters are assumed to be right-handed unless the player decides otherwise. \n\t\tActions that require precise eye-hand coordination, such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} or \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, suffer a −2 penalty when done solely with the off-hand.</p>\n\t<p>Off-hand weapons don’t add their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} bonus unless the hero is \n\t\t<strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Ambidextrous]{Ambidextrous}</strong>.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Prone</h2>\n\n\t<p>Ranged attacks suffer a −4 penalty to hit prone characters from a range of 3″ (6 yards) \n\t\tor greater (this does not stack with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover}) \n\t\tand subtract four points of damage from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Area Effect attacks}.</p>\n\t<p>If a prone defender is caught in melee, his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} is reduced by 2 and he must subtract 2 from his \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls.</p>\n\t<p>Standing from prone is a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}, but costs a character 2″ of movement.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Push</h2>\n\n    <div>\n\t\t<img src=\"/assets/art/45 Bar Fight.webp\" />\n\t</div>\n\t\n\t<p>Sometimes characters may want to push a foe in hopes of knocking him out of position, prone, or even into a deadly hazard.</p>\n\t<p>Pushing a foe is an action that requires opposed roll of Strength. If the attacker is successful he pushes the foe back 1″ (two yards), or twice that with a raise.</p>\n\t<p>A character who’s successfully Pushed must make an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll (at −2 if the attacker got a raise) \n\t\tor be knocked @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone}.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Running:</strong> If the attacker runs at least 2″ (four yards) before the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Push]{Push}, he adds +2 to his total.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Size Matters:</strong> Double the distance pushed if the attacker’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} is larger than the foe’s. \n\t\tCreatures may not generally Push a foe more than two Sizes larger then themselves unless they have exceptional Strength for their Size (GM’s call).</p>\n\t<p><strong>Skill:</strong> The attacker or defender may roll Athletics instead of Strength if they choose.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Shields:</strong> Attackers and defenders add their shield’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} bonus to their Strength \n\t\t(or Athletics) rolls when pushing.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Ranged Weapons in Melee</h2>\n\n\t<p>Heroes may fire ranged weapons when engaged in melee with a few caveats:</p>\n\t\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>The attacker may only use a power or a one-handed ranged weapon (such as a thrown dagger) when in melee. \n\t\t\tHe may not fire two-handed weapons such as a bow. The TN is the defender’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} instead of \n\t\t\tShort Range as he struggles back and forth, etc.</li>\n\t\t<li>If attacking a non-adjacent target with a ranged attack <em>while</em> in melee, the attacker instantly becomes\n\t\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Vulnerable}.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\n\t<h2>Readying Weapons</h2>\n\n\t<p>Characters may “ready” up to two items per turn as a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}. Readying means drawing, holstering, or \n\t\totherwise moving an item into or out of an easy-to-reach location.</p>\n\t<p>Each additional item readied is an action, as is recovering an item from a difficult location like an ankle sheath, off the floor after being disarmed, \n\t\tor other exten­uating circumstances.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Reloading</h2>\n\n\t<p>Nocking an arrow or loading a sling is a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}, \n\t\tbut reloading any ranged weapon requires two hands (thrown weapons are readied, see above).</p>\n\t<p>Some weapons, like heavy crossbows, are slower to reload. They require a number of actions to reload, listed as “Reload X” in their description.</p>\n\n\t<blockquote><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> \n\t\tOur ranger fires a heavy crossbow (Reload 2) as part of a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Action}, \n\t\tusing his other two actions that turn to reload. Since this is three actions, his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} roll is made at −4. \n\t\tOn his next turn, he's ready to fire again.\n\t</blockquote>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>Running &amp; Reloading:</strong> Running and loading requires an Agility roll (at the usual −2 penalty for running). \n\t\tFailure means no progress toward reloading was made that action.</p>\n\n\n\t<h2>Rest</h2>\n\t<p>Whenever a party decides to rest for a prolonged period (at least eight hours of no activity), each @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card}\n\t\tin the party recovers one @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny}. \n\t\tOf course, the party's enemies are able to regather their strength, too, so the GM also regains a Benny.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Size and Scale</h2>\n\t<p>Characters and creatures have a Size ranging from −4 for very small beings up to Size 20 and higher for massive behemoths. \n\t\tSpecific creature Sizes are listed in their statistics, and explained on the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Size Table]{Size Table}</strong>.</p>\n    <p>The Size Table lists seven different “Scales,” from Tiny to Gargantuan, and the Scale Modifier that goes with each.</p>\n\t<p>When creatures of different Scales attack each other, the smaller creature <em>adds</em> the difference between its Scale and its target to its attacks. \n\t\tA Tiny fairy (−6 Scale modifier), for example, adds +10 to attack a Huge dragon (+4). \n\t\tThe larger creature <em>subtracts</em> the difference from its attacks. \n\t\tA Very Small eagle (−4) subtracts 2 from its Fighting totals when attacking a Tiny fairy (−6).</p>\n\t\n\t<table>\n\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\">\n\t\t\t\t\tScale Modifiers\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tModifier\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tScale &amp; Examples\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−6\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Tiny:</strong> Armor joint, baseball, mouse\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−4\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Very Small:</strong> Human hand or head, basketball, house cat\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−2\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Small:</strong> Human limb, bobcat\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t—\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Normal:</strong> Human, bull, horse\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t+2\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Large:</strong> Hippo, most vehicles\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t+4\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Huge:</strong> Dragon, whale\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t+6\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Gargantuan:</strong> Building, kaiju, ship\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t</tbody>\n\t</table>\n\t\n\t<h3>Called Shots &amp; Target Size</h3>\n\t\t<p>Use the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} of the target when making Called Shots against creatures, not <em>their</em> Scale. \n\t\t\tIf an archer wants to shoot the eye of a mature dragon, for example, use the Scale of the <em>eye</em>, not the dragon.\n\t\t</p>\n\t\t<p>Hitting certain vital areas have extra effects listed under <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Called Shots]{Called Shots}</strong>.</p>\n\n\t<h2>Stunned</h2>\n\t<p>Creature abilities, the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{stun}</em> power, electrical hazards, \n\t\tor other shocks to the brain or nervous system make a character essentially helpless until they manage to shake it off.</p>\n\t<p>Restart the process if a stunned character is stunned again.</p>\n\t\n\t<h3>Stunned characters</h3>\n\t<ul class=\"bullet\">\n\t\t<li>Are @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted} (this is removed at the end of a victim’s next turn as usual)</li>\n\t\t<li>Are @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Vulnerable} Vulnerable (this remains until a victim recover from being Stunned) </li>\n\t\t<li>Fall prone (or to their knees, GM’s call)</li>\n\t\t<li>Can’t move or take any actions</li>\n\t\t<li>Don’t count toward the \"@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ganging Up]{Gang Up} bonus</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>Recovery:</strong> At the start of a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned} char­acter’s turn, he makes a Vigor roll as a \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}. \n\t\tSuccess means he’s no longer Stunned but remains Vulnerable until the end of his <em>next</em> turn.\n\t\tWith a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, his Vulnerable state goes away at the end of this turn.\n\t</p>\n\n\t<h2>Support</h2>\n\n\t<p>Sometimes characters may want to cooperate or help an ally with a task. If so, and the GM decides it’s possible, \n\t\tsupporting characters roll the relevant skill (as an action if the game is in rounds) and declare which of their ally’s skills they’re attempting to Support.</p>\n\t<p>Success grants the ally +1 to one skill total this round, and a raise adds +2.\n\t\tA @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} on the support roll subtracts 2 from the lead’s total— \n\t\tsometimes extra hands just get in the way!\n\t</p>\n\t<p>Remove all Support bonuses at the end of the recipient’s turn, whether he used them or not (perhaps by taking an action different than the one he was Supported for).</p>\n\t<p>The maximum bonus from all Support rolls is +4. Strength checks are an exception and have no maximum bonus since more muscle can always manage more mass.</p>\n\t<p>Players and GMs should be creative when making Support rolls. An adventurer with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}, for example, \n\t\tmight make a roll to find useful herbs for an ally attempting a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} check, \n\t\tor a character with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Academics]{Academics} might recall historical information helpful to a wizard doing research \n\t\ton an ancient relic.\n\t</p>\n\t<p>General encouragement (a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll) such as “You can do it!” or “Check your six!” are perfectly acceptable, \n\t\tbut at the GM’s discretion lose effectiveness if repeated.\n\t</p>\n\n\t<blockquote>\n\t\t<em><strong>Example:</strong></em> \n\t\tThe heroes mount up for a day’s ride. Spooked by a pack of wolves, the horses bolt. The cleric, having no @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding} skill, \n\t\tfinds herself in danger of losing control of the mount. The paladin shouts “Hold the reins loosely!” She rolls Riding and gets a raise. \n\t\tThe cleric adds +2 to the unskilled Riding roll to control her horse.\n\t</blockquote>\n\n\n\t<h2>Surprise</h2>\n\n\t<aside class=\"sidebar\">\n\t\t<h1>Support VS. Test</h1>\n\t\t<p>The Support option can be used against an opponent narratively, but the only effect it can have is as detailed above. \n\t\t\tIf a character wants to “trip up” an ogre to help a friend make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} roll against it, for example, \n\t\t\tshe can add +1 or +2 to his roll, but she doesn’t actually trip the ogre. It’s not made @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone}, \n\t\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted or Vulnerable} or \n\t\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} as it might if she had used the \n\t\t\t<strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test}</strong> option.\n\t\t</p>\n\t\t<p>The advantage for a player in making a Support roll over a Test is to help an ally and avoid a more difficult opposed roll for the Test \n\t\t\t(even though narratively it might seem like it should be an opposed roll).</p>\n\t</aside>\n\n\t<p>Combat often starts before everyone involved is prepared. An ambush, a sudden double-cross, or a trap might all give one side in a fight an advantage. \n\t\tWhen this happens, the ambushers are automatically on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{Hold}. \n\t\tDeal them in as usual anyway in case one of them gets a Joker.</p>\n\t<p>The victims of the attack make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll. Those who make it are dealt in as usual. \n\t\tThose who fail get no Action Card and can’t act in the first round of combat.</p>\n\t<p>See the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} skill if someone attempts a sneak attack before the round begins.</p>\n\t\t\n\t<h2>Test</h2>\n\n\t<p>The <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}</strong> option allows a character to help out her allies. \n\t\tTest is the opposite— it lets him make things more difficult for his foes! \n\t\tTests include embarrassing an opponent, throwing sand in his eyes, staring him down with a steely gaze, or anything else a clever player can think of to rattle \n\t\this enemy and put him off-balance.\n\t</p>\n\t<p>To perform a Test, the player describes the action and works with the GM to determine the most appropriate skill to roll for it. \n\t\tTests are resisted instinctively, so the “attacker’s” skill roll is opposed by the attribute it’s linked to. \n\t\tTripping someone is an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll versus Agility since that’s what Athletics is linked to. \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Taunt]{Taunt} is linked to Smarts, so verbally humiliating someone is resisted by that attribute. \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, when used as a Test instead of an actual attack, \n\t\tisn’t compared to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry}— it’s opposed by Agility. \n\t\tWhatever skill is used, performing a Test is an action.\n\t</p>\n\t<p>If the attacker wins the opposed roll, he can choose to make his foe \n\t\t<strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted or ­Vulnerable}</strong>. \n\t\tIf he wins with a raise, the target is also @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}, \n\t\tand there may be other subjective effects as the GM allows, such as a tripped foe being knocked @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone}.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Modifiers:</strong> The GM must determine which modifiers apply to a Test. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, for example, \n\t\tshould include @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover}, \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Illumination}, etc. \n\t\tA hero with a bonus to his Parry does <em>not</em> add it to his Agility when challenged with a Fighting roll, however, because the defender resists with Agility— \n\t\tnot his Parry.\n\t</p>\n\t<p>Take the details into consideration as well— using a shameful secret to hit a rival’s ego where it hurts, for example, might be worth a +2 bonus to the attacker.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Repetition:</strong> Using the same or similar action repeatedly quickly grows less effective, so the GM shouldn't allow players to use \n\t\tthe same tactics, insults, or threats more than once an encounter.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Additional Dice:</strong> If characters have addi­tional dice for a Test, such as when using a weapon with a high Rate of Fire, \n\t\the may roll all the dice but takes only the highest as his Test total. He doesn’t get multiple results and he can’t spread them out to other targets.\n\t</p>\n\n\t<aside class=\"sidebar\">\n\t\t<h1>Dungeoneering</h1>\n\t\t<p>When heroes delve into dungeons— or ruins or even buildings— combat can get cramped.</p>\n\t\t<p>In <cite>Pathfinder for Savage Worlds</cite>, creative use of these <strong>Situational Rules</strong> give the characters options during combat. \n\t\t\tInstead of just waiting for your turn to get through a door and attack, for example, your hero can attempt other actions to make an impact with teamwork.</p>\n\n\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t<li>\n\t\t\t\t<strong> Support:</strong> Coordinate your actions and use Support to ensure success. \n\t\t\t\tFor example, the paladin tries to Push past an ogre blocking the entrance to the villain’s chamber, hoping to create space for the fighter. \n\t\t\t\tThe rogue rolls Support using @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Taunt]{Taunt} (“Is that all you got?”) \n\t\t\t\tto assist with the paladin’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Push]{Push} attempt.\n\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t<li>\n\t\t\t\t<strong>Test:</strong> Coordinate tactics to make it harder for enemies to fight back. In the Push example above, the sorcerer— \n\t\t\t\twho wants to save @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} for attacks on the villain— can @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test} \n\t\t\t\tthe ogre with Taunt. Knowing it speaks Giant, she shouts insults in that tongue. \n\t\t\t\tIf she succeeds on the opposed roll, she makes the ogre @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted}, \n\t\t\t\twhich helps the paladin win the opposed Push.\n\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t</ul>\n\t</aside>\n\n\t<h2>Touch Attack</h2>\n\n\t<p>A character who simply wants to touch a foe (usually to deliver a magical effect of some kind) may add +2 \n\t\tto his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} roll.</p>\n\t\t\n\t<h2>Two Weapons</h2>\n\t<p>A character armed with two melee weapons adds +1 to his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls if his foe has a single weapon or is unarmed, \n\t\tand has no shield. It adds no bonus against creatures with <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons}</strong>.</p>\n\t<p>Wielding two small ranged weapons offers no special advantage other than additional ammunition or narrative embellishments.</p>\n\t<p>Those wanting to specialize further can take the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Two-Weapon Fighting]{Two-Weapon Fighting}</strong> Edge.</p>\n\n\n\t<h2>Unarmed Defender</h2>\n\n\t<p>It’s difficult to parry a blade with one’s bare hands. An attacker armed with a melee weapon adds +2 to his \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} attacks if his foe has no weapon or shield. \n\t\t(This doesn’t stack with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.The Drop]{The Drop}.)</p>\n\t\n\t<h2>Unstable Platform</h2>\n\t\n\t<p>A character attempting to fire or throw a ranged weapon from the back of a horse or other mount, a moving vehicle, or other “unstable platform” \n\t\tsubtracts 2 from his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing) or \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} totals.</p>\n\t\n\t<h2>Vehicles</h2>\n\t\n\t<p>Attacking from or on vehicles such as ships, carriages, or airships works as usual— see \n\t\t<strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Vehicles]{Vehicles}</strong>.</p>\n\t\n\t<h2>Wild Attack</h2>\n\t\n\t<p>Sometimes a desperate character may want to throw caution to the wind and attack with everything he’s got.</p>\n\t<p>A Wild Attack adds +2 to the character’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} or \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing) attacks and resulting damage rolls for the turn, \n\t\tbut he is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Vulnerable} until the end of his <em>next</em> turn (not this one).</p>\n\t<p>Wild Attacks can be used with multiple attacks, such as from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Actions} or \n\t\tthe @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Frenzy]{Frenzy} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Sweep]{Sweep} Edges. \n\t\tIt can't be combined with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Desperate Attack]{Desperate Attack}.</p>\n\n\n\t<h2>Withdrawing From Melee</h2>\n\n\t<p>Whenever a character retreats from melee, all adjacent non-@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} \n\t\tand non-@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned} opponents get an immediate Free Attack \n\t\t(see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Attacks]{Free Attacks}</strong>).</p>\n\n\t<blockquote>\n\t\t<em><strong>Example:</strong></em> \n\t\tOur druid is surrounded by three bandits. She must get to a wounded sorcerer. She takes the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Defend]{Defend} option \n\t\t(increasing her @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} by +4) and backs away from the bandits. \n\t\tAll three of her opponents get a Free Attack, at +2 for Ganging Up. Fortunately, the druid’s Parry bonus fends them off and she makes her way to her injured friend.\n\t</blockquote>\n\t\t\t\n\t<br />\n\t\n\t<div>\n\t\t<img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/gazetteer-cover.webp\" />\n\t</div>\n\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_tl96ca99gn","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Co4JCVUhhhKP7AzB"}}}
{"_id":"G4s4UvoLBfVFUcn5","name":"Aim","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Aim</h2>\n\t\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} rolls assume a character is moving about, dodging attacks, and keeping an eye on the chaos around her. \n\t\t\tIf she focuses her attention and aims, she can make a much more accurate shot.</p>\n\t\t\n\t\t<p>If a character spends her entire turn Aiming a ranged weapon at a particular target or spot (GM's call) and takes no other actions, <em>on her next turn</em> \n\t\t\tshe may ignore up to 4 points of\"@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range}, \n\t\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover %26 Obstacles]{Cover}, \n\t\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Called Shots]{Called Shot}, \n\t\t\tor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size %26 Scale]{Scale} penalties; or add +2 to her roll. \n\t\t\tHer attack must be used on the first action of her next turn or the bonus is lost.</p>\n\n\t\t<p>The shooter must be relatively stationary to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aim]{Aim}. \n\t\t\tShe can’t walk, run, ride a horse, or be constantly jostled.</p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.sUYNS218qHShciXd"}}}
{"_id":"GAiVziUexhsTgu49","name":"2 Crafting Magic Items","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Crafting Magic Items</h1>\n<p>Characters with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Artificer]{Artificer Edge} can imbue their powers into @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Arcane Devices]{arcane devices} for later use or give them to their allies. This ties up their own @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{Power Points}, however, and such creations are temporary.</p>\n<p>With enough time and resources, however, an artificer can create more permanent items of wonder, and best of all he doesn’t have to tie up his own Power Points in the process!</p>\n<h3>The Crafting Process</h3>\n<p>After each week spent Crafting, the artificer makes an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Occult]{Occult} roll for each item he’s working on. A success makes 500 gp worth of progress toward its completion, and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} makes 1,000 gp progress.</p>\n<p>If the roll is failed, no progress is made on that item but the crafter may try again the following week. With a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}, a mishap loses the creator 500 gp worth of progress!</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Ammunition:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Arrows]{Arrows}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Sling Stones]{sling stones}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Bolts]{bolts}, or other types of ammunition are enchanted in batches of 12 at a time. If it can be recovered, each projectile has a 50% chance of remaining intact once fired.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Requirements</h2>\n<img class=\"float-right\" style=\"shape-outside:url('https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/artificer-warforged.webp')\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/artificer-warforged.webp\" />\n<p>A character can create any of the items listed in this book if she has the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Artificer]{Artificer} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Craft Arcane Device]{Craft Arcane Device} edges, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{Downtime}, the item to be enchanted, access to a workshop, and any spells and materials listed in the item’s Craft entry.</p>\n<p><strong>The Item:</strong> Only items of quality craftsmanship are typically given permanent @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Enchantments]{enchantments}. Armor, shields, weapons, and other permanent items must be of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Masterwork]{masterwork} quality.</p>\n<p>Potions, scrolls, and wands have no additional cost, but other permanent items should be exceptional examples of their type, and cost 50% more than usual.</p>\n<p><strong>Requirements:</strong> The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Artificer]{artificer} must have any powers and materials listed in the item’s Craft entry. Materials are precious gems, metals, powders, oils, or other rare components represented by the listed gold value listed (typically half the item’s value if purchased from others).</p>\n<p><strong>Workshop:</strong> A simple workshop allows a crafter to work on a single item at a time. A standard workshop allows him to work on two, and a grand workshop allows the creation of up to three items at a time.</p>\n<h2 class=\"example\">Example: Lini's Gift</h2>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Lini]{Lini} the druid wants to craft @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Slippers of Spider Climbing]{slippers of spider climbing} for @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Merisiel]{Merisiel} the rogue. She has access to a standard workshop and can create two things at once, so she decides to make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Potion of Major Healing]{Potion of Major Healing} at the same time.</p>\n<p>The slippers have a Craft cost of 2,400. The potion’s crafting cost is 150. Lini has @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker} (a requirement for the slippers) and gathers 2,550 gp worth of other materials.</p>\n<p>After a week’s work, she rolls and gets a success. That’s 500 gp worth of progress toward their creation. Now she rolls for the potion of <em>healing</em>. She’s successful, and since its cost is less than 500 gp, it’s finished and ready to use.</p>\n<p>Lini continues on the slippers the next week and gets a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} on her roll. That’s a total of 1,500 gp progress. The third and fourth weeks she gets another success, giving her another 1,000 gp worth of progress. The slippers are finished and she gifts them to her friend— who she warns only to use them for the good of the Pathfinder Society!</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_xadnq2n2oe8","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.lVlGOrgxiDCVD6Oe"},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"620eXVOwguVjobRa\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"swpf-core-rules.swpf-actors\",\"actorID\":\"wZeXxHyFw76ifngC\",\"name\":\" Lini\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"wZeXxHyFw76ifngC\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"wZeXxHyFw76ifngC\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]},{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"swpf-core-rules.swpf-actors\",\"actorID\":\"dlwHvpr15wGGflKC\",\"name\":\" Merisiel\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"dlwHvpr15wGGflKC\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"dlwHvpr15wGGflKC\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"}}}
{"_id":"GS91WjXaNV1B0dna","name":"Armor Piercing","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Armor Piercing</h2>\n    <p>The attack is focused to defeat armor or seeks out a foe’s exposed areas.\n        Each Power Point spent grants the power \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor Piercing (AP)]{AP} 2 to a\n        max­imum of AP 6.</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{See full Powers rules here}</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{See full Powers list here}</p>\n&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Updated upstream\n    <p>@Compendium[@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n=======\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Stashed changes\n    \n    \n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.l6zsUc3B9bmIT4Hq"}}}
{"_id":"GframHMiA57wfqbr","name":"Losing Glory","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Losing Glory</h1>\n<p>Glory can be won, bit can also be lost. In general, a hero must deliberately act in a less than heroic way to suffer a Glory penalty. Everyone makes mistakes and crosses the line at some point, but minor misdemeanors should be ignored unless the character makes a habit of such actions.</p>\n<p>Sample penalties are included below</p>\n<table class=\"table value-table\" style=\"width:80%\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Glory Penalties</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Glory</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Event</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Special</td>\n<td>Slaying a good and just powerful NPC.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–1 to –10</td>\n<td>Caught committing a crime</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–3</td>\n<td>Cowardice or leaving a comrade behind</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–3</td>\n<td>Refusing orders</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–10</td>\n<td>Breaking an oath</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>NEGATIVE GLORY</h2>\n<p>Heroes with negative Glory do not earn rewards, but they do garner drawbacks.</p>\n<h3>WANTED</h3>\n<p>When a hero reaches –20 Glory, he gains the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Wanted]{Wanted} (Minor) Hindrance. At –40, this changes to the Major version.</p>\n<p>Generally, the Minor Hindrance extends to a single realm, usually the one where the Glory penalty was incurred. The Major version, on the other hand, covers pretty much all the civilized, settled domains of Khorvaire. A hero who gains enough Glory to rise above the rating at which he gained this Hindrance, doesn’t lose the Hindrance. He may have performed some heroic deeds, but he is still a wanted man.</p>\n<h3>ENEMY</h3>\n<p>At –10 Glory, the hero acquires the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} (Minor) Hindrance. At –30 (or lower), the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} becomes a Major Hindrance.</p>\n<p>The exact nature of the enemy depends on the villain’s deeds. </p>\n<p>Again, it doesn’t matter if the hero’s Glory rises above the level at which he gained his foe—his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} doesn’t give up his vendetta.</p>\n<p>Should the hero gain a Major @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} while his Minor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} is still at large, the foe simply steps up his campaign against the character. Otherwise, the hero gains a new enemy.</p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"HJvBPRZpySo8PeF4","name":"Desperate Attack","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Desperate Attack</h2>\n\n\t<p>Determined to land a blow, the warrior unleashes a frantic attack, focusing on hitting his target at the expense of damage. \n\t\tHe adds +2 or +4 to any Fighting roll and subtracts a like amount from damage if he hits. \n\t\tThis can be determined per attack (before rolling), and can't be combined with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Attack]{Wild Attack}.</p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.wulQRkRhT1bQL7Da"}}}
{"_id":"HZfE01HPHYWvGB23","name":"5 Edges","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n\t\t\t<h1 class=\"wide\">Edges</h1>\n\n\t\t\t<p>The following are dozens of Edges for <cite>Savage Eberron</cite>. Edges are grouped by type to help during character creation, and you’ll find a handy summary of each @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{here}.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Unless an Edge specifically says otherwise, it may only be selected once.</p>\n\t\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Below each Edge is the minimum <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Rank}</strong> required to take it along with any other prerequisites such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{attributes}, skills, or other Edges.</p>\n\t\t\t\n<h2>Background Edges</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<p>These Edges are typically advantages a character is born with, learns from prolonged and extensive training, or gains after exposure to certain events.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Players can choose these Edges after character creation with a little rationalization. An individual might choose the Attractive Edge, for example, by cleaning himself up, getting a makeover, and generally paying more attention to physical appearance. Characters might also be able to gain an Arcane Background by finding and studying a spellbook or training with another arcane type in their party during downtime between adventures.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Alertness</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Alertness]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Not much gets by this hero. Very observant and perceptive, she adds +2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} rolls to hear, see, or otherwise sense the world around them.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Ambidextrous</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Ambidextrous]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Agility d8+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Your warrior is equally deft with both hands. She ignores the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Off-Hand Attacks]{Off-Hand}</strong> penalty.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>If holding a weapon in each hand, she may stack Parry bonuses (if any) from both weapons.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Arcane Background (Magic or Miracles)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Magic)]{Link to Magic Journal Entry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Miracles)]{Link to Miracles Journal Entry}</p>\n<p></p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Exposure to strange energies, studies at a magical school, or gifts from divine or spiritual entities sometimes grant champions their own powers and abilities. </p>\n\t\t\t<p>If you want to play a bard, cleric, druid, sorcerer, or wizard based on the original Pathfinder game system's character classes, see the Class Edges further below. If you want to make your own custom mage or priest, use the rules here:</p>\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Arcane Background (Magic):</strong> Mages use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} as their arcane skill, and have Armor Interference (Light) (meaning they subtract 4 from their Spellcasting rolls and from their agility and agility-based skill rolls if using medium or heavy armor or shields). On taking this Edge, you get three starting powers and 10 Power Points. </p>\n\t\t\t<p>A mage’s <strong>available powers are:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{arcane protection}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Baleful Polymorph]{baleful polymorph}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{banish}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{barrier}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{beast friend}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{blast}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{blind}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost/lower trait}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{burrow}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{burst}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{confusion}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{conjure item}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{curse}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{damage field}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{darksight}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{deflection}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{detect/conceal arcana}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{disguise}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{dispel}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{divination}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Drain Power Points]{drain power points}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{elemental manipulation}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{empathy}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{environmental protection}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{farsight}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{fear}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{fly}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{growth/shrink}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{havoc}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{illusion}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{intangibility}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{invisibility}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light / Darkness]{light/darkness}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{locate}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{mind link}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{mind reading}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{mind wipe}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{object reading}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Plane Shift]{plane shift}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{puppet}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{relief}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Scrying]{scrying}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{shape change}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{sloth/speed}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{slumber}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{sound/silence}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{speak language}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{stun}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{summon ally}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{telekinesis}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{teleport}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Time Stop]{time stop}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{wall walker}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{warrior's gift}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wish]{wish}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{zombie}.</em></p>\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Arcane Background (Miracles):</strong> Priests use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} as their arcane skill and must choose a <strong>Domain</strong> (see Cleric). When they take this Edge, they get 10 Power Points, any three powers listed under the cleric's available powers list or their Domain. They also gain @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Vow]{Vow} (Major) to serve their deity.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Arcane Resistance</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Resistance]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Spirit d8+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Magic and the supernatural hold little sway with this individual. Whether by nature, heritage, or training the character is particularly resistant to magic and other supernatural energies.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Enemy arcane abilities targeting the hero suffer a −2 penalty and magical damage is reduced by 2 as well. This includes magical bonuses granted to weapons, such as the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em> power or the Damaging @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Enchantments]{enchantment}.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Improved Arcane Resistance</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Improved Arcane Resistance]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Arcane Resistance</p>\n\t\t\t<p>As above, but the penalty to the arcane skill roll and damage are increased to 4.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Aristocrat</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Aristocrat]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice</p>\n\t\t\t<p>This individual was born into privilege or came into it later in life. She may or may not have money, but she still walks in the elite social circles of the world.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Aristocrats add +2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} when <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Networking]{Networking}</strong> with the local elite, nobles, or other aristocrats. They also add +2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} rolls made to know the etiquette of the upper class, recognize family trees or heraldry, or recall gossip concerning others of their station.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Attractive</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Attractive]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Vigor d6+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>It’s no secret people are more willing to help those they find physically attractive. Your character adds +1 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} rolls if the target is attracted to his general type (gender, sex, species, etc.).</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Very Attractive</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Very Attractive]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Novice, Attractive</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Your hero is drop-dead gorgeous. He increases his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} bonus to +2.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Brave</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Brave]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Spirit d6+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Those with this Edge have learned to master their fear, or have dealt with so many horrors they’ve become jaded. These valiant explorers add +2 to Fear checks and subtract 2 from <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-tables.Fear]{Fear Table}</strong> results.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Brawny</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Brawny]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Strength d6+, Vigor d6+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Your bruiser is very large or very fit. Her Size increases by +1 (and therefore Toughness by 1) and she treats her Strength as one die type higher when determining <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Encumbrance]{Encumbrance}</strong>  and <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Minimum Strength]{Minimum Strength}</strong> to use armor, weapons, and equipment without a penalty.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Brawny can’t increase a character’s Size above +3, and it has no effect on Armor Interference or Armor Restriction.</p>\n\t\t\t<img class=\"float-right\" style=\"shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/alain.webp')\" src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/alain.webp\" />\n\t\t\t<h3>Brute</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Brute]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Strength d6+, Vigor d6+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Brutes focus on core strength and fitness over coordination and flexibility. They treat @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} as linked to Strength instead of Agility for purposes of Advancement. The character may also resist Athletics Tests with Strength if he chooses.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Finally, Brutes increase the Short Range of any thrown item by +1. Double that for the adjusted Medium Range, and double again for Long Range. If a thrown item’s Range is 3/6/12, for example, a Brute’s Range is 4/8/16.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Charismatic</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Charismatic]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Spirit d8+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Your hero is likable for some reason. She may be trustworthy or kind, or might just exude confidence and goodwill. You get one free reroll on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} rolls.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Elan</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Elan]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Spirit d8+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Elan means energy or spirit. Those who have it rise to the occasion when the going gets toughest. When you spend a Benny to reroll a Trait, add +2 to the total. The bonus applies only when rerolling. It doesn’t apply to damage rolls (since they’re not Trait rolls), nor does it apply to Soak rolls unless you’re using <em>another</em> Benny to reroll the Vigor check.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Fame</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Fame]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Your character is a minor celebrity of some sort. She might be a popular bard in a small fiefdom, a warrior who saved the town, or a beloved wizard who entertains children.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>She makes double the normal fee when performing for pay (see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance}</strong>). She can also use her celebrity to add +1 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} rolls if a target is friendly and knows who she is (a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} roll modified by how likely the individual is to know the celebrity).</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The downside of Fame is that the individual is often recognized, others frequently want something from her, she may be followed by fans or admirers, or she may not be able to shirk obligations, performances, or other duties without causing trouble for herself.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<img class=\"float-left\" style=\"shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/bard2.webp')\" src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/bard2.webp\" />\n\t\t\t<h3>Famous</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Famous]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Seasoned, Fame</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Your hero is truly famous. She’s well-known in a large circle such as a city, kingdom, or a popular traveling road show. She makes 5× the normal fee when performing and adds +2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} rolls when influencing friendly individuals who know who she is.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The price is higher for the truly Famous, too, with more demands on her time, obligations, rivals, scandals, and an inability to operate in crowds without being recognized.</p>\n\t\t\t<p> </p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Fast Healer</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Fast Healer]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Vigor d8+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Those with this blessing add +2 to Vigor rolls for natural healing, and check every three days instead of five (see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing}</strong>).</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Fleet-Footed</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Fleet-Footed]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Agility d6+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The hero’s Pace is increased by +2 and his running die increases one step (from d6 to d8, for example).</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Linguist</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Linguist]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Smarts d6+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>This world-traveler has an ear for languages. Characters know a number of languages equal to half their Smarts die type automatically.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Those taking this Edge know a number of languages equal to her Smarts die type instead. See the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Common Languages}</strong> table.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Luck</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Luck]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The adventurer seems to be blessed by fate, karma, the gods, or whatever external forces he believes in (or believe in him!).</p>\n\t\t\t<p>He draws one extra Benny at the beginning of each game session, allowing him to succeed at important tasks more often than most, and survive incredible dangers.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Great Luck</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Great Luck]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Luck</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The player draws two extra Bennies instead of one at the start of each session.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Quick</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Quick]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Agility d8+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Quick characters have lightning-fast reflexes and a cool head. Whenever you are dealt an Action Card of Five or lower, you may discard it and draw again until you get a card higher than Five.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Characters with both the Level Headed and Quick Edges first draw their additional card and choose which to take. If that card is a Five or less, the Quick Edge may be used to draw a replacement until it’s Six or higher.</p>\n\t\t\t\n<h2>Class Edges</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<p>Every player character in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> gets a Class Edge for free (or a Background or Professional Edge if you prefer not to have a Class Edge). This helps your adventurer capture the feel of the original Pathfinder system’s character classes.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Class Edges are also the foundation for higher Rank advanced Edges and exciting new <strong>Prestige Edges</strong> further down. Class Edges are usually taken at character creation, as most reflect years of training and specialization. You can take them later (or “multi-class”) if you like, but work with your GM to explain how your character suddenly acquires such impressive abilities later in her career.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>You’ll find eleven core Class Edges as well as advanced Edges for higher Ranks below. Look for additional Class Edges in future modules.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Multi-Classing</h3>\n\t\t\t<p>Characters in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> can take an additional core Class Edge or new core Prestige Edge, but only once each Rank.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>If a character takes a new Arcane Background, she gets the new powers, and a d4 in its arcane skill if she doesn’t already have it. If she already has an Arcane Background or Mystic Powers, she doesn’t get new Power Points, she must share her existing pool with all her Arcane Backgrounds and Mystic Powers. Otherwise, she also gets the Power Points listed for the Edge.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Class Edge abilities apply only to spells provided by that class.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3>Iconic Characters</h3>\n\t\t\t<p>Each Class Edge on the following sections includes an example “Iconic” character. These named individuals feature in Pathfinder’s lore, and you might find them in Paizo’s fiction, games, and other material.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The Iconics are examples of how you <em>might</em> build each class. Each has a full set of Advances you can use if you want to play these heroes along their journey to legendary status. Note: the advances show how <em>these individuals</em> advanced. When you build <em>your</em> character you may choose differently. </p>\n<article class=\"class-container\">\n\t<h1 class=\"wide\">Barbarian</h1>\n\t<h3>Barbarian</h3>\n\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Barbarian]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements</span>: Novice, Strength d6+, Vigor d6+</p>\n\t<p>For some, there is only rage. In the ways of their people, in the fury of their passion, in the howl of battle, these brutal souls swear by the creed of conflict. Battle possessed, these savage warriors disdain the life of the professional guard or soldier. They seek to fight for the sake of the act itself. </p>\n\t<p>Known as barbarians, these warmongers know little of tactics, preparation, or the rules of warfare. For them, only the moment exists. They embrace the possibility that the next battle might hold their death. Within the barbarian’s heart beats the primal spirit of struggle. Those who face their rage, beware.</p>\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Armor Restriction</span> <strong>(Medium):</strong> A barbarian’s fighting style requires great freedom of movement. They subtract 4 from Agility and Agility-based skill rolls when wearing heavy armor or using a heavy shield.</li>\n\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Fast:</span> Barbarians are fast and durable runners. They increase their base Pace by +2. This doesn’t affect their running die, but does stack with Edges like Fleet-Footed or ancestral modifiers.</li>\n\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Rage:</span> Barbarians can call upon inner reserves of strength and ferocity in desperate circumstances. As a limited free action, a barbarian may “rage” voluntarily. If she’s Shaken or Wounded, she must make a Smarts roll or rage whether she wants to or not.<br />Rage lasts five rounds. After the barbarian’s fifth turn raging, she takes a level of Fatigue that can only be recovered with an hour’s rest (generally no walking, riding, etc). <br />An @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Exhausted} barbarian who rages is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} afterward. See @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{here} for more on Fatigue.</li>\n\t</ul>\t\t\n\t<p>While raging, a barbarian gains the following abilities: </p>\n\t    <ul class=\"bullet\">\n\t\t<li><strong>Fury:</strong> Her Strength increases a die type  (ignoring her usual maximum) and every attack must be a <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Attack]{Wild Attack}</strong>. She can’t use any skill or ability that requires more than a few seconds of concentration (GM’s call). </li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Enraged:</strong> She ignores two points of Wound penalties and all Fatigue penalties (this stacks with any other abilities that reduce those penalties.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Reckless Abandon:</strong> If a barbarian rolls a Critical Failure on an attack roll while raging, she hits a random target within range of her attack (<em>not</em> the intended target), friend or foe. If there are no applicable targets, she injures herself and suffers @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Bumps &amp; Bruises}.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t<h3 class=\"item\">Powerful Blow</h3>\n\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Powerful Blow]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Seasoned, Barbarian</p>\n\t<p>The barbarian's savage @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Attack]{Wild Attacks} cause +4 damage instead of +2.</p>\n\t<h3 class=\"item\">Intimidating Glare</h3>\n\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Intimidating Glare]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Veteran, Barbarian</p>\n\t<p>The fearsome and baleful gaze of the wild barbarian unsettles all but the stoutest souls.</p>\n\t<p>When the barbarian’s Action Card is a Jack or higher, she may make an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} roll as a limited free action. She also ignores the usual advice on Repetition (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Tests}). She may issue threats and insults if she wants, but her terrible glare is often enough to send shivers down her foes' spines.</p>\n\t<h3 class=\"item\">Strength Surge</h3>\n\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Strength Surge]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Heroic, Barbarian</p>\n\t<p>The barbarian’s rage knows no bounds! Her Strength increases two die types when raging instead of just one. This can exceed the character’s ancestral limit.</p>\n\n\t<h2 class=\"iconic-path\">Amiri <span class=\"reduced\">(Novice, Iconic Path Barbarian)</span></h2>\n\t<div>\n\t\t<p>Fiery of heart and fierce in battle, @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Amiri]{Amiri} demands respect. Those who offend the barbarian soon learn the wrath of her blood rage. She wields an over-sized bastard sword, her most-prized possession, won from a frost giant years ago. Other than this, Amiri shows no interest in material belongings. She spends freely whenever chance provides, embracing life in the moment and expecting a noble death with the dawn of every day.</p>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div>\n\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Ancestry:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Human]{Human} (Adaptable)</p>\n\t</div>\n\t<div class=\"statblock\">\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"red-label\">Attributes</span>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Agility d8</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Smarts d4</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Spirit d6</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Strength d10</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Vigor d8</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"red-label\">Derived</span>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Parry: 6</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Toughness: 8 (2)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Pace: 8</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Bennies: 3</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"red-label\">Hindrances:</span> Bloodthirsty, Death Wish, Poverty</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"red-label\">Edges:</span> Barbarian, Brute</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"red-label\">Languages:</span> Common, Goblin, Halfling</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div>\n\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Skills:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} d4, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} d8, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} d4, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding} d4, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} d4, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival} d4</p>\n\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Gear:</span> Bastard Sword (Str+d8, AP 1), short bow (Range 12/24/48, Damage 2d6), 20 arrows, handaxe (Str+d6), studded leather tunic and leggings (+2), adventurer’s kit, 9 gp.</p>\n\t</div>\n\t<div style=\"width:50%;float:left\">\n\t\t<h2>Advancement</h2>\n\t\t<table class=\"advencement\">\n\t\t\t<tbody><tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>1 –</strong> Trademark Weapon (Bastard Sword)\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>2 –</strong> Sweep\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>3 –</strong> Vigor d10\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr class=\"advanced\">\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>S –</strong> Powerful Blow\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>5 –</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} d10\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>6 </strong><strong>–</strong> Menacing\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>7 –</strong> Counterattack\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr class=\"advanced\">\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>V –</strong> Intimidating Glare\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>9 –</strong> Trademark Weapon (Imp)\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>10 –</strong> Sweep (Imp)\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>11 –</strong> Giant Killer\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr class=\"advanced\">\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>H –</strong> Strength Surge\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>13 –</strong> Counterattack (Imp)\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>14 –</strong> Fighting d12\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>15 </strong><strong>–</strong> No Mercy\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr class=\"advanced\">\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>L –</strong> Vigor d12\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>17 –</strong> Tough as Nails\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>18 –</strong> Tougher than Nails\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>19 –</strong> Weapon Master\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>20 –</strong> Master of Arms\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t</tbody></table>\n\t\t\t<p> </p>\n\t</div>\n\t<div style=\"float:right;width:50%\">\n\t\t<img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/barbarian-pawn.webp\" />\n\t</div>\n\n</article>\n<article class=\"class-container\">\n\t\t\t<h1 class=\"wide\" style=\"clear:both\">Bard</h1>\n\t\t\t<h3>Bard</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Bard]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Novice, Spirit d6+, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} d6+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>The bards of Eberron bring epic tales of heroism and tragedy to the people. Many are renowned far and wide for their talents, but few realize how crucial they are to parties of brave adventurers. They bolster their allies in dire circumstances, beguile their enemies, and often battle evil with a sword in one hand and a lute in the other.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Bards cast spells by singing, reciting poetry, or reciting epic tales. They are usually erudite individuals, traveling the land to learn bawdy songs, great histories, and epic legends.</p>\n\t\t\t<p>Allies must be able to hear the bard to benefit from his various abilities.</p>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Arcane Background</span> <strong>(Bard):</strong> Bards use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} as their arcane skill. They have 3 starting powers and 10 Power Points.<br /><strong>Available Powers:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane protection}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{banish}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{barrier}</em>,@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{beast friend},<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost/lower trait}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{confusion}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{deflection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{detect/conceal arcana}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{conjure item}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{dispel}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{divination}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Drain Power Points]{drain power points}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{empathy}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{fear}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{illusion}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{mind link}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{mind reading}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{object reading}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{puppet}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{sloth/speed}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{slumber}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{sound/silence}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{speak language}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{stun}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{summon ally}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{teleport}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{warrior's gift}</em>.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Armor Interference</span> <strong>(Light):</strong> Bulky armor interferes with a bard’s grace and dexterity. They subtract 4 from their Performance rolls and from their Agility and Agility-based skill rolls if using medium or heavy armor or shields.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Sharp Tongued:</span> Bards may use Performance as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Taunt]{Taunt} to Test a foe. They may also ignore the Repetition advice given under @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Tests}, as long as they recite different verses, stanzas, lyrics, etc. Bards may also substitute Performance for Taunt to meet Edge Requirements.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t<h3 class=\"item\">Inspire Heroics</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Inspire Heroics]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Seasoned, Bard</p>\n<p>Bards inspire their comrades with epic tales of valor and bravery. Once during any combat encounter (GM’s call), the bard can spend a Benny to gain five Inspiration tokens. This is a limited free action.</p>\n<p>For the remainder of the encounter, the bard may give these tokens to anyone within a Range of Smarts except himself. This may be done at any time (as long as the bard is conscious). The recipient must use the token immediately— it cannot be saved.</p>\n<p>Each Inspiration token allows a character to reroll a Trait or damage roll. A Trait or damage roll may only benefit from a single Inspiration Token, even if there are multiple bards present. Further rerolls require spending a Benny or a special ability.</p>\n<p>Inspiration tokens aren’t Bennies, don’t trigger Edges that use Bennies (such as Elan), and can’t be used as such in any other way such as drawing new Action Cards or Soaking Wounds.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3 class=\"item\">Countersong</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Countersong]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Veteran, Bard</p>\n<p>The bard and all allies within 5” (10 yards) get a free reroll when opposing enemy spell effects or attempting to recover from them. This includes rolls to recover from any magical effect as <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{blind}</em>,<em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{lower trait}, </em>or<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{stun}. </em>Countersong doesn’t help targets resist or recover from natural effects.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3 class=\"item\">Dirge of Doom</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Dirge of Doom]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Heroic, Bard</p>\n<p>This baleful song builds dread in the bard’s foes. At his discretion, any enemy who spends a Benny to Soak or reroll a Trait or damage roll within 10” (20 yards) and line of sight of the bard subtracts 2 from the final total.</p>\n\n<h2 class=\"iconic-path\">Lem <span class=\"reduced\">(Novice, Iconic Path Bard)</span></h2>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Lem]{Lem} possesses a delightful sense of humor, along with a boundless optimism, despite his childhood as a slave in Cheliax. Constantly humming tunes from lore or of his own invention, the impulsive halfling is quick to intervene whenever he witnesses cruelty.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Ancestry:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Halfling]{Halfling} (Agile, Keen Senses, Lucky, Reduced Pace, Size −1, Sure-Footed)</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\n\t<div class=\"statblock\">\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"red-label\">Attributes</span>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Agility d8</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Smarts d6</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Spirit d8</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Strength d6</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Vigor d6</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"red-label\">Derived</span>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Parry: 5</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Toughness: 6 (2)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Pace: 5 (d4)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Bennies: 4</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"red-label\">Hindrances:</span> Impulsive, Mild Mannered, Quirk (Hums)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"red-label\">Edges:</span> Bard, Charismatic, Luck</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"red-label\">Languages:</span> Common, Elven, Gnome, Halfling</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Skills:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Academics]{Academics} d4, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Occult]{Occult} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} d8, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} d4</p>\n\t\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">POWERS:</span> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{confusion}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{empathy}.</em></p>\n\t\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Gear:</span> Dagger (Str+d4), sling (Range 4/8/16, Damage Str+d4, uses Athletics), 20 stones, entertainer’s outfit, soft leather tunic and leggings (+2), adventurer’s kit, flute, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Potion of Minor Healing]{potion of minor healing}, vial of antitoxin, 5x tinder twigs, 18 gp. </p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"width:50%;float:left\">\n<h2>Advancement</h2>\n\t<table>\n\t<tbody><tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>1 –</strong> Spirit d10\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>2 –</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} d10, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} d8\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>3 –</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} d8, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} d8\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>S –</strong> Inspire Heroics\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>5 –</strong> Power Points (15 total)\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>6 </strong><strong>–</strong> New Powers: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{slumber}</em>\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>7 –</strong> Rabble-Rouser\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>V –</strong> Countersong\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>9 –</strong> Humiliate\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>10 –</strong> New Powers: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{puppet}</em>\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>11 –</strong> Smarts d8\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>H –</strong> Dirge of Doom\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>13 –</strong> Performance d12\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>14 –</strong> Power Points (20 total)\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>15 </strong><strong>–</strong> New Powers: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Drain Power Points]{Drain Power Points}, <br />@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{warrior's gift}</em>\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>L –</strong> Fighting d10\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>17 –</strong> Channeling\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>18 –</strong> Sidekick\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>19 –</strong> Professional (Performance d12+1)\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>20 –</strong> Expert (Performance d12 + 2)\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t</tbody></table>\n\t<p> </p>\n\t</div>\n\t<div style=\"float:right;width:50%\">\n<img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/bard.webp\" style=\"width:150%;height:auto;shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/bard.webp')\" />\n\t</div>\n</article>\n\n<article class=\"class-container\">\n\t\t\t<h1 class=\"wide\" style=\"clear:both\">Cleric</h1>\n\t\t\t<h3>Cleric</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Cleric]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Novice, Spirit d6+, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Occult]{Occult} d6+</p>\n\t\t\t<p>In faith and the miracles of the divine, many find a greater purpose. Called to serve powers beyond most mortal understanding, all priests provide for the spiritual needs of their people. More than mere preachers, clerics serve as emissaries of their gods. </p>\n\t\t\t<p>While clerics of different faiths share similar abilities, they are as different from one another as the divinities they serve. Some offer healing and redemption, others judge law and truth, and still others spread conflict and corruption.</p>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Arcane Background</span> <strong>(Cleric):</strong> Clerics use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} as their arcane skill. On taking this Edge, a character gains 10 Power Points and must choose a Domain for the deity she serves from the list below. All clerics start with the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> power and two other powers from their available powers.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Available Powers:</span> Clerics have access to powers from the list below plus the powers listed  for their chosen Domain: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{banish}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost/lower trait}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{conjure item}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{darksight}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{dispel}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{divination}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{empathy}</em><em>, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light / Darkness]{light/darkness}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{relief}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Resurrection]{resurrection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sanctuary]{sanctuary}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{slumber}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em>,<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{sound/silence}</em>. </li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Channel Energy:</span> Clerics can cast the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> power at a Range of Spirit rather than Touch. Their <em>healing</em> power also has the Additional Recipients Power Modifier, allowing them to heal nearby allies at the cost of one extra Power Point each.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Vow</span> <strong>(Major):</strong> Clerics have a major vow to serve their deity. Those who wish to draw energy from divine sources must uphold the principles of their Domain. <br />If the cleric violates their deity's trust  (GM's call) the cleric subtracts 2 from Faith rolls for a week. Truly sacrilegious acts might rob her of her powers entirely until she atones in some way.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t<h3 class=\"item\">Destroy Undead</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Destroy Undead]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Seasoned, Cleric</p>\n<p>As an action, the cleric spends 2 Power Points to channel positive energy in a Medium Blast Template centered on herself. Every undead creature within the template must make a Spirit roll or take a Wound (this may be Soaked as usual).</p>\n\t\t\n\t\t\t<h3 class=\"item\" style=\"clear:both\">Favored powers (Cleric)</h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t    <img class=\"float-right\" src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/Mitre.webp\" />\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Favored Powers (Cleric)]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Veteran, Cleric</p>\n<p>The cleric has great familiarity with some of her core powers and can cast them quickly and easily. As a limited free action she may ignore up to two points of <em>any</em> penalties (Multi-Action, Wounds, Fatigue, etc.) when casting <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sanctuary]{sanctuary},</em><em> </em>or<em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}.</em></p>\n<p>This Edge doesn’t give her those powers— they must be taken separately.</p>\n\t\t\t<h3 class=\"item\">Divine Mastery</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Divine Mastery]{Link to Journal Entry}</p>\t\t\t\n<p><span class=\"red-label\">Requirements:</span> Heroic, Cleric</p>\n<p>Deities reward their clerics with additional power and energy to power their miracles. A cleric who takes this Edge gains access to all her powers’ @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{Epic Power Modifiers}.</p>\n\n<h2 class=\"iconic-path\">Kyra <span class=\"reduced\">(Novice, Iconic Path Cleric)</span></h2>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Kyra]{Kyra}’s vow to Sarenrae guides her path. With each new day, the cleric renews her oath to fight evil, heal the sick, and protect the innocent. Kyra takes great pride in her faith, her divine powers, and her prowess with a scimitar— all in service to her goddess. </p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Ancestry:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Human]{Human} (Adaptable)</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"statblock\">\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"red-label\">Attributes</span>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Agility d6</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Smarts d8</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Spirit d8</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Strength d6</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Vigor d6</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"red-label\">Derived</span>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Parry: 5</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Toughness: 7 (2)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Pace: 6</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Bennies: 3</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"red-label\">Hindrances:</span> Code of Honor, Heroic, Vow (Major—serve Sarenrae)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"red-label\">Edges:</span> Cleric (Good), Healer</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"red-label\">Languages:</span> Celestial, Common, Elven, Halfling, Kelish</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Skills:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} d4, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} d4, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} d8, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Occult]{Occult} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding} d4, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} d4</p>\n\t\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">POWERS:</span> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{Healing}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em></p>\n\t\t\t<p><span class=\"red-label\">Gear:</span> Scimitar (Str+d6), sling (Range 4/8/16, Damage Str+d4, uses Athletics), 20 stones, cleric’s vestments, leather tunic, helm, and leggings (+2), adventurer’s kit, healer’s kit, silver holy symbol, holy water, 29 gp.</p>\n\t\t</div>\t\n<div style=\"width:50%;float:left\">\n<h2>Advancement</h2>\n\t<table>\n\t<tbody><tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>1 –</strong> New Powers: <em>Boost/lower Tra</em><em>it, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{relief}</em>\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>2 –</strong> Strength d8\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>3 –</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} d8, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Occult]{Occult} d8\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>S –</strong> Destroy Undead\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>5 –</strong> New Powers: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel},</em><em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sanctuary]{sanctuary}</em>\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>6 –</strong> Channeling\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>7 –</strong> Spirit d10\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>V –</strong> Favored Powers (Cleric)\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>9 –</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} d10, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} d8\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>10 –</strong> Holy Warrior\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>11 –</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} d8\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>H –</strong> Divine Mastery\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>13 –</strong> New Powers: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{sloth/speed}</em>\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>14 –</strong> Vigor d8\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>15 </strong><strong>–</strong> Power Points (15 total)\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>L –</strong> New Powers: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Resurrection]{resurrection}</em>\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>17 –</strong> Extraction\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>18 –</strong> Spirit d12\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>19 –</strong> Faith d12, Persuasion d10\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t<tr>\n\t<td class=\"left\">\n\t\t\t<strong>20 –</strong> Tough as Nails\n\t</td>\n\t</tr>\n\t</tbody></table>\n\t<p> </p>\n\t</div>\n\t<div style=\"float:right;width:50%\">\n\t<img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/cleric.webp\" />\n\t</div>\n</article>\n\t\n\t<h1 class=\"wide\" style=\"clear:both\">Deities &amp; Domains</h1>\n\t\t\t<p>A cleric must choose a Domain appropriate for the deity she serves. Each deity has different aspects representing the god's personality and a unique powers list. When choosing powers, a cleric can choose from this list in addition to the list of powers available to all clerics. </p>\n\t\t\t\n\t<h2>Domains</h2>\n\t\t\t<h3>Civilization <span style=\"font-size:80%\">(Community, Nobility)</span></h3>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Aspects:</span> Cities, towns, legacy, linage</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Deities:</span> Abadar, Erastil</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Available Powers:</span> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{disguise}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{environmental protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{locate}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{mind link}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{puppet}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{speak language},</em><em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{summon ally}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{warrior's gift}</em>.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t<h3>Death</h3>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Aspects:</span> Birth, fate, prophecy, repose</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Deities:</span> Norgorber, Pharasma, Urgathoa, Zon-Kuthon.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Available Powers:</span> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Curse]{curse}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{damage field}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Drain Power Points]{drain power points}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{fear}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{Mind Wipe}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Planar Binding]{planar binding}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{zombie}</em><em> </em>.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t<h3>Destruction <span style=\"font-size:80%\">(Evil, Madness)</span