{"_id":"JbDV9v0JyG1xoUIj","name":"Fear","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Fear</h1>\n  <p>\n    Cold dread seizes the heroine as she enters the lost tomb. A dragon emerges from the cave, belching smoke and fire at the adventurers who threaten its hoard. An investigator stumbles upon a scene of grisly, ritualistic carnage.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    These rules reflect the horror of these terrible situations upon your heroes’ psyches.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> When a creature has the @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Fear]{Fear} Special Ability, or the Game Master decides a situation is particularly disturbing.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>The Basics:</strong> Characters make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Spirit} roll when confronted by creatures or situations that cause Fear.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Fear Checks</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    The heroes make a Fear check (a Spirit roll as a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}) when they first spot a creature with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Fear]{Fear}Fear ability}.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Success means a character manages to overcome the situation and carry on. A failed Fear check means the unfortunate soul faces the consequences below, depending on whether the source of fear was grotesque or terrifying in nature:\n  </p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Nausea:</span> If the scene was grotesque or horrific, such as a grisly discovery or learning a secret \"Man Was Not Meant to Know,\" the character is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigued} from the mental strain. Critical Failure means the victim must roll on the <strong>Fear Table</strong> as well.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Terror:</span> A terrifying trigger, such as a monstrous creature or unknowable evil, is much more intense. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extras} are typically Panicked. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} must roll on the <strong>Fear Table</strong> (at +2 with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} on the Fear check). Roll a d20 and add the monster’s Fear penalty, if any, to the roll (a −2 adds +2 to the roll, for example).\n    </li>\n  </ul>\n  <h3>Becoming Jaded</h3>\n  <p>\n    After encountering a particular type of creature, the character doesn’t have to make Fear checks every time he sees another in that particular scenario.  If the party clears out an asylum full of spectral inmates, for example, they should only have to roll the first time they encounter them — not in every room. The Game Master might require a roll if the heroes encounter such horrors in a particularly different or frightening situation, however.\n  </p>\n  <table>\n    <colgroup>\n      <col></col>\n      <col></col>\n    </colgroup>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Fear Table</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">d20*</th>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">Effect</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>1–3</td>\n        <td>\n          \n          <strong>Adrenaline Surge:</strong> The hero’s \"fight\" response takes over. He acts as if he had a Joker this action!\n          \n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>4–6</td>\n        <td>\n          \n          <strong>Distracted:</strong> The hero is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted} until the end of his next turn.\n          \n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>7–9</td>\n        <td>\n          \n          <strong>Vulnerable:</strong> The target is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Vulnerable} until the end of his next turn.\n          \n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>10–12</td>\n        <td>\n          <strong>Shaken:</strong> The character is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}.\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>13</td>\n        <td>\n          \n          <strong>The Mark of Fear:</strong> The hero is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned} and suffers some cosmetic physical alteration — a white streak forms in his hair, his eyes twitch constantly, or some other minor physical alteration manifests.\n          \n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>14–15</td>\n        <td>\n          \n          <strong>Frightened:</strong> The character gains the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Hesitant]{Hesitant} Hindrance for the remainder of the encounter. If he already has it, he’s Panicked instead.\n          \n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>16–17</td>\n        <td>\n          \n          <strong>Panicked:</strong> The character immediately moves his full @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} plus running die away from the danger and is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}.\n          \n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>18–19</td>\n        <td>\n          \n          <strong>Minor Phobia:</strong> The character gains a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Phobia]{Minor Phobia} Hindrance somehow associated with the trauma.\n          \n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>20–21</td>\n        <td>\n          \n          <strong>Major Phobia:</strong> The character gains the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Phobia]{Major Phobia} Hindrance.\n          \n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>22+</td>\n        <td>\n          \n          <strong>Heart Attack:</strong> The hero is so overwhelmed with fear that his heart stutters. He must make an immediate @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Vigor} roll at –2. If successful, he’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned}. If he fails, he’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{dies} in 2d6 rounds. In the latter case, a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} roll at –4 saves his life, but he remains Incapacitated. He may be treated normally thereafter.\n          \n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <p>\n    <em>*Add the creature’s Fear penalty as a positive number to this roll.</em>\n  </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wz3EGUxCmSngGaR2"}}}
{"_id":"JhcJ7SaCSqAKA0Lu","name":"Range","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Range</h2>\n  <p></p><p>This lists the weapon’s Short, Medium, and Long Range. Extreme Range is up to 4×its Long Range. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Attacks]{Ranged Attacks}</strong> for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} (throwing) modifiers and more details.</p> <p></p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.CF9OGDpTTWEbAfsd"}}}
{"_id":"KSBHDrReNupapVpQ","name":"Using Magic Items","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Using Magic Items</h1>\n<p>Savage Eberron is a mythic place. Magic, both light and dark, flows through everything. The study and use of it has happpened by mystical beings such as dragons and Overlords, since the birth of the World ro present times. Much of this study and use has gone into pooling the energy into items of power.</p>\n<h3>Detecting Magic Items</h3>\n<p>In the magically-charged world of Eberron, any character with an Arcane Background can sense magical or divine auras within 5” (10 yards), unless they are magically concealed. This is an action.</p>\n<p>Detecting magic at a greater range or gaining specific information requires the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{detect arcana} spell, which can also be used to reveal items or beings protected by @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{conceal magic}. </p>\n<h3>Identifying Powers of Magical Items</h3>\n<p>There are three methods for determining what powers reside within an item. First, an arcane spellcaster can deduce the powers within an item simply through study. How long it takes is up to you, but a few minutes for a potion (given some basic testing equipment or a more dangerous taste test) and an hour for other items is usually enough.</p>\n<p>Second, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Identify (from detect arcana)}</em> can be used to identify a magic item's powers and how they work.</p>\n<p>Third, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{object reading}</em> will reveal the powers of any object the spellcaster is touching when he casts the spell. This would be seperate from the casting to determine if the item is in fact magical, and means a mage might need to cast it twice (once to detect magic and once to scrutinize).</p>\n<h3>Attuning</h3>\n<p>A hero who wishes to wield a magical item and benefit from it's power must first attune himself. Attunement can only happen after knowledge of the items powers and benefits has been discerned. The hero must then spend one hour with the item, and they are then attuned to it an may use it's powers.</p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size:1.125em\">Common Magic Item Rules</span></h3>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Active Powers are Actions:</strong> An item that requires a Trait roll is an action unless it says otherwise. Critical Failure means the user takes Fatigue (and loses a charge if the item has them).</li>\n<li><strong>Edges and Abilities:</strong> If an item grants an Edge or Monstrous Ability and the wielder already has that Edge, it grants the improved version (if there is one).</li>\n<li><strong>Minor and Major Powers:</strong> Some items grant minor or major powers as listed with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers Summary List]{Powers}. A <em>minor</em> power automatically activates with the effect of a standard success, and a <em>major</em> power activates with the effect of a raise (no Trait roll is made). Unless the item says otherwise, this is an action and the effect lasts for the power’s full Duration and cannot be maintained.</li>\n<li><strong>Stacking:</strong> If two sources would increase a Trait, use only the highest modifier (effects don’t stack). Increases to a Trait from a magic item’s effects don’t count for determining Trait Advancements. They do affect secondary statistics like Parry or Toughness, however.</li>\n<li><strong>Multiple Items:</strong> A character can only wear one magic item in each location (head, eyes, shoulders, neck, chest, belt, wrists, hands, feet). Putting on a second necklace or a second belt, for example, has no effect. The exception to this rule is rings. A character can wear two rings and benefit from both magical effects.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Enemies with Magic Items</h3>\n<p>Enemy characters and monsters equipped with enchanted and magical items have the bonuses conferred by those items built into their profiles.</p>\n<p>So an evil knight wearing plate armor enchanted with the Aegis enchantment, for example, might have a Toughness of 12(5), where the plate armor's bonus of +4 has already been increased by the Aegis enchantment's +1.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Articles on Magic Items</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic Items]{Using Magic Items}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Purchasing Magic Items]{Purchasing Magic Items}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Enchantments]{Enchantments}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crafting Magic Items]{Crafting Magic Items}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/artificer-infusing-armor.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2},"cf":{"id":"temp_xadnq2n2oe8","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"KSMBz6b82i7E4UsI","name":"Conviction","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Conviction</h2>\n<p>Conviction is a special award granted when a character experiences a great victory or catastrophic misfortune. If possible, use a themed token to note the award; maybe a Marshal’s Badge for <cite>Deadlands</cite>, a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Benny} of a different color, a toy doubloon for <cite>50 Fathoms</cite>, and so on.</p>\n<p>Conviction can be spent to add a d6 to all a character’s @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Trait} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Dealing Damage]{damage} totals until the beginning of her next @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Actions]{turn}. This die can @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Ace}, and its result is added to the final total.</p>\n<p>Conviction tokens aren’t @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Bennies} and can’t be used as such. They <em>are</em> kept between sessions, however.</p>\n<p>A character may maintain Conviction from round to round by spending a Benny (at the start of his turn, before it runs out). Once Conviction lapses, however, the effect ends.</p>\n<h3>Triumph And Tragedy</h3>\n<p>Conviction is granted for personal triumph and tragedy, drawing on a character’s entire background, including—but not limited to—his @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Edges]{Edges} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances}.</p>\n<p>Savage settings may also grant Conviction for certain world-specific actions or events.</p>\n<p><strong>Triumph:</strong> Characters gain Conviction when they overcome significant obstacles core to their overall goals and motivations. This might mean defeating powerful enemies, saving a true love, or overcoming some great mystery or problem.</p>\n<p>The victory should be an achievement over and above the usual. A vampire hunter in <cite>Rippers</cite> shouldn’t get Conviction every time he kills a vampire, for example, but he might when he wipes out an entire coven or slays a powerful master vamp­ire. A super hero might gain Conviction when she saves her true love from a death trap or the clutches of a powerful villain. She wouldn’t earn it just because her boyfriend is in a dangerous encounter.</p>\n<p><strong>Tragedy:</strong> Some of the most interesting heroes of fiction, film, and legend spend as much time battling their personal demons as they do fighting their foes. Eventually these same issues give them strength as they work through their grief or overcome obstacles to rise once more against the challenges they face.</p>\n<p>When a character experiences a significant personal loss or destructive event, and the GM feels it’s appropriate, he gains Conviction. The death of a loved one or close friend (including a party member he was close to), losing an important job, giving in to harmful character flaws and vices, being removed from a case or quest, or getting framed for a crime are all classic examples of heroic tragedy.</p>\n<p>These might happen in the course of the game, but players should also proactively suggest their own ideas to the Game Master. Consider your hero’s backstory and occasionally look for ways to do what your favorite authors do to their characters—torture them! Think about what’s important to them and threaten it or take it away. Most of the time this should be done as a quick narrative tale or a scene with a little interaction and roleplaying so as not to distract from the main campaign or the other players’ time, but occasionally it might inspire a side-trek or adventure to regain—or avenge!—whatever was lost.</p>\n<p>Note that earning Conviction for harmful behavior is motivation for players in a game to occasionally spotlight their character’s dark side. It is not an endorsement or rationalization of poor conduct in the real world.</p>\n<h2 class=\"blue-example\">Example: Red's Rage</h2>\n<p>Emily is Red, a fighter in a fantasy campaign. She has “anger management issues” but didn’t take the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Mean]{Mean} Hindrance because she’s had her problem under control for a year or so. But it’s a fun part of her backstory and Emily loves roleplaying constantly managing her character’s temper.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, Red and her constant ally Gabe failed in their last adventure. Emily decides this is a good time for Red to go on a rampage. She narrates a story about going into town and terrorizing everyone in sight with her surly attitude. During the course of a “bad day,” she breaks a window, turns over an apple cart, and even insults a friar’s mule!</p>\n<p>The GM loves Emily’s story and awards her a point of Conviction. In the game, Red is barred from the local tavern, has to pay for all the damage she caused, and is refused help by the friar (the town’s only healer!) until she performs some act of penance (a new quest!)</p>\n<p>More importantly, Emily told a story about her heroine’s tragic flaw—and has a point of Conviction to carry her through the next chapter of her quest.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.oTHp7O0sfn2BV0em"}}}
{"_id":"KYMG9nM38gK7QWeB","name":"3 Healing","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <div>\n    <h1 class=\"wide\">Healing</h1>\n  </div>\n  <p>\n    The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} skill is used\n    to remove @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{wounds}. Each\n    attempt requires 10 minutes per wound level of the patient. Subtract 1 from\n    Healing rolls without a basic healer's kit or similar supplies.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    A success removes one Wound, and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} removes two. \n    Failure means no Wounds are removed. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} <em>increases</em> the victim’s Wound level by one.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>The Golden Hour:</strong> A character may only attempt to heal\n    Wounds on a patient once within the hour they were sustained. Failing the\n    roll means the healer isn’t able to treat those particular injuries. A\n    <em>different</em> character may attempt a Healing roll on the same patient,\n    however.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Once the Wounds are over an hour old, only @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Healing]{natural healing} or\n    the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> power (using <em>greater healing</em>) can heal Wounds.\n  </p>\n  <p> \n    <strong>Bleeding Out:</strong> The Healing skill can also be used to stabilize someone who’s \n    <strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bleeding Out]{Bleeding Out} </strong>. Each attempt is an action, and if successful the victim is stabilized.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Incapacitation:</strong> Healing at least one Wound on an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} patient removes that state \n    (and restores consciousness if he was knocked out).\n  </p>\n  <div><img class=\"float-right\" style=\"shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/relief.webp')\" src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/relief.webp\" /></div>\n  <h2>Natural Healing</h2>\n  <p>\n    Wounded characters make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Vigor} roll every five days. Success recovers one\n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wound}, and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} recovers two.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    A  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} <em>increases</em> the victim’s Wound level by  one--\n    either from infection, blood loss, or aggravating the injuries. If this causes @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitation}, \n    don’t use the usual rules for taking damage. Instead, the victim lapses in and out of consciousness and makes a Vigor roll every 12 hours. \n    If the roll is failed, he expires. Success means he must roll again 12 hours later. With a raise he stabilizes and wakes. Allies may also attempt to stabilize the hero \n    as explained under <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bleeding Out]{Bleeding Out}</strong>.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Support:</strong> Don’t forget to use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support} when your party has\n    been beaten up a bit. Characters with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}, or other \n    skills can make Support rolls to help allies make their Vigor rolls to heal!\n  </p>\n\n  \n\n  <h2>Aftermath &amp; Extras</h2>\n  <p>\n    If it’s important to know what happens to Extras who were @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}\n    during a fight, make a  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Vigor} roll for each. Those who succeed survive and\n    must be cared for, taken prisoner, or released. This can present interesting\n    challenges for your heroes in the aftermath of savage combat!\n  </p>\n\n  <aside class=\"sidebar\">\n    <h2>The Golden Hour</h2>\n    <p>\n      Patients who survive their initial trauma have about an hour to survive\n      most life-threatening injuries. If they receive medical attention during\n      that time, they can generally be saved. The longer the wait, however, the\n      more likely the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds} are to be fatal.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      In <cite>Savage Eberron</cite>, we extend this concept to healing in\n      general. Besides reflecting the real-world concept, it also provides good\n      game balance and drama as the party has to decide whether to press on\n      despite their injuries.\n    </p>\n  </aside>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_tl96ca99gn","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.IsfyesPrLlFj9frZ"}}}
{"_id":"KotQOseBZ7sAWykR","name":"Mithral","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2 class=\"wide\">Mithral</h2>\n<p>A rare metal on Eberron, mithral is forged like steel but weighs much less. Mithral reduces the Minimum Strength of weapons, armor, and shields one die type (this stacks with the bonus from masterwork). Weapons and shields made primarily of mithral (GM's call) cost 100 times normal, while armor costs 10 times normal per piece.</p>\n<p>Mithral weapons count as silver for purposes of creatures with a silver @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Weakness]{Weakness}.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Special Materials]{See Special Materials here}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"KvpisyD5ypHVNIoy","name":"6 Advancement","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<div>\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Advancement</h1>\n</div>\n<p>One of the many great aspects of roleplaying games is advancing your character, watching her grow from a Novice adventurer to a Legendary hero.</p>\n<p>Advances are granted by the Game Master at the end of some game \"sessions\" (about 4–5 hours of play).</p>\n<p>An Advance lets a character make one of the adjustments listed below. Remember that no @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Trait} may be raised above its maximum (usually d12 unless modified by an ancestral ability, Edge, etc).</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Attribute:</span> Increase one attribute one die type. This option may be taken only once per Rank. Legendary characters may raise an attribute no more than every fourth Advance, up to the ancestral or class maximum.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Skills:</span> Increase a skill that is equal to or greater than its linked attribute one die type;<br />OR increase two skills that are lower than their linked attributes by one die type each (including new skills the character didn’t have before at d4). You cannot increase the same skill twice with the same Advance.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Edge:</span> Gain a new Edge. You should have a story-based reason to take a Background or a core @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Class Edge}. You can’t become a barbarian overnight, after all. Gaining these @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edges} should usually take years or some dramatic change in the character’s life, and should only be done with the Game Master’s permission. Core Class Edges and core @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Prestige Edges} are also limited to one per Rank. Legendary characters may choose a core Class Edge (or Prestige Edge) no more than every fourth Advance.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Buy Off a Hindrance:</span> Permanently remove a Minor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Hindrance Summaries]{Hindrance}, or reduce a Major Hindrance to a Minor (if possible). The player and GM should work out how and when this happens. Perhaps the shocking death of an ally triggers a change in attitude, the hero puts real effort into improving harmful behavior, or seeks professional help during @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{Downtime}.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Rank</h2>\n<p style=\"font-size:14px\">“Ranks” reflect a character’s competence and experience. They provide balance between players and grant access to more powerful abilities as one “Advances.” A character begins at Novice Rank and works upward from there. Advances are given out after one or more game sessions. The GM has more detailed information in the Advancement section @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{here}.</p>\n<p style=\"font-size:14px\">Only player characters use Ranks— Game Master-controlled characters and creatures don’t (we’ll tell you more about this later).</p>\n<table style=\"width:705.333px;font-size:14px\"><colgroup><col></col><col></col></colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"3\">Rank</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Advances</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Rank</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">0–3</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">Novice</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">4–7</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">Seasoned</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">8–11</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">Veteran</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">12–15</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">Heroic</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">16+</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">Legendary</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3>Starting With Experienced Characters</h3>\n<p style=\"font-size:14px\">If the Game Master wants to start a game with more experienced characters, or you're making a replacement for a fallen hero, you should still make a Novice starting profile and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Advance} it from there. This ensures characters are balanced just as if they had gained experience normally.</p>\n<p style=\"font-size:14px\">Additional goods, equipment, or other assets must be determined by the Game Master. As a quick rule of thumb, Seasoned heroes have 10,000 gold pieces worth of goods and magic items, Veteran characters get 40,000, Heroic 150,000, and Legendary 500,000.</p>\n<h2>Advancement Pace</h2>\n<p>How fast characters Advance in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> depends on the campaign.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Official Adventure Paths:</span> These epic tales tell the Game Master when to give the party an Advance. They typically start at Novice Rank and end at Legendary+, spreading improvements along as the story advances to different stages.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Short Campaigns:</span> If you’re running a campaign of your own creation and expect it to last 10 sessions or less, we recommend giving characters an Advance after each session.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Long Campaigns:</span> Grant an Advance after every two or three sessions for a long campaign, slowing it down to every four or five sessions once the heroes hit Heroic Rank.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Milestone Campaigns:</span> Grant an Advance after certain objectives are met in the campaign. You can grant Advances a bit more often in the early stages, slowing things down in the middle and later chapters.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Allies &amp; Advancement</h2>\n<p>Followers and other allies who stay with the party for extended periods can improve their abilities as well.</p>\n<p>If the party advances and the Game Master feels the allies have played a significant role in the story, they Advance as well. This gives player characters a group of loyal retainers and hirelings to interact with and deepens immersion.</p>\n<p>You’ll find an Ally Sheet on our website the group can fill in and use to keep up with their retainers' profile, gear, history, and other notes.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_intbwo9s2if","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2W11VvNYjkYIk1YB"}}}
{"_id":"KxFfUAb8Xj8zlzRK","name":"Elf","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Elf</h1>\n<p>Tens of thousands ofyears ago, the elves of the distant continent of Xen'drik rose up against the giants who ruled over them. This rebellion is the defining event in elf history. As the ancient war progressed, the magebreeders of the giants bound magic into the elves who remained loyal to them, forming the drow-assassins bred to prey on their other kin. Ultimately, the elves fled from Xen'drik and settled the island nation of Aerenal, where they split into two distinct cultures: the introspective Aereni and the warlike Tairnadal. Thus, a war nearly forty thousand years ago established the pattern of how elves live today.</p>\n<p>Neither the Aereni nor the Tairnadal (which include the elves of Valenar) have much interest in human activities, but small numbers of elves have immigrated to Khorvaire over the centuries and have more or less integrated with the cultures of the Five Nations. The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Elf, Drow]{drow}, though, are virtually unknown on Khorvaire.</p>\n<p>As a whole, elves are driven by tradition and respect for the past. Where humans value innovation, elves strive to master and perfect the techniques of their ancestors over the course of studies lasting centuries. Elf society has changed little over the last five thousand years, while Khorvaire is constantly evolving. Whatever the origin of your elf character, consider your relationship wit.h the past: Do you value the traditions ofyour ancestors? Or do you fear that your people are too mired in the past, and need to find a way to adapt and move forward?</p>\n<h3>Elves of the Five Nations</h3>\n<p>Throughout history, elves have occasionally migrated to live among the other peoples of Khorvaire. On rare occasions, entire families have relocated (as House Phiarlan did, almost three thousand years ago), but more often wanderers and exiles have come to Khorvaire and made their way there.</p>\n<p>As an elf born and raised in Khorvaire, your character has grown up among the shorter-lived races. You might not be as concerned with history and tradition as the Aereni and Tairnadal; you could even live your life entirely in the moment, with no care for your family or your legacy. Or you could be fascinated by the history and traditions ofyour ancestors and try to relearn the ways your family has forgotten.</p>\n<p>Consider also whether you've outlived human friends and how that might affect you. Did you know the parents or grandparents of another member of your party? Are you trying to repay a debt or fulfill a promise to that long-dead friend, or are you trying to recapture some spark of the friendship you felt years ago? Do you remember a time before the Last War? Did you fight in the war?</p>\n<h3>Elves and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>The <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Shadow]{Mark of Shadow}</em> first appeared among the elves of the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Phiarlan]{Phiarlan} line, and the house quickly turned the mark's powers of shadow and illusion into an economic dynasty. The suspicion of their kin drove them from Aerenal to Khorvaire, and the house splintered during the Last War, giving rise to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Thuranni]{House Thuranni}. The two houses of shadow control the business of espionage throughout Khorvaire, but they also operate more legitimate ventures related to art and entertainment.</p>\n<p>Phiarlan blood still runs among some of the Aereni elves, and the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Shadow]{Mark of Shadow}</em><em> </em>appears once or twice in each elven generation. Elves bearing this mark are always inducted into the elite force of the Cairdal Bladesan espionage agency in the service of Aerenal's Sibling Kings.</p>\n<h3>Aereni and Tairnadal</h3>\n<p>For thousands of years, the island nation of Aerenal has been ruled and protected by the godlike power of the Undying Court, a council of undead high elves. The greatest heroes of the Aereni join the Undying Court after death, joining their heroic ancestors in immortality.</p>\n<p>Tairnadal elves dedicate themselves to the arts of war. The greatest heroes of the Tairnadal's many wars-against giants, dragons, and the champions of Dhakaan—live on after death, becoming the patron ancestors of the Tairnadal. Upon reaching adulthood, a Tairnadal elf forms a bond with one of these ancestors and strives to follow in the footsteps of this ancestor, living as the patron did. In this way, the champion comes to embody their ancestor, allowing the dead to live on.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Agile:</strong> Elves are graceful and agile. They start with a d6 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Agility} instead of a d4. This increases maximum @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Agility} to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Elven Magical Nature]{Elven Magical Nature}:</strong> Elves were born of ancient giant magic and have an inherent connection to arcane energies. Elves get a free reroll when rolling to resist enemy powers.</li>\n<li><strong>Keen Senses:</strong> Elves have exceptionally keen senses. They add +1 to any @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} check.</li>\n<li><strong>Intelligence:</strong> Elves are highly intelligent and long-lived. They start with a d6 in Smarts instead of a d4. This increases maximum Smarts to d12 + 1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Elves from Aerenal or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Valenar]{Valenar} start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Elvish} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Low Light Vision]{Low Light Vision}:</strong> Elves eyes amplify light like a cat's, allowing them to see in the dark. Low Light Vision ignores up –2 penalties for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination}. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Pitch Darkness} remains unaffected.</li>\n<li><strong>Slender: </strong>Elves are graceful but more frail than other races. Their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness} is reduced by 1 and they have a −1 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Vigor} checks.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/elf.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/elf.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L4NqGfd9AVja33DY"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"L7RLEvVFAWYxJIRY","name":"Archeologist","content":"<p>An archaeologist learns about the long-lost and fallen cultures of the past by studying their remains -their bones, their ruins, their surviving masterworks, and their tombs. Those who practice archaeology travel to the far corners of Eberron to root through crumbled cities and lost dungeons, digging in search of artifacts that might tell the stories of monarchs and high priests, wars and cataclysms, and most importantly, their magic and technology.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Fighting, Language, Lore, Notice, Persuasion, Religion, Research, Science, Shooting, Stealth, Survival</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Alertness, Brave, Linguist</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Artifact Hunter, Explorer, Investigator, Scholar, Thief</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Scavenger</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.hW3xL2LcVGgDuDwA"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"LHDtUPSeEN7w6l4I","name":"Melee Weapons Table","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"6\">Melee Weapons</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Type</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Damage</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Min Str.</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Weight</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Cost</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\" style=\"width:40%\">Notes</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"6\"><span class=\"no-class\">Simple Weapons</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Club, Great]{Club, Great}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Two Hands]{Two hands}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Club, Heavy]{Club, Heavy}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">7 sp</td>\n<td>—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Club, Light]{Club, Light}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 sp</td>\n<td>—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Dagger]{Dagger}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 gp</td>\n<td>—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Mace]{Mace}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4</td>\n<td style=\"text