{"_id":"LLA2pHnPtbGAP6AB","name":"Backlash","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Backlash</h2>\n    <p>A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} when activating a power is\n        called Backlash. It causes a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} and all currently active\n        powers instantly terminate.</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Activation]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Q7PoZJOf66nxLpZn"}}}
{"_id":"LNNPSdAGAXwrwe2H","name":"Bounty Hunter","content":"<p>The most reputable bounty hunters in Khorvaire are members of House Tharashk’s Finders Guild. Still others might operate independently to avoid the strict policies and procedures imposed by House Tharashk, but competition with the Finder’s Guild is stiff.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Fighting, Healing, Intimidation, Shooting, Survival, Thievery</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Alertness, Luck</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Calculating, Level Headed</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Escape Artist, Explorer, Investigator, Jack-of-all-Trades</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Streetwise</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Danger Sense, Scavenger</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.G4Pzh2XyhAw9EiYp"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"LYBxYmje2TRv4x95","name":"Sinking","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Sinking</h1>\n<p>A wrecked boat begins to sink. Unless the vessel is cracked wide open and sinks instantly, this generally takes a little time. Use the guidelines below should it become important.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Small craft (rowboats, canoes) sink at the end of the round in which they’re wrecked.</li>\n<li>Medium craft, such as galleys, sink in [[/r 1d6]] minutes.</li>\n<li>Large craft, such as a trade ship of the monarch of the East, sink in [[/r 4d6]] minutes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Any ships grappled to the unfortunate vessel must release their grappling lines or be dragged down along with it.</p>\n<p>A sinking ship becomes a hazard to other ships still involved in combat.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Boarding]{Boarding}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranks of Archers]{Ranks of Archers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Sinking]{Sinking}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6g48t5q06rw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"LnvOqhHPsx6eq0vg","name":"Light","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>The weapon casts light in a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Medium Blast Template}. The user activates the illumination with her will as a free action.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 1</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 2,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light]{Light}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"M0tdBeBuOMp4qJJI","name":"Arcane Background (Psionics)","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Background (Psionics)</h2>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Edge:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Psionics)]{Arcane Background (Psionics)}</li>\n<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Novice}</li>\n<li><strong>Arcane Skill: </strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Psionics]{Psionics} (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Smarts})</li>\n<li><strong>Mental Power:</strong> Psionics may take Edges that require @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Background (Psionics)]{Arcane Background (Psionics)}.</li>\n<li><strong>Backlash: </strong>When a psionicist rolls a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Psionics]{Psionics} roll, the Dungeon Master rolls on the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash} to see what happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Starting Powers: </strong>3</li>\n<li><strong>Power Points:</strong> 10</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Accelerate Healing]{Accelerate Healing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Analyze Foe]{Analyze Foe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burrow]{Burrow}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{Burst}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{Confusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Damage Field]{Damage Field}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/Conceal Arcana}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Disguise]{Disguise}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Elemental Manipulation]{Elemental Manipulation}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{Entangle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{Environmental Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fear]{Fear}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Gift of Battle]{Gift of Battle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{Growth/Shrink}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{Healing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{Invisibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{Locate}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{Mind Link}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{Mind Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{Mind Wipe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Repair]{Repair}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Scrying]{Scrying}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{Shape Change}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{Speak Language}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{Teleport}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>What is Psionics</h2>\n<p>Simply put, psionics is the art of tapping the mind’s potential. A psionic character is blessed with a form of innate ability that enables him or her to use mental power to achieve goals or perform tasks that nonpsionic characters can accomplish—if they’re even capable of doing them at all—only by using gross physical skills such as brute strength or raw agility, or by using intellect or force of will distinct from the natural power of the mind itself.</p>\n<p>Your character’s mind is an infinite metaphorical plane, where all things are possible. It may be that all characters have within them the potential for harnessing the energy of the mind, but only those who succeed in tapping into that potential can become psionic characters. A psionic character knows the mental pathways that lead to amazing edifices of thought and energy. Knowing the path, the psionic character walks it. Like a flare being thrown off a star, a power is manifested from a psionic character’s energy of consciousness.</p>\n<h3>Secrets of the Mind</h3>\n<p>From the duergar traditions of the Akiak dwarves to the quori techniques of the kalashtar and Inspired, psionics are strong in Sarlona. Adventurers might have no recourse but to travel to Sarlona to learn certain psionic arts. The traditions of the psychic warrior are begining to find their way to Khorvaire, but it is still very rare.</p>\n<h3>Casting</h3>\n<p>Psionic powers spring from sentient minds and are manifested through intense concentration. The psion merely needs to concentrate to manifest his inborn powers, drawing on his abilities by tapping a reservoir of mental strength. He has no need for messy material components, verbal cues, or awkward gestures.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>TRappings of psionic power are wide and varied. They can draw fire from thin air, move a boulder without touching it, catch a glimpse of the future, and communicate with others who are miles away. Force is a common trapping for psionic powers.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yqngxv6403a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.3. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2}}}
{"_id":"MFfSUaRTzgUnMaY8","name":"1 Gear","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<div class=\"chapter-heading\">\n<h1>Gear</h1>\n<figure class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter Two</figure>\n</div>\n<p class=\"drop-cap\">This section contains rules and equipment. Read the notes below before you go to the outfitters to understand what various keywords mean.</p>\n<br />\n<h2>Costs</h2>\n<p>Characters are assumed to have clothes and other personal items. If the GM allows it, adventurers may also have a home with other supplies and necessities.</p>\n<p>The starting funds (300 gp) are for “adventuring gear” in addition to such personal items. The costs listed in the following sections represent standards; in the marketplace or the bazaar, all costs are negotiable. Character gear lists don’t need to include anything beyond “adventuring gear”.</p>\n<p>Use the lists and prices in this book as a baseline for your game when looking for equipment that isn't listed here.</p>\n<p>Some items are extremely difficult to price because they're created by decree or necessity, such as engineers and soldiers in a siege building catapults and trebuchets. Their prices reflect an estimate of the time and resources needed to create them.</p>\n<h2>Gear Notes</h2>\n<h3>Armor</h3>\n<p>This is the amount of Armor provided by the equipment, listed in parentheses beside the wearer’s total Toughness. Unless an attacker states otherwise, hits are always directed at the victim’s torso.</p>\n<p>Worn armor doesn't stack with other worn armor, but does stack with natural armor (such as scaly skin) at its full value.</p>\n<h3>Armor Piercing (AP)</h3>\n<p>The weapon or projectile ignores this many points of Armor value. A weapon with an AP value of 4, for instance, ignores 4 points of Armor. Excess AP is lost.</p>\n<h3>Damage</h3>\n<p>Damage is listed in terms of dice. Projectile weapons have fixed damage (such as 2d6). Melee weapons have damage based on the wielder’s Strength die plus another die, as listed under individual weapon entries. A dagger, for instance, inflicts Str+d4 damage.</p>\n<h3>Heavy weapon (HW)</h3>\n<p>The weapon can affect vehicles or other devices with <strong>Heavy Armor</strong> (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Vehicles]{Vehicles}). This is not to be confused with categories of personal armor— such as heavy armor or shields.</p>\n<h3>Minimum Strength</h3>\n<p>Certain items have a “Minimum Strength” required to use without penalty. Note that some items list a d4 since it is possible to have a Strength lower than d4.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Armor/Shields/Worn Gear:</span> Each die type differ­ence between the character’s Strength and the item’s Minimum Strength inflicts a −1 penalty to Pace (minimum of 1), Agility, and Agility-related skill rolls. This is cumulative for those weak but determined adventurers who wear or use multiple items too heavy for their build.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Melee/Thrown Weapons:</span> A thrown or melee weapon’s damage die is limited by the user’s Strength die. If a scrawny kid (Strength d4) picks up a long sword (Str+d8), he rolls d4+d4 damage instead of d4+d8. Also, if the user’s Strength is less than its Minimum Strength, he doesn’t benefit from any of the weapon’s positive abilities such as Reach or Parry bonuses. He still retains any penalties, however.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Weapons:</span> The user suffers a −1 attack penalty for each die step difference between his Strength and the weapon’s minimum.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Parry</h3>\n<p>The weapon adds the bonus to the character’s Parry score. If a character wields a weapon in each hand, penalties to Parry stack but bonuses do not (unless she has the Ambidextrous Edge). This also applies to carrying two shields at once (use the best Parry bonus).</p>\n<h3>Range</h3>\n<p>This lists the weapon’s Short, Medium, and Long Range. Extreme Range is up to 4×its Long Range. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Attacks]{Ranged Attacks}</strong> for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} (throwing) modifiers and more details.</p>\n<p>Ranges are listed in inches so you can use a ruler to move, shoot, and fight on the tabletop with miniatures. If you’re not using miniatures, each inch equals two yards (6 feet).</p>\n<p>Weapon ranges are “effective” ranges for the table-top.</p>\n<h3>Rate of Fire</h3>\n<p>This is the number of shots that may be fired by this weapon in a single action. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rate of Fire]{Rate of Fire}</strong> for further details.</p>\n<h3>Reach</h3>\n<p>Weapons with “Reach” allow their user to make Fighting attacks at the listed range. A Reach of 1, for example, allows a character to strike a target 1″ (2 yards) distant. Weapons without a Reach value can only strike targets at arm’s length (adjacent).</p>\n<p>Reach can be very important when fighting from horseback and <em>against</em> mounted foes (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mounted Combat]{Mounted Combat}).</p>\n<h3>Reload</h3>\n<p>A character can ready and fire a bow every action— see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reloading]{Reloading}. Heavy crossbows and black powder muskets are slower to reload. The number after the Reload keyword is how many actions of reloading it takes before a weapon can be fired again.</p>\n<h3>Two Hands</h3>\n<p>A two-handed weapon can be used with one hand at a −4 penalty. The hero counts full Strength for damage but loses all other advantages such as Reach or Parry bonuses.</p>\n<p>Two-handed weapons are normally required to make use of the Sweep Edge.</p>\n<h2>Encumbrance</h2>\n<p>Most of the time you don’t need to worry about how much weight a character is carrying. If it becomes important to track, use the <strong>Encumbrance Levels</strong> table. If a character carries more than the listed weight, he’s Encumbered.</p>\n<p>Encumbered characters subtract 2 from Pace (minimum 1), running rolls, Agility and all linked skills, and Vigor rolls made to resist <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}</strong>.</p>\n<p>At three times the lifted weight or more, he can move at a Pace of 1 for a number of rounds equal to his Vigor. Every round thereafter he must succeed at a Vigor roll or take a level of Fatigue.</p>\n<p>The maximum weight a character can lift or carry is four times the listed weight.</p>\n<p><strong>Bulky Items:</strong> Carrying a bulky, awkward, or unbalanced item, such as a large box, treasure chest, a person, and so on, may make a character Encumbered despite its actual weight (GM’s call).</p>\n<table style=\"width:80%\"><colgroup> <col></col> <col></col> </colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Encumbrance</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading center\">Strength</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading center\">Can Freely Carry Up To...</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">d4</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">20 lbs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">d6</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">40 lbs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">d8</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">60 lbs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">d10</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">80 lbs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">d12</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">100 lbs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">Each +1</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">+20 lbs</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>Currency</h2>\n<p><cite>Pathfinder for Savage Worlds</cite> uses a gold standard for trade across Eberron. In general, commerce relies on four precious metals, coined throughout the continents. Some traders accept gemstones when bargaining.</p>\n<p>Naturally, trade also occurs via bartering, although most characters (and merchants!) prefer coins when buying or selling wares. Costs default to gold pieces (gp) on Gear tables unless otherwise noted.</p>\n<table><colgroup> <col></col> <col></col> <col></col> <col></col> <col></col> </colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"5\">Coins &amp; exchange value</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Coin</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">CP</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">SP</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">GP</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">PP</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Copper (cp)</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1/10</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1/100</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1/1,000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Silver (sp)</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">10</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1/10</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1/100</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Gold (gp)</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">100</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">10</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1/10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Platinum (pp)</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1,000</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">100</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">10</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">1</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>Special Materials</h2>\n<p>Weapons and armor are often created with special materials found on Eberron. These materials improve combat effectiveness or have effects against creatures with resistances and weaknesses. Special materials don’t stack, only the best quality applies in any situation.</p>\n<p>Anything made from the following materials is considered masterwork, adding 300 gp to its base cost before other cost modifiers (see @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Masterwork]{Masterwork}).</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Adamantine:</span> Mined from rocks that fell from the heavens, adamantine adds +1 AP to any melee weapon or ranged weapon ammunition made of its metal. This stacks with the bonus from masterwork items. Adamantine weapons cost an additional 3,000 gp. Ammunition costs an addition 60 gp per missile.<br />Adamantine armor is harder to pierce than that made from other materials. It ignores up to 2 points of AP. Armor made from this material costs an extra 3,000 gp per point of armor bonus.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Darkwood:</span> This rare wood is much lighter than normal. Items carved from it weigh half as much as typical equivalents and cost an additional 10 gp per pound of the original weight to the price of a masterwork version of the item. Darkwood items increase Hardness (or Toughness if the hull of a vehicle) by 2.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Dragonhide:</span> Armorers can fashion their products with the hides of dragons when such wonders become available. The number of armor pieces that can be crafted from a single dragon is equal to half its size (rounded up). The hide can be used to craft light, medium, or heavy armor and counts as masterwork, granting the same bonus as other armors of the same type ( +2 to +4). Additionally, wearing dragonhide armor grants the wearer an additional +4 armor against the element tied to the dragon's breath weapon. For example, blue dragonhide gives resistance to electricity. This benefit stacks with the Energy Resistance enchantment. Dragonhide costs an additional 2500 gp beyond the cost of the normal armor it's mimicking. So a Dragonhide Breastplate costs 3000 gp.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Iron, Cold:</span> Mined from the deepest depths of Eberron, cold iron is the weakness of certain demons and fey creatures. Weapons forged with cold iron increase Hardness by 2 and cost twice as much as normal.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Mithral:</span> A rare metal on Eberron, mithral is forged like steel but weighs much less. Mithral reduces the Minimum Strength of weapons, armor, and shields one die type (this stacks with the bonus from masterwork) and the weight by half. Weapons and shields made primarily of mithral (GM's call) cost 100 times normal, while armor costs 10 times normal <em>per piece.</em><br />Mithral weapons count as silver for purposes of creatures with a silver Weakness.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Silver, Alchemical:</span> A complex process involving metallurgy and alchemy can bond silver to a steel weapon. This allows them to affect creatures with a Weakness to silver, such as lycanthropes. They cost ten times normal price.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Masterwork</h2>\n<p>Masterwork items are finely crafted versions of normal gear made by top artisans.</p>\n<p>Weapons of masterwork quality are +1 AP. Masterwork melee and ranged weapons add 300 gp to the cost.</p>\n<p>Masterwork arrows, bolts, or other ammunition subtract 1 point of Range penalty at Long or Extreme Range, and cost six additional gold pieces per unit. Masterwork ammunition loses its bonus after use even if recovered.</p>\n<p>Armor and shields of masterwork quality reduce the Minimum Strength requirement by one die type, to a minimum of d4. Shields cost an extra 300 gp, while armor costs an extra 150 gp <em>per piece.</em></p>\n<p>You can’t usually upgrade existing armor, weapons, or shields to masterwork quality— they must be crafted to high standards from the beginning.</p>\n<p>The availability of masterwork items— whether for sale in the marketplace or commissioned— depends on the size of the settlement and is up to the GM. Such items typically take twice as long to create if commissioned.</p>\n<h2>Weapon Size</h2>\n<p>Weapons wielded by some creatures may be larger or smaller than those listed here. A Giant’s battleaxe, for example, is larger than a human’s, while a kobold’s longsword is smaller. The GM can increase or decrease the Minimum Strength and weight as logically needed, but other statistics (Range, damage, etc.) remain as listed.</p>\n<table><colgroup> <col style=\"width:33.3%\"></col> <col style=\"width:33.3%\"></col> <col style=\"width:33.3%\"></col> </colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main