ron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Growth/Shrink]{Growth/Shrink}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{Invisibility}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{Locate}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Magic Mark]{Magic Mark}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Message]{Message}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{Mind Link}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{Mind Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Wipe]{Mind Wipe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Plane Shift]{Plane Shift}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{Puppet}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Repair]{Repair}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Scrying]{Scrying}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Secret Writing]{Secret Writing}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Shape Change]{Shape Change}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{Speak Language}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Beast]{Summon Beast}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Telekinesis]{Telekinesis}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{Teleport}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Time Stop]{Time Stop}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wish]{Wish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Zombie]{Zombie}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2>Playing those with Innate Magic</h2>\n<p>Those with innate magic, create magic the way a poet creates poems, with inborn talent honed by practice. They have no books, no mentors, no theories—just raw power that they direct at will. Scions of innately magical bloodlines, the chosen of deities, the spawn of monsters, pawns of fate and destiny, or simply flukes of fickle magic, sorcerers look within themselves for arcane prowess and draw forth might few mortals can imagine. Emboldened by lives ever threatening to be consumed by their innate powers, these magic-touched souls endlessly indulge in and refine their mysterious abilities, gradually learning how to harness their birthright and coax forth ever greater arcane feats. Just as varied as these innately powerful spellcasters' abilities and inspirations are the ways in which they choose to utilize their gifts. While some seek to control their abilities through meditation and discipline, becoming masters of their fantastic birthright, others give in to their magic, letting it rule their lives with often explosive results. Regardless, sorcerers live and breathe that which other spellcasters devote their lives to mastering, and for them magic is more than a boon or a field of study; it is life itself.</p>\n<h3>Raw Magic</h3>\n<p>Magic is a part of every sorcerer, suffusing body, mind, and spirit with a latent power that waits to be tapped. Some sorcerers wield magic that springs from an ancient bloodline infused with the magic of dragons. Others carry a raw, uncontrolled magic within them, a chaotic storm that manifests in unexpected ways.</p>\n<p>The appearance of sorcerous powers is wildly unpredictable. Some draconic bloodlines produce exactly one sorcerer in every generation, but in other lines of descent every individual is a sorcerer. Most of the time, the talents of sorcery appear as apparent flukes. Some sorcerers can't name the origin of their power, while others trace it to strange events in their own lives. The touch of a demon, the blessing of a dryad at a baby's birth, or ataste of the water from a mysterious spring might spark the gift of sorcery. So toa might the gift of a deity of magic, exposure to the elemental forces of the [nner Planes or the maddening chaos of Limbo, or a glimpse into the inner workings of reality.</p>\n<p>Sorcerers have no use for the spellbooks and ancient tomes of magic lore that wizards rely on. nor do they rely on a patron to grant their spells as warlocks do. By learning to harness and channel their own inborn magic, they can discover new and staggering ways to unleash that power.</p>\n<h2>CASTING</h2>\n<p>Sorcerers must make gestures with at least one free hand and speak aloud various magical words at least at a whisper. If either their hands are bound or they are prevented from speaking, they cannot cast their spells.</p>\n<h2>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</h2>\n<p>Wielding magic that is innate and from some untold force, sorcerers can wield very versatile magic. There are no limitations on the kinds of trappings that can be utilized by a sorcerer.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yqngxv6403a","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.3. Arcane Backgrounds","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":5}}}
{"_id":"MZMbGzX3W9Py2BZE","name":"Unarmored Hero","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Unarmored Hero</h2>\n<p>Pulp action tales often feature heroes with little or no armor defeating far more heavily armored adversaries.</p>\n<p>In these settings, if a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} chooses not to wear <em>any</em> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor]{armor} (ignoring shields), he adds +2 bonus to his @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Soak Rolls]{Soak rolls}!</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.YDEIHvvbxv1dDtDr"}}}
{"_id":"MkKQzOv5yLS1VTGA","name":"Enchant","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Enchant</h1>\n<p>A character that is an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Artificer]{Artificer} or can @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Craft Arcane Device]{Craft Arcane Device} can spend her time at a workshop @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crafting Magic Items]{crafting magic items}.</p>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/artificer-working-with-shard.webp\" /></div>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Downtime Activities</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Carouse]{Carouse}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Center]{Center}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Earn]{Earn}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Enchant]{Enchant}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Train]{Train}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Research]{Research}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rest]{Rest}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2},"cf":{"id":"temp_lrlfbg8dda","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Downtime keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"MliuyWwR54HWUBmV","name":"Hazards","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Hazards</h1>\n<p>Heat, cold, hunger, thirst, lack of sleep, and other hazards can wear down even the hardiest of heroes, sending them into a downward spiral that can lead to death if they can’t improve their situation.</p>\n<p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Hazards intro­duce resource management to long trips through dangerous regions. They also push the party toward critical resources like water or shelter where encounters with other travelers or creatures are likely present.</p>\n<p>The other Hazards listed here, such as falling, poison, disease, and the like, generally come up in response to a creature or situation.</p>\n<p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Each Hazard is different, but most are an attribute check made periodically against some dangerous effect. Failure tends to cause <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}</strong> . Use the standard rules modified by any changes noted in this section.</p>\n<h2>Hazards</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps &amp; Bruises}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Climbing]{Climbing}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cold]{Cold}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Disease]{Disease}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Drowning]{Drowning}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Electricity]{Electricity}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Falling]{Falling}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fire]{Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heat]{Heat}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.High Altitude]{High Altitude}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hunger]{Hunger}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Poison]{Poison}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Radiation]{Radiation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Random Traps]{Random Traps}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Sleep]{Sleep}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Thirst]{Thirst}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Traps and Haunts]{Traps and Haunts}</h3>\n</div>\n<br />\n<aside class=\"graph_quarter\">\n<h2>The Rule of Threes</h2>\n<p>Extreme survivalists often talk about the “rule of threes.” All of these apply to reasonably healthy individuals, of course. Those with illnesses or other infirmities will fare worse.</p>\n<p>These “rules” encourage those in dangerous circumstances to prioritize, seeing to their shelter in a freezing environment before worrying about water and food, for example. In the game, these conditions should only come into play when dramatically appropriate.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>AIR: </strong>A standard rule of survival says most people can survive three minutes without air (though they likely pass out and need resuscitation after a minute).</li>\n<li><strong>SHELTER: </strong>You can live for three hours without shelter in a harsh environment, such as sub-zero temperatures.</li>\n<li><strong>WATER: </strong>You can live for three days without water.</li>\n<li><strong>FOOD: </strong>You can live three weeks without food.</li>\n</ul>\n</aside>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.pZcItqT9WqEaOjHs"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":9},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"MnOXCuX96tmhjrVf","name":"Fast Healing","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Fast Healing</h2>\n<p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} make natural @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Healing]{healing} rolls once per day instead of every five days (or once per hour if the race has @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Special Ability (Regeneration)]{Special Ability - Regeneration}).</p>\n<p><strong>Bumps &amp; Bruises:</strong> Wild Cards recover one level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps &amp; Bruises}</strong> every four hours instead of the usual 24.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.FmGO2E3ySh1dZIhO"}}}
{"_id":"MyF1K4eUC8jq5ZZe","name":"Etherealness","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Armor Enchantment</h3>\n<p>On command, the wearer of this armor becomes ethereal, gaining minor <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{intangibility}</em>. The character can remain ethereal for as long as desired, but once he returns to normal, he cannot use this ability again for 24 hours.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 2</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 49,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Intangibility]{Intangibility}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"NAMuh46e6Qmur1t3","name":"Limited Actions","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Limited Actions</h2>\n  <p>\n    Some actions are so complex or involved they require greater concentration.\n    A character may only perform one limited action on their turn. It may be\n    part of a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Action} as usual.\n  </p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Combat]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aeejh0xnzv6","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Combat keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Kbv8oWxV4jnGtDmt"}}}
{"_id":"NKgWJ2j9EfjAIPpt","name":"House Scion","content":"<p>Forget the noble families of Galifar—the real power lies in the hands of the dragonmarked houses. You are a member of one of those houses, and though power comes with any number of responsibilities, you welcome your house duties as a reasonable price to pay for the social, political, economic, and magical power to which you are heir.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Common Knowledge, Dragonmark Focus, Persuasion, Traditions</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Dragonmark), Charismatic, House Scion, Rich, Filthy Rich</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.SyGFQAUWO5lYWqmd"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"NYhETbE41KC3wWo2","name":"Healing Incapacitation","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Healing Incapacitation</h2>\n    <p>Healing at least one Wound on an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} patient removes that state (and restores consciousness if he was knocked out).</p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Healing]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yxu1ag41di","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Healing keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.PTivdGkh6lkujTWf"}}}
{"_id":"NYrM6iwCJJ6rAd68","name":"Other Movement Issues","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Other Movement Issues</h2>\n  <ul>\n    <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Jumping:</span> Characters can jump 1″ (two yards) horizontally, or 0.5″ vertically as a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}. \n      Double these numbers if the hero can run at least 2″ (four yards) prior to the jump. If the hero chooses, she may make an \n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll as an action to increase her horizontal distance by 1″ (2″ with a raise), or half that vertically. \n      Jumping does not allow a character to exceed her total Pace for the turn.\n    </li>\n    <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Prone:</span> A hero may fall @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone} as a free action during her\n      turn. She may crawl while prone (see above). Standing is a free action but\n      reduces total Pace for the turn by 2.\n    </li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Combat]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aeejh0xnzv6","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Combat keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.w0TEC6T7NVzBF0sk"}}}
{"_id":"Nf5GxdfgFzE1izmV","name":"Opposed Rolls","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Opposed Rolls</h2>\n  <p>Sometimes rolls are “opposed” by an opponent. The attacker gets a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Trait} total, then the defender attempts to beat it.</p>\n    <p>The exact skills or attributes used in a contest are specified in each circumstance, or the GM can decide what makes the most sense. \n        If two characters try to pull something from each other’s hands, for example, they make opposed Strength rolls. \n        Sneaking up on someone is a Stealth roll opposed by Notice (which is detailed in the Stealth skill description @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{here}).</p>\n    <p>The acting character in an opposed roll always makes the Trait total first (including spending any <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Bennies}</strong>), \n        and must get at least a basic success (TN 4) or he fails. The defender rolls next and must <em>meet</em> or <em>exceed</em> the first character’s result or the attacker wins.\n    </p>\n    <p>The winner also uses the opponent’s total for purposes of determining raise effects.</p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0urjihl2ptj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Rules keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.TLXBjOLElvXZCwoK"}}}
{"_id":"NjKrO6ZSMYE0wCqX","name":"Law Domain","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Law Domain</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Aspects:</strong> Justice, law, order, truth</li>\n<li><strong>Deities:</strong> Aureon, The Silver Flame, The Blood of Vol, The Path of Light</li>\n<li><strong>Available Powers:</strong>\n<div class=\"available-powers\">\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Analyze Foe]{Analyze Foe}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Augury]{Augury}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{Bolt}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost/Lower Trait}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Champion of Faith]{Champion of Faith}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Conjure Item]{Conjure Item}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Consecrate/Desecrate Ground]{Consecrate Ground}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Darksight]{Darksight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{Detect/Conceal Arcana}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{Dispel}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Divination]{Divination}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{Empathy}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{Entangle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Environmental Protection]{Environmental Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Gift of Battle]{Gift of Battle}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Havoc]{Havoc}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Leaping]{Leaping}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{Light/Darkness}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Locate]{Locate}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Lock/Unlock]{Lock/Unlock}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Reading]{Mind Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Object Reading]{Object Reading}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{Protection}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{Relief}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sanctuary]{Sanctuary}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sentry]{Sentry}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{Sloth/Speed}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Slumber]{Slumber}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{Sound/Silence}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Speak Language]{Speak Language}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{Stun}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{Summon Ally}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Teleport]{Teleport}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Wall Walker]{Wall Walker}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Warrior's Gift]{Warrior's Gift}</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0bt6afhtf6wi","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Magic#/CF_SEP/4.2. Domains","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"NoMtEbD6o879JlVI","name":"2 Trappings","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Trappings</h1>\n  <p>\n    Trappings allow the core powers presented in this chapter to have many\n    different appearances. They don't usually have a game effect of their\n    own, but are important for atmosphere and theme.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    One character might fire magical missiles of glowing white energy while\n    another hurls deadly icicles. Both use the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> power and share the\n    same mechanics, but they look and \"feel\" different.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Trappings <em>do</em> matter when an obstacle or opponent has a particular\n    strength or weakness. If an ice troll suffers +4 damage from fire- or\n    heat-based attacks, for example, a <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{blast}</em> a player describes as a\n    fireball counts as a fire attack and does +4 damage.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Once described, a power’s Trappings don’t change unless the caster uses an\n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Advance}.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    A character can alter the power’s effects or Trappings as she wishes using\n    <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}</strong>.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Synergy</h3>\n  <p>\n    Sometimes logic dictates a power’s Trapping should have some additional\n    effect. Zapping someone with a lightning bolt while they’re standing in\n    water should cause additional damage, for example.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    When this occurs, the GM can decide there’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Synergy]{synergy} that either increases or\n    decreases the effect or damage (GM’s call) by +2 or −2.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Oppositional forces, such as fire and ice or light and darkness,\n    <em>don’t</em> have synergy against one another (though such effects are\n    sometimes accounted for in some creatures’ @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Special Abilities]{Special Abilities)}. If a fire\n    <em>blast</em> hits ice armor<em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{(protection)}</em>, for example, there’s no\n    additional effect because they cancel each other out.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Adding &amp; Changing Trappings</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    A character can learn two new powers when he takes the\n    <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.New Powers]{New Powers}</strong> Edge. \n    He may instead add Trappings to\n    his powers in place of one or two of the new powers. A hero who takes the\n    New Powers Edge, for example, could choose one new power and add an ice\n    Trapping to her <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>. The GM may also allow a player to\n    <em>change</em> the Trapping of existing power when she gains an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Advance}.\n    This should reflect a major change in the character in some way as\n    determined by the player and GM.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Limitations</h2>\n  <div>\n    <img class=\"float-right\" style=\"shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/storm-woman.webp')\" src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/storm-woman.webp\" width=\"300\" height=\"424\" />\n  </div>\n  <p>\n    Sometimes a power’s Trapping imposes a limitation on the power. \n    This gives the power focus at the expense of versatility. The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Limitations]{Limitation} is permanent and always in effect unless \n    changed with an Advance as noted below.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Each limitation placed upon the power reduces its total @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} cost by\n    one (to a minimum of 1). If this would normally reduce the cost to 0, you\n    gain a +1 bonus (+2 maximum) to the arcane skill total instead.\n  </p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Range:</span> The power’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range} is reduced to Touch\n      (if its usual Range is greater).\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Personal:</span> The power’s Range becomes Self (if its usual\n      Range is Touch or it has the range Limitation, above). This includes an\n      item if the power is normally cast on an object (such as <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em>).\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Aspect:</span> The character can only access one aspect of a\n      power (that has more than one choice), such as <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{sloth/speed}</em> or\n      <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost/lower}</em> Trait.\n    </li>\n  </ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_vv8zdhdw0l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.BkENWqUArSLYVWJr"}}}
{"_id":"Nwo9Uzzm9fHtl5HD","name":"Homunculus","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Homunculus</h1>\n<p>A homunculus is a construct servant created by a wizard or an artificer. Homunculi are little more than tools designed to carry out assigned tasks. All homunculi are essentially extensions of their creators, sharing the same alignment and basic nature.</p>\n<p>A homunculus is a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} with respect to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{Wounds} and rolling a Wild Die with its @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls}. It doesn’t get @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Bennies}, but the artificer can spend his own on its behalf. The homunculus and it's creator share a telepathic link out to a distance of 1 mile.</p>\n<p>The homunculus has 5 Power Points of its own. It cannot cast spells, but the artificer can draw on them as if they were his own. They recharge separately and at the same rate as the artificer’s.</p>\n<p>If a homunculus dies, the artificer is automatically @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned} (no matter how far away he is). He can craft another after 10 days and can change the type if she chooses.</p>\n<p>Homunculus don’t advance, but instead gain one of the advantages below for each of its master’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Advancement]{Ranks} (including @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Novice}) and for every fourth advance the hero gains past @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Advancement]{Legendary}.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li>The owner may use the homunculus’ senses as if they were her own, with a maximum range of 1 miles. She is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted and Vulnerable} while doing so.</li>\n<li>The artificer can increase one of the homunculus' @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Traits} one die type (no more than once per @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Trait}).</li>\n<li>The homunculus gains an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge}. It must make sense for the homunculus' type (DM’s call) and meet the Requirements as usual.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Available Homunculi</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Arbalaster]{Arbalaster}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Dedicated Wright]{Dedicated Wright}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Expeditious Messenger]{Expeditious Messenger}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Furtive Filcher]{Furtive Filcher}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Iron Defender]{Iron Defender}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Packmate]{Packmate}</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_vv8zdhdw0l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1}}}
{"_id":"O38A93lgARjC0H4t","name":"Crafting Magic Items","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Crafting Magic Items</h1>\n<p><img class=\"right table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/gnome-artificer.displaying-work.webp\" width=\"296\" height=\"400\" /></p>\n<p>Characters with the Artificer Edge can imbue their powers into arcane devices for later use or give them to their allies (see Arcane Devices). This ties up their own Power Points, however, and such creations are temporary.</p>\n<p>With enough time and resources, however, an artificer can create more permanent items of wonder, and best of all he doesn’t have to tie up his own Power Points in the process!</p>\n<h2>THE CRAFTING PROCESS</h2>\n<p>After each week spent Crafting, the artificer makes an Occult roll for each item he’s working on. A success makes 500 gp worth of progress toward its completion, and a raise makes 1,000 gp progress.</p>\n<p>If the roll is failed, no progress is made on that item but the crafter may try again the following week. A Critical Failure destroys the item and all the materials required to create it!.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Ammunition: </strong>Arrows, sling stones, bolts, or other types of ammunition are enchanted in batches of 12 at a time. If it can be recovered, each projectile has a 50% chance of remaining intact once fired.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>REQUIREMENTS</h2>\n<p>A character can create any of the items listed in this book if she has the Artificer Edge (page 77), Downtime (page 148), the item to be enchanted, access to a workshop, and any spells and materials listed in the item’s Craft entry.</p>\n<p><strong>The Item: </strong>Only items of quality craftsmanship are typically given permanent enchantments. Armor, shields, weapons, and other permanent items must be of masterwork quality (page 108). additional cost, but other permanent items Potions, scrolls, and wands have no should be exceptional examples of their type, and cost 50% more than usual.</p>\n<p><strong>Requirements: </strong>The artificer must have any powers and materials listed in the item’s Craft entry. Materials are precious gems, metals, powders, oils, or other rare components represented by the listed gold value listed (typically half the item’s value if purchased from others).</p>\n<p><strong>Workshop: </strong>A simple workshop allows a crafter to work on a single item at a time. A standard workshop allows him to work on two, and a grand workshop allows the creation of up to three items at a time.</p>\n<h2 class=\"blue-example\">EXAMPLE: EzREN's Gift</h2>\n<p>Ezren the wizard wants to craft slippers of spider climbing for Merisiel the rogue. He has access to a standard workshop and can create two things at once, so he decides to make a potion of healing at the same time.</p>\n<p>The slippers have a Craft cost of 2,400. The potion’s crafting cost is 150. Ezren has wall walker (a requirement for the slippers) and gathers 2,550 gp worth of other materials.</p>\n<p>After a week’s work, he rolls and gets a success. That’s 500 gp worth of progress toward their creation. Now he rolls for the potion of healing. He’s successful, and since its cost is less than 500 gp, it’s finished and ready to use.</p>\n<p>Ezren continues on the slippers the next week and gets a raise on his roll. That’s a total of 1,500 gp progress. The third and fourth weeks he gets another success, giving him another 1,000 gp worth of progress. The slippers are finished and he gifts them to his friend.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Articles on Magic Items</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic Items]{Using Magic Items}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Purchasing Magic Items]{Purchasing Magic Items}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Enchantments]{Enchantments}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crafting Magic Items]{Crafting Magic Items}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2},"cf":{"id":"temp_xadnq2n2oe8","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"OE7vtNLxW8E9L71E","name":"Innocent Bystandards","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Innocent Bystandards</h2>\n  <p>When an attacker misses a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing) roll, \n\t\tit may sometimes be important to see if any other targets in the line of fire were hit. \n\t\tThe GM should only use this rule when it’s dramatically appropriate— not for every missed shot in a hail of arrows.</p>\n\t<p>Each skill die that’s a 1 hits a random victim adjacent to or directly in the line of fire to the original target.</p>\n\t<p>A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} must miss with his Wild Die for a RoF 1 weapon to hit an Innocent Bystander—  \n\t\twild dice never hit innocent bystanders.</p>\n\t<p>This sometimes means it's easier to hit an adjacent victim than the original target. That may not be entirely realistic, \n\t\tbut is simple, dramatic, and requires some care in tight tactical situations.</p>\n    \n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>\n\t\t\t<strong>RoF 2+:</strong>  Although rare on Eberron, weapons with a Rate of Fire or 2 or more, or that fire in a spread, are much more likely to hit others. \n\t\t\tEach skill die that rolls a 1 <em>or</em> a 2 hits a bystander.\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.LaYSGthrjh2vwkOt"}}}
{"_id":"OSJbtcJqOKAPiK7Y","name":"Falling","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Falling</h2>\n  <p>\n    Falling damage is 1d6+1 for every full 10 feet (or d6+1 per 2\" on the tabletop), to a maximum of 10d6+10.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Snow:</strong> Particularly soft ground, such as very deep snow,\n    acts as a cushion. Every foot of soft snow reduces damage 1 point.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Water:</strong> A successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll halves damage into\n    reasonably deep water at heights of 10″ (20 yards) or less. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} negates\n    the damage entirely. Those who fall into water from heights greater than 20\n    yards take damage as if they’d hit solid earth.\n  </p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4txb7iklyvb","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Hazards keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.VWsotOh2lybrA8kA"}}}
{"_id":"Oa7JJuizo56hM6jL","name":"Domains","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Domains</h1>\n</div>\n<p>Domains are spheres of divine power, often represented by Eberron's deities and faiths. Some mortals worship the Domain itself, such as druids who pledge themselves to Nature. Others worship deities that represent their beliefs, such as paladins who follow Dol Arrh because she represents Goodness and Protection.</p>\n<table class=\"table gear-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Deities and their Domains.</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" style=\"width:40%\" scope=\"col\">Faith</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" style=\"width:30%\" scope=\"col\">Province</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" style=\"width:30%\" scope=\"col\">Suggested Domains</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"3\" scope=\"colgroup\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper\"> <span class=\"table-subheader-center-content\">The Sovereign Host</span> </span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>The Sovereign Host</td>\n<td>Civilization, Communty, Growth, Justice</td>\n<td>Any of the below</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Arawai]{Arawai}</td>\n<td>Life and Love</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Life Domain]{Life}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nature Domain]{Nature}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Aureon]{Aureon}</td>\n<td>Law and Lore</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Knowledge Domain]{Knowledge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Law Domain]{Law}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Balinor]{Balinor}</td>\n<td>Beasts and the Hunt</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Animal Domain]{Animal}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nature Domain]{Nature}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Boldrei]{Boldrei}</td>\n<td>Community and Hearth</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Life Domain]{Life}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Protection Domain]{Protection}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Arrah]{Dol Arrah}</td>\n<td>Honor and Sunlight</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Light Domain]{Light}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.War Domain]{War}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dol Dorn]{Dol Dorn}</td>\n<td>Strength at Arms</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.War Domain]{War}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Kol Korran]{Kol Korran}</td>\n<td>Trade and Wealth</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trade Domain]{Trade}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trickery Domain]{Trickery}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Olladra]{Olladra}</td>\n<td>Feast and Good Fortune</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Life Domain]{Life}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Protection Domain]{Protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trickery Domain]{Trickery}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Onatar]{Onatar}</td>\n<td>Artifice and the Forge</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Earth Domain]{Earth}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Knowledge Domain]{Knowledge}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"3\" scope=\"colgroup\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper\"> <span class=\"table-subheader-center-content\">The Dark Six</span></span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>The Dark Six</td>\n<td>Passion, Destruction, Fear, Bloodshed</td>\n<td>Any of the below plus @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Evil Domain]{Evil}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Devourer]{The Devourer}</td>\n<td>Nature's Wrath</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nature Domain]{Nature}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Tempest Domain]{Tempest}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Fury]{The Fury}</td>\n<td>Passion and Revenge</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.War Domain]{War}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Keeper]{The Keeper}</td>\n<td>Death and Greed</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Chaos Domain]{Chaos}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Death Domain]{Death}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trade Domain]{Trade}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Mockery]{The Mockery}</td>\n<td>Betrayal and Bloodshed</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Chaos Domain]{Chaos}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trickery Domain]{Trickery}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.War Domain]{War}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Shadow]{The Shadow}</td>\n<td>Ambition and Dark Magic</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Chaos Domain]{Chaos}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Knowledge Domain]{Knowledge}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Traveler]{The Traveler}</td>\n<td>Change and Chaos</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Chaos Domain]{Chaos}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trickery Domain]{Trickery}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"3\" scope=\"colgroup\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper\"> <span class=\"table-subheader-center-content\">Other Faiths</span></span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Silver Flame]{The Silver Flame}</td>\n<td>Purity, Good, Light, Self-sacrifice</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Law Domain]{Law}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Life Domain]{Life}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Light Domain]{Light}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Protection Domain]{Protection}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.War Domain]{War}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Blood of Vol]{Blood of Vol}</td>\n<td>Immortality</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Death Domain]{Death}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Evil Domain]{Evil}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Law Domain]{Law}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Life Domain]{Life}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cults of the Dragon Below</td>\n<td>Madness</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Evil Domain]{Evil}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trickery Domain]{Trickery}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Maskweavers</td>\n<td>Talenta Halflings</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Animal Domain]{Animal}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nature Domain]{Nature}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Path of Light]{Path of Light}</td>\n<td>Light and Self-improvement</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Law Domain]{Law}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Life Domain]{Life}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Light Domain]{Light}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Spirits of the Past</td>\n<td>Elven ancestors</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nature Domain]{Nature}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.War Domain]{War}</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Undying Court]{Undying Court}</td>\n<td>Elven ancestors</td>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Knowledge Domain]{Knowledge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Life Domain]{Life}</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_vv8zdhdw0l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1}}}
{"_id":"OcgFjzJjgHtjK2tR","name":"Special Materials","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Special Materials</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>Weapons and armor are often created with special materials found on Eberron. These materials improve combat effectiveness or have effects against creatures with resistances and weaknesses. Special materials don’t stack, only the best quality applies in any situation.</p>\n<p>Anything made from the following materials is considered @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Masterwork]{masterwork}.</p>\n<h2>Special Materials</h2>\n<div class=\"swade-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Adamantine]{Adamantine}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Alchemical Silver]{Alchemical Silver}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cold Iron]{Cold Iron}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Darkwood]{Darkwood}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dragonscale]{Dragonscale}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mithral]{Mithral}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2},"cf":{"id":"temp_ebw221m1i2","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/2.2. Materials and Craftsmanship","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Omb2MPIUQZnZOW9Q","name":"Illumination","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Illumination</h2>\n  <p>Darkness conceals details and makes it more difficult to detect objects and targets. Subtract the Illumination Penalties \n\t\t(see the <strong>Illumination Penalties</strong> table below) from active @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls} affected by Illumination, \n\t\tsuch as attacks, arcane skill and Notice rolls, etc. </p>\n\t\n\t<p>It’s up to the Game Master exactly what Trait rolls are affected, but here are a few examples of rolls that should <em>not</em> be penalized:</p>\n\t\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Resisting powers</li>\n\t\t<li>Resisting grappling attempts</li>\n\t\t<li>Recovering from a negative status, such as being Shaken or Stunned</li>\n\t\t<li>Verbal Support rolls</li><li>Verbal Tests</li>\n\t\t<li>A friendly, cooperative, adjacent character in Pitch Darkness where touch and communication overcome lack of sight</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t\n\t<p>Note that foes may get bonuses for attacking a target that can’t see them (see <strong>Attacking from Stealth</strong> in \n\t\tthe Stealth subsection in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Traits}).\n\t</p>\n\t\n\t<table>\n\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\">\n\t\t\t\t\tILLUMINATION PENALTIES\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tPenalty\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tLighting\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−2\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Dim:</strong> Twilight, light fog, night with a full moon. Visibility is generally limited to 25\" (50 yards).\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−4\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Dark:</strong> Typical night conditions with some ambient light from stars, a clouded or partial moon, \n\t\t\t\t\t\ta few flickering torches in a large space, etc. Targets aren’t visible outside of 10″.\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t−6\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Pitch Darkness:</strong> Complete and total darkness (or the target is hidden or invisible). \n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tPowers that require sight may not be possible.\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t</tbody>\n\t\t\t</table>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.AZ16LJMpcOFSGgRn"}}}
