{"_id":"PQx6xzRY4u7fDZAQ","name":"Chronicler","content":"<p>People need news, and you’re the one to provide it. You could be an investigative reporter searching for issues of national importance such as conspiracies, corruption, threats of war, or news about the Mourning. You could be gathering gossip, or sharing the tales of bold adventurers, so make sure your friends do something worthy of a story! You could also be a general agent of the Library of Korranberg, always watchful for anything that could expand the repository of general knowledge.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Common Knowledge, Language, Lore, Performance, Persuasion, Research, Taunt</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Alertness, Linguist</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Something </p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Something</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Something </p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Entertainer, Investigator, Honey Tongue, Jack-of-all-Trades, Scholar</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Streetwise, Work the Room, Work the Crowd</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.DmIr9SbZXF7Yu2ND"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"PRZmw7z2PB8OuXnH","name":"Thirst","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Thirst</h2>\n  <p>\n    An average-sized human requires two quarts of water a day. This requirement\n    is doubled in very dry conditions (such as the desert) or areas of great\n    heat and high humidity (the jungle) as the character perspires constantly\n    and begins to dehydrate.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    If enough water isn’t available, the hero begins to suffer from dehydration.\n    A day after he can’t get enough water, he must make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Vigor} roll every eight\n    hours (every four hours in a very hot or humid environment). Failure incurs\n    a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    See the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}</strong> skill when a character wants to\n    search for water from the local environment.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Recovery:</strong> Characters recover Fatigue levels normally after\n    receiving sufficient water.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Death:</strong> An individual @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} by thirst @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{perishes} after 2d6 hours.\n  </p>\n\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4txb7iklyvb","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Hazards keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.mkjVsGYPXrmobBjR"}}}
{"_id":"PeSNTMqtRrY96Kwg","name":"Dwarf","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Dwarf</h1>\n<p>The origin of the dwarves is shrouded in mystery. Some of their legends tell of a great migration that led the ancient dwarves to Khorvaire from \"a land of endless ice.\" Many believe this refers to the arctic lands of the Frostfell, while others claim that the first dwarves must have come from the frozen plane of Risia. Wherever their roots, these migrant dwarves established a mighty nation beneath the surface of Khorvaire.</p>\n<p>Most dwarven legends, unconcerned with the question of origin, dwell on the mighty artifacts and priceless treasures crafted by ancient deep-dwelling dwarves, and of the bloody wars they waged against the goblin Empire of Dhakaan. Dwarves today cherish the memory of this ancient nation, for all dwarves in Khorvaire are descended from exiles driven from the realm belowwhich was later destroyed by the daelkyr. Particularly in the Mror Holds, many dwarves cherish the idea of returning to the subterranean reaches and reestablishing their ancient nation, restoring them to a greatness they have all but forgotten. </p>\n<h3>Dwarves of the Mror Holds</h3>\n<p>The dwarves of the Mror Holds are defined in part by their relationship to the ancient Realm Below. In a desperate effort to rediscover and reclaim the holdings of their old nation, the dwarves have recovered many weapons of war created in the final days of the empire. Some of these weapons were forged by the dwarves to wield against the daelkyr, but others were made by the daelkyr for the use of their minions-strange symbiotic items that use the life force of their hosts to power their magical abilities.</p>\n<p>Some clans have banned the use of these symbiotic weapons and any exploration of daelkyr magic, notably the prominent Clan Mroranon. Others, particularly Clan Soldorak, have embraced this magic to use against the daelkyr. Defining a relationship to these discoveries can be an important element ofyour character's background; you might be a Mroranon paladin or ranger dedicated to expunging any trace of daelkyr magic from the Realm Below, or a Soldorak warlock drawing on the magic of Xoriat in pursuit of your own power, as well as glory for your clan.</p>\n<p>Another important question to consider in playing a Mrorian character is why you have left the Holds. The Leaving the Mror Holds table offers some suggestions that might spark further ideas.</p>\n<h3>Dwarves of the Five Nations</h3>\n<p>Dwarves are spread across Khorvaire. Dwarf soldiers and engineers were part of the armies that united the Five Nations, and dwarf masons laid the foundations of the greatest cities of Galifar. Traditionally loyal to family and clan, dwarves who were born outside the Mror Holds tend to transfer their fierce clan loyalty to their new homes-and particularly to the edifices of stonework that symbolize the permanence and stability of those places. A Brelish dwarf might feel a deep, personal connection to the towers of Sharn or the great walls of Wroat; some dwarves love the great Cathedral of the Silver Flame in Thrane more than devout followers of the Silver Flame. Ultimately, the typical dwarf in wider Khorvaire is more patriotic than the average human of the Five Nations, and many dwarves fought for their nations in the Last War, at least for a time.</p>\n<p>When creating a dwarf character from the Five Nations, consider both your national loyalty and the role your family plays in your life. Do you live near family? What kind of work do your closest family members pursue, and is that reflected in the background you choose? Are you close to your relatives, or have you had a falling out? Did you lose kin in the Last War?</p>\n<h3>Dwarves and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>The <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Warding]{Mark of Warding} </em>appears on dwarves of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Kundarak]{House Kundarak}, which had its origins as one of the clans of the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Mror Holds]{Mror Holds}. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Kundarak]{Kundarak} dwarves live across Khorvaire while maintaining close ties to the Mror Holds and their loyalty to the house over any particular nation.</p>\n<p>In addition to providing all manner of security, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Kundarak]{House Kundarak} dominates Khorvaire's banking industry. As a dragonmarked house, it is obliged to remain neutral in the politics of all nations, including its homeland. As a result, Clan Kundarak is no longer represented on the Iron Council that rules the Mror Holds. However, it wields an influence over the other clans that reflects its wealth and its status in the world beyond the Holds, and the voice of Kundarak members arguing against the use of daelkyr magic carries significant weight.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Dwarven Resilience]{Dwarven Resilience}:</strong> Dwarves are hardy and resistant to toxins. They gain a +4 bonus to resist the effects of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Poison]{poison}. Damage from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Poison]{poison} is also reduced by 4.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Darkvision]{Darkvision}: </strong>Dwarven eyes are accustom to the gloom of Khyber. Darkvision ignores up to –4 penalties for all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Illumination} up to 10\" away. Beyond 10\" they ignore up to –2 penalties. Such vision is in black and white (monchrome) only.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Dwarves from the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Mror Holds]{Mror Holds} start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Dwarvish} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n<li><strong>Reduced Pace:</strong> Dwarves have short legs compared to most races. Decrease their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} by 1 and their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{running die} one die type.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Stability]{Stability}: </strong> Dwarves have a low center of gravity. They recieve a +2 bonus to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} rolls for performing and resisting @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Push]{Push} attacks. This also gives them a +2 bonus for to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} rolls for to resist being knocked @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{Prone} from a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Push]{Push} attack or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Grappling]{Grappling}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Stonecunning]{Stonecunning}: </strong> Dwarves grow up in halls and caverns of worked stone, and get a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll at +2 as a free action within 10 feet of unusual stonework such as traps and hidden doors. Success means they know something is off, and a raise gives them more specific information such as how to trigger the trap or open the door. They also add 2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} rolls also related to stonework or mechanical work.</li>\n<li><strong>Tough:</strong> Dwarves are stout and tough. They start with a d6 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Vigor} instead of a d4. This increases maximum @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Vigor} to d12+1. Their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} is considered one die type higher for armor and worn gear (not weapons) and when determining Encumbrance. This ability stacks with  the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Brawny]{Brawny} Edge if the dwarf has it.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/dwarf.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/dwarf.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L4NqGfd9AVja33DY"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Pfd0tj6sZwIB6POi","name":"Arcane Devices","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Arcane Devices</h2>\n<p>A character with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Infuse Item]{Infuse Item} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge} from the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Artificer]{Artificer} class @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge} or the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Craft Arcane Device]{Craft Arcane Device} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge} can focus items into devices for herself or others. The advantage is that they can be given to and used by allies. The trade-off is that devices take a little preparation to create and can be lost or destroyed.</p>\n<p>Devices may be technological in nature, or they might be sacred, enchanted, or psychically powered objects, depending on the creator’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Background}.</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Arcane devices are relatively temp­orary creations player characters can create from their powers. Truly permanent “magic” items or devices are setting-specific, don’t use Power Points, and are created by the Game Master as she sees fit (such as those found in the <cite>Savage Worlds Fantasy Companion</cite>).</p>\n<p>The <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.No Power Points]{No Power Points}</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Rules]{Setting Rule} isn’t compatible with Arcane Devices.</p>\n<h3>Creation</h3>\n<p>Creating a device takes one hour per @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers]{power} that can be activated through it. The player must list which powers are in the device and then allocate Power Points to it. The device can only use the powers and Power Points allocated to it.</p>\n<p>Power Points invested in an arcane device are lost to the inventor until they’re used or recovered with <strong>Tinkering</strong>, see below (they don’t recharge).</p>\n<p><strong>Power Modifiers:</strong> A user may spend a device’s Power Points as desired, including enabling any applicable @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}.</p>\n<p>Arcane devices may not be <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Activation]{Shorted}</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Limitations:</strong> Arcane devices may benefit from <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trappings]{Limitations}</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Activation:</strong> The creator uses his arcane skill as usual. Others use whatever skill is associated with the device’s form—swords use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, alchemical potions use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing), and so on. If there is no other obvious skill, such as for a potion or worn item, the character rolls the inventor’s arcane skill as if it were his own (he does <em>not</em> benefit from any of the creator’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges} or other abilities, however).</p>\n<p>Failure to activate the device costs one Power Point as usual, and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} causes the user @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</p>\n<p><strong>Tinkering:</strong> A creator can reassign up to five Power Points per action between an arcane device and her own pool. She must be in physical contact with the item to do so. Artificers should lend out their devices very carefully!</p>\n<aside class=\"parchment\">\n<h2>Arcane Device Examples</h2>\n<p>Merrix d'Cannith makes an <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{invisibility}</em> belt and gives it to one of his minions. He has 20 Power Points and puts 5 of them into the belt, reducing his remaining pool to 15.</p>\n<p>When the minion wants to turn <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{invisible}</em>, he rolls Merrix’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair} skill. This costs 1 less Power Point than usual because of the belt’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trappings]{Limitation}—it must be worn to activate so it has a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range} of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Touch Attack]{Touch}.</p>\n<p>Merrix also gives the minion the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> power in the form of a wand and invests it with 10 Power Points. The minion rolls @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} to fire it.</p>\n<p>The minion suffers @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} if he rolls a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} activating either device.</p>\n<p>Once the belt or wand is out of energy, Merrix d'Cannith can recover the Power Points he invested in it normally (see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Activation]{Recharging}</strong>).</p>\n<p>Meanwhile, Ezren is an alchemist. He makes an “oil of sharpness” Red can rub on her sword to activate the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em> power. He invests four Power Points into it. Red soon finds herself in battle with the undead. She rubs the oil on the blade and rolls Ezren’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair} (since there’s no other obvious skill). She fails, which drains the oil of one Power Point. She tries again in the next round and gets a raise, granting her sword +4 damage. <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</em> normally costs 2 Power Points but Ezren’s Trapping has the “@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Touch Attack]{Touch}” Limitation so it only costs 1 point each time she applies it (see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</strong>).</p>\n</aside>\n<img src=\"modules/swade-core-rules/assets/art/pg153_quote_arcane_devices.webp\" /></div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_fsjso9rnq9","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/4.1. Using Magic","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":6}}}
{"_id":"PlI3MhjIncD23HfQ","name":"Accurate","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>The weapon grants the user +1 in the skill required to use it (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}).</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 1</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 4,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost trait}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"PlIcz5SJyqS0CzRb","name":"Vorpal","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Blade Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>A vorpal weapon ignores penalties for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Called Shots]{Called Shots} to the head. Anyone @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{Incapacitated} by it is decapitated!</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 5</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 50,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{Smite}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"PvuH3yi0ex3BiWzF","name":"Throwing","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Melee Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>The weapon can be thrown using @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing). Its Range is 4/8/16.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 1</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{Boost trait}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"Q0UcH2KGfEzcByRQ","name":"Heavy Weapon","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Heavy Weapon, Modifier</h2>\n    <p>The caster creates a focused blast. The attack counts as a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heavy Weapon]{Heavy Weapon}.</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{See full Powers rules here}</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{See full Powers list here}</p>\n&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Updated upstream\n    <p>@Compendium[@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n=======\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Stashed changes\n    \n    \n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.yQpvuGgokfSkWKWC"}}}
{"_id":"Q9Vr29t3Nj9YdU0W","name":"Enchantments","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Enchantments</h1>\n<p>Masterwork armor, shields, and weapons can be enchanted with the qualities listed below. Each item can hold five points worth of enchantments. The number of points a particular quality takes is listed in parentheses after its name.</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> An item cannot be enchanted with the same quality more than once.</p>\n<p><strong>Named Items:</strong> The named magic armor, shields, and weapons named in the rest of this chapter can’t have additional enchantments.</p>\n<h3>Armor &amp; Shield Enchantments</h3>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aegis]{Aegis}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Animated]{Animated}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arrow Deflection]{Arrow Deflection}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Deflecting]{Deflecting}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Energy Resistance]{Energy Resistance}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Etherealness]{Etherealness}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fortification]{Fortification}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glamered]{Glamered}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reflecting]{Reflecting}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Spell Resistance]{Spell Resistance}</strong></p>\n</div>\n<p> </p>\n<h3>Weapon Enchantments</h3>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Accurate]{Accurate}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bane]{Bane}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Brutal]{Brutal}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dancing]{Dancing}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damaging]{Damaging}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distance]{Distance}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Elemental]{Elemental}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Keen]{Keen}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Light]{Light}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mighty Cleaving]{Mighty Cleaving}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Returning]{Returning}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Speed]{Speed}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Throwing]{Throwing}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Vicious]{Vicious}</strong></p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Vorpal]{Vorpal}</strong></p>\n</div>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Articles on Magic Items</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic Items]{Using Magic Items}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Purchasing Magic Items]{Purchasing Magic Items}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Enchantments]{Enchantments}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crafting Magic Items]{Crafting Magic Items}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/artificer-infusing-armor.webp\" /></div>\n<p> </p>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_xadnq2n2oe8","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2}}}
{"_id":"QglKCs8kAuAgTChB","name":"Breaking Things","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Breaking Things</h2>\n\n\t<p>Occasionally a character may want to break a solid object, such as a weapon, lock, or door. \n\t\tUse the wielder’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} if held, or 2 if it’s motionless. \n\t\tIf a damage roll equals or exceeds the object’s Hardness, it’s broken, bent, shattered, or otherwise ruined. \n\t\tThe GM decides the exact effect.\n\t</p>\n\t<p>Most anything can be broken given enough time and effort, so use this system only when attempting \n\t\tto break things in a hurry (such as during combat rounds).\n\t</p>\n\n\n\t<table>\n\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\">\n\t\t\t\t\tObject Hardness\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tHardness\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tObject\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t4\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tRope\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t6\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tBow\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t8\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tPolearm, thin wooden door or wall\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t10\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tShield*, longsword, thick wooden door or wall\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t12\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tIron lock, manacles, shackles\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t</tbody>\n\t\t</table>\n\n\t<p>*A character must specifically state he’s trying to break a shield to do so—don’t check every time the shield-bearer is hit.</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>No Bonus Damage or Aces:</strong> Attacks against solid objects don’t get bonus damage from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raises}, \n\t\tand damage rolls don’t @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aces]{Ace}. \n\t\tUnlike a person or complex device like a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Vehicles]{vehicle}, \n\t\tan attack can’t hit a “vital” area on a lock or a door and thus do more damage.</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>Damage Types:</strong> Certain types of attacks can’t break certain types of objects. A club can’t cut a rope, for example. \n\t\tUse common sense when determining whether or not a particular type of weapon can destroy an object.</p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.JCujnvJtaGftNWDH"}}}
{"_id":"QidFE9mdVmwG3LAM","name":"Fighter/Warrior","content":"<p>Soldiers, mercenaries, bodyguards–these are just a few of the roles played by the guilds of House Deneith. The Blademarks Guild, the Defenders Guild, and the Sentinel Marshals train the best of Khorvaire’s fighters and warriors. Others unaffiliated with these guilds find their way in post-war Khorvaire, some formerly soldiers fighting on behalf of their nation currently seeking independent employment or joining local law enforcement.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Fighting, Gabling, Intimidation, Shooting</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Ambidextrous, Brave, Brawny, Brute</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Any combat edge</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Guardian, Soldier</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Menacing, Provoke</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.BLSS2IDTA3BoVZPB"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"R3wogi9heYwCWmQE","name":"Electricity","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Electricity</h2>\n  <p>\n    On Eberron, characters may encounter natural or magical sources of\n    electricity. Contact with a high voltage electrical source (GM’s call)\n    causes 3d6 damage. Increase the damage by +1d6 if the victim is standing in\n    deep water or driving rain, and +2 if the victim wears mostly metal armor\n    (chainmail, platemail).\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Armor:</strong> Armor doesn’t protect from electrical damage unless it’s specifically designed to do so (e.g., a rubberized suit).\n  </p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4txb7iklyvb","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Hazards keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.ft2wuqQUU0jMzYwl"}}}
{"_id":"RIUS4mQm97tF0fnk","name":"Sorcerer","content":"<p>In a world where dragonmarked dynasties dominate the mystical economy, it’s easy to imagine how sorcerous bloodlines can fit into the world. What defines the sorcerer is the fact that their magic comes from within, that they must exert their will to coax the powers that lay dormant within them to manifest, whether it be from dragon’s blood, inherited power, the Mourning, the Daelkyr or being a product of Vadalis magebreeding.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Focus</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Gifted), Arcane Resistance, Improved Arcane Resistence, Charismatic, Elan</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Channeling, Concentration, Extra Effort, New Powers, Power Points, Power Surge, Soul Drain</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Strong Willed, Iron Will</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.9oJEqxGPoymsbx7q"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"RdNbmZbTmR89KI0m","name":"Glory Benefits","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Glory Benefits</h1>\n<p>Being a hero has its perks. When a hero reaches a multiple of 20 Glory he must immediately pick one benefit from the list below, meeting any requirements. Some heroes may opt to acquire Followers or become leaders of men and build a personal army. Others might use their fame to gain valuable connections or become better combatants, while others may prefer to rely on their reputation to ensure a friendly welcome in civilized lands.</p>\n<p>Unless otherwise stated, benefits can be taken multiple times—the number in parentheses after the name indicates the maximum number of times the benefit may be taken. Fill in the appropriate section of the character sheet.</p>\n<p>Should Glory drop below a multiple of 20, any benefits above the character’s current Glory level are temporarily lost (unless otherwise stated) until Glory is regained. Dropping below 20 and then rising above it again does not grant the opportunity to take a new benefit—it simply allows the “lost” one to be used again.</p>\n<h2 class=\"blue-example\">Example: Barak the Fair</h2>\n<p><em>Dave’s character, Barak the Fair, has the Heroic Status benefit, which he took he reached 20 Glory. When he reaches 40 Glory he takes the Connection Edge (Church of the Silver Flame).</em></p>\n<p><em>Due to a \"misunderstanding\" regarding a visit to noble’s daughter’s bedchamber late one night, he suffers a 2-point Glory penalty, lowering his total to 38. The Church of the Silver Flame immediately suspend ties to the hero, but Barak retains his Heroic Status. Only if Barak’s Glory drops below 20, will he lose his Heroic Status as well.</em></p>\n<p><em>Later on, Barak earns +4 Glory, bringing his total to 42. The Church of the Silver Flame open relations again now the hero’s reputation is not as sullied—Barak does not get to pick a new benefit.</em></p>\n<table class=\"table summary-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Glory Edges</h2>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\">Edge</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\">Requirements</th>\n<th class=\"table-column-header\">Summary</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Combat Prowess]{Combat Prowess}</td>\n<td>20+ Glory</td>\n<td>Gain a Combat Edge.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Connection]{Connection}</td>\n<td>40+ Glory</td>\n<td>Hero gains friend(s) among an organzition aligned with him.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Favored]{Favored}</td>\n<td>60+ Glory</td>\n<td>Hero gains an extra @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Followers]{Followers}</td>\n<td>40+ Glory</td>\n<td>Hero gains @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Followers]{Followers}, as per the Edge.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Heroic Aura]{Heroic Aura}</td>\n<td>40+ Glory</td>\n<td>The Hero's @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness} increases by 1.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Heroic Status]{Heroic Status}</td>\n<td>20+ Glory</td>\n<td>+1 bonus to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Reaction Table]{Reaction Table} results, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}, and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Networking]{Networking}.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Immortalized in Song]{Immortalized in Song}</td>\n<td>Heroic Status taken 4 times</td>\n<td>Number of Followers the Hero has doubles.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Leader of Men]{Leader of Men}</td>\n<td>40+ Glory</td>\n<td>Hero can take a Leadership Edge.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Sidekick]{Sidekick}</td>\n<td>80+ Glory</td>\n<td>Leader gains the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Sidekick]{Sidekick} Edge.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Additional Glory Articles</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Variable Glorious Deeds]{Variable Glorious Deeds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fixed Glory Awards]{Fixed Glory Awards}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glory Benefits]{Glory Benefits}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Losing Glory]{Losing Glory}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2},"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"ReGQatwF2KrMYdQC","name":"Surprise","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Surprise</h2>\n  <aside class=\"sidebar\">\n\t\t<h1>Support VS. Test</h1>\n\t\t<p>The Support option can be used against an opponent narratively, but the only effect it can have is as detailed above. \n\t\t\tIf a character wants to “trip up” an ogre to help a friend make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} roll against it, for example, \n\t\t\tshe can add +1 or +2 to his roll, but she doesn’t actually trip the ogre. It’s not made @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone}, \n\t\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted %26 Vulnerable]{Distracted or Vulnerable} or \n\t\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} as it might if she had used the \n\t\t\t<strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test}</strong> option.\n\t\t</p>\n\t\t<p>The advantage for a player in making a Support roll over a Test is to help an ally and avoid a more difficult opposed roll for the Test \n\t\t\t(even though narratively it might seem like it should be an opposed roll).</p>\n\t</aside>\n\n\t<p>Combat often starts before everyone involved is prepared. An ambush, a sudden double-cross, or a trap might all give one side in a fight an advantage. \n\t\tWhen this happens, the ambushers are automatically on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{Hold}. \n\t\tDeal them in as usual anyway in case one of them gets a Joker.</p>\n\t<p>The victims of the attack make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll. Those who make it are dealt in as usual. \n\t\tThose who fail get no Action Card and can’t act in the first round of combat.</p>\n\t<p>See the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} skill if someone attempts a sneak attack before the round begins.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.FI1zJZSItSPG9fYA"}}}
{"_id":"RkQ18cLFRsGUhuaF","name":"Adventure Toolkit of Savage Eberron","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<div class=\"chapter-heading\">\n<h1>The Adventure<br />Tool kit</h1>\n<figure class=\"chapter-number\">Savage Eberron</figure>\n</div>\n<p>The following chapter contains tools the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Game Mastering]{Dungeon Master} can use for all the special situations that often come up in a game, such as:</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Allies]{ALLIES}:</strong> Managing Extras under the player character’s control.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Chases and Vehicles]{CHASES &amp; VEHICLES}:</strong> Dynamic and thrilling chases on foot, in cars, or on motorcycles, or dogfights between massive fleets of starships!</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{DOWNTIME}:</strong> Activities a character might engage in during time between adventures.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dramatic Tasks]{DRAMATIC TASKS}:</strong> Add tension and drama to situations like defusing a bomb or hacking a computer.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fear]{FEAR}:</strong> The effects of overwhelming terror.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{HAZARDS}:</strong> The effects of scorching heat, bitter cold, radiation, and more.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Interludes]{INTERLUDES}:</strong>  Narrative storytelling for long trips or to reveal bits about the player characters’ backstories.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mass Battles]{MASS BATTLES}:</strong> Desperate last stands against incredible odds between armies.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{NAUTICAL CAMPAIGNS}:</strong> Rules for dealing with nautical campaigns. Combat, contact, fire, crews, and more.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Networking]{NETWORKING}:</strong> Gathering information or asking for favors.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Quick Encounters]{QUICK ENCOUNTERS}:</strong> A fast and easy way to resolve fights, heists, or capers when pressed for time.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Rules]{SETTING RULES}:</strong> A host of special rules you can use to customize your setting!</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shadowing]{SHADOWING}:</strong> Rules for how to tail a target without getting discovered.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Social Conflict]{SOCIAL CONFLICT}:</strong> Run a court trial, plead for aid, or convince a crowd.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Travel]{TRAVEL}:</strong> Figure out how long it takes for the party to cross Khorvaire!</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wealth]{WEALTH}:</strong> An optional system for those who don’t want to worry about tracking income and expenses.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.8vMT7u9GSOuWmfyH"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":19},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"RzY7ELwswcUIxwti","name":"Celestial Bloodline","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Celestial</h1>\n<p>A celestial ancestor or divine intervention of some sort blessed this hero’s bloodline. Her <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{blast}</em>, and <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{burst}</em> spells cause +2 damage to evil creatures (this stacks with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Champion]{Champion}). She also gains @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Enviromental Resistance]{enviromental resistance} to cold and acid.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>★ Advanced Form: </strong>The celestial can extend angel-like wings as a free action. This grants her @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Flight]{Flight} at @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} 12.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_w2j6cd7pbcs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.4. Bloodlines","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
