{"_id":"Th8y0tJTKCrWo0s5","name":"Magewright","content":"<p>Magewrights highly skilled and focused on a few certain spells, which they use to craft specific magical technology. They are most frequently found in cities and large towns, where they are about as common as adepts.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Crafting, Dragonmark Focus, Lore, Magecraft, Repair, Research, Science</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Arcane Background (Dragonmark of Making or Magecraft)</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Artificer, Adept Artificer, Master Artificer, Attune Arcane Weapon, Enchant, Improved Enchant, Expert Artificer, Finely Tuned, Imbue Item, Tinkerer</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Jack-of-all-Trades, Mr. Fix It</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Scavenger</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.owEB6QK3kUGdi03l"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"TmjnYRYWfaENN0V5","name":"Improvised Weapons","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Improvised Weapons</h2>\n  <p>Heroes often fight with objects that aren’t intended for use as weapons. Torches, vases, chairs, tankards, bottles, tools, and other mundane items \n\t\tare frequently pressed into service in combat.</p>\n\t<p>Characters with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Improvised Weapons]{improvised weapons} count as armed but subtract 2 from attack rolls. \n\t\tRange, damage and Minimum Strength are determined by type:</p>\n\t\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Light:</strong>  Beer stein, fist-sized rock, dagger pommel (as a club). Range 3/6/12, Damage Str+d4, Min Str d4.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Medium:</strong> Hammer, pick, wooden chair. Range 2/4/8, Damage Str+d6, Min. Str d6.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Heavy:</strong> Head-size rock, sack of stones, log. Range 1/2/4, Damage Str+d8, Min. Str d8.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t\n\t<p>The GM should adjust the damage and other factors as makes sense for the particular item.</p>\n\t\n\t<div>\n\t\t<img src=\"/assets/art/2 Kobold Ambush_v2.webp\" />\n\t</div>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.qI2NsY2L7DyR6IsV"}}}
{"_id":"TvvVcgvLMiApH2WZ","name":"Hold","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Hold</h2>\n\t<p>A hero may choose to delay her turn by going on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{\"Hold\"}. \n\t\tThis allows her to resolve her actions later in the round if she wishes, and lasts until it’s used. \n\t\tIf a character is on Hold when a new round begins, she’s not dealt a new Action Card but can go at any point in the round she chooses. \n\t\t(Discard her current card and mark her as “On Hold” with a counter of some sort.)</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} and </strong><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned}</strong> \n\t\tIf a character is Shaken or Stunned while on Hold, she immediately loses her Hold status \n\t\tand her turn for the round. (Shaken or Stunned characters can’t go on Hold either.)</p>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>Interrupting Actions:</strong> If a character on Hold wants to interrupt an action (including a rival who was also on Hold), \n\t\tshe and the opponent make opposed  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} rolls. \n\t\tWhoever rolls highest goes first. In the rare case of a tie, the actions are simultaneous.\n\t</p>\n\n\t<p>If the character interrupting fails, she loses her Hold status but gets a turn after the foe finishes his. \n\t\tShe may take whatever actions she wishes when her turn comes up— she’s not locked into whatever she was trying to do when she failed to interrupt.\n\t</p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.QzTAIH1jeyKyDwGI"}}}
{"_id":"TzBd003A5kSCFFK4","name":"Using Magic","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Using Magic</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<aside class=\"half-torn-parchment floated-aside\">\n<h2>Multiple Arcane Backgrounds</h2>\n<p>If a character takes a new Arcane Background, she gets a d4 in its arcane skill if she doesn’t already have it and any new powers it grants. If she already has an Arcane Background, she doesn’t get new Power Points, she must share her existing pool with all her Arcane Backgrounds. Otherwise, she also gets the Power Points listed for the class.</p>\n<p>Power Edges apply to all a character’s applicable powers, but Class Edge abilities apply only to spells provided by that class.</p>\n</aside>\n<p>The following setting rules apply to <em>all</em> forms of Arcane Backgrounds in the <cite> Savage Eberron</cite> setting. Unless a change is noted below, the normal rules apply.</p>\n<h3>Detecting Magic</h3>\n<p>In the magically-charged world of Eberron, any character with an Arcane Background can sense magical or divine auras within 5” (10 yards), unless they are magically concealed. This is an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Actions]{action}.</p>\n<p>Detecting magic at a greater range or gaining specific information requires the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{detect arcana}</em> spell, which can also be used to reveal items or beings protected by <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{conceal magic}</em>.</p>\n<p>Identifying magic items requires an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} roll for everyday items like healing potions. More obscure items require an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana]{Arcana} roll.</p>\n<h3>Using Magic</h3>\n<p>A character activates a power by picking a target within Range and making an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll. Failure means the power doesn’t activate. Success means the power activates and consumes all the Power Points allocated to it, even if it misses the target (such as with bolt), or the defender resists. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} has additional effects noted in the particular power description.</p>\n<p><strong>Backlash: </strong>A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} when activating a power is called Backlash. It causes a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} and all currently active powers instantly terminate.</p>\n<h3>CASTING REQUIREMENTS</h3>\n<p>A character must be able to see his target and cannot be @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound} or silenced.</p>\n<h3>MAINTAINING POWERS</h3>\n<p>When a power ends, the caster can spend one Power Point to extend it by its base Duration. If a power’s Duration is five rounds, for example, it can be maintained for another five rounds for 1 Power Point.</p>\n<p>Maintenance is per target but ignores other Power Modifiers, so renewing <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost Trait}</em> on three allies costs 3 Power Points and extends the effect of each another five rounds.</p>\n<p>Unless a power says otherwise, the caster can terminate it as a free action.</p>\n<h3>RECHARGING</h3>\n<p>A character recovers 5 Power Points per hour spent resting.</p>\n<p>What constitutes rest is up to the GM, but generally, it means sitting, eating, tending wounds, sleeping, and avoiding any strenuous activity. Walking or riding a horse isn’t usually restful, but riding in a cushioned carriage might be.</p>\n<p>A few interruptions don’t stop a character from resting — standing watch, planning, sharpening weapons, and so on (GM’s call).</p>\n<p>An arcane hero can also spend a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny} to regain five of her Power Points. This is a free action.</p>\n<h3>POWERS AS MULTI-ACTIONS</h3>\n<p>Each power activated is its own action, and the same or different powers may be cast multiple times as a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Action}. A wizard might start combat by invoking <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}</em> and <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{deflection}</em>, for example, or a priest might attempt to <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{banish}</em> a spirit while invoking <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em> on his mace.</p>\n<h3>SHORTING</h3>\n<p>A character may cast a power with fewer Power Points than required (whether she has them or not) by increasing the difficulty of her @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll.</p>\n<p>For every Power Point a character shorts, she suffers a −1 penalty to the roll. Casting a 3-point <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> with 0 Power Points, for example, inflicts a −3 penalty.</p>\n<p>Shorting is risky. If a character fails a shorted @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll, it’s considered a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure}!</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Magic and Powers</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Using Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Activation]{Activation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers Summary List]{Powers Summary list}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cantrips]{Cantrips}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{Schools of Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3> </h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":5},"cf":{"id":"temp_fsjso9rnq9","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/4.1. Using Magic","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"U608qYyoWOY9wwoc","name":"Stunned","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Stunned</h2>\n\t<p>Creature abilities, the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{stun}</em> power, electrical hazards, \n\t\tor other shocks to the brain or nervous system make a character essentially helpless until they manage to shake it off.</p>\n\t<p>Restart the process if a stunned character is stunned again.</p>\n\t\n\t<h3>Stunned characters</h3>\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Are @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted %26 Vulnerable]{Distracted} (this is removed at the end of a victim’s next turn as usual)</li>\n\t\t<li>Are @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted %26 Vulnerable]{Vulnerable} Vulnerable (this remains until a victim recover from being Stunned) </li>\n\t\t<li>Fall prone (or to their knees, GM’s call)</li>\n\t\t<li>Can’t move or take any actions</li>\n\t\t<li>Don’t count toward the \"@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ganging Up]{Gang Up} bonus</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t\n\t<p><strong>Recovery:</strong> At the start of a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned} char­acter’s turn, he makes a Vigor roll as a \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}. \n\t\tSuccess means he’s no longer Stunned but remains Vulnerable until the end of his <em>next</em> turn.\n\t\tWith a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, his Vulnerable state goes away at the end of this turn.\n\t</p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.y7c8OOE2yhMJxVxm"}}}
{"_id":"UAMEyV9F5pSbf3jn","name":"Swashbuckler","content":"<p>You focus your training on the art of the blade, relying on speed, elegance, and charm in equal parts. While some warriors are brutes clad in heavy armor, your method of fighting looks almost like a performance. Duelists and pirates typically belong to this archetype. A Swashbuckler excels in single combat, and can fight with two weapons while safely darting away from an opponent.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Fighting, Intimidate, Notice, Performance, Persuasion, Stealth, Taunt</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Ambidextrous, Elan, Fleet-Footed, Quick</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Block, Improved Block, Close Fighting, Improved Close Fighting, Dirty Fighter, Really Dirty Fighter, Dodge, Improved Dodge, Extraction, Improved Extraction, Feint, First Strike, Improved First Strike, Level Headed, Improved Level Headed, Lunge, Two-Fisted</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Acrobat, Combat Acrobat, Femme Fatale/Ladykiller, Thief</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Humiliate, Menacing</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Something</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.Wl3UstbQHWHgaplR"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"UeiJs3y8MFrNRv1Z","name":"Quick Encounters","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Quick Encounters</h1>\n\n  <p>\n    Sometimes the Game Master may want to quickly sum up an encounter rather\n    than track every action round by round. \"Quick Encounters\" resolve these\n    kinds of situations with good collaborative storytelling, tension, and risk.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Use Quick Encounters when\n    you're pressed for time, the group isn't as interested in tactical fights,\n    or they do something the GM isn't prepared for, like infiltrating an enemy\n    compound she hasn't yet detailed.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>The Basics:</strong> Characters make a skill roll based on the type\n    of encounter and their goal and interpret the results narratively with the\n    Game Master.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Encounter Types</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    No @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Cards} are dealt in a Quick Encounter. Instead, the GM describes\n    the scene, and then the players agree on a general plan and what their\n    characters will do to resolve the situation.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Once all the players state their intent, they pick the skill that best\n    represents their actions during the encounter and roll. Here are some common\n    examples:\n  </p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Combat:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, arcane skill.</li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Crisis:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} (to calm bystanders), @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair}.\n    </li>\n    <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Heist:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery}.</li>\n    <li>\n      <span class=\"list-heading\">Mission:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Battle]{Battle}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{Boating}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting},\n      @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth}.\n    </li>\n    <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Trek:</span> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}.</li>\n  </ul>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Modifiers:</strong> The GM should assign modifiers based on the\n    situation. If the heroes greatly outnumber their opposition, pursue much\n    slower prey, have prior experience with the obstacles in their path, or\n    special equipment to deal with hazards, the roll might be made at +1 to +4.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Very difficult encounters, such as powerful foes (relative to the party),\n    faster prey, or extreme conditions inflict a −1 to −4 penalty.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Turn Order &amp; Critical Actions</h3>\n  <p>\n    Players can go in whatever order they want in a Quick Encounter. This might\n    be important if some of their actions are dependent on someone else's. In a\n    heist, for example, the group might depend on a smooth-talker to gather\n    information about the target's security before the thief attempts to break\n    in. Similarly, a battle commander might need to send a scout across enemy\n    lines before sending in a team to sabotage the enemy's war engine.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Resolve these kinds of actions in the order that makes sense, and allow\n    those who come after to change their own plans as the situation changes.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    If a critical task is failed, the GM must decide if it stops the encounter\n    or simply complicates it (perhaps inflicting a penalty to everyone else's\n    roll). In the heist example above, for example, maybe the charmer gets the\n    information but tips off someone who adds extra sentries, inflicting a −2\n    penalty to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} rolls. Likewise, the scout might find the war\n    engine's location but the enemy moves the device shortly thereafter, adding\n    the need for additional reconnaissance for the team of saboteurs.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    These kinds of complications might also mean resolving the encounter in\n    multiple stages instead of one roll as the heroes must react to the changing\n    circumstances (see <strong>Staged Encounters,</strong> below).\n  </p>\n  <h3>Staged Encounters</h3>\n  <p>\n    Quick Encounters are typically a single die roll followed by some narration\n    between the GM and the players. But some encounters might need additional\n    rounds to better reflect the results or any new information or events that\n    come to light.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    If the heist to break into a wizard's tower and steal a powerful occult\n    artifact goes badly, for example, the next stage might become a crisis when\n    the tower suddenly bursts into supernatural flames. That might then lead to\n    a combat encounter as an artifact in the wizard's study breaks and releases\n    an angry djinn!\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The beauty of staged encounters is their ability to handle complex problems\n    when the constraints of time or larger narrative require a speedy\n    resolution.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Encounter Results</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    Once each player has determined her skill and any modifiers, she rolls the\n    dice and works with the Game Master to narrate the details based on the\n    total, the situation, and the other players' actions.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Dangerous Encounters</h3>\n  <p>\n    If a character fails his roll in a dangerous situation he takes a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wound} (or\n    d4 Wounds with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}). If he's the driver of a vehicle, it\n    takes a Wound (or d4 with a Critical Failure). Wounds may be @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Soak Rolls]{Soaked} as\n    usual.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Success means the hero emerges with only <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}</strong>, and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} means he escapes unscathed.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Nonlethal Encounters</h3>\n  <p>\n    If the encounter isn't physically dangerous, failure means the hero doesn't\n    contribute to the party's overall success somehow. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means\n    she suffers social stigma, loses or breaks a piece of vital equipment, is\n    positively identified, or gets the wrong information. This likely means\n    moving on to a second stage of the encounter as she deals with the fallout\n    of her errors.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Success &amp; Failure</h3>\n  <p>\n    In general, narration and individual actions determine the success or\n    failure of an encounter. If the smooth-talker can't learn the habits of the\n    sentries, for example, and the GM decides this fact shuts down the operation\n    rather than complicating it, the encounter fails. In other words, let the\n    story tell the tale.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    In a more dynamic situation such as combat, assume the group \"wins\" if there\n    are at least as many total successes (one for each success and raise) as\n    there are player characters. They get the information, drive off their foes,\n    complete the mission, or avert (or escape) the crisis. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support} rolls\n    <em>don't</em> count as successes.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    If there are fewer successes than player characters, they fail. Specifics\n    are up to the Game Master, but this might mean the party has to fall back or\n    retreat from their foes, their prey escapes, they don't get the object or\n    information they sought, they survive the crisis but can't save most of the\n    bystanders, and so on.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    If they can try again, the GM should \"reset\" the encounter with the new\n    narrative so the group has to come up with a new plan. And of course, their\n    foes are likely on to them now!\n  </p>\n  <h3>Ammo &amp; Power Points</h3>\n  <p>\n    Use the rules for <strong>Ammo &amp; Power Points</strong> under <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mass Battles]{Mass Battles}</strong> for combat encounters if desired.  Otherwise the player and GM can just decide what resources were consumed in the encounter.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2 class=\"example\">Example: Night on the prowl</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    Our heroes must break into a nobleman's library, steal an ancient book, and stop an evil conspiracy that threatens all of Eberron.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The group decides to play out the break-in as a Quick Encounter. The rogue\n    plans to use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} to break into the library, take the manuscript, then\n    escape out the back. The bard supports her with a diversionary recital in the town square.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The GM decides the rogue's Thievery roll is at −2 to get into the library.\n    The bard gets a success with his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}. He adds +1 to his\n    friend's roll.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The rogue manages a single success, but since there are two player characters and the rules say they need at least as many successes as there are characters, they fail.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The GM says three of the nobleman's guards are alerted by the pair's\n    actions. The heroes can continue if they want, but the encounter is now more\n    difficult (−2). The GM also says it's now a Dangerous Encounter as the\n    guards are armed and nervous.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    With the fate of Eberron at stake, the party agrees to press on. The rogue\n    now uses @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} to avoid the guards. The bard disguises himself and knocks\n    on the door, pretending to be lost! The GM tells the bard to use Performance\n    for this Support roll. He rolls a 21! Both characters are successful, so the\n    ancient manuscript is secured!\n  </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.DjD7PCIuFxCUJFDW"}}}
{"_id":"UkkEVL299DxWDbWJ","name":"Ranks of Archers","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Ranks of Archers</h1>\n<p>Instead of firing individually, archers may fire in ranks. When using this option make a single attack roll using the lowest @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} die type of all the characters involved. Firing in ranks is resolved exactly the same as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Suppresive Fire]{Suppresive Fire}, but the size of the template depends on the number of archers firing.</p>\n<p>A minimum of five archers can affect a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Small Blast Template}, 10 archers affect a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Medium Blast Template}, and 20 archers (the maximum) affect a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Large Blast Template}.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Boarding]{Boarding}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranks of Archers]{Ranks of Archers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Sinking]{Sinking}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6g48t5q06rw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Uy2B6UKQq8nZ7dsN","name":"Range modifier","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Range (+1/+2)</h2>\n    <p>\n        Double the power’s listed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range} \n        for 1 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Point}, or triple it for +2. This\n        modifier may not be used on powers with a Range of Touch or the Cone or\n        Stream Template.\n      </p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{See full Powers rules here}</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{See full Powers list here}</p>\n&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Updated upstream\n    <p>@Compendium[@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n=======\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Stashed changes\n    \n    \n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.kIndCLq07IllEoi3"}}}
{"_id":"V9hOYSuQ0f2ECPN2","name":"Half-orc","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Half-orc</h1>\n<p>Thousands of years beforc humans came to Khorvaire, the land was dominated by wild orcs and goblinoids of the Dhakaani Empire. The goblin empire scattered the orc tribes and forced them into harsh and unwanted lands: the swamps of the Shadow Marches, the Demon Wastes, and the depths of the Ironroot Mountains. But in the Shadow Marches, the orcs learned the secrets of druidic magic from the dragon Vvaraak, becoming the first of the Gatekeepers. With the invasion of the alien daelkyr from Xoriat, the Gatekeepers put the dragon's teaching to the test, creating magical seals that bound the daelkyr in the depths of Khyber and protected Eberron against further incursion from the plane of madness.</p>\n<p>Three prominent groups of orcs have survived into the present age:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Ghaash'kala are servants of the Silver Flame (which they call Kalok Shash, the \"binding flame\"), who devote their lives to battling the fiends of the Demon Wastes. Humans from the Carrion Tribes of the wastes sometimes hear the call ofKalok Shash and join the Ghaash'kala, leading to a significant population of half-orcs there.</li>\n<li>The Jhorash'tar orcs are a perpetual threat in and around the Ironroot Mountains, shaped by their resentment of the Mror dwarves who drove them underground. These orcs are isolated from humans, so half-orcs here are rare.</li>\n<li>The Shadow Marches holds the largest numbers of orcs and the most significant population of half-orcs.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Orcs of the Shadow Marches</h3>\n<p>The orc Gatekeepers played a crucial role in defeating the daelkyr and binding their evil in Khyber, and their descendants continue to maintain the ancient seals and fight aberrations spawned by the daelkyr's corruption. However, many orcs succumbed to that same corruption and embraced the madness of the cults of the Dragon Below. orcs who follow both of these paths continue to live in the Shadow Marches, and centuries of battles between them have diminished both sides.</p>\n<p>Humans settled in the Shadow Marches long ago, and the first half-orcs helped to cement the bond between these outsiders and the native orcs. Certain Marcher clans contain humans, orcs, and half-orcs in roughly equal numbers.</p>\n<p>When playing an orc or half-orc character from the Shadow Marches, consider what circumstances brought you into the wider world. The Leaving the Shadow Marches table offers some inspiration.</p>\n<h3>Half-orcs of Khorvaire</h3>\n<p>With the rise ofthe dragonmarked House Tharashk, ores and half-orcs have spread through the Five Nations and beyond. In general, the people of the Five Nations know little about half-ores. When people imagine a half-orc, they usually think of a Tharashk bounty hunter or dogged inquisitive, but a few ignorant sorts might still hold the stereotype of a \"simpleton from the swamps.\"</p>\n<h3>Half-orcs and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>The <em>Mark of Finding</em> appears among half-orcs of House Tharashk. Dragonmarked half-orcs work extensively with humans, orcs, and unmarked half-orcs in pursuit of the house's mission of bounty hunting, inquisitive work, and prospecting. Across Khorvaire, anyone who wants to find something or someone turns to House Tharashk.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Heritage: </strong>Half-orcs may retain the strength of their orc parent. A half-orc starts with a d6 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} instead of a d4 (which also increases his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} maximum to d12+1).</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Half-orcs from the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Shadow Marches]{Shadow Marches} may start with a d8 in d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Goblin} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Orcish} instead of d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n<li><strong><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Low Light Vision]{Low Light Vision}</strong>:</strong> Orc eyes are accustomed hunting at night, having eye's similiar to a cats. Low Light Vision ignores up –2 penalties for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination}. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Pitch Darkness} remains unaffected.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Primal Intuition]{Primal Intuition}: </strong>Half-orcs start with a d4 in one of the following skills: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{athletics}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{healing}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{intimidation}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{notice}, </em>or <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{survival}</em>. If the chosen skill is a core skill, it starts at d6 and the skill's maximum increases to d12+1.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/half-orc.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/half-orc.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.hXW8dnse3pIGZnz5"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"VI5zQ7tfo8NLSkxM","name":"Creative Combat","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n\t<h1 class=\"wide\">Creative Combat</h1>\n\t\t\n\t\t<p>Creative Combat is an optional rule a Game Master may allow to give @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Tests} more varied results. It’s especially useful if a group prefers a slightly more pulpy or swashbuckling feel.</p>\n\t\t<p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Use these rules when you want Tests to have a little more variety.</p>\n\t\t<p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Roll on the table when a character Tests a foe with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}.</p>\n\t\t\t\n\t<h2>Tests of Mettle</h2>\n\n\t\t<p>Creative Combat occurs only when the game is in rounds. A regular success on a <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test}</strong> works as usual. If a character succeeds with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, she can decide if she wants to take the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} result or roll on the Creative Combat table. She can decide if she wants to make her foe @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted or Vulnerable} after she rolls on the table.</p>\n\n\t\t<p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Merisiel]{Merisiel} battles an ogre on the edge of a cliff. She feints the clumsy brute and gets a raise. The GM rolls on the Creative Combat table and gets a Setback. She decides the ogre has to make an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Agility} roll or fall off the cliff. Merisiel makes the creature Distracted so it has a greater chance of failure!</p>\n\t\t<br />\n\t<table>\n\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\tCreative Combat\n\t\t\t\t\t</th>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<th class=\"sub-heading left\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t2d6\n\t\t\t\t\t</th>\n\t\t\t\t\t<th class=\"sub-heading left\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\tResult\n\t\t\t\t\t</th>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t2\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Second Wind:</strong> The foe hesitates, giving your hero time to catch her breath. She may remove a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} or a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wound} (her choice). If she has neither, the enemy is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} and she receives a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny}.\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t3\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Inspiration:</strong> Fate favors the bold. The clever hero receives a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny}.\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t4–5\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Double Whammy:</strong> The target is both @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted and Vulnerable}.\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t6–8\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p><strong>Shaken:</strong> The foe is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t9–10\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p><strong>Setback:</strong> The target suffers a setback of some sort. She might fall off a ledge, lose the confidence of her minions (who then desert her), take a rash but foolish action, or simply lose her next turn as she attempts to recover from whatever situation she finds herself in.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t11\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p><strong>Insight:</strong> The hero gains insight into the target’s nature. Once during this encounter, she may add +d6 to any @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait} roll made to directly @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Attacks]{attack}, affect, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage]{damage} the same foe.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t12\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p><strong>Seize the Moment:</strong> After the hero resolves this turn, she immediately gets an entire additional turn. This includes @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{movement} as well! She may use the turn to go on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{Hold} if she wishes.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t</tbody>\n\t\t</table>\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t<img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/climb.webp\" />\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.cI5LbEJBw9Aej6Za"}}}
{"_id":"VXMu5Z8kiKjnYaJZ","name":"Area Effect Attacks","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Area Effect Attacks</h2>\n\n\t\t<p>Spell effects, breath weapons, and other attacks that cover a large area are @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{“area effect attacks”}. \n\t\t\tThe most common are Small, Medium, and Large Blast Templates, and the Cone and Stream Templates. \n\t\t\tThere are copies you can print out on our website.</p>\n\t\t<p>Area effect weapons target a location rather than individuals and so ignore defensive bonuses for targets \n\t\t\tcovered by the template, such as the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Dodge]{Dodge} Edge or speed penalties.</p>\n\t\t<p>Cone and Stream templates are placed with one end (usually the narrow end for the cone template) emanating from \n\t\t\tthe attacker and fired with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} skill \n\t\t\t(or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} for breath weapons and other natural attacks). \n\t\t\tA basic success means those beneath the template are hit. Failure means the attack didn’t occur for some reason— \n\t\t\tthe creature failed to belch up noxious gas, the flamethrower malfunctioned, etc.</p>\n\t\t<p>To attack with a blast template, the player places it on the tabletop (or describes where he wants it to land) \n\t\t\tand rolls Shooting, or Athletics for thrown weapons and breath attacks. If the attack fails and there’s a chance \n\t\t\tthe miss might hit someone else, see Deviation, below.</p>\n\t\t<p>If the roll is successful, any target even partially beneath the template is affected, regardless of any attack penalties to hit such as the Dodge Edge. \n\t\t\tIf the effect causes damage, roll for each victim separately. Attacks that hit with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} \n\t\t\tcause bonus damage as usual.</p>\n\t\t\t\n\t\t<h3>Deviation</h3>\n\t\t\n\t\t<p>Most of the time, the GM can ignore a missed @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{area effect attack}. \n\t\t\tIf it's important to know where a missed blast lands, thrown items deviate 1d6″. \n\t\t\tFired projectiles deviate 2d6\". Multiply by 2 if the attack was made at Medium Range, 3 if Long, and 4 for Extreme.</p>\n\t\t<p>Next roll a d12 and read it like a clock facing to determine the direction the missile deviates. A weapon can never deviate more than half the distance \n\t\t\tto the original target (that keeps it from going behind the thrower).</p>\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\n\t\t<table>\n\t\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tTemplate\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tDiameter\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tTargets Affected\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tSmall\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t4 yards\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t2\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tMedium\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t8 yards\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t3\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tLarge\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t12 yards\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t4\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tCone\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t18-yard-long cone\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t3\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tStream\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t24 × 2-yard line\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t3\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t</tbody>\n\t\t</table>\n\n\t<aside>\n\t\t<h1>Templates Without Miniatures</h1>\n\t\t<p>Use the measurements below when you need to figure out how many enemies a template might affect and you aren't using miniatures.</p>\n\t\t<p>The <strong>Targets Affected</strong> column above shows the GM how many enemies are hit in narrative situations, modifying the result if \n\t\t\tthe targets are spread out (like trained assassins) or bunched up (like mindless zombies).</p>\n\t\t<h3>Cover and Area Effect Attacks</h3>\n\t\t<p>Solid obstacles like trees or thick walls protect against @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{area effect attacks} \n\t\t\tif they’re between the center of the blast and a victim and the GM thinks they’d offer protection. \n\t\t\tReduce the damage by half the object's hardness, see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover %26 Obstacles]{Cover &amp; Obstacles}</strong>\n\t\t</p>\n\t</aside>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.ASUPXL8QF7GxNvpW"}}}
{"_id":"VXwP3qDzCI6krLaI","name":"Armor","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Armor</h2>\n<p>This is the amount of Armor provided by the equipment, listed in parentheses beside the wearer’s total Toughness. Unless an attacker states otherwise, hits are always directed at the victim’s torso.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Armor]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.mBvna5Qwheesre9K"}}}
{"_id":"VkPL3z2XC8kETCw9","name":"#[CF_tempEntity]","content":"","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ebw221m1i2","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/2.2. Materials and Craftsmanship","color":"#000000","name":"2.2. Materials and Craftsmanship","children":["cuk99xgVS3uKgIyX","4GTRoTLe6ph9AxWK","lI5IPZPThORV5qsg","E4sTwgDhOnICfEVT","yoUFXQcdUme8zOYF","ZTDoRmjFdaQlHYKl","KotQOseBZ7sAWykR","OcgFjzJjgHtjK2tR"],"folderPath":["temp_5n9ndtjortv","temp_7e7xz1a6a2k"]}}}
{"_id":"VnQIXVphRqhsbO1x","name":"More Skill Points","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>More Skill Points</h2>\n<p>Thanks to technology and improved education, characters in modern and futuristic settings have 15 Traits @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{skill points} at character creation rather than 12. This helps them take @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Driving]{Driving}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Electronics]{Electronics}, and other skills common in the modern world.</p>\n<p>It’s up to the GM if this makes sense in her particular setting. A futuristic but “savage” world of planetary romance probably doesn’t need it, but it works well for most anything set in the developed world from about 1950 on, hard scifi, or “exploration” scifi like <cite>The Last Parsec</cite>.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.OUZ4f9EeVBgfcFuj"}}}
{"_id":"VrjXvee8KFg6e8G6","name":"Hobgoblin","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Hobgoblin</h1>\n<p>The goblinoid species-goblins, hobgoblins, and bugbears—were once the dominant civilization in Khorvaire, with the goblinoid Empire of Dhakaan ruling the continent for thousands of years. It was crippled by a long conflict with the daelkyr and their aberrant armies; even though the daelkyr were defeated, the seeds of madness took root in the empire and tore it apart. Today there are four primary goblinoid cultures in Khorvaire.</p>\n<p>Among the <em>dar</em> or goblin people, hobgoblins are known as <em>ghaal'dar</em> or \"mighty people\". Hobgoblins are the most organized and intelligent of the goblinoid species, often holding the positions of power and organization.</p>\n<h3>The Ghaal'dar</h3>\n<p>The Ghaal'dar tribes arose from the remnants of the Dhakaani Empire. Hobgoblins are the leaders of the Ghaal'dar, enforcing their will on their goblin and bugbear peers. The history of the Ghaal'dar is filled with strife; when they weren't fighting Galifar or Zilargo, the tribes usually turned on one another. This came to an end with the Last War. House Deneith hired Ghaal'dar mercenaries, and this gave focus to the divided tribes. A brilliant hobgoblin, Haruuc, united the Ghaal'dar, and under his leadership they seized control of what is now Darguun. The aging Lhesh Haruuc remains as the ruler of Darguun, and many fear that his death could throw the region into chaos.</p>\n<p>As a Ghaal'dar goblinoid, you hold your place through cunning and strength. You may have been a former mercenary now seeking adventure. You could be working as an emissary for one of the Ghaal'dar tribes or even Lhesh Haruuc himself. Or you could have been driven from your tribe by the actions of a rival; perhaps you're seeking allies to reclaim your birthright.</p>\n<h3>The Heirs of Dhakaan</h3>\n<p>Though the Dhakaani Empire defeated the alien daelkyr, the war left seeds ofcorruption strewn throughout the empire. As Dhakaan began to fall, a number of generals and governors gathered their forces and retreated into shelters deep within the earth, determined to preserve their civilization until the Empire could finally be restored. After thousands of years, their descendants have finally emerged, competing among themselves to determine which leader deserves the imperial crown. Once this is settled, they will turn to the conquest of Darguun and Khorvaire.</p>\n<p>The Dhakaani are far fewer in number than the Ghaal'dar; they had to carefully limit their population in the underground vaults they've dwelled in for the past age. However, they have held onto the martial discipline and techniques that allowed their ancestors to dominate the continent. Their weaponsmiths are superior even to the artificers of House Cannith, and they are experts in the working of adamantine and other exotic metals. Anyone who presumes to look down upon goblinoids should be surprised by the skills of the Dhakaani.</p>\n<p>The Heirs of Dhakaan are an agnostic society and don't have clerics, paladins, or druids. Their focus is on martial excellence, and their spiritual leaders are bards, who tell tales of past glory. Among the Dhakaan, goblinoids work together. Hobgoblins are the strategists and commanders, typically having the skills of fighters, bards, or rangers. Bugbears cultivate a focused battle rage and are typically barbarians. Goblins are largely artisans and laborers, but exceptional goblins join the khesh'dar (\"silent folk\"), learning the skills of rogues, monks, or rangers. The khesh'dar spread agents across the Five Nations, and one can never know when a city goblin might turn out to be an assassin.</p>\n<p>As an adventurer from a Dhakaani clan, consider why are you working with the other player characters? Are you a scout gathering information? Are you searching for allies to defeat a rival clan, or to support your own unlikely bid for the Imperial throne? Are you an exile? If so, do you hope to regain your position, or have you abandoned your ties to the Dhakaani?</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Darkvision]{Darkvision}:</strong> Hobgoblin eyes are accustomed to the dark of Khyber. Darkvision ignores up to –4 penalties for all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Illumination} up to 10\" away. Beyond 10\" they ignore up to –2 penalties. Such vision is in black and white (monchrome) only.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Hobgoblins start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Goblin} instead of <span style=\"color:#191813\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</span></li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Martial Training]{Martial Training}:</strong> Hobgoblin are trained in war as soon as they can hold a weapon in their hand. They start with a d4 in one skill of their choice from <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Battle]{Battle}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}</em>, or <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}</em>. If the skill is a core skill this will increase the skill's maximum to d12+1.</li>\n<li><strong>Warrior Trained: </strong>Hobgoblins are born and bred as warriors and leaders. Hobgoblins begin play with one free Combat or Leadership @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge}.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/hobgoblin.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/hobgoblin.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.Xml542xziJ7D56S8"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":2},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"WBLcCNrEQHf5jfWq","name":"Armor and Swimming","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Armor and Swimming</h1>\n<p>It is particularly difficult to swim while wearing armor. Characters subtract any Encumbrance penalties as usual from the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (Swimming) rolls, but also subtract the natural bonus of any armor worn as well. Ignore magical bonuses, considering only the bonus of a basic suit of that type.</p>\n<p>A suit of leather, for example, adds +1 to the user’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}, and so subtracts –1 from his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (Swimming) rolls.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Boarding]{Boarding}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranks of Archers]{Ranks of Archers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Sinking]{Sinking}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_6g48t5q06rw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"WBLgzqujVw1w1mOF","name":"Abyssal Bloodline","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Abyssal</h1>\n<p>Generations ago, a demon corrupted the hero’s heritage. She has @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Enviromental Resistance]{enviromental resistance} to electricity, +1 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}, and sharp claws that cause Str+d4, AP 2 damage.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>★ Advanced Form: </strong>The abyssal can conjure demons to aid her. The cost for s@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Summon Ally]{summon ally} is reduced by 2 (to a minimum of 1), and the entities summoned cause @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Fear]{Fear}. She also gains @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Enviromental Resistance]{enviromental resistance} to cold, fire, and electricity.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_w2j6cd7pbcs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.4. Bloodlines","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"WJs8tQhTJwgNgPfP","name":"Pilot/Ship Captain","content":"<p>Commanders and pilots of elemental bound vehicles, such as lightning rails, wind galleons, or the new air ships. Pilots are often members of House Lyrandar or House Orien. However there are those who are just teamsters in caravans, or ship masters from the Lhazaar Principalities.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Athletics, Boating, Common Knowledge, Cosmology, Gambling, Piloting, Repair</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Natural Swimmer</p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Any leadership edge</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Ace, Acrobat, Boarder, Rope Monkey</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Storm Chaser, Wind Sense</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.7w65EIgR0PjvvXF0"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"WMP04MKwGhgfLNla","name":"Movement","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Movement</h2>\n  <p>\n    Characters can move a number of tabletop inches equal to their Pace each turn, and may freely set their facing as they do so.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Each inch of movement spent climbing, crawling, or swimming uses 2″ of Pace.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Running:</strong> A hero can “run” as a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action} once per turn,\n    increasing her Pace for the round by her running die (a d6 by default) at the cost of a −2 penalty to all other actions that turn. Running dice never\n    Ace. (The running die is random to account for nuances of terrain not depicted on the tabletop and for the “risk to reward” decision players must make.)\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Out of combat situations, a character can move twice the sum of her full Pace + maximum running die for a number of minutes equal to half her Vigor\n    die type. Thus a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Fleet-Footed]{Fleet-Footed} character with Vigor d6 can sprint at a Pace\n    of 32 for three minutes.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Difficult Ground:</strong> Each inch a hero moves over rough terrain\n    such as thick forest, up or down a steep incline, slippery ice, etc., counts\n    as 2″ of her Pace. Crawling is unaffected by Difficult Ground.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Hazards:</strong> If the GM feels movement is hazardous for some\n    reason--climbing under duress, swimming a fast-moving river, walking a\n    tightrope--she can require an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll to move. Success means she continues on normally. \n    Failure means she can’t move. With a \"@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} the character takes \n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from <strong>Bumps &amp; Bruises</strong>, falls if climbing or in a precarious position \n    (see <strong>Falling</strong>), or drowns if swimming (see <strong>Drowning</strong>) both in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}.\n  </p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Combat]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aeejh0xnzv6","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Combat keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1SD62JpUgl3LIXrG"}}}
{"_id":"WcENR3Htn0nHdJsm","name":"Climbing","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Climbing</h2>\n  <p>\n    Climbing uses the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} skill, and the basics are covered under <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Movement}</strong>. When the game is in rounds, each inch climbed takes 2″ of Pace.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    No roll is usually needed to ascend ladders or trees with sturdy limbs unless the GM feels there’s a good reason (being chased, injured, etc.).\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Under stress (such as during combat rounds), the climber must roll @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} to make progress. Success means he moves normally, failure means he doesn’t make any progress that round, and a Critical Failure indicates a fall! If\n    secured by a rope or other restraint, he falls half the length of the restraint and suffers Fatigue from <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}</strong>. If unsecured, see the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Falling]{Falling}</strong> rules.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Modifiers:</strong> The GM should assign a bonus (+2) if the surface has numerous hand- and footholds or the climber has good equipment. Assign a penalty (−1 to −4) for smooth surfaces, lack of equipment, bad weather, etc.\n  </p>\n\n  <div>\n    <img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/yeti.webp\" />\n  </div>\n\n  <h3>Prepared Climbs</h3>\n  <p>\n    Break lengthy ascents like climbing mountain sides into three roughly even sections. Assume any falls occur at the \"top\" of each section.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The GM might also consider using the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dramatic Tasks]{Dramatic Tasks}</strong> system if the surface must be ascended in a certain amount of time — such as before weather hits, guards return, etc.\n  </p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4txb7iklyvb","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Hazards keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.pZmd90mFLiput2h3"}}}
{"_id":"WgsZrMpvPDwBfgXi","name":"Human","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Human</h1>\n<p>The first human settlers came to Khorvaire about 3,000 years ago, landing in the area now known as the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Lhazaar Principalities]{Lhazaar Principalities}. From there, they began a slow but inexorable spread across the continent, disrupting the placid elven empire of Aerenal and leaving further ruined remnants of fallen Dhakaani goblin kingdoms in their wake. During this migration, they founded the settlements that would grow into the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Five Nations]{Five Nations}. Even today humans make up the majority of the population in these countries. Despite their relatively short lifespans—or perhaps because of them—humans are innovative, adaptable, and aggressive, always pushing their limits and pursuing new ideas.</p>\n<p>Humans prove extremely diverse; a barbarian from the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Demon Wastes]{Demon Wastes} has little in common with a Brelish rogue. When creating a human character, consider where you're from and how that's reflected in your class and background. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Aundair]{Aundair} is a logical place of origin for a wizard character, but your wizard could be a down-andout arcanist from the alleys of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Sharn]{Sharn} or a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Lhazaar Principalities]{Lhazaar} pirate with a knack for the mystic arts.</p>\n<h3>Humans and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>Five different dragonmarks appear among humans, reflecting their dominant status among the races of Khorvaire:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Making]{Mark of Making} </em>is found in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Cannith]{House Cannith}, which has used it to become one of the most powerful houses, creating an abundance of both magical and technological wonders.</li>\n<li>The <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Handling]{Mark of Handling} </em>appears in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Vadalis]{House Vadalis}, which uses it to breed fine mounts and other creatures.</li>\n<li>The <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Passage]{Mark of Passage} </em>aids the humans of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Orien]{House Orien} in operating the lightning rail and trade caravans running across the continent.</li>\n<li>The <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Sentinel]{Mark of Sentinel} </em>makes the bodyguards, mercenaries, and Sentinel Marshals of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Deneith]{House Deneith} widely respected across Khorvaire.</li>\n<li>Humans also number among @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Tharashk]{House Tharashk} and manifest the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Finding]{Mark of Finding}</em> with their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Half-orc]{half-orc} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Orc]{orc} kin.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Adaptable: </strong>umans are extremely easy to adapt and learn new things. They begin play with one free @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Novice} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge}. They must meet all the requirements for the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge} as usual. They also gain a d6 in any one @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Attribute} instead of a d4. This does <em>not</em> increase the attribute limit.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}:</strong> Humans from Sarlona start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Riedran} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/human.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/human.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.p3IjYDRfpFs5fvXk"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"WraAjojcW3QT4Mn4","name":"Barbarian","content":"<p>Even in these enlightened times, primal warriors linger on the edges of Khorvaire. Fearsome fighters, defined by durability, speed, instinct, and the ability to channel oneself into a physical frenzy. Traditionally barbarians are savage champions of cultures seen as primitive, relying on force and fury in place of sophisticated techniques.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Fighting, Intimidation, Notice, Riding, Stealth, Survival</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Alertness, Berserk, True Berserker, Brawny, Brute</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Any combat edge</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Monster Hunter</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Humiliate, Provoke, Strong Willed, Iron Will</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Danger Sense, Liquid Courage</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.OwFGvHEjm9cHtgDD"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"X3HTifMkEwLlwKTi","name":"Ammo Table","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"4\">Ranged weapons ammunition</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Ammunition</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Cost</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Weight</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Notes</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow]{Arrow}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 cp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.05 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow, Alchemist's Acid]{Arrow, Alchemist's Acid}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.2 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">Explode in a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Small Blast Template} causing 2d4 acid damage.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow, Alchemist's Fire]{Arrow, Alchemist's Fire}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.2 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">Explode in a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Small Blast Template} causing 2d4 fire damage.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow, Alchemist's Frost]{Arrow, Alchemist's Frost}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.2 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">Explode in a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Small Blast Template} causing 2d4 frost damage.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow, Alchemist's Spark]{Arrow, Alchemist's Spark}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.2 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">Explode in a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Small Blast Template} causing 2d4 spark damage.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow, Blunt]{Arrow, Blunt}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4 gp/20</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.5 lbs/20</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">Non-lethal damage.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow, Grappling]{Arrow, Grappling}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.5 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">Half range.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow, Smoke]{Arrow, Smoke}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.25 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">Fills a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{Small Blast Template} with smoke.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow, Sticky]{Arrow, Sticky}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">40 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.25 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">Alchemical arrow that <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangles}</em> a single target.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Arrow, Whistling]{Arrow, Whistling}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 sp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.05 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">Emit a keening sound audible within 30\" of it's flight path.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bolt]{Bolt}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 cp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">.05 lbs</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bolt, Alchemist's Acid]