{"_id":"X683x7mOEytP1E9Z","name":"Evasion","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Evasion</h2>\n  <p>Some attacks are slow or require the user to “telegraph” their delivery, like flamethrowers or dragon’s breath. \n\t\tSuch attacks state they may be Evaded. If an attack <em>doesn’t</em> say it can be \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Evasion]{Evaded}, it can’t— \n\t\tvictims are simply hit if the attack is successful and take damage.</p>\n\t<p>If an attack can be Evaded and the character is aware of it, he makes an Agility roll at −2. \n\t\tThose who are successful manage to avoid the attack and take no damage.\n\t\tIf this was an area effect attack, the GM should place the figure to the side or rear of the template \n\t\tas makes sense in the situation.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1r8FbVsCs6nKHleQ"}}}
{"_id":"XNUtg8SGOTzQVuBT","name":"Wizard","content":"<p>As a wizard, you’re an arcane scientist and, like any scientist, you could be diligent, eccentric, or even stark-raving mad. Among the other magically inclined, you have every reason to be proud of your talents. Bards? Stage magicians obsessed with fame. Sorcerers? Freaks who won the genetic lottery. You earned your power. You’re a bona fide genius and it’s unlikely that anyone will soon forget how bright your brilliance burned, especially if you go out in a fireball of glory.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Common Knowledge, Cosmology, Language, Lore, Science, Spellcasting</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Magic), Arcane Resistance, Improved Arcane Resistance, Linguist, University Trained</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Channeling, Concentration, Power Surge, Wizard</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Familiar, Scholar</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.23nhljaxcjJ23SWE"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Xb9qG3Vf9kH7qjRU","name":"The Wild Die","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>The Wild Die</h2>\n  <p>Extras roll a single die when making a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll}. \n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} roll an extra d6 and take the highest of \n    their Trait die or the “Wild Die.” Both of these dice can Ace (see below).</p>\n\n<p><strong>One Wild Die Per Action:</strong> When Wild Cards roll multiple dice for a single action, they roll only one Wild Die. \n    It may replace a Trait die or be ignored--it never adds another action or attack to the roll.</p>\n\n<blockquote class=\"flavor\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> A fighter has the <em><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Frenzy]{Frenzy}</strong></em> Edge. \n    He rolls an extra Fighting die when making a melee attack along with a Wild Die. Only two of his dice can cause hits since the Wild Die can only replace a die, \n    not add another attack.\n</blockquote>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0urjihl2ptj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Rules keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.zEzVhxckliT5E0mN"}}}
{"_id":"Xmyol3CnHsjJ0ZeJ","name":"Spy","content":"<p>The lords, nobles, dragonmarked houses and wealthy merchants of the cities of Khorvaire like to keep tabs on one another, probing for weaknesses and looking for ways to take advantage of each other. They often send spies to infiltrate their enemies, who work undercover and send back reports to their employers. A spy often pretends to be of another profession as a means to remain undetected.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Common Knowledge, Fighting, Gambling, Intimidation, Performance, Persuasion, Shooting, Stealth, Thievery</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Alertness, Charismatic, Linguist, Quick</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Escape Artist, Honey-Tongue, Investigator, Jack-of-all-Trades, Thief</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Streetwise</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.bK89SODAdsBQv317"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
