{"_id":"YlQ8wzGsRiFRNjYL","name":"Tiefling","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Tiefling</h1>\n<p>Many tieflings are born to the Carrion Tribes, the barbarians who live in the Demon Wastes. Such tieflings are touched by the fiendish forces bound beneath the Wastes, and the tribes consider them to be blessed. If you're playing such a tiefling, why have you left the Wastes? It could be that you were destined for some evil purpose-perhaps even serving as an avatar for an imprisoned Overlord-and you are fleeing that destiny.</p>\n<p>Other tieflings are shaped not by fiendish powers, but by the influence of the fiend-tainted planes. Such tieflings might be born in manifest zones, where a plane exerts influence over a region. Planar tieflings are oddities, often seen as strange but not necessarily evil.</p>\n<p>Finally, the Venomous Demesne—a city-state hidden on the far side of Droaam—is populated by tieflings. These tieflings descend from Sarlonan mages who bargained with dark powers, with the Demesne's lords being powerful warlocks and wizards. The Venomous Demesne has had no significant contact with the Five Nations and few know it exists. Your character could be an envoy or exile from it, or simply an adventurer driven by a desire to see what lies beyond your homeland.</p>\n<h3>Self-Reliant and Suspicious</h3>\n<p>Tieflings rarely appear in the cities and towns of Khorvaire, with most dwelling at the fringes of civilization. Tieflings subsist in small minorities found mostly in human cities or towns, often in the roughest quarters of those places, where they grow up to be swindlers, thieves, or crime lords. Sometimes they live among other minority populations in enclaves where they are treated with more respect.</p>\n<p>Lacking a homeland, tieflings know that they have to make their own way in the world and that they have to be strong to survive. They are not quick to trust anyone who claims to be a friend, but when a tiefling’s companions demonstrate that they trust him or her, the tiefling learns to extend the same trust to them. And once a tiefling gives someone loyalty, the tiefling is a firm friend or ally for life.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Darkvision]{Darkvision}:</strong> Tieflings infernal heritage allows them to see into the darkness of Khyber. Darkvision ignores up to –4 penalties for all @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Illumination} up to 10\" away. Beyond 10\" they ignore up to –2 penalties. Such vision is in black and white (monchrome) only.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Fiendish Sorcery]{Fiendish Sorcery}: </strong>Tieflings inherently have innate magic from their fiendish ancestry. Tieflings can choose two of the following powers: <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Confusion]{confusion}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Light/Darkness]{darkness}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Empathy]{empathy}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{illusion}</em>, <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Mind Link]{mind link}</em>, or <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Puppet]{puppet}</em>.\n<p>The tiefling has 10 Power Points that recharge normally. As a limited free action, they automatically activate the power with a success for its regular cost, or with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} for an additional Power Point.  They may use applicable <strong>Power Modifiers </strong>if desired.</p>\n<p>Fiendish Sorcery doesn’t grant access to Edges requiring an Arcane Background. If they also has an Arcane Background, none of its Edges, abilities, or Power Points can be used with Fiendish Sorcery (and vice-versa).</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Infernal Resistance]{Infernal Resistance}: </strong>Due to Teiflings infernal heritage they recieve a +1 bonus to resist acid, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cold]{cold}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heat]{heat} and fire effects. Damage from these sources is also reduced by 1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}:</strong> Tieflings may start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Infernal} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Outsider (Tiefling)]{Outsider (Major)}:</strong> Tieflings are viewed with heavy suspicious in most areas of civilizied culture. Tieflings have a –2 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{persuasion} rolls made to influence those who aren't their kind. They also have very few is any legal rights in most civilized nations.</li>\n<li><strong>Spirited:</strong> Tieflings have a strength of spirit and willpower. They start with a d6 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Spirit} instead of a d4. This increases maximum @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Spirit} to d12+1.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/tiefling.webp\" /></div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/tiefling.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.9HqI82YeMZdTAeIK"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":5},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Yq1zbc1vsRzjCojQ","name":"Orc","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Orc</h1>\n<p>Thousands of years beforc humans came to Khorvaire, the land was dominated by wild orcs and goblinoids of the Dhakaani Empire. The goblin empire scattered the orc tribes and forced them into harsh and unwanted lands: the swamps of the Shadow Marches, the Demon Wastes, and the depths of the Ironroot Mountains. But in the Shadow Marches, the orcs learned the secrets of druidic magic from the dragon Vvaraak, becoming the first of the Gatekeepers. With the invasion of the alien daelkyr from Xoriat, the Gatekeepers put the dragon's teaching to the test, creating magical seals that bound the daelkyr in the depths of Khyber and protected Eberron against further incursion from the plane of madness.</p>\n<p>Three prominent groups of orcs have survived into the present age:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Ghaash'kala are servants of the Silver Flame (which they call Kalok Shash, the \"binding flame\"), who devote their lives to battling the fiends of the Demon Wastes. Humans from the Carrion Tribes of the wastes sometimes hear the call ofKalok Shash and join the Ghaash'kala, leading to a significant population of half-orcs there.</li>\n<li>The Jhorash'tar orcs are a perpetual threat in and around the Ironroot Mountains, shaped by their resentment of the Mror dwarves who drove them underground. These orcs are isolated from humans, so half-orcs here are rare.</li>\n<li>The Shadow Marches holds the largest numbers of orcs and the most significant population of half-orcs.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Orcs of the Shadow Marches</h3>\n<p>The orc Gatekeepers played a crucial role in defeating the daelkyr and binding their evil in Khyber, and their descendants continue to maintain the ancient seals and fight aberrations spawned by the daelkyr's corruption. However, many orcs succumbed to that same corruption and embraced the madness of the cults of the Dragon Below. orcs who follow both of these paths continue to live in the Shadow Marches, and centuries of battles between them have diminished both sides.</p>\n<p>Humans settled in the Shadow Marches long ago, and the first half-orcs helped to cement the bond between these outsiders and the native orcs. Certain Marcher clans contain humans, orcs, and half-orcs in roughly equal numbers.</p>\n<p>When playing an orc or half-orc character from the Shadow Marches, consider what circumstances brought you into the wider world. The Leaving the Shadow Marches table offers some inspiration.</p>\n<h3>Half-orcs and Dragonmarks</h3>\n<p>The <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Mark of Finding]{Mark of Finding}</em> appears among orcs of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Tharashk]{House Tharashk}. Dragonmarked orcs work extensively with humans and half-orcs in pursuit of the house's mission of bounty hunting, inquisitive work, and prospecting. Across Khorvaire, anyone who wants to find something or someone turns to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Tharashk]{House Tharashk}.</p>\n<h2>Racial Abilities</h2>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Brutish Size: </strong>Orcs are naturally strong. They start with a d6 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} instead of a d4. This increases their maximum @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} to d12+1 Additionally, they are larger than humans standing about 6 1/2-7 1/2 feet tall, increasing their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} (and therefore their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}) by 1.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Language]{Language}: </strong>Orcs may start with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Dwarven}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Goblin} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Orcish} depending on where they are from, instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common}.</li>\n<li><strong><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Low Light Vision]{Low Light Vision}</strong>:</strong> Orc eyes are accustomed hunting at night, having eye's similiar to a cats. Low Light Vision ignores up –2 penalties for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Dim and Dark Illumination}. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Pitch Darkness} remains unaffected.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Primal Brute]{Primal Brute}: </strong>Orcs focus on core strength and fitness over coordination and flexibility. They treat @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} as linked to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Agility} for purposes of Advancement. The character may also resist @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Tests} with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} if she chooses. Finally, Orcs increase the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Short Range} of any thrown item by +1. Double that for the adjusted @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Medium Range} , and double again for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Long Range}. If a thrown item’s Range is 3/6/12, for example, an Orc's Range is 4/8/16.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-racial-abilities.Primal Passion]{Primal Passion (Major)}: </strong>Orcs are reactive and driven by a primal passion. They often take action without thinking things through.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/orc.webp\" /></div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/races/orc.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.PIgr30tajsiG03nz"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":6},"cf":{"id":"temp_di56kj2145l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.1. Races","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"YxOmp1XHPSkI0LoD","name":"Aftermath and Extras","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Aftermath &amp; Extras</h2>\n  <p>\n    If it’s important to know what happens to Extras who were @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}\n    during a fight, make a Vigor roll for each. Those who succeed survive and\n    must be cared for, taken prisoner, or released. This can present interesting\n    challenges for your heroes in the aftermath of savage combat!\n  </p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Healing]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yxu1ag41di","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Healing keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9efS8PDbAytHODNh"}}}
{"_id":"Z2ekzQtFXSnlBF8Z","name":"Size and Scale","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Size and Scale</h2>\n\t<p>Characters and creatures have a Size ranging from −4 for very small beings up to Size 20 and higher for massive behemoths. \n\t\tSpecific creature Sizes are listed in their statistics, and explained on the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Size Table]{Size Table}</strong>.</p>\n    <p>The Size Table lists seven different “Scales,” from Tiny to Gargantuan, and the Scale Modifier that goes with each.</p>\n\t<p>When creatures of different Scales attack each other, the smaller creature <em>adds</em> the difference between its Scale and its target to its attacks. \n\t\tA Tiny fairy (−6 Scale modifier), for example, adds +10 to attack a Huge dragon (+4). \n\t\tThe larger creature <em>subtracts</em> the difference from its attacks. \n\t\tA Very Small eagle (−4) subtracts 2 from its Fighting totals when attacking a Tiny fairy (−6).</p>\n\t\n\t<table>\n\t\t<colgroup>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t\t<col></col>\n\t\t</colgroup>\n\t\t<tbody>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\">\n\t\t\t\t\tScale Modifiers\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tModifier\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\tScale &amp; Examples\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−6\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Tiny:</strong> Armor joint, baseball, mouse\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−4\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Very Small:</strong> Human hand or head, basketball, house cat\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t−2\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Small:</strong> Human limb, bobcat\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t—\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Normal:</strong> Human, bull, horse\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t+2\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Large:</strong> Hippo, most vehicles\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t+4\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Huge:</strong> Dragon, whale\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t+6\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t\t<td>\n\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Gargantuan:</strong> Building, kaiju, ship\n\t\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t</tbody>\n\t</table>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.jPdOgnX9r5Qa6mcv"}}}
{"_id":"ZTDoRmjFdaQlHYKl","name":"Masterwork","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h2>Masterwork</h2>\n<p>Masterwork items are finely crafted versions of normal gear made by top artisans.</p>\n<p>Weapons of masterwork quality are +1 AP. Masterwork melee and ranged weapons add 300 gp to the cost.</p>\n<p>Masterwork arrows, bolts, or other ammunition subtract 1 point of Range penalty at Long or Extreme Range, and cost six additional gold pieces per unit. Masterwork ammunition loses its bonus after use even if recovered.</p>\n<p>Armor and shields of masterwork quality reduce the Minimum Strength requirement by one die type, to a minimum of d4. Shields cost an extra 300 gp, while armor costs an extra 150 gp <em>per piece.</em></p>\n<p>You can’t usually upgrade existing armor, weapons, or shields to masterwork quality— they must be crafted to high standards from the beginning.</p>\n<p>The availability of masterwork items— whether for sale in the marketplace or commissioned— depends on the size of the settlement and is up to the GM. Such items typically take twice as long to create if commissioned.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Special Materials]{See Special Materials here}</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.lDlA8nZ7gxnatdiR"}}}
{"_id":"ZccN4AQ8NHW3ssFz","name":"Two Weapons","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Two Weapons</h2>\n  <p>A character armed with two melee weapons adds +1 to his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls if his foe has a single weapon or is unarmed, \n\t\tand has no shield. It adds no bonus against creatures with <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons}</strong>.</p>\n\t<p>Wielding two small ranged weapons offers no special advantage other than additional ammunition or narrative embellishments.</p>\n\t<p>Those wanting to specialize further can take the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Two-Weapon Fighting]{Two-Weapon Fighting}</strong>Edge.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.c7MpSd7TJpzCM6Ep"}}}
{"_id":"ZorZKqztTyK1U0AA","name":"6 Arcane Devices","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Arcane Devices</h1>\n  <p>\n    A character with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Artificer]{Artificer} \n    Edge can focus powers into devices for herself or others. The advantage is that they \n    can be given to and used by allies. The trade-off is that devices take a little \n    preparation to create and can be lost or destroyed.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    In <cite>Pathfinder for Savage Worlds</cite>, arcane devices are usually\n    sacred, enchanted, or otherwise magically powered objects in line with the\n    creator’s Arcane Background. For example, a cleric with Artificer may create\n    a silver talisman with the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{relief}</em> power, \n    while a druid may make a wooden amulet with the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{beast friend}</em> power.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Note:</strong> Arcane devices are relatively temporary items crafters can create with their powers and the Artificer Edge. \n    More permanent magic items are created differently, with additional requirements for ample\n    undisturbed time and resources. See Magic Items entries for more details.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Creation</h3>\n  <p>\n   Creating a device takes one hour per power that can be activated through it. The player must list which powers are \n    in the device and then allocate @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} to it. \n    The device can only use the powers and Power Points allocated to it.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Power Points invested in an arcane device are lost to the inventor until\n    they’re used or recovered with <strong>Tinkering</strong>. \n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Power Modifiers:</strong> A user may spend a device’s Power Points\n    as desired, including enabling any applicable\n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}.\n  </p>\n  <p>Arcane devices may not be <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shorting]{Shorted}</strong>.</p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Limitations:</strong> Arcane devices may benefit from\n    <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Limitations]{Limitations}</strong>.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Activation:</strong> The creator uses his arcane skill as usual.\n    Others use whatever skill is associated with the device’s form— bows use\n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, \n    knives use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing), \n    and so on. If there is no other obvious skill, such as for a potion or worn item, the character rolls the\n    inventor’s arcane skill as if it were his own (he does <em>not</em> benefit\n    from any of the creator’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edges} or other abilities, however).\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Failure to activate the device costs one of the device's @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Point},\n    and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} \n    causes the user @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Tinkering:</strong> A creator can reassign up to five \n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points}\n    per action between an arcane device and her own pool. She must be in\n    physical contact with the item to do so. Characters should lend out their\n    devices very carefully!\n  </p>\n\n  <h2 class=\"example\">Arcane Device Examples</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    A powerful vizier makes an <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{invisibility}</em> cloak and gives it to one\n    of his spies. He has 20 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} and puts 5 of them into the cloak,\n    reducing his remaining pool to 15.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    When the spy wants to turn <em>invisible</em>, she rolls the vizier’s \n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} skill. \n    This costs 1 less Power Point than usual because of the cloak’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Limitations]{Limitation}— \n    it must be worn to activate so it has a Range of Touch.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The vizier also gives the spy the <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> power in the form of a wand\n    and invests it with 10 Power Points. The spy rolls @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} to activate the\n    wand.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The spy suffers  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} if she rolls \n    a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} activating either\n    device.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Once the cloak or wand is out of energy, the vizier can recover the Power\n    Points he invested in it normally.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Meanwhile, Ezren the wizard makes an “oil of sharpness” for Valeros the\n    fighter. When rubbed on a sword it activates the \n    <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em> power. Ezren\n    invests four Power Points into it. The pair soon find themselves in battle\n    with the undead. Valeros rubs the oil on the blade and rolls Ezren's\n    Spellcasting. The roll fails, which drains the oil of one Power Point. Next\n    turn, Valeros tries again, getting a raise and granting the sword +4 damage.\n    <em>Smite</em> normally costs 2 Power Points but Ezren's Trapping has\n    the Range Limitation so it only costs 1 point for each application. See\n    <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</strong>.\n  </p>\n  <div>\n    <img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/npc-codex.webp\" />\n  </div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_vv8zdhdw0l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.lHTqnJNuGpk4HI9q"}}}
{"_id":"ZsJH3vR3Sxp5OApK","name":"Hinder or Hurry","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Hinder or Hurry, Modifier</h2>\n    <p>\n        The target is slowed in some way, perhaps due to intense cold, a slippery surface, or even binding matter or energy. His base Pace is reduced by 2.</p>\n    <p>\n        A caster can @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hinder or Hurry]{Hurry} the recipient instead, granting increased energy, sure\n        footing, or more powerful muscles. His Pace is increased by 2.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n        Effects of either modifier aren’t cumulative.\n    </p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{See full Powers rules here}</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{See full Powers list here}</p>\n&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Updated upstream\n    <p>@Compendium[@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n=======\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Stashed changes\n    \n    \n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.f932sPsBphFB4lV6"}}}
{"_id":"a6zhxHsRdTKFfSg3","name":"Minimum Strength","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Underlined Header</h2>\n  <p>Certain items have a “Minimum Strength” required to use without penalty. Note that some items list a d4 since it is possible to have a Strength lower than d4.</p>\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\n\t\t\t\t<li><strong>Armor/Shields/Worn Gear:</strong> Each die type differ­ence between the character’s Strength and the item’s Minimum Strength inflicts a −1 penalty to Pace (minimum of 1), Agility, and Agility-related skill rolls. This is cumulative for those weak but determined adventurers who wear or use multiple items too heavy for their build.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><strong>Melee/Thrown Weapons:</strong> A thrown or melee weapon’s damage die is limited by the user’s Strength die. If a scrawny kid (Strength d4) picks up a long sword (Str+d8), he rolls d4+d4 damage instead of d4+d8. Also, if the user’s Strength is less than its Minimum Strength, he doesn’t benefit from any of the weapon’s positive abilities such as Reach or Parry bonuses. He still retains any penalties, however.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><strong>Weapons:</strong> The user suffers a −1 attack penalty for each die step difference between his Strength and the weapon’s minimum.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Pg3vdY3wcCDvIij5"}}}
{"_id":"aZEJmkUkqowudAkK","name":"Casting Requirements","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Casting Requirements</h2>\n    <p>\n        A character must be able to see his target and cannot be\n        <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound}</strong> or silenced.\n      </p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{See full Powers rules here}</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{See full Powers list here}</p>\n&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Updated upstream\n    <p>@Compendium[@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n=======\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Stashed changes\n\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Activation]{See full rules here}</p>\n    \n    \n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.tvOzAPcuJBLqVxKJ"}}}
