{"_id":"hdxrlLEkbHxVD6CA","name":"4 Traits","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<div>\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Traits</h1>\n</div>\n<p>Characters are defined by their \"Traits,\" attributes and skills ranked by die types. A d6 is average for humans, while higher die types reflect much greater ability.</p>\n<p><strong>Attributes</strong> are primarily passive or innate abilities used for resisting effects like fear or supernatural attacks. <strong>Skills</strong> are used to <em>actively</em> do things or affect others.</p>\n<p>Exceptions occur, but these are the foundational differences between the two concepts.</p>\n<h2>Attributes</h2>\n<p>Attributes don’t directly affect skill rolls. <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> treats learned knowledge and training as the most relevant and direct factors. A high attribute allows one to increase a skill faster and opens up options to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges} that greatly differentiate two characters with the same skill.</p>\n<p>Every character starts with a d4 in each of five attributes and has five points with which to improve them.</p>\n<p><strong>Agility</strong> is a measure of a character’s nimbleness, dexterity, and general coordination.</p>\n<p><strong>Smarts</strong> measures raw intelligence, mental acuity, and how fast a heroine thinks on her feet. It’s used to resist certain types of mental and social attacks.</p>\n<p><strong>Spirit</strong> is self-confidence, backbone, and willpower. It’s used to resist social and supernatural attacks as well as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fear]{fear}.</p>\n<p><strong>Strength</strong> is physical power and fitness. It’s also used as the basis of a warrior’s damage in hand-to-hand combat, and to determine how much he can wear or carry.</p>\n<p><strong>Vigor</strong> represents an individual’s endurance, resistance to disease, poison, or toxins, and how much physical damage heroes can take before they can’t go on. It is most often used to resist @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} effects, and as the basis for the derived stat of Toughness.</p>\n<h3>Using Attributes</h3>\n<p>Attributes are used to:</p>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>Determine how fast skills increase during <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Advancement}</strong>.</li>\n<li>Limit access to <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges}</strong>, including Class Edges.</li>\n<li>Derive secondary statistics such as Toughness or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Melee Attacks]{melee} damage.</li>\n<li>Resisting powers or social attacks such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Taunt]{Taunt} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}; @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Evasion]{evading} @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Area Effect Attacks]{area effect attacks}.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Skills</h2>\n<p>Heroes have 12 points to buy skills during character creation. A skill that’s below the linked attribute (noted in parentheses beside the skill name) is cheaper to increase than one that’s at or above it. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Character Creation}</strong> and <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Advancement}</strong>. </p>\n<p>Core skills are marked with a <span class=\"red\">red star</span>, and start at d4 for player characters.</p>\n<p>Characters can attempt skills they don’t have but it’s more difficult. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Unskilled Attempt]{Unskilled Attempts}</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Academics (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Academics]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Academics reflects knowledge of the arts, history, archaeology, religion, and similar fields, or the ability to find that information. If an explorer wants to research when the Imperial Calendar began or cite a line from <em>Azvadeva Pujila</em>, or use his linguistic expertise to decipher a dead language, this is the skill to have.</p>\n<h3 class=\"red star-icon\">Athletics (Agility)</h3>\n<p>Athletics combines an individual’s coordination with learned skills such as climbing, jumping, balancing, wrestling, swimming, throwing, or catching. Characters who rely on physical power more than coordination can take the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Brute]{Brute}</strong> Edge to link this skill to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Strength} instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Agility}.</p>\n<h3>Battle (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Battle]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Battle is an individual’s command of strategy and tactics. It can be used for general military knowledge and is critical when commanding troops in <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mass Battles]{Mass Battles}</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Boating (Agility)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Characters with this skill can handle most any common waterborne boat or ship. They also know how to handle common tasks associated with their vessel such as tying knots, rigging sails, or following currents.</p>\n<h3 class=\"star-icon red\">Common Knowledge (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Characters roll Common Knowledge to know people, places, and things of their locale, including etiquette, geography, culture, current events, contacts, and customs.</p>\n<aside class=\"sidebar float-right\">\n<h1>Languages</h1>\n<p>Most individuals speak several languages. Instead of languages being skills, heroes in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> either know a language or they don't. All characters know Common plus a number of languages equal to half their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Smarts} die (typically chosen from the native language(s) listed in their Ancestry). Each increase on Smarts earns the character another language.</p>\n<p><strong>Comprehension:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Taunt]{Taunt} require the character to make herself understood to be effective. If a hero attempting one of these skill is using a language the target doesn't understand, the attempt is made at –2.</p>\n<table><colgroup> <col></col> <col></col> </colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Common Eberron Languages</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Language</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Typical Speakers</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Abyssal</td>\n<td>Demons and evil outsiders.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Aklo</td>\n<td>Inhuman or otherworldly monsters; evil Fey.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Aquan</td>\n<td>Aquatic creatures.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Auran</td>\n<td>Flying creatures.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Celestial</td>\n<td>Angels and good outsiders.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Common</td>\n<td>Humans and hero races.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Draconic</td>\n<td>Dragons and reptilian humanoids.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Druidic</td>\n<td>Druids.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dwarven</td>\n<td>Dwarves.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Elven</td>\n<td>Elves and half-elves.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Giant</td>\n<td>Cyclops, Giants, Ogres, and Trolls.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Gnome</td>\n<td>Gnomes.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Goblin</td>\n<td>Bugbears, Goblins, and Hobgoblins.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Gnoll</td>\n<td>Gnolls.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Halfling</td>\n<td>Halflings.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ignan</td>\n<td>Fire-based creatures.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Infernal</td>\n<td>Devils and evil outsiders.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Orc</td>\n<td>Orcs and half-orcs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sylvan</td>\n<td>Centaurs, Fey, plant creatures, and unicorns.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Terran</td>\n<td>Earth-based creatures.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Undercommon</td>\n<td>Drow, duergar, morlocks, and svirfneblin</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</aside>\n<h3>Driving (Agility)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Driving]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Although rare on Eberron, Driving allows a hero to control any powered ground vehicle. Self-powered transports use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, while beast-drawn conveyances use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding}.</p>\n<p>Driving rolls are typically only needed in dangerous or stressful conditions, such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Chases]{chases} or when navigating dangerous roads or attempting to race through crowded city streets.</p>\n<h3>Faith (Spirit)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Cleric]{Clerics} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Druid]{druids} use Faith as the arcane skill required for their <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Miracles)]{Arcane Backgrounds}</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Fighting (Agility)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Fighting covers all hand-to-hand (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Melee Attacks]{melee}) attacks, whether it’s with fists, axes, swords, or martial arts. It reflects skill as well as raw power, savagery, and fearlessness.</p>\n<h3>Gambling (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Gambling]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Gambling is common in taverns, roadside inns, the barracks of most armies, or below decks of ships at sea.</p>\n<p>To simulate an hour of gambling without having to roll for every single toss of the dice or hand of cards, have everyone agree on the stakes, such as 10 gold coins, etc. Everyone in the game then makes a Gambling roll. The lowest total pays the highest total the difference times the stake. The next lowest pays the second highest the difference times the stake, and so on. If there’s an odd man left in the middle, he breaks even.</p>\n<p class=\"example\"><strong>Example:</strong> A rogue rolls highest with a 10 and the bard rolls lowest with a 4. The difference is 6, so the bard pays 6 × the stake of 10, or 60 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Cheating:</strong> A character who cheats adds +2 to his roll. The GM may raise or lower this modifier depending on the particulars of the game or the method of cheating. If a cheater rolls a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}, however, she's caught. The consequences depend on the circumstances and who noticed, but are usually unpleasant!</p>\n<h3>Healing (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Healing has multiple uses, from treating Wounds to diagnosing diseases and analyzing certain kinds of forensic evidence.</p>\n<p>See the rules on mending and treating @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds}, and treatment of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Disease]{disease} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Poison]{poison}.</p>\n<p>Healing can also be used to analyze evidence that relates to anatomical trauma, including cause of death and approximate time, a general angle of attack, and similar matters. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Success} provides basic information and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} increases the details uncovered.</p>\n<h3>Intimidation (Spirit)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Intimidation is the art of frightening an opponent so that he backs down, reveals information, or flees.</p>\n<p>Intimidation is an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Opposed Rolls]{opposed roll} resisted by the opponent’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Spirit}. In combat, this is a <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test}</strong>. Out of combat, a successful roll means the foe backs down for the most part, reveals some information, or slinks away when the opportunity presents itself. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} might mean the target backs down for the remainder of the scene, spills all the beans, or runs away as fast as possible.</p>\n<p>In or out of combat, a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} on the roll means the target is immune to this character’s Intimidation attempts for the remainder of this encounter!</p>\n<p><strong>Networking:</strong> Intimidation can also be used as a \"macro\" skill to simulate several hours of working the streets. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Networking]{Networking}</strong> to see how to crack some heads for favors or information.</p>\n<h3 class=\"star-icon red\">Notice (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Notice is a hero’s general awareness and alertness. It’s used to sense sights, sounds, tastes, and smells, spot clues, detect ambushes, spot hidden weapons on a foe, or tell if a rival is lying, frightened, happy, etc.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Success} conveys basic information— the character hears movement in the forest, smells distant smoke, or senses someone isn’t being completely truthful.</p>\n<p>A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} grants more detail, such as the direction of a sound or odor or what topic a person is avoiding or lying about.</p>\n<h3>Occult (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Occult]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Occult reflects knowledge and experience of magical and supernatural events, processes, items, and creatures.</p>\n<p>It can be used to decipher glyphs, recall information about Eberron's monsters, recall cures for supernatural maladies like lycanthropy or vampirism, and so on.</p>\n<p>Finding information in a library, a wizard’s lair, or in an old dusty tome uses the Academics skill. If the investigator’s Occult skill is higher, she may use that instead. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Academics]{Academics}</strong>.</p>\n<p>Some esoteric information will be familiar to people with certain skills. If the situation warrants (and with the GM's permission), you may substitute @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Faith]{Faith} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} in place of Occult.</p>\n<h3>Performance (Spirit)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>A good entertainer can lift spirits, rally a crowd to action, or simply earn a few coins from the locals. Specifics depend on the situation, setting, and how well the character is known in the area.</p>\n<p>Performance covers singing, acting, playing an instrument, or similar tasks that require an audience to appreciate. It is also the arcane skill used by bards.</p>\n<p><strong>Raising Funds:</strong> The amount of money a character can raise by performing is extremely subjective, but as a general rule a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{successful} performance earns 50 gp × the character's Rank (Novice 1, Seasoned 2, 3 for Veteran, 4 for Heroic, and 5 for Legendary). A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} doubles the amount earned.</p>\n<p>If the performer has built up a solid reputation in the area or the venue is particularly large, the GM should increase the base gp value appropriately.</p>\n<p><strong>Deception:</strong> Performance can be used instead of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} if the character is attempting to deceive, bluff, or disguise herself and the GM agrees it makes sense in the context of the situation.</p>\n<aside class=\"sidebar float-left\">\n<h1>Reactions</h1>\n<p>The GM can use the table below to roll or choose a character or group’s initial attitude.</p>\n<table><colgroup> <col></col> <col></col> </colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Reaction Table</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">2d6</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Initial Reaction</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">2</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Hostile:</strong> The target is openly hostile. He may attack if possible, or otherwise betray, report on, or hinder the party at the first opportunity. He doesn’t help without an overwhelming reward or threat of some kind.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">3</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Unfriendly:</strong> The character isn’t interested in helping unless he has little choice and/or is offered a substantial payment or reward.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">4–5</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Uncooperative:</strong> The target isn’t interested in getting involved unless there’s a significant advantage to himself.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">6–8</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Neutral:</strong> The character has no particular attitude toward the group. He expects fair payment for any sort of favor or information.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">9–10</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Cooperative:</strong> The character is generally sympathetic. He helps if he can for a small fee, favor, or kindness.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">11</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Friendly:</strong> The individual goes out of his way for the hero. He likely does simple tasks for very little, and is willing to do more dangerous tasks for fair pay or other favors.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"centered\">12</td>\n<td>\n<p><strong>Helpful:</strong> The target is anxious to help the hero and probably does so for little or no reward.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</aside>\n<h3 class=\"star-icon red\">Persuasion (Spirit)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Persuasion is the ability to convince others to do what you want through reason, cajoling, deception, rewards, or other friendly means. Persuasion isn’t mind control. It can change someone’s attitude but not their goals. A bandit may let you keep a sentimental piece of jewelry with a good Persuasion roll but still takes all your other goods.</p>\n<p>When used to <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}</strong> allies it’s an unopposed roll. If the target is resistant, it’s an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Opposed Rolls]{opposed roll} vs. the target’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Spirit}. The GM should modify the roll as appropriate based on roleplaying, any pertinent @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Hindrance Summaries]{Hindrances} that affect the conversation, and the circumstances.</p>\n<p><strong>Reaction Level:</strong> How much a person is willing to cooperate depends largely on their attitude toward whoever’s talking to them. The Game Master can decide how nonplayer characters feel based on the setting, or roll on the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-tables.Reaction]{Reaction Table}</strong> (see sidebar) when having no preconceived notions.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Success} improves the target’s attitude one level and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} improves it two. Further increases aren’t generally possible in the same encounter— it takes individuals a little time to adjust their biases.</p>\n<p>Failure means the target won’t change his mind this encounter or until the situation changes in some important way. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} also <em>reduces</em> the target’s attitude two levels.</p>\n<p>Only one roll should generally be allowed per interaction unless new information is revealed, a substantial reward is offered, etc.</p>\n<p><strong>Networking:</strong> Characters can also use Persuasion as a \"macro skill,\" simulating a few hours or an evening’s time hobnobbing and socializing to gain favors or information. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Networking]{Networking}</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Piloting (Agility)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Piloting]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Although rare on Eberron, Piloting allows a character to maneuver any kind of airship.</p>\n<p>A being with the innate ability to fly (having wings, for example) uses @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} instead.</p>\n<h3>Repair (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Repair is the ability to take apart and/or fix mechanical gadgets, vehicles, weapons, and other simple devices. It also covers the use of demolitions and explosives.</p>\n<p>How long a Repair roll takes is up to the GM and the complexity of the task. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Success} means the item is functional. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} on the Repair roll halves the time required.</p>\n<p><strong>Tools:</strong> Characters suffer a minor penalty (−1 to −2) to their roll if they don’t have access to basic tools, or a major penalty (−3 to −4) if the device requires specialized equipment.</p>\n<h3>Riding (Agility)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Riding allows a hero to mount, control, and ride any beast or beast-drawn vehicle. This includes horses, camels, dragons, wagons, chariots, and the like. See the rules for <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mounted Combat]{Mounted Combat}</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Science (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Science]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Those with this skill have studied various disciplines from architecture to natural sciences to engineering and other \"hard\" sciences.</p>\n<p>A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{successful} roll reveals basic information about a topic, and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} grants more details.</p>\n<h3>Shooting (Agility)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Shooting covers all attempts to hit a target with a ranged weapon such as a bow or crossbow (thrown weapons use <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}</strong>). See @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Combat]{Chapter Three} for details on ranged combat.</p>\n<h3>Spellcasting (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Sorcerer]{Sorcerers} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Wizard]{wizards} use Spellcasting as their arcane skill when casting spells. See @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{Chapter Five} for more information on magical powers.</p>\n<img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/taldor.webp\" />\n<h3 class=\"star-icon red\">Stealth (Agility)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Stealth is the ability to hide and move quietly. A simple @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{success} on a Stealth roll means the character avoids detection if enemies aren’t particularly alert. If the character fails the roll, the enemy realizes something is amiss and begins actively searching for whatever roused them.</p>\n<p>Once foes are alerted and active, Stealth is opposed by @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} (a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Group Rolls]{group roll} if there are many foes).</p>\n<p>The GM should apply any circumstantial penalties to Notice rolls for darkness, cover, noise, distractions, and any difference in the target’s Scale (just like when attacking, see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale}</strong>). Sneaking through dry leaves might subtract 2 from the Stealth roll, for example, while spotting someone in the dark uses the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Illumination} penalty. Don’t apply the same modifier to both rolls, however. If Stealth is at −2 for the leaves, don’t give Notice a +2 for them as well.</p>\n<p><strong>Attacking from Stealth:</strong> Sneaking up close enough to make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Melee Attacks]{melee} attack <em>always</em> requires an opposed Stealth roll versus the target’s Notice, whether the guard is actively looking for trouble or not.</p>\n<p>If @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{successful}, the attacker is considered on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{Hold} and the victim is <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Vulnerable}</strong> to him (but not others) until the attacker’s turn ends (not the defender’s in this case). With a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, the attacker has <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.The Drop]{The Drop}</strong> instead.</p>\n<p>Before the attacker strikes, the defender and any other beings on his side must check for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Surprise]{Surprise}. The attacker may come off Hold and resolve his strike; then the rest of the round progresses normally.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Movement}:</strong> In combat, characters roll Stealth each turn as a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action} at the end of their move or any action the GM thinks might draw attention.</p>\n<p>Out of combat, the distance moved depends entirely on the situation. The GM might want a roll every minute if the group is sneaking around the perimeter of a defensive position, or every few miles if they’re trying to quietly walk through a dark forest without alerting the creatures that live there.</p>\n<h3>Survival (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Survival allows a character to find food, water, or shelter in hostile environments. It can also be used to navigate wilderness environments, figure out which plants are good to eat and which aren’t, and so on.</p>\n<p>A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{successful} Survival roll provides enough food and water for one person for one day; or five people with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}.</p>\n<p>More detailed information on <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hunger]{Hunger}</strong> and <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Thirst]{Thirst}</strong> can be found under <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Tracking:</strong> Survival can also be used to detect and follow tracks. Each roll generally covers following the tracks for one mile, but the GM should adjust this as needed for specific circumstances. A character moves at half@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace} and cannot run while tracking a foe.</p>\n<p>The Game Master should assign a bonus or penalty based on the target, environment, and time. Tracking a large group that recently passed through a snow-covered area might grant a bonus of +4, while following a single person over rocks and streams after more than a day incurs a −4 penalty.</p>\n<img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/daggermark.webp\" />\n<aside class=\"sidebar float-right\">\n<h1 class=\"center\">Comprehensive Modifiers</h1>\n<p>Rather than a long list of specific bonuses and penalties to skill rolls such as Stealth, Survival, Thievery, etc, <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> leaves any modifiers to the GM.</p>\n<p>This approach allows her to look at the entire situation and assign a bonus or penalty as the situation requires, usually from +4 to −4. She can consider all the factors more generally, especially those that overlap, like dual penalties for rain or darkness that both limit visibility and therefore shouldn’t stack, and assign an overall modifier without having to consult a table in the middle of a tense scene.</p>\n<p>As a general guideline, +/–1 is a very minor modifier and +/–2 is a typical advantageous or disadvantageous circumstance. A modifier of −3/–4 means the task is very difficult, and extremely unlikely to do well (a raise result), while +3 /+4 all but guarantees @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{success} and makes a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} very likely.</p>\n</aside>\n<h3>Taunt (Smarts)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Taunt]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Taunt attacks a person’s pride through ridicule, cruel jests, or oneupmanship.</p>\n<p>Taunt is an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Opposed Rolls]{opposed roll} resisted by the opponent’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Smarts}. In combat, this is a <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test}</strong>.</p>\n<p>Out of combat, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{success} means the defender backs down, slinks away, or starts a fight. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} might leave the victim cowed for the remainder of the encounter, cause them to storm out in tears, or even make a reckless attack.</p>\n<p>A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} on the Taunt means the target is immune to this character’s Taunts for the remainder of the encounter.</p>\n<h3>Thievery (Agility)</h3>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{See the skill here}.</p>\n<p>Lockpicking, safecracking, picking pockets, sleight of hand, setting and disabling traps, and similar acts of misdirection, sabotage, subterfuge, and manipulation are called Thievery.</p>\n<p>If used to pick a lock, crack a safe, disable a trap, or perform a simple unopposed action, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{success} opens or disables the device, and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} does it in less time, without tripping alarms, or whatever else the GM feels is appropriate.</p>\n<p>Sleight of hand, hiding or planting an item, or picking a pocket require a simple success. If foes are actively watching the character, Thievery is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Opposed Rolls]{opposed} by @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}.</p>\n<p>The Game Master should assign penalties for particularly difficult circumstances. Picking a heavy padlock might have a −4 penalty, while hiding a dagger in bulky winter clothing might grant a +2 bonus. Failure typically means the character is spotted or it takes too much time (after which the character can try again). A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} typically sets off the trap, alerts the victim, or jams the device so that it must be opened or interacted with in a different way.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_intbwo9s2if","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.lRNoZn2p2zgzj00q"}}}
{"_id":"heSgMAcO34Wen3t0","name":"Paladin","content":"<p>Like clerics, Paladins are the champions of the churches, most notably the Church of the Silver Flame and, in some cases, select churches of the Sovereign Host. Paladins follow an exalted life and are held to a higher standard than even clerics. Clerics can fall to corruption and still retain their abilities, but paladins are above the corruption that can infect a church and adhere to the highest ideals of their faiths.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Athletics, Faith, Fighting, Healing, Persuasion, Riding</p>\n<p><strong>Hindrance:</strong> Code of Honor, Vow</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Arcane Background (Miracles), Charismatic</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Any combat edge</p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Any leadership edge</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Guardian, Knight</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Bolster, Provoke, Strong Willed, Iron Will</p>\n<p><strong>Weird Edges:</strong> Champion</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.w8MXUYWW2zi3Phyx"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"hmAkzsuEpE1NCole","name":"Wandslinger","content":"<p>Magic evolves. When Galifar I forged his kingdom, his wizards hadn’t mastered fire bolt or ray of frost. The development of the simpilier wand magic took centuries, as the Arcane Congress studied Aereni techniques and the powers of sorcery. The soldiers of the united kingdom relied on sword and bow. But as the Last War began, Aundair took stock of its resources. Thanks to the presence of the Arcane Congress, Aundair led Galifar in mystical education. Assembling the first regiment of arcane dragoons, Aundair developed the <em>war staff</em> and <em>battle rod</em>. Over the course of the Last War, these techniques spread across the Five Nations and beyond. Today it’s no surprise to see a tough inquisitive or a Sentinel Marshal with a sword in one hand and a wand in the other. But no one calls these people “arcane dragoons.” If you fight your battles with with <em>assault wands</em>, <em>battle rods</em>, or <em>war staves</em>, you’re known as a “wandslinger.”</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Arcana, Fighting, Performance, Taunt, Wand magic</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges:</strong> Ambidextrous, Arcane Background (Wand Magic), Arcane Resistance, Improved Arcane Resistance, Elan, Quick</p>\n<p><strong>Combat Edges:</strong> Dodge, Improved Dodge, Extraction, Improved Extraction, Level Headed, Improved Level Headed, Two-Fisted</p>\n<p><strong>Power Edges:</strong> Power Surge</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Humiliate, Rabble-Rouser</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.28ZrVCCrEGX0SY49"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"hmSUtKQXgB3r4MNp","name":"Adding and Changing Trappings","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Adding &amp; Changing Trappings</h2>\n    <p>\n        A character can learn two new powers when he takes the\n        <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.New Powers]{New Powers}</strong> Edge. \n        He may instead add @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings} to\n        his powers in place of one or two of the new powers. A hero who takes the\n        New Powers Edge, for example, could choose one new power and add an ice\n        Trapping to her <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>. The GM may also allow a player to\n        <em>change</em> the Trapping of existing power when she gains an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Advance}.\n        This should reflect a major change in the character in some way as\n        determined by the player and GM.\n      </p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{See full Powers rules here}</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{See full Powers list here}</p>\n&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Updated upstream\n    <p>@Compendium[@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n=======\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Stashed changes\n\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{See full rules here}</p>\n    \n    \n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.KEPTUmRJIVeKXB9Z"}}}
{"_id":"hz2KOH8IaL8kn09K","name":"Travel","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Travel</h1>\n<p>Many epic tales feature trips across great expanses. A party may sail the Inner Sea or ride across the frontier of Varisia or navigate every district in Absalom.</p>\n<p>Below are some guidelines to help you figure out how long these journeys take and what dramatic events might happen along the way.</p>\n<p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> If it doesn’t matter how long the trip takes, skip all this. Narrate the journey, maybe do an <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Interludes]{Interlude}</strong>, and get to the next scene. If you need to know how long the trip takes, or want to insert an obstacle or encounter of some sort, use the information below as a guideline.</p>\n<p><strong>The Basics:</strong> The mode of travel determines how many miles the group makes per day.</p>\n<h2>Travel Times</h2>\n<p>The rates below assume reasonable terrain and weather. Difficult conditions can drastically decrease progress (or increase it in the case of sailing with strong winds).</p>\n<table style=\"width:50%;margin:auto\"><colgroup> <col></col> <col></col> </colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Average Travel Times</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Transport</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Miles/8 hour Day</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Foot</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">24</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Horse, Light]{Horse}</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">30</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Cart]{Cart} (one beast)</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">30</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Carriage]{Carriage}</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">40</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Wagon, Light]{Wagon} (per beast)</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">30</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Rowboat]{Rowboat}</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">24</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Sailing Ship]{Sailing Ship}*</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">30</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Steam Ship*</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">40</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Airship (Dirigible)]{Airship (Dirigible)}</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">80</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Glider]{Glider}</td>\n<td class=\"centered\">60</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><em> *Sailing ships are greatly affected by currents and winds. Strong winds or currents in the right direction allow them to travel about 60 miles per day. Poor winds or going against the current reduce them to 20 miles per day or less. </em></p>\n<h2>Encounters</h2>\n<p>If an area is dangerous or lawless, draw a card from the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Deck} once per day (or even two or three times a day in particularly dangerous areas). A face card or higher represents an encounter, and the card suit can be used to determine the type.</p>\n<p>Draw twice more if the card is a Joker and combine the results — such as Enemies and an Obstacle, or Strangers and Treasure.</p>\n<p>Game Masters are highly encouraged to customize encounters based on their setting.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Spades — Enemies:</span> Monsters, enemies, or hostile beasts bar the way. Perhaps they lie in ambush if it’s a popular path, waiting for the next band of unwary travelers.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Hearts — Strangers:</span> The group comes upon neutral or friendly nonplayer characters such as merchants, lost travelers, a guide, or even other adventurers.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Diamond — Treasure:</span> Somewhere along the way is something of value — a caravan eager for trade or a forgotten ruin with treasure— and guardians to protect it!</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Clubs — Obstacle:</span> The heroes encounter an obstacle of some kind and must figure out how to circumvent it. Some examples are a flooded river, a decaying rope bridge, a dangerous whirlpool, etc. The obstacle might be defended by creatures or enemies as well.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"example\">Example: Cinderlands</h2>\n<p>Our heroes are traveling across the frontier of Varisia, traversing the burning plains of the Cinderlands.</p>\n<p>The GM draws a Jack of Clubs and decides the area is currently in the throes of an emberstorm— a dangerous black blizzard of dust and ash. This slows progress to a crawl for hours and makes the characters roll for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from heat and the relentless dusty winds (see the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</strong> section).</p>\n<p>The GM draws again later that day and gets a Queen of Spades. From an unseen burrow under the charred ground, an ankheg surfaces, hungry for fresh prey.</p>\n<div><img src=\"modules/fvtt-swfp/assets/art/p166_Mokmurian_Fight.webp\" /></div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":9},"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.vYLl6c9JNynuusmI"}}}
