{"_id":"nxaDn2NywYgEJOXA","name":"Disarm","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Disarm</h2>\n  <p>A character can try to make an opponent drop a weapon or other object by making an attack against the limb or hand \n\t\t(see <strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Called Shots]{Called Shot}</strong>). \n\t\tIf the attack hits a weapon, the attacker rolls damage normally for an item \n\t\t(no raise effect or Aces, see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Breaking Things}</strong>). \n\t\tThe defender must make a Strength roll equal to the damage or drop the item.</p>\n\n\t<p>If an attack against a target's hand or limb @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shakes} or \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds} him, he must make a Strength roll at −2 if it hit his limb or −4 if it hit his hand. \n\t\tFailure means he drops whatever item is in that hand.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.fThdgxvoyzuNe9P0"}}}
{"_id":"o48ZmxmDpzoIZ48g","name":"Cold","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Cold</h2>\n  <p>\n    Trudging through deep snow for hours on end, facing biting winds, or falling in ice water can wear down and kill even a hearty warrior.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    A character must make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Vigor} roll every four hours spent in weather below freezing (32° F); at −2 if the temperature is below 0° F. Failure means the hero incurs a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} level.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Roll only once per day if a character has appropriate cold weather gear (heavy furs and the like), or once every five days if well-provisioned with shelter, food, and other resources.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Death:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} victims @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{die} after 2d6 hours instead of waking @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Exhausted}.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Recovery:</strong> Victims can recover @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} only after they receive adequate warmth and shelter.\n  </p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4txb7iklyvb","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Hazards keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.gABbcMVDMotapw4c"}}}
{"_id":"oJjFbSjjuIDOeLGV","name":"Networking","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Networking</h1>\n\n  <p>\n    Pathfinders often need to find information or ask for favors. You can\n    roleplay these encounters out, or you can allow them to use their skills in\n    a \"macro\" sense — summing up hours of effort with a single roll.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} is the nice way of interacting with one’s contacts. The flip side\n    of the coin is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}. Either can get the job done but in slightly\n    different ways, as shown below.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> When the player characters want to\n    ask around town for favors or information.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>The Basics:</strong> Characters use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} to\n    gather favors or information.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Persuasion (The Nice Way)</h3>\n  <p>\n    Characters use @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} to socialize within their various social circles\n    for information or favors. When used in this way, Persuasion isn’t a single\n    exchange but several hours of networking, hobnobbing, carousing, drinks,\n    gifts, bribes, or entertaining. This might represent time roaming a\n    marketplace, a series of meetings with important people, or an evening of\n    food and drink.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Success grants most of what the character wants, though it may take a while,\n    cost some money, or require a favor in return. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} either gets more of\n    whatever he was looking for, or at a lower cost.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Failure means the hero’s efforts are in vain. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means he’s\n    cut off from that particular group for a while (up to the GM but typically about a week).\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Money Talks:</strong> You can catch more flies with honey than\n    vinegar, the saying goes. A character with a little lucre to spread around\n    gets a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{reroll} on her networking attempt, spending money on better bribes,\n    gifts, or wining and dining her contacts.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The amount required is up to the GM, the location, and the nature of the\n    contact(s) she interacts with. As a rule of thumb, use the expenses listed\n    under <span>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{Carousing}</span> and modify as appropriate from\n    there.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Intimidation (The Not-so-Nice Way)</h3>\n  <p>\n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} can also be used to gather information, call in favors, or make\n    demands, but it’s a little less savory.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Each attempt to \"work the streets\" takes several hours of threats and\n    general unpleasantness, rousting the local populace for whatever the hero\n    needs.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Success grants the character most of what she wants, though her victims\n    might decide to get some payback later on. A raise means she gets more info,\n    gets it faster, or her victims are too scared or otherwise preoccupied to\n    plot revenge.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Failure means the bully doesn’t get anything useful. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}\n    means she ends the evening with a fat lip, black eye, or broken nose (see\n    <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}</strong>). She can work her contacts\n    again the next day, but they’re more likely to be waiting for her this time!\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Busting Heads:</strong> The bruiser can improve her odds by getting\n    more violent or extreme than usual. This alienates her contacts for a week\n    but grants her a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{reroll} on the Intimidation check.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    This raises the stakes as well. A simple failure means the evening ends with\n    <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}</strong>. A Critical Failure bears\n    more serious consequences. The GM might break the action down to an actual\n    encounter (which might be an ambush!). The hero might run afoul of the law,\n    come back with two levels of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from Bumps &amp; Bruises, or her\n    questions might trigger a deadly reaction from a more powerful enemy!\n  </p>\n\n  <h2 class=\"example\">Example: Savage Measures</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    Amiri the barbarian needs to locate a town official held for ransom by\n    nefarious bandits. Her @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} is better than her @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, and she\n    has the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Menacing]{Menacing} Edge, which adds +2 to Intimidation rolls. Time is tight so\n    she decides to bust some heads. That gives her a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{reroll} as well. With the\n    bonus and reroll she gets a success and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}. The barbarian finds the\n    bandit hideout and learns how many goons guard the official.\n  </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.GuXcVph4kABTSXeU"}}}
{"_id":"oLAjTLkRfe8KA6ui","name":"Crew Pay","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Crew Pay</h1>\n<p>The standard fee for sailors is 50 silver sovereigns per month. A crew of 12, for example, costs 600 sp each month in wages. The captain must also pay for their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{provisions}.</p>\n<p>First mates, mages, navigators, healer, artificers, and other specialized crew cost at least an additional 100 sp per month.</p>\n<p>If the crew comes upon a prize of some kind, such as a floating hulk, buried treasure, or the Booty of some creature they manage to kill, it is divided up in shares.</p>\n<h3>Shares</h3>\n<p>Pirate ships and privateers don’t pay their crews—they give them shares of any booty. Paid crews use shares as well when figuring how to split unexpected payouts.</p>\n<p>The typical arrangement often is two shares for the ship’s “bank,” (to be used for repairs, provisions, and so on), three shares for the captain, two shares for the first mate, navigator, mages, super, and surgeon. The rest of the crew get one share each.  </p>\n<h2 class=\"blue-example\">Example: The Jolly Edward's salvage</h2>\n<p><em>The Frigate Jolly Edward sets sail with twelve crew. The crew includes the captain, the first mate, an artificer, and navigator. For the ship this creates a total of 20 shares on the Jolly Edward. 2 for the ship, 3 for captian, 2 for first mate, 2 for artificer, and 9 for the rest of the crew.</em></p>\n<p><em>The Jolly Edward comes upon a derelict ship. They salvage the cargo on board it. When the cargo is finally sold at Regalport. The Jolly Edward gains 400 galifars. So each share is worth 20 galifars. The ship's \"bank\" gets 40 galifars, the captain 60, first mate and artificer 40 each, and each of the rest of the crew gets 20 gp.</em></p>\n<p><strong>Hunger:</strong> Wild Cards suffer from starvation normally (one provision a day counts as adequate food). For the rest of the crew, make a group @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Vigor} roll each day they have half rations (one provision for every two men). Subtract 2 if the men have less than this.</p>\n<p>Should the crew collectively reach @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{Incapacitated} state, 10% of the men perish each day from starvation. Most crews mutiny long before this starts to happen.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Boarding]{Boarding}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranks of Archers]{Ranks of Archers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Sinking]{Sinking}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6g48t5q06rw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"oPEbUM3YO1HnjWZU","name":"Game Master Bennies","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Game Master Bennies</h2>\n  \n  <p>Game Masters start each session with a pool of one Benny per player character. These may be used by any of her characters (including non-Wild Cards!).</p>\n    <p>The GM’s Wild Cards also have Bennies of their own, a base of three modified by their Edges and Hindrances. They can use these or any of the Bennies in the common pool\n        as the GM wishes.</p>\n    <ul>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Joker’s Wild:</span> Anytime the villains draw a Joker, put one Benny in their general pool and give another to each enemy @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card}.\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0urjihl2ptj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Rules keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.0Y8PsBKEtehUok2K"}}}
{"_id":"oY3kPP5PFYeZfhC4","name":"Damage","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Damage</h2>\n  <p>Damage is listed in terms of dice. Projectile weapons have fixed damage (such as 2d6). Melee weapons have damage based on the wielder’s Strength die plus another die, as listed under individual weapon entries. A dagger, for instance, inflicts Str+d4 damage.</p> \n  \n  <p>See Applying Damage @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Applying Damage]{here}</p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.QpHqmscpSXVFaXZy"}}}
{"_id":"obG6dv3AdX8PsvIm","name":"Cantrips Activation","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Cantrip Activation</h2>\n    <p>\n        A character may cast a cantrip by making an arcane skill roll. This is an\n        action, and the effect must be based on one of the character’s existing\n        powers. A sorcerer could use <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> with a \n        fire @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trapping} to light a\n        campfire, for example. A druid could use <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> to make vines\n        dance to entertain a group of children. A wizard can use <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{sound}</em> to\n        ring a bell calling a servant to his study.\n      </p>\n      <p>\n        Success means the desired effect occurs. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}\n        has an additional narrative impact of some kind— the candle glows brightly, the vines dance in perfect\n        synchronicity, or the bell rings loud and pure.\n      </p>\n      <p>\n        Failure causes the spell to fail without effect. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}\n        causes the spell to backfire, which requires the caster to lose 1 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points}\n        (or suffer @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} if the caster has no Power Points). Critical Failure also\n        causes an embarrassment or minor mishap of some sort— an animated broom\n        carelessly knocks a jar of ink onto the floor, a conjured flame lights a\n        book on fire, or the power makes an embarrassing sound or smell.\n      </p>\n      <p>\n        A successfully cast cantrip’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Duration]{Duration} is the same as the power it’s based\n        on and may be maintained by spending Power Points as usual.\n      </p>\n      <p>\n        The GM has the final say on what a cantrip can do, but the effect must not\n        replace a power or cause damage (at least directly). It can be used to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test}\n        or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}, or grant a +1 bonus on a subsequent roll in the same encounter.\n        For example, if the bard uses a cantrip to impress the children of\n        Sandpoint, the GM might give him +1 to a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll later on if he\n        talks to their parents or someone else who witnessed the kindness.\n      </p>\n      <div>\n        <img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/halfwizard.webp\" />\n      </div>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{See full Powers rules here}</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{See full Powers list here}</p>\n&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Updated upstream\n    <p>@Compendium[@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n=======\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Stashed changes\n\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Cantrips]{See full rules here}</p>\n    \n    \n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.ljEUJH8ZHd9F1628"}}}
{"_id":"ofFuPTnVboV6K9vd","name":"Glamered","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Armor Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Upon command, a piece of glamered armor changes shape and appearance to assume the form of a normal piece of clothing. The armor retains all of its properties when it is so disguised.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 0</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 900 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Illusion]{Illusion}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"ofgy9z4ARFmfqETK","name":"Stacking Powers","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Stacking Powers</h2>\n    <p>\n        Powers don't stack beyond their maximum benefit or drawback. This\n        includes effects from magic items that specifically use those powers. A ring\n        that simply says it increases Strength a die type does so even if the\n        wearer's Strength is currently increased by\n        <em>boost Trait</em>(Strength), for example. If the same ring said it\n        boosts Strength a die type, however, it would only stack with the actual\n        spell or other items up to the power's maximum (two die types).\n      </p>\n      <p>\n        Powers that target different Traits or abilities, such as\n        <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost/lower Trait}</em>, are considered separate powers in this context.\n        Strength may only be increased up to two die types by <em>boost Trait</em>,\n        for example, but Strength and Fighting could both be boosted up to two die\n        types as each one is a separate Trait. Similarly, a sorcerer could cast\n        <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}</em> (melee) on an ally who's already benefiting from a\n        ring of <em>protection</em> (ranged).\n      </p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{See full Powers rules here}</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{See full Powers list here}</p>\n&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Updated upstream\n    <p>@Compendium[@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n=======\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Stashed changes\n\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Activation]{See full rules here}</p>\n    \n    \n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.oxdOmtbnMoVHPUfK"}}}
