{"_id":"p6yIkqlwVlQCBTp0","name":"Selective","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <h2>Selective (+1)</h2>\n    <p>\n        With intense focus, the caster can choose not to affect any or all\n        individual targets within a power’s area of effect (picking all enemies\n        instead of allies in a <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{blast}</em>, for example).\n      </p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{See full Powers rules here}</p>\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{See full Powers list here}</p>\n&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Updated upstream\n    <p>@Compendium[@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n=======\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{See full Power Modifiers list here}</p>\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Stashed changes\n    \n    \n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_inkjjer1fuj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/Powers keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cp8HdirWE8Z3b0d5"}}}
{"_id":"pIXs0JkdAj0IYDDL","name":"Distance","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Ranged Weapon Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Decrease any @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range} penalties by one when using this weapon.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 1</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 2,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Farsight]{Farsight}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"pOKB7L8FBYoHRVp6","name":"Ranged Attacks","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Ranged Attacks</h2>\n  <p>\n    The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} skill covers everything from bows to crossbows and even some\n    magic items that shoot projectiles. Throwing knives, spears, and other thrown projectiles uses the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} skill.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    All ranged weapons have a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range} statistic written like this: 5/10/20, or\n    Short/Medium/Long Range.\n  </p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Combat]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aeejh0xnzv6","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Combat keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.gBBFCAw4KUsbEufT"}}}
{"_id":"pUyad7MI3dctSTLk","name":"1 Rules","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-heading\">\n        <h1>Rules</h1>\n        <figure class=\"chapter-number\">\n            Chapter Three\n        </figure>\n    </div>\n    \n    \n\n    <p class=\"drop-cap\">S<em>avage Pathfinder</em> provides a simple framework for your tales of adventure and glory. \n        In this chapter we show you how to make basic skill and attribute checks--and make your combats Fast, Furious, and Fun!</p>\n\n    <h2>Wild Cards &amp; Extras</h2>\n\n    <p>Your hero (a player character), and unique allies, villains, and monsters are collectively called “Wild Cards.” \n        These beings have a better chance at doing things, are a little tougher to put down, and are generally more detailed than common guards, minions, or lackeys--\n        collectively called “Extras.”</p>\n\n    <p> Wild Cards are noted with a design of some sort before their name, like this:\n        \n        </p><h3 class=\"dragon-icon\">Goblin Warchanter</h3>\n        In <cite>Pathfinder for Savage Worlds</cite> the Wild Card symbol is a distinctive dragon head. <p></p>\n    <p>Player characters are always Wild Cards. The Game Master must decide which of her nonplayer characters and monsters are Wild Cards. \n        The sergeant of the City Watch probably isn’t a Wild Card, but Sergeant Grimlock of the City Watch may be. \n        Skytch the Dragon is also a Wild Card, though his three young wyrms aren’t.</p>\n    <p>Wild Cards are those who have stepped up to do more than most. They dare, aspire, and risk it all to be a hero--or a villain!</p>\n    <p>They have two special abilities in the game:</p>\n    \n    <ul>\n        <li>Wild Cards can take three @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds} before they’re \n            @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}.</li>\n        <li>Wild Cards roll a Wild Die (usually a d6) along with their skill or attribute die when making Trait rolls and \n        take the highest of the two as their total.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h2>Trait Rolls</h2>\n\n    <p>To make a skill or attribute “check” or “roll,” simply roll the die assigned to it. If the result is a 4 or better (the “Target Number” or TN), the action is successful. \n        For example, if a character’s Strength is a d6, he rolls a six-sided die. On a 4 or better, he’s successful.</p>\n    <p><strong>Modifiers:</strong> Circumstances modify the die roll, such as shooting at something far away or finding a well-hidden clue. \n        Some things, such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Attacks]{ranged attacks}, have standard modifiers. It’s up to the GM to determine any modifiers for more subjective tasks, \n        such as spotting an ambush or eavesdropping on a conversation through a door.</p>\n    <p>In general, an easy task, such as finding tracks in the mud, is made at +2. A difficult task, such as finding tracks by torchlight, is made at −2. \n        A very difficult task, such as finding tracks in a rainstorm, is made at −4.</p>\n    <p><strong>Multiple Dice:</strong> When a character rolls multiple dice, such as when firing two arrows with the \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Rapid Shot]{Rapid Shot} Edge, check each die separately.</p>\n\n    <h3>The Wild Die</h3>\n    <p>Extras roll a single die when making a Trait roll. \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} roll an extra d6 and take the highest of \n        their Trait die or the “Wild Die.” Both of these dice can Ace (see below).</p>\n\n    <p><strong>One Wild Die Per Action:</strong> When Wild Cards roll multiple dice for a single action, they roll only one Wild Die. \n        It may replace a Trait die or be ignored--it never adds another action or attack to the roll.</p>\n\n    <p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> A fighter has the <em><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Frenzy]{Frenzy}</strong></em> Edge. \n        He rolls an extra Fighting die when making a melee attack along with a Wild Die. Only two of his dice can cause hits since the Wild Die can only replace a die, \n        not add another attack.\n    </p>\n\n    <h3>Aces</h3>\n    <p>All Trait and damage rolls in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> are open-ended. \n        That means that when you roll the highest number possible on a die (a 6 on a d6, an 8 on a d8, and so on), you get to roll that die again and add it to the total. \n        This is called an “Ace.” Any modifiers to the die roll should be tacked on after adding up an Aced roll.</p>\n\n    <p class=\"example\">\n        <em><strong>Example:</strong></em> A rogue attempts to leap a dangerous ice chasm. She’s a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} \n        with a d8 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, so she rolls a d8 and a d6 and takes the highest result. \n        In this case, both dice Ace (8 on the d8 and 6 on the d6). She rolls the d8 again and gets a 4 for a total of 12 on the d8. \n        She rolls the d6 again and gets another 6, followed by a 2—that’s a total of 14 on the Wild Die. The wily rogue leaps the chasm with ease! \n    </p>\n\n    <h3>Raises</h3>\n    <p>Sometimes it’s important to know just how successful a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll} was. \n        Every 4 points over the Target Number is called a “raise.” If your hero needs a 4 to shoot an opponent and rolls an 11, he hits with a raise. \n        Figure raises after adjusting for any modifiers.\n    </p>\n    <p>A raise always provides an additional effect of some sort, such as bonus damage when attacking or a benefit determined by the GM for other rolls.</p>\n\n    <h3>Opposed Rolls</h3>\n    <p>Sometimes rolls are “opposed” by an opponent. The attacker gets a Trait total, then the defender attempts to beat it.</p>\n    <p>The exact skills or attributes used in a contest are specified in each circumstance, or the GM can decide what makes the most sense. \n        If two characters try to pull something from each other’s hands, for example, they make opposed Strength rolls. \n        Sneaking up on someone is a Stealth roll opposed by @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} (which is detailed in the Stealth skill description @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{here}).</p>\n    <p>The acting character in an opposed roll always makes the Trait total first (including spending any <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Bennies}</strong>), \n        and must get at least a basic success (TN 4) or he fails. The defender rolls next and must <em>meet</em> or <em>exceed</em> the first character’s result or the attacker wins.\n    </p>\n    <p>The winner also uses the opponent’s total for purposes of determining raise effects.</p>\n\n    <h3>Critical Failures</h3>\n    <p>A Critical Failure occurs when a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} rolls a 1 on both the skill die and Wild Die of a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll}. \n        The attempt automatically fails and something bad happens--a weapon is dropped or gets stuck, the attack hits a friend, the vehicle crashes, spells misfire \n        (see <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Backlash]{Backlash}</strong>), and so on.</p>\n    <p>Critical Failures cannot be rerolled by any means, even with <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Bennies}</strong>.</p>\n    <p><strong>Extras and Critical Failures:</strong> If an Extra rolls a 1 on a Trait check <em>and it’s important to know if it’s a Critical Failure</em>, \n        such as when casting a spell, roll a d6. On a 1, it’s a Critical Failure. Otherwise it’s just a normal failure.</p>\n    <p><strong>Multiple Dice:</strong> Some abilities allow characters to roll multiple Trait dice, such as the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Frenzy]{Frenzy} Edge or \n        firing a weapon with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rate of Fire]{Rate of Fire} higher than 1. A Critical Failure with multiple dice occurs when more than half the die results are a natural 1. \n        If the character is a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card}, the Wild Die <em>must</em> be a 1 as well.</p>\n\n    <p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> \n        A fighter with the Frenzy Edge rolls two Fighting dice and one Wild Die. If two or more of the dice come up 1s, including the Wild Die, it’s a Critical Failure.\n    </p>\n\n    <h3>Unskilled Attempts</h3>\n    <p>If a character doesn’t have a skill for an action he’s attempting, he rolls a d4 for his skill die (and a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.The Wild Die]{Wild Die} if a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card}) \n        and subtracts 2 from the total.</p>\n    <p>The GM may decide certain tasks cannot be attempted unskilled, such as repairing a steam engine or piloting an airship.</p>\n\n    <h3>Reroll</h3>\n    <p>Some Edges or abilities allow a character to reroll Traits (as long as they’re not a \n        @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}). \n        To do so, roll <em>all</em> the dice again and get a new total. You may keep any set you like <em>unless</em> you roll a Critical Failure. This ends all rerolls immediately \n        and becomes the result of the attempt--that’s the risk one takes in pushing the limits!</p>\n    <p>Multiple rerolls may be granted from different @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Bennies}, or other abilities.</p>\n\n    <h3>Group Rolls</h3>\n    <p>When the GM wants to make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll} for a group of Extras with like @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Traits}, \n        roll one Trait die as usual along with a Wild Die and treat this as the group’s result. This gives a decent average without making rolls for every individual.</p>\n\n    <p class=\"example\">\n        <em><strong>Example:</strong></em> \n        A group of soldiers attempts to pass by an enemy encampment. The GM rolls their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} die (a d6) and a Wild Die and takes the best of the two as the soldiers’ total.\n    </p>\n\n    <h2>Bennies</h2>\n    <p>Every now and then, dice rolls may not work in your favor. That’s why <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> gives players a little control over their hero’s fate.</p>\n\n    <h3>Player Character Bennies</h3>\n    <p>Players start each game session with three “Bennies” (American slang for “benefits”), represented by poker chips, gaming stones, the official Bennies we make for all of our games, \n        or other tokens that signify a little bit of good luck or fate. Bennies are discarded at the end of each session--use them or lose them!</p>\n    <p><strong>Combat:</strong> If a session ends in the middle of combat or other dramatic event, wait until it’s resolved in the next session before giving out new Bennies.</p>\n\n    <p><strong>GM Rewards:</strong> Bennies are earned during the game in two ways:</p>\n\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n            <span class=\"list-heading\">Awards:</span> The Game Master should occasionally reward players for clever actions, roleplaying their character (especially any @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Hindrance Summaries]{Hindrances}), or \n            great feats of heroism.<br />She can also award players a Benny for telling a great story in character, delivering a fantastic line that makes everyone laugh, \n            or creating an emotional moment.\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <span class=\"list-heading\">Joker’s Wild:</span> When a player character draws a Joker during combat, <em>all</em> player characters receive a Benny! If the players get both Jokers \n            everyone gets <em>two</em> Bennies!\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h3>Game Master Bennies</h3>\n    <p>Game Masters start each session with a pool of one Benny per player character. These may be used by any of her characters (including non-Wild Cards!).</p>\n    <p>The GM’s Wild Cards also have Bennies of their own, a base of three modified by their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Hindrance Summaries]{Hindrances}. They can use these or any of the Bennies in the common pool\n        as the GM wishes.</p>\n    <ul>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Joker’s Wild:</span> Anytime the villains draw a Joker, put one Benny in their general pool and give another to each enemy \n            @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card}.\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h3>Using Bennies</h3>\n    <p>Bennies may be spent at any appropriate time and don’t incur any sort of penalty. They may only be used for your own character.</p>\n    <p>Here are the ways players can use Bennies.</p>\n    <ul>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Reroll a Trait:</span> Bennies grant a hero a reroll on <em>any</em> Trait (see <strong>Rerolls,</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{here}).</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Recover from Shaken:</span> This is instant and may be done at any time, even interrupting another’s actions if desired. See Shaken @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{here}.</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Recover Power Points:</span> A character with an Arcane Background, Mystic Powers, or any other ability that grants @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} can \n            spend a Benny as a free action to recover five Power Points.</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Soak Rolls:</span> Bennies can be used to prevent @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds} or recover from being Shaken.\n        </li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Draw a New Action Card:</span> When the game is in rounds, a character can spend a Benny to get a new \n            <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Cards}</strong>. \n            This occurs after all cards are dealt and@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Hindrance Summaries]{Hindrances} like \n            @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Quick]{Quick}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Level Headed]{Level Headed}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Hesitant]{Hesitant} are resolved. <em>Then</em> players or \n            the GM may spend Bennies for an additional card as many times as they like and take their choice of all their draws. Edges like Quick or Level Headed <em>do not</em> apply to \n            these additional cards drawn with Bennies. This continues until everyone (including the GM) passes. Then the round begins and no further cards may be drawn.</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Reroll <span>Damage:</span></span> You may spend a Benny to reroll damage. Include any additional dice you may have gained for a raise on the attack roll.</li>\n        <li><span class=\"list-heading\">Influence the Story:</span> This one is entirely up to the Game Master, who may allow a character to spend a Benny to find an additional clue if you’re stuck, \n            come up with some mundane but needed item, or push a nonplayer character into being a bit more agreeable.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <p class=\"example\">\n        <em><strong>Example:</strong></em> The party is adrift on a storm-tossed sea. None of the characters purchased navigational equipment, \n        but @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Harsk]{Harsk} the ranger had been aiding their doomed captain through the previous encounters. Harsk's player asks the Game Master if he might have been given his\n         own compass and maps while aiding the captain, and might still have them in his bag. The GM agrees—for a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny}. \n         Harsk suddenly remembers the tools in his pack and turns the boat toward shore.</p>\n\n    <aside class=\"sidebar\">\n        <h1>Awarding Bennies</h1>\n        <p>It takes a few games to figure out how many @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Bennies} you should award players during a session. In general, we recommend you be fairly free with them, \n            especially early in the game. If someone makes everyone laugh (and isn’t distracting the flow of the game), toss the player a Benny. \n            When players roleplay a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Hindrance Summaries]{Hindrance}, reward them. When someone does something clever or heroic or imaginative, acknowledge it with a Benny.</p>\n        <p>Some GMs worry the game will become too easy if Bennies are too common, but we find the opposite is true. When Bennies are plentiful, \n            players often spend them on trivial things that are important to <em>them</em>. Maybe the rogue <em>really</em> wants to pick the lock on a chest. \n            There’s nothing particularly valuable inside and the player probably knows it, but the character is the <em>rogue</em> and wants to prove it to the rest of the party.\n        </p>\n        <p>When Bennies are scarce, however, players tend to save them for injuries, death, or taking out the big bads. That’s fine, but takes away from the fun and heroics that \n            got them to this point. <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> is about big action and players should be encouraged to take chances. The “currency” of these chances are \n            those Bennies.\n        </p>\n        <p>Veteran <cite>Savage Worlds</cite> GMs might also notice Bennies tend to flow fairly fast early on in a session. The group is settling in, laughing, and are rewarded \n            for roleplaying their Hindrances the first time or two. In the mid-to-late game, Bennies tend to be spent faster than they’re gained. That’s a fantastic pace. \n            It gives the heroes opportunities to do big things in the early and mid-game then forces some critical resource management for the final showdown.\n        </p>\n        <p>If you find yourself being stingy, go the other way the next time you run and see how it affects your group. Then you’ll know what’s right for you and your friends.</p>\n    </aside>\n\n    <h2>Conviction</h2>\n    <p>Conviction is a special award granted when a character experiences a great and meaningful victory; or a painful and catastrophic misfortune. \n        Either drives the hero to increase her efforts, giving her inner strength she can draw on in the most desperate situations.</p>\n    <div>\n        <img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/sorrowful-regret.webp\" style=\"padding:1%\" />\n    </div>\n    <p>Like @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Bennies}, players should receive a physical token of some sort to note their Conviction. \n        The tokens can be spent at any time to add a d6 to all the character’s Trait and damage totals until the beginning of her next turn. \n        This die can @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aces]{Ace}, and its result is added to the final total.</p>\n    <p>Conviction tokens don't stack, but the bonus may be maintained from round to round by spending a Benny at the start of the character's turn. \n        Once Conviction lapses, however, the effect ends.</p>\n    <p>Conviction tokens aren’t Bennies and can’t be used as such. They <em>are</em> kept between sessions, however, and a hero can have more than one \n        Conviction token at a time.</p>\n    <p>\n        <strong>Refresh:</strong> A hero may also spend Conviction to trigger or refresh abilities that are usually only usable once per session, day, encounter, \n        and so on, even if they’ve already been used.\n    </p>\n\n\n    <h2 class=\"example\">Example: Tragedy &amp; Triumph</h2>\n\n    <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Seelah]{Seelah} the paladin of Iomedae and her companions signed on to escort a caravan from Turtleback Ferry to Sandpoint. Over the course of the journey, they made friends with \n        the caravanners. Seelah became particularly close with a young girl she thought of as a daughter, Julia.</p>\n    <p>Then tragedy struck. A savage and brutal band of ogres descended from the hills and attacked the caravan. Seelah and her friends tore into the ogres with savage ferocity,\n         but when the dust settled, Julia was found dead.</p>\n    <p>Given her close relationship with the girl, the Game Master decides Seelah's player gains Conviction. \n        The paladin burns with rage at the murderous ogres and chastises herself for failing to protect her friend.</p>\n    <p>Later on, the party corners the ogres' chief in his hilltop fortress. Seelah personally defeats the brute in single combat and avenges Julia's death. \n        The Game Master decides the paladin's triumph is also worthy of Conviction.\n    </p> \n\n    <div>\n        <img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/campaign-guide.webp\" />\n    </div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_tl96ca99gn","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9WCTAf4B2YXyDViU"}}}
{"_id":"pbCQNBzz4ARtuBAk","name":"Animated","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Shield Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Once per encounter, an animated shield can be loosed to defend its wielder. For the next three rounds, it hovers near its owner, following him if he moves and granting its @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} and cover bonus as usual without needing to be held. Its type still applies for purposes of Armor Interference or Restriction.</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 3</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 10,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Fly]{Fly}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"qGjYjXzmRCGp041W","name":"Diplomat","content":"<p>Khorvaire is a miasma of different races and cultures, and keeping the peace of the Last War is a full time job. As well as trying to maintain the status quo, many diplomats seek to better the options for their nations with the Dragonmark Houses.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Common Knowledge, Language, Lore, Performance, Persuasion, Taunt</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Charismatic</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Femme Fatale/Ladykiller</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Connections, Reliable, Work the Room</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.loVCK5EwenityQtq"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"qOIiUnpBoon5ONtw","name":"Vehicles","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Vehicles</h2>\n<p>Attacking from or on vehicles such as ships, carriages, or airships works as usual— see the section on\n  <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Vehicles]{Vehicles}</strong> for more.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.FnDf7QQuRfG5mptC"}}}
{"_id":"qSksgGlXgKQhAvSO","name":"Reroll","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Reroll</h2>\n  <p>Some Edges or abilities allow a character to reroll @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Trait} (as long as they’re not a \n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}). \n    To do so, roll <em>all</em> the dice again and get a new total. You may keep any set you like <em>unless</em> you roll a Critical Failure. This ends all rerolls immediately \n    and becomes the result of the attempt--that’s the risk one takes in pushing the limits!</p>\n<p>Multiple rerolls may be granted from different @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edges}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Bennies}, or other abilities.</p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0urjihl2ptj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Rules keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.sWUINHx4N1ZAvy8f"}}}
{"_id":"qkHddqwIVbroPmd3","name":"1 Making Characters","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<div class=\"chapter-heading\">\n<h1>Characters</h1>\n<figure class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter One</figure>\n</div>\n<h2>Concept</h2>\n<p>Begin your adventure by thinking about the kind of character you want to play. Do you want to try a wily @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Wizard]{wizard}, a burly @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Barbarian]{barbarian}, a tricksy @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Rogue]{rogue}, or some original idea you’ve come up with yourself? The <cite>Savage Worlds</cite> rules allow you to create most anything.</p>\n<p>For the world of <cite>Savage Eberron</cite>, take a close look at the Class Edges subsection in Setting Edges @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{here}. These special abilities form the foundation of the typical player character types found in Eberron. Keep these in mind as you follow the rest of these steps so you can build toward those if you want to play a traditional Eberron-style hero.</p>\n<h2>Ancestry</h2>\n<p>This core rule book comes with seven recommended ancestries to use when creating player characters. See ancestries for more info @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Ancestries]{here}.</p>\n<h2>Hindrances</h2>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Hindrances]{Hindrances} are flaws, drawbacks, or dark secrets drawn from a character’s backstory. They provide up to four additional “Hindrance points” you can use to enhance your hero during character creation.</p>\n<p>Taking Hindrances not only helps you define and roleplay your hero, but also allows you to increase his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{attribute or skill} points, take @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edges}, or have additional gold to buy better adventuring gear.</p>\n<p>A Major @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Hindrances]{Hindrance} is worth 2 Hindrance points, and a Minor is worth 1. A hero could thus take two Major Hindrances, four Minor, or any combination that adds up to 4 character points. (You can take <em>more</em> Hindrances if you want but the maximum benefit is 4 points!)</p>\n<p><strong>For 2 Hindrance points you can:</strong></p>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>Raise an attribute one die type, or</li>\n<li>Choose an Edge</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>For 1 Hindrance point you can:</strong></p>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>Gain another skill point, or</li>\n<li>Start play with an additional 600 gold pieces.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Traits</h2>\n<p>Characters are defined by attributes and skills, collectively called “Traits.” Attributes and skills are ranked by die types, typically from d4 to d12, with d6 being the average for adult humans. Higher is better!</p>\n<p>Attributes typically govern how fast your skills can increase, and are used for passive effects such as resisting spells or recovering from injuries.</p>\n<h3>Attributes</h3>\n<p>Every character starts with a d4 in each of five attributes: Agility, Smarts, Spirit, Strength, and Vigor (discussed in more detail in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Traits}).</p>\n<p>You then have 5 character points to increase your attributes. Raising a d4 to a d6, for example, costs 1 point.</p>\n<p><strong>Attribute Limit:</strong> No attribute may be raised above a d12 unless an ancestral ability or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edge} says otherwise. Each increase beyond a d12 adds a +1 modifier. Increasing a d12 Strength two steps or “die types,” for example, gives your hero a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Strength} score of d12+2.</p>\n<h3>Skills</h3>\n<p>Skills are learned abilities such as firing weapons, hand-to-hand combat, scientific knowledge, professional aptitudes, and so on.</p>\n<p>Skills in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> are very broad to keep the action simple and straightforward. The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} skill, for example, covers all types of bows and crossbows. The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} skill covers thrown weapons, as well as grappling, swimming, and climbing. Detailed customization comes in the form of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges}.</p>\n<p><strong>Core Skills:</strong> Five skills are marked with a red star in the list for skills in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Traits}: <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}</strong>, <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge}</strong>, <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}</strong>, <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}</strong>, and <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth}</strong>. These are “innate” abilities most adult adventurers have. Unless an ancestral ability, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edge}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Hindrances]{Hindrance} says otherwise, your character starts with a d4 in each of these five core skills.</p>\n<p><strong>Buying Skills:</strong> After core skills are assigned, you have 12 additional character points to raise core skills or buy and raise new skills as you see fit.</p>\n<p>Each die type costs 1 point (starting at d4) as long as the skill is equal to or less than the attribute it’s linked to (listed beside the skill in parentheses, in the list starting in the Skills subsection in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Traits}). If you exceed the linked attribute, the cost becomes 2 points per die type.</p>\n<p><strong>Languages:</strong> Your character starts with Common and knows additional languages equal to half her @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Smarts} die type. Typical choices are listed with each ancestry. See Languages in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Traits} for more information.</p>\n<p><strong>Skill Limit:</strong> Skills may not be increased above d12 during character creation unless the character’s ancestry starts with the skill at d6. If the skill starts with a d6, increase her maximum to d12+1. Elves in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Ancestries]{Ancestries} start with a d6 in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, for example, which means their Notice skill may be increased to d12+1.</p>\n<h3>Derived Statistics</h3>\n<p>Your character sheet contains a few other statistics you need to fill in, described below.</p>\n<p><strong>Pace</strong> is how fast your character moves in tactical situations like combat. Standard Pace is 6, which means six tabletop inches per game round. Each inch is two yards (6 feet) in the real world. <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Movement}</strong> is explained in detail in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Combat]{Combat}.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry}</strong> is equal to 2 plus half your character’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} die type (a total of 2 if a character doesn’t have Fighting), plus any bonuses for shields or certain weapons. This is the Target Number (TN) to hit your hero in hand-to-hand combat.</p>\n<p>For Fighting skills higher than d12, such as d12+1, add half the fixed modifier, rounded down. For instance, Fighting d12+1 grants a Parry of 8, while Fighting d12+2 results in a Parry of 9.</p>\n<p><strong>Size:</strong> A hero’s default @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Size} is 0 unless altered by ancestral abilities, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edges}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Hindrances]{Hindrances}. It cannot be less than −1 or more than +3.</p>\n<p><strong>Toughness</strong> is your hero’s damage thres­hold. Damage rolls that equal or exceed this number @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Applying Damage]{cause harm} (explained later in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Rules]{Rules}).</p>\n<p>Toughness is 2 plus half your hero’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Vigor}, plus @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Armor]{Armor} (use the armor worn on his torso. Vigor over a d12 is calculated just like @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry}, above.</p>\n<h2>Edges</h2>\n<p>Attributes and skills are a character’s basic statistics, but what really makes individuals different are their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges}.</p>\n<p>In <cite>Pathfinder for Savage Worlds</cite>, every character starts with a Class Edge for free. The character must qualify for the Edge as usual. (If a player doesn’t want to take a Class Edge, she may take a free Background or Professional Edge she qualifies for instead.)</p>\n<p>Characters get additional Edges by taking @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Hindrance Summaries]{Hindrances}, from racial abilities (such as Humans’ Adaptability), or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Advances} once play begins.</p>\n<p>A comprehensive list of Edges for use in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> is available @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{here}.</p>\n<h2>Gear</h2>\n<p>Player characters have 300 gold pieces (or “gp”) to purchase any of the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Personal Weapons]{weapons}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Armor]{armor}, and adventuring gear presented in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{the Gear Chapter}.</p>\n<p>This might represent everything the character owns or it may represent only “adventuring” gear, with the hero’s more mundane belongings stored at a home or elsewhere.</p>\n<h2>Background</h2>\n<img class=\"float-right\" style=\"shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/p18_Crafting_Spear_Maker.webp')\" src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/p18_Crafting_Spear_Maker.webp\" />\n<p>Finish your new hero by filling in any additional history or background you see fit. Ask yourself why she’s where she is and what her goals are. Where does she live? Does she have any close friends or family who might be relevant to the game? Why did she join the Pathfinders?</p>\n<p>Or just start playing and fill in these details as they become important and you walk around in her shoes a bit.</p>\n<p>You might also want to talk to the other players. Maybe your characters know each other right from the start. Or you might collectively decide to optimize your group a bit and ensure you’ve got a good assortment of skills and abilities. If so, make sure you’re playing what you want to play. There’s no point in being the party’s healer if that’s not a role you care to play.</p>\n<h3>Deities and alignment</h3>\n<p>The conflict between Good and Evil is a core theme of any <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> game. Typically, heroes fight for Good, but not always.</p>\n<p>Alignments in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> indicate the general moral compass of a person, creature or organization. Where alignment is listed, it is a tool for the Game Master to identify the broad outlook of that entity, and how it may interact with others, including the adventurers. When choosing an alignment for your character, you decide what ethical path he will follow, guided by the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Hindrance Summaries]{Hindrances} you chose to define him. Unless your GM specifically agrees, you cannot choose Evil as your alignment.</p>\n<p>Some character concepts require choosing a deity or “Domain” that governs powers and certain abilities. Likewise, the player’s choice of Hindrances can involve a Deity or a cause, such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Vow]{Vow} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Code of Honor]{Code of Honor}. Deities have a listed alignment, either Good, Neutral, or Evil to indicate the general philosophy of the deity and her followers. Of course, adherents to a particular faith might not necessarily share the same outlook as the deity's alignment. Terrible deeds might be perpetrated in the name of a good or merciful god. You can find more information on domains and deities in the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edges} section.</p>\n<div>\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Character creation summary</h1>\n<h3>Concept</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>Start with a general idea of what you want to play. Review the classes and the Iconic Path character profiles for ideas.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Ancestry</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>Choose your character’s ancestry from the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Ancestries]{ancestries} entry and apply any special abilities it grants.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Hindrances</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>Choose up to 4 points of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Hindrances]{Hindrances} (Major Hindrances are worth 2, Minor are worth 1).\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>For 2 Hindrance points you can raise an attribute one die type, or choose an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edge}.</li>\n<li>For 1 Hindrance point you can gain another skill point, or gain 600gp in additional starting funds.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Attributes</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Attributes} start at d4. You have 5 points to distribute among them. Each step costs 1 point.</li>\n<li>Attributes may not be raised beyond d12 unless the hero’s ancestry or class states otherwise.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Skills</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} are core @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{skills} and start at d4 for free. Any given skill might be increased because of ancestry.</li>\n<li>You have 12 points to put into these or any other skills. Each die type costs 1 point up to and equal to the linked attribute; then 2 points per die type after that.</li>\n<li>Your character knows Common plus a number of starting Languages equal to half your character’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Smarts} die type. A Smarts of d6, for example, gives you three additional starting languages. Typical choices are listed with each ancestry.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Derived Statistics</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li><strong>Standard @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace}</strong> is 6 and may be adjusted by ancestral abilities, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edges}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Hindrances]{Hindrances}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry}</strong> is 2 plus half of Fighting.</li>\n<li><strong>Toughness</strong> is 2 plus half of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Vigor}, plus any @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Armor]{Armor}. Track the amount of armor in parentheses like this— Toughness: 11 (2). This means 2 points of the total 11 Toughness comes from Armor. An @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor Piercing]{Armor Piercing (AP)} attack could bypass those 2 points but not the other 9.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Edges</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>All characters get a Class Edge for free (or a Background or Professional Edge if desired).</li>\n<li>Use any leftover @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Hindrances]{Hindrance} points to take @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Edges]{Edges} if you like.</li>\n<li>Each Edge costs 2 Hindrance points.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Gear</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>Purchase up to 300 gp worth of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{equipment}.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Background</h3>\n<ul class=\"bullet\">\n<li>Unless the Game Master says otherwise, your character’s basic Alignment is Good or Neutral for purposes of certain@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges}, abilities, and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.8 Powers]{powers}. Beyond that, who is she? Where does she come from? Does she have any family? Does she worship any of Eberron’s major deities?</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div><img style=\"shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/pathfinderrpg.webp')\" src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/pathfinderrpg.webp\" /></div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_intbwo9s2if","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.BN83CxFdZeLigPTe"}}}
{"_id":"qkjzekxatRh8bviu","name":"Firing Into Melee","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Firing into Melee</h2>\n  <div>\n\t\t<img src=\"/assets/art/PF17.webp\" />\n\t</div>\n\t<p>Occasionally, heroes have to fire into the middle of hand-to-hand fights. \n\t   The trouble is that even though we might see figures standing perfectly still on the tabletop, \n\t   in “reality,” they’re circling each other, wrestling back and forth, and moving erratically. \n\t   For that reason, firing into a tangle of people, such as a melee, is quite dangerous. \n\t   Use the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Innocent Bystandards]{Innocent Bystander}</strong> rules when this occurs.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1lBwaD4TozRhYx3L"}}}
{"_id":"r1TYWhlyGeNUcC8c","name":"Downtime","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Downtime</h1>\n  <p>\n    Adventurers often have time between their epic quests. Some might spend it\n    practicing their sword fighting techniques or enchanting magic items. Others\n    may pray to their gods, try to earn a few coins in town, spend time with\n    their friends, or aid locals in need.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> When the party has at least a week between adventures.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>The Basics:</strong> Each player chooses one of the activities below and gains its benefits.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Personal Time</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    When the Game Master decides there’s Downtime of at least a week, you can\n    choose one of the following activities. Each provides a benefit of some\n    sort, from financial rewards to limited but valuable skill bonuses. Narrate\n    what your hero is doing then follow the instructions under each activity.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Unless an option says otherwise, its effect may only be gained once regardless of how long the downtime lasts.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Carouse</h3>\n  <p>\n    Carousing characters spend their time socializing with friends, making new\n    ones, or cementing relationships with their contacts. This usually involves\n    considerable cost and time spent at local restaurants and taverns.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    During her Downtime, the character spends 50gp in food, drink, and\n    entertainment. Double that for each Rank thereafter: 100 gp for Seasoned,\n    200 gp for Veteran, 400 gp for Heroic, and 800 gp if she’s Legendary.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    In exchange, she gains a local favor she can call in at any time. The\n    greater her Rank and her overall standing in the community (GM’s call), the\n    greater the favor.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Center</h3>\n  <p>\n    The hero focuses on whatever brings her happiness. That might include\n    quality time with friends, a solitary hunt through a secluded forest, riding\n    a favorite horse, painting, reading, writing, performing, dancing, or\n    courting a romantic interest.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Whatever the activity, the goal is inner peace and happiness. Taking a week to enjoy the fruits of one’s labors grants the character Conviction.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Earn</h3>\n  <p>\n    The hero earns currency in some way. Perhaps he takes on odd jobs, kills\n    rats in the local tavern, or even \"procures\" it from the local\n    thieves' guild!\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The hero must make a relevant skill roll to earn her reward — @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} for\n    scoundrels, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} for Mercenaries, \"@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} for entertainers, etc. Use\n    an appropriate attribute for more mundane jobs.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means the character doesn't make any money and\n    embarrasses herself somehow. If the job was dangerous, she also takes d4 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds}. Failure means she doesn't make any money and takes @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}<strong>.\n  </strong></strong></p><strong><strong>\n  <p>\n    Success earns her 100 gp if she's Novice rank, 200 gp if Seasoned, 300 gp if Veteran, 400 gp for Heroic, and 500 gp if she’s Legendary. Double the reward with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Enchant</h3>\n  <p>\n    A character with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Artificer]{Artificer Edge} can spend her time at a workshop creating @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Devices Creation]{magic items}.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Train</h3>\n  <p>\n    An adventurer can practice a specific skill or attribute to temporarily\n    increase its effectiveness. A character might train @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} by sparring\n    with a swordmaster, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} by public speaking, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Occult]{Occult} by studying \n    forbidden tomes, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{Strength or Vigor} with vigorous exercise, and so on.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The character must possess at least d4 in any skill chosen for training.\n    Afterwards, she gets one free @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{reroll} when failing that skill or attribute\n    for one entire encounter. This stacks with any other rerolls she may have from other sources.\n  </p>\n  <p>The player chooses when to activate her rerolls as a free action.</p>\n  <p>If she Trains again, the previous focus is lost.</p>\n  <img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/city.webp\" />\n  <h3>Research</h3>\n  <p>\n    A character can spend her Downtime developing or learning new powers. This\n    doesn’t permanently give her a power, but allows her to use any spell or\n    miracle from her Available Powers list and of her Rank or lower for one\n    entire encounter.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The character may also temporarily change the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trapping} of a power she already has for one encounter — turning a fireball into an ice blast, for example.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The spell is cast at a −2 penalty, but is otherwise treated just like one of the caster’s regular powers. This can be particularly useful if the mage or priest must prepare to face a threat with a particular weakness.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Finally, Research can also be used to reveal deep information about a particular subject. No @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll} is required. The GM decides just how much the investigator can learn in a week given the topic, the location, and resources at hand.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Rest</h3>\n  <p>\n    Those who have suffered grievous @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds} might need to do so during Downtime to recover their health.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Use the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Healing]{Natural Healing}</strong> rules during the week.  Any healers in the group can provide @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}, as can other allies or hired professionals such as priests at a temple, or physicians in a nobleman’s employ.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Characters may choose to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rest]{rest} even if they have no Wounds. The provides the same benefits as Centering, with the hero doing nothing but resting mind and body to recover from the stress of adventuring.\n  </p>\n</strong></strong></div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":9},"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.KH8Zu7VcwrBTn66W"}}}
{"_id":"r5lE43dA61yrLc1J","name":"Careening","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Careening</h1>\n<p>Wooden vessels must be “careened” on occasion. The ship is beached and turned on its side so that barnacles, sea worms, and other parasites can be scraped off. Failure to careen a ship every four months decreases its speed. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Vehicle Notes]{Handling} is reduced by one every month thereafter, to a maximum penalty of –4.</p>\n<p>Any of the Great Ports offer careening for 50 golden galifars times the vessel’s base @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}, and is done in a number of days equal to half its base @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}.</p>\n<p>A ship can also be careened on an island by its crew. This is a tiring and tedious process, taking a number of days equal to the craft’s base @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness} (a base @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness} of 17 requires 17 days, for instance). This is an average number based on the standard crew for a ship that size. A crew with twice the usual number of workers can careen the vessel in half the time, half the required crew takes twice the time, and so on.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Ship Setting Rules</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor and Swimming]{Armor and Swimming}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Boarding]{Boarding}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Careening]{Careening}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Pay]{Crew Pay}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Crew Provisions]{Crew Provisions}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fighting Below Deck]{Fighting Below Deck}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Contact]{Nautical Contact}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Navigation]{Navigation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranks of Archers]{Ranks of Archers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Fire]{Ship Fire}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Sinking]{Sinking}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ship Repairs]{Ship Repairs}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Storms at Sea]{Storms at Sea}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6g48t5q06rw","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Nautical keywords","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"rL6oX7lqCRNnFEfN","name":"Bumps and Bruises","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Bumps and Bruises</h2>\n  <p>\n    Stumbling down a slope or running through a cavern in the dark might cause numerous cuts, scrapes, and bumps.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Characters moving through injurious terrain make an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll. Those who fail gain a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Recovery:</strong> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} levels from Bumps &amp; Bruises improve one level every 24 hours instead of every hour.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    A character may use the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} skill to treat the injuries. Success relieves one level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from Bumps &amp; Bruises and a raise relieves two. Each healer may attempt this roll only once unless the GM decides a change in circumstances warrants another opportunity (finding medical supplies, for example).\n  </p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_4txb7iklyvb","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Hazards keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.D0aEqN5JkGM3UzjS"}}}
{"_id":"rsGzYeMC1p2XA0g2","name":"Unarmed Defender","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Unarmed Defender</h2>\n  <p>It’s difficult to parry a blade with one’s bare hands. An attacker armed with a melee weapon adds +2 to his \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} attacks if his foe has no weapon or shield. \n\t\t(This doesn’t stack with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.The Drop]{The Drop}.)</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6EVpFRBp7j7QvV1k"}}}
{"_id":"rx9Hgk3J6ChBpjMP","name":"Ranged Weapons Table","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"8\">Ranged Weapons</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Type</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Range</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Damage</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">AP</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">RoF</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Min Str.</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Weight</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Cost</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"8\"><span class=\"no-class\">Common Weapons</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Axe, Throwing]{Axe, Throwing}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bow]{Bow}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12/24/48</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">30 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bow, Long]{Bow, Long}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15/30/60</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">75 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bow]{Bow, Composite}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12/24/48</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str +d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">100 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Crossbow, Hand]{Crossbow, Hand}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">6/12/24</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">75 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>Hand-drawn.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Crossbow, Heavy]{Crossbow, Heavy}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15/30/60</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2d8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">18</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>Requires a windlass to load. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reload]{Reload} 2.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Crossbow, Light]{Crossbow, Light}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10/20/40</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>Hand-drawn.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Javelin]{Javelin}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 sp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Knife]{Knife}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Sling]{Sling}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4/8/16</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 sp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"8\"><span class=\"no-class\">Exotic Weapons</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Bolas]{Bolas}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes:</strong></em> A target hit with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Entangled}. Bolas are Hardness 8.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Boomerrang, Talenta]{Boomerrang, Talenta}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">6/12/24</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>On a miss, returns to the thrower.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Boomerrang, Xen'drik]{Boomerrang, Xen'drik}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">6/12/24</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">20 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>On a miss, returns to the thrower.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Cutting Wheel]{Cutting Wheel}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2/4/6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Str+d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>Wielder ignores the –2 penalty on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Traits]{Strength} rolls to resist @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Disarm] attempts.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Net (Weighted)]{Net (Weighted)}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"8\"><strong><em>Notes: </em></strong>A successful hit means the target is <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Entangled}</strong>. The net is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Hardness} 10 and vulnerable only to cutting attacks.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_dl21vgq63wq","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear tables","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"rxx3N1t2lTaCc5Kn","name":"Nonlethal Damage","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Nonlethal Damage</h2>\n  <p>A character who wants to beat someone up without killing them can choose to do nonlethal damage. \n\t\tThis requires the attacker use only his fists or a blunt weapon of some sort. Edged weapons may be used if they have a flat side, \n\t\tbut this subtracts −1 from the attacker’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls.</p>\n\n\t<p>Nonlethal damage causes Wounds as usual, but if a character is rendered @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}, he cannot Bleed out.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.jSAgG9EQrgVS5GWt"}}}
{"_id":"rzXHocFfj0JYEcz7","name":"Mounted Combat","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Mounted Combat</h2>\n  <p>Characters fighting from horseback (or other beasts) have certain advantages and disadvantages in combat, as described below.</p>\n\t<p>Mounts aren’t dealt Action Cards— they act with their riders. Animals may attack during their rider’s action if desired. </p>\n\t<p><strong>Horsemanship:</strong> Characters who wish to fight from horseback must use the lowest of their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}\n\t\tor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding} skills. This also applies to other more extraordinary mounts.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Falling:</strong> If a character is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}, \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stunned]{Stunned}, \n\t\tor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounded} while mounted, or his mount is @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}, \n\t\the must make a Riding roll. If he fails, he falls. If the mount was running, \n\t\tthe rider suffers 2d4 damage (2d6 with a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}). \n\t\tIncrease the damage by an additional die or two if the mount is particularly fast, flies, or the rider falls in particularly rough or dangerous terrain.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Missed Ranged Attacks:</strong> \n\t\tMounts and riders are affected by the <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Innocent Bystandards]{Innocent Bystander}</strong> rules. \n\t\tIf a shot intended at a rider rolls a 1, it hits the mount instead.</p>\n\t<p><strong>Wounded Mounts:</strong> When an animal is Shaken or Wounded, it rears or bucks. A rider must make a Riding roll to stay mounted, or falls as above.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.eqWd1qb1fC72b4Mm"}}}
{"_id":"s6TBU0MflXkaeMd0","name":"Wild Cards and Extras","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Wild Cards &amp; Extras</h2>\n  <p>Your hero (a player character), and unique allies, villains, and monsters are collectively called “Wild Cards.” \n    These beings have a better chance at doing things, are a little tougher to put down, and are generally more detailed than common guards, minions, or lackeys--\n    collectively called “Extras.”</p>\n\n<p> Wild Cards are noted with a design of some sort before their name. \n    In <cite>Pathfinder for Savage Worlds</cite> the Wild Card symbol is a distinctive dragon head. </p>\n<p>Player characters are always Wild Cards. The Game Master must decide which of her nonplayer characters and monsters are Wild Cards. \n    The sergeant of the City Watch probably isn’t a Wild Card, but Sergeant Grimlock of the City Watch may be. \n    Skytch the Dragon is also a Wild Card, though his three young wyrms aren’t.</p>\n<p>Wild Cards are those who have stepped up to do more than most. They dare, aspire, and risk it all to be a hero--or a villain!</p>\n<p>They have two special abilities in the game:</p>\n<ul>\n    <li>Wild Cards can take three @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds} before they’re @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}.</li>\n    <li>Wild Cards roll a Wild Die (usually a d6) along with their skill or attribute die when making @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls} and take the highest of the two as their total.</li>\n</ul>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Rules]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_0urjihl2ptj","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Rules keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.r0H6X9dqYUURygBg"}}}
{"_id":"sCCVHUYELip4NDA5","name":"Damage Effects","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Damage Effects</h2>\n  <p>Damage can result in three effects: @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wounds]{Wounds}, \n    and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitation}.</p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Combat]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aeejh0xnzv6","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Combat keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.wyMaOQJgcazAw5Fa"}}}
{"_id":"sG7NzEEiEQKZAHro","name":"Arrow Deflection","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h3>Shield Enchantment</h3>\n<p>Ranged attacks against the bearer suffer an additional −1 penalty, regardless of the attacker's position (front, rear, etc).</p>\n<p><strong>Enchantment Points:</strong> 1</p>\n<p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Craft:</strong> <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{Deflection}</em></p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_cgm3zn2v579","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/6. Magic Items#/CF_SEP/Enchantments keywords","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"sa0rnE8zOGMjdX0h","name":"Armor Piercing (AP)","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Armor Piercing</h2>\n  <p>The weapon or projectile ignores this many points of Armor value. A weapon with an AP value of 4, for instance, ignores 4 points of Armor. Excess AP is lost.</p>\n\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_kfkrm0kt7s","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1ZWU1fmrLlw4b3v7"}}}
{"_id":"synczfLjS5SKBd3b","name":"Shields Table","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"6\">Shields</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"6\">\n<p>Shields add to a character’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} as long as the defender is aware of the attack. Light shields add +1, and medium and large shields add +2. Facing in melee can usually be ignored since a defender can turn to face individual opponents throughout the combat round. If she's attacked by multiple creatures on the same @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Card}, however, the shield protects against half the attackers (rounded up; defender's call which ones). Ignore that if the shield bearer has a superior position, such as flanked by allies with no foes behind them, blocking a doorway, corner, or narrow hallway, and so on. If using miniatures, remember that they're static but characters in the game world aren't.</p>\n<p>The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} bonuses from a shields is written in parentheses next to a character’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry}, like this: 8 (2). This means 2 points of the character’s 8 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} comes from a shield. Half of the foes who attack this character on the same @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Action Cards (Initiative)]{Action Card} can bypass those 2 points but not the other 6.</p>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover} subtracts from ranged attacks from the front and shielded side (attacks from the rear or unprotected side ignore cover). Unless stated otherwise, shields are Hardness 10.</p>\n<p>While worn, shields can be used to bash for Str+d4 damage.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"sub-heading left\">Type</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Parry</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Cover</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Min Str.</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Weight</th>\n<th class=\"sub-heading\">Cost</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"6\"><span class=\"no-class\">Shields</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Buckler Shield]{Buckler Shield}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Heater Shield]{Heater Shield}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">−2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Round Shield]{Round Shield}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">−2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Kite Shield]{Kite Shield} (–1 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace})</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">−4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-equipment.Tower Shield]{Tower Shield} (–1 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Movement]{Pace})</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">−4</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">d8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"6\"><span class=\"no-class\">Extras</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Shield spikes</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">20 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"6\"><strong><em>Notes:</em></strong> +1 damage when attacking with the shield.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_dl21vgq63wq","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/2. Gear#/CF_SEP/Gear tables","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"t7cEySUJEeGkcuOn","name":"Allies","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Allies</h1>\n  <p>\n    Allies play a big part in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> games. They serve\n    as troops under your hero’s command in war, loyal retainers serving\n    strongholds, or fellow fighters in glorious rebellions against oppression.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Use these rules to help keep track\n    of the party’s followers and give them a little extra personality to play\n    off of as well.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>The Basics:</strong> Players create, control, and track their own followers and nonplayer character allies.\n  </p>\n\n  <h2>Using Allies</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    Keeping up with allies in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> is simple. Just download the Ally Sheet from our website and fill in the blanks.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Allied @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extras} are divided up among all the players to control. This is a\n    very important part of <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> because our adventures\n    often feature allied bands of skilled hirelings, fellow grunts, or loyal\n    retainers, and the game is designed to handle them quickly and easily. It’s\n    also designed for the players to control them — not the Game Master.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    It doesn’t matter whether the <em>characters</em> control the allies, only\n    that the <em>players</em> do. This keeps everyone involved in the action\n    even if his hero is out of the fight, and makes running large combats much\n    easier and more fun for everyone. Of course the GM can always take charge of\n    Extras when the need arises, but with good roleplayers this is rarely\n    necessary.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Allied Personalities</h3>\n  <p>\n    You can add a little flavor to your allies by rolling on the\n    <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-tables.Allied Personalities]{Allied Personalities}</strong> table. Jot down the keyword on the\n    Ally Sheet so you and your Game Master have a little insight into each\n    particular ally’s character.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Consider these general impressions with no particular game effect. They help\n    both the player and GM decide just how an ally might react in a given\n    situation.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    If a party of adventurers tasks a retainer with keeping watch, it's helpful to know which ones are Observant and which ones are Lazy!\n  </p>\n\n  <table>\n    <colgroup>\n      <col></col>\n      <col></col>\n      <col></col>\n      <col></col>\n    </colgroup>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"4\">Allied Personalties</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading left\">d20</th>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading\">Personality</th>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading\">d20</th>\n        <th class=\"sub-heading\">Personality</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>1</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Treacherous</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">11</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Crude</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>2</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Cruel</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">12</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Agile</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>3</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Old</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">13</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Observant</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>4</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Happy</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">14</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Clueless</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>5</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Experience</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">15</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Mysterious</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>6</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Gung-Ho</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">16</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Creative</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>7</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Lazy</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">17</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Artistic</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>8</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Sneaky</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">18</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Fearless</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>9</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Bright</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">19</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Cowardly</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>10</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Young</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">20</td>\n        <td class=\"centered\">Heroic</td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <h3>Allies &amp; Advancement</h3>\n  <p>\n    Allies can improve their abilities as well. See <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Advancement]{Advancement}</strong>.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Ammo</h3>\n  <p>\n    Keeping track of ammunition for all your allies can be difficult. Here’s an easy and dramatic way to handle this problem.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The ammo level of each group of allied @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extras} starts at Very High, High (the usual level), Low, or Out, as determined by the GM.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    After each fight, the ammo automatically drops a level. This makes for\n    dramatic situations and realistic logistical problems while eliminating the\n    bookkeeping.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The GM can always decide otherwise, of course. Perhaps the troops are told\n    to fight with hand weapons instead of their bows and crossbows, or they\n    don’t get to fire off more than a couple of shots before the fight is over.\n  </p>\n\n  <div>\n    <img src=\"modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/p144_figure_collage.webp\" />\n  </div>\n\n  <h2>Typical Allies</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    Here are a few typical archetypes you might use for your\n    <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> game. Fill in any additional @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Trait Summaries]{skills} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.9 Edge Summaries]{Edges}\n    as you see fit. A group of rangers, for example, should have the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}\n    skill, while cavalrymen should have @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding}. Add appropriate @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Gear]{gear} for the situation as well.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Soldier</h3>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Soldier]{See the actor here.}</p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Attributes:</strong> Agility d6, Smarts d4, Spirit d6, Strength d6, Vigor d6\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Skills:</strong> Athletics d6, Common Knowledge d6, Fighting d6, Intimidation d6, Notice d6, Persuasion d6, Shooting d6, Stealth d4\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Pace:</strong> 6; <strong>Parry:</strong> 5; <strong>Toughness:</strong> 5\n  </p>\n  <p><strong>Hindrances:</strong> —</p>\n  <p><strong>Edges:</strong> Soldier</p>\n  <h3>Experienced Soldier</h3>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Experienced Soldier]{See the actor here.}</p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Attributes:</strong> Agility d6, Smarts d6, Spirit d6, Strength d8, Vigor d8\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Skills:</strong> Athletics d6, Common Knowledge d6, Fighting d8,\n    Intimidation d6, Notice d6, Persuasion d6, Shooting d8, Stealth d6\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Pace:</strong> 6; <strong>Parry:</strong> 6;\n    <strong>Toughness:</strong> 6\n  </p>\n  <p><strong>Hindrances:</strong> —</p>\n  <p><strong>Edges:</strong> Soldier and any two combat Edges.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.VNmBIg74wJBdBGUd"}}}
