{"_id":"wBNcuIXYanzMu5hq","name":"Unstable Platform","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Unstable Platform</h2>\n  <p>A character attempting to fire or throw a ranged weapon from the back of a horse or other mount, a moving vehicle, or other “unstable platform” \n\t\tsubtracts 2 from his @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing) or \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} totals.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1tLxcg8oFoJ1dWTS"}}}
{"_id":"wTq3kIGPky0mCbsP","name":"Character Creation Summary","content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"character-creation\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Character Creation Summary</h1>\n</div>\n<h3>Concept</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Start with a general idea of what you want to play. Your setting book likely provides many ideas.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Races]{Race}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Choose your character’s @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Races]{race} and apply any bonuses or special abilities it grants.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Select up to four points of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances} (Major Hindrances are worth 2, Minor are worth 1).</li>\n<li>For 2 Hindrance points you can raise an @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{attribute} one die type, or choose an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{edge}.</li>\n<li>For 1 Hindrance point you can gain another skill point, or gain additional starting funds equal to twice your setting’s starting amount.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Attributes}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Attributes start at d4. You have 5 points to distribute among them. Each step costs 1 point.</li>\n<li>Attributes may not be raised beyond d12 unless your hero’s racial bonus states otherwise.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Skills]{Skills}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} are core skills and start at d4 for free.</li>\n<li>You have 15 points to put into these or any other skills.</li>\n<li>Each die type costs 1 point up to and equal to the linked attribute; then 2 points per step after that.</li>\n<li>Your character knows @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Common} plus a number of starting @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{Languages} equal to half your character’s Smarts die type. A Smarts of d6, for example, gives you three additional starting  @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Languages]{languages}. </li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Derived Statistics}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Standard @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Movement]{Pace}</strong> is 6″, but may be changed by racial abilities, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges}, or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hindrances]{Hindrances}.</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Parry}</strong> is 2 plus half of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Toughness}</strong> is 2 plus half of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Characters]{Vigor}, plus any @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor]{Armor}.</p>\n<p>Note the amount of armor in parentheses like this—Toughness: 11 (2). This means 2 points of the total 11 Toughness comes from Armor. An @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor Piercing (AP)]{Armor Piercing (AP)} attack could bypass those 2 points but not the other 9.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Edges]{Setting Edges}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Every character starts with one free @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Edges]{Class Edge}, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Background Edge} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Professional Edge}. This edge must be tied to the story of your characters experiences during her life in the Last War.</li>\n<li>Use any leftover Hindrance points to take @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edges} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Edges]{Setting Edges} if you like.</li>\n<li>Each @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Edges]{Edge} costs 2 Hindrance points.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Gear]{Gear}</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Purchase up to 300 galifars (gp) worth of equipment.</li>\n</ul>\n<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></div>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/logo-eberron-circle-black.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_intbwo9s2if","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation","color":"#000000"},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":7}}}
{"_id":"wZ1Aksns9mqXwzJI","name":"1 The Adventure Tool Kit","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<div class=\"chapter-heading\">\n<h1>The Adventure<br />Tool kit</h1>\n<figure class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter Four</figure>\n</div>\n<p class=\"drop-cap\">The following chapter contains tools the Game Master can use for all the special situations that often come up in a game, such as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Allies]{Allies}:</span> Managing Extras under the player character’s control.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{Downtime}:</span> A way to determine the benefits of character activity between adventures.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dramatic Tasks]{Dramatic Tasks}:</span> Add tension and drama to situations like crossing a vast chasm.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fear]{Fear}:</span> The effects of overwhelming terror.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}:</span> The effects of scorching heat, bitter cold, poison, and more.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Interludes]{Interludes}:</span> Narrative storytelling for long trips or to reveal bits about the player characters’ backstories.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mass Battles]{Mass Battles}:</span> Desperate last stands against incredible odds between armies.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Networking]{Networking}:</span> Gathering information (the nice way or the not-so-nice way).</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.The Planes]{The Planes}:</span> Information about other Planes of existence.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Quick Encounters]{Quick Encounters}:</span> A fast and easy way to resolve fights, heists, or capers when pressed for time.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Social Conflict]{Social Conflict}:</span> Run a court trial, plead for aid, or convince a crowd.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Travel]{Travel}:</span> Figure out how long it takes for the party to cross tracts of Eberron.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_coxsqc2solv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.saWZBYviwN32CLvh"}}}
{"_id":"waegrrt5t2ywDk7p","name":"Bleeding Out","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Bleeding Out</h2>\n  <p>\n    The injured character is dying and must make a Vigor roll at the start of his turn. Failure means he perishes. With success he survives but must roll again next turn (or every minute if not in combat). With a raise, he stabilizes and no further rolls are required.\n  </p>\n  <p>The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} skill can also be used to stabilize someone who’s \n    Bleeding out. Each attempt is an action, and if successful the victim is stabilized.</p>\n  <p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Healing]{See full rules here}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_yxu1ag41di","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Healing keywords","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.mo17NvZSvFEO13hW"}}}
{"_id":"wl2uXpMiroMYZIiI","name":"Fixed Glory Awards","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Fixed Glory Awards</h1>\n<p>Fixed Glory awards cover lesser deeds not played out (such as events during long periods of downtime), killing smaller number of foes during an adventure (they do slowly add up over time), or rewards for which there are many witnesses (battles or rescues). These are in addition to any Glory gained above.</p>\n<p>GM’s are encouraged to devise their own modifiers for things like concluding peace treaties or founding new mercantile routes that benefit a large population. Although notable deeds, the rewards for these types of endeavor should not be overly high—few people will remember who signed a peace treaty, but you can bet they’ll recall a hero who risked his life to venture into the heavily guarded camp of the enemy commander and kill him in an epic duel.</p>\n<h2>ACHIEVE RANK</h2>\n<p>Even without performing major heroic deeds, a hero can become famous through his collective lesser deeds. Such rewards are typical of the examples above, especially the slaying of lesser foes.</p>\n<p>These are wrapped into a single +5 Glory bonus gained when a hero achieves a new Rank. It is possible, though rare, for a hero to reach Legendary status with no additional Glory—he has performed many deeds, but none stand out as truly heroic.</p>\n<h2>Mass Battles</h2>\n<p>War is a terrible thing and something sane men avoid, but it can also grow and break reputations.</p>\n<p>Use the table below whenever the characters are involved in a fight using the Mass Battle rules. Whereas skirmishes are commonplace, true mass battles remain rare events. Hence, all Glory modifiers are fixed.</p>\n<table class=\"table gear-table\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Mass Battle Glory Table</h2>\n</caption>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"table-header-row\">\n<th class=\"table-column-header\" scope=\"col\">Reason</th>\n<td class=\"table-column-header\" style=\"width:20%\">Modifier</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Size</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Smallest army had hundreds of troops</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Smallest army had thousands of troops</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Smallest army had more than 10,000 troops</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Enemy</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hated rival of your nation</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+/–1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Undead Army</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+/–2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Victory</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Enemy had less tokens or was equal</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>For each token the enemy had above yours</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Defeat</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Enemy had more tokens or was equal</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>For each token less your enemy had</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">–3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Personal Heroics</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Two raises on Heroes in Mass Battles rolls</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"table-column-header table-subheader-center\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"table-subheader-center-wrapper table-subheader-center-content\">Commander</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>You commanded the army</td>\n<td style=\"width:20%\">x2</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Character Roll:</strong> Scoring a double raise is more than just a die result. It represents a major event within a battle, such as slaying an enemy commander or slaughtering so many foes a battalion breaks.</p>\n<p>However, the modifier only applies if the number of enemy tokens was less than or equal to your army’s tokens at the time (slaying an enemy commander when you have a +3 bonus is nowhere near as heroic as when you have a –3 penalty.</p>\n<p><strong>Commander: </strong>A hero who commands an army gains greater Glory than his troops for victory, but also suffers more ignominy if he loses the field. Take the final Glory modifier and double it to see what the hero earned.</p>\n<p><strong>Defeat:</strong> Defeat is never easy to live with, but the ignominy is far worse if you outnumbered your foe. For each token you outnumbered your enemy at the start of a battle you suffer a –3 penalty.</p>\n<p><strong>Enemy Forces: </strong>Certain races are more despised than others. To qualify for the bonus, the specific enemy must account for more than 75% of the enemy army’s troop strength.</p>\n<p>Add the modifier if the heroes won, and subtract it if they lost (a defeat by a hated foe usually means the enemy will grow more confident and thus pose a greater danger in the future).</p>\n<p><strong>Size: </strong>Huge armies are rare in Khorvaire now the Last War is over, and thus while any battle earns Glory, the more participants there are the greater the tale told.</p>\n<p><strong>Victory: </strong>Everybody loves a winner. The greater the size of the enemy army, the more reward is earned. For each token your enemy’s army was larger than yours when battle commenced, the hero earns a +2 Glory bonus.</p>\n<h2>RESCUE</h2>\n<p>Even if the heroes’ tale of how they killed a hundred orcs doesn’t earn them any immediate Glory, having prisoners recount the tale of their rescue quickly causes word to spread.</p>\n<p>Important NPCs must be famous, powerful, and named. A merchant, wizard, priest, minor noble, or similar is worth +1 Glory. Saving a count or a skilled spellcaster is worth +3. Rescuing a prince, king, or truly powerful spellcaster gains the hero +5 Glory.</p>\n<p>For groups of lesser NPCs, rescuing ten or so is worth +1 Glory, a few tens +2, and a hundred or more +3. Saving a lone villager from an orc tribe is brave, but not enough to be retold by skalds.</p>\n<p>Rescue doesn’t have to mean entering a prison and breaking captives out. Liberating a village beset by frostreavers, for instance, counts as a rescue. If the rescue involves a Mass Battle rather than tabletop action, the party is deserving of the Mass Battle rewards as well.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Additional Glory Articles</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Variable Glorious Deeds]{Variable Glorious Deeds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fixed Glory Awards]{Fixed Glory Awards}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glory Benefits]{Glory Benefits}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Losing Glory]{Losing Glory}</h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_rv4q29jrhjs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/4. The Adventure Toolkit#/CF_SEP/Setting Rules","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"wmYouRnUuWxqfqNt","name":"Off-Hand Attacks","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h2>Off-Hand Attacks</h2>\n  <p>Characters are assumed to be right-handed unless the player decides otherwise. \n\t\tActions that require precise eye-hand coordination, such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} or \n\t\t@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, suffer a −2 penalty when done solely with the off-hand.</p>\n\t<p>Off-hand weapons don’t add their @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} bonus unless the hero is \n\t\t<strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Ambidextrous]{Ambidextrous}</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{4 Situational Rules}</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_bljq2qm1bis","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/3. Rules#/CF_SEP/Situational Rules","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.yws3LCOzYhEtoOZT"}}}
{"_id":"wqqU4hNbMPWxGLno","name":"Bard/Skald","content":"<p>Bards and skalds usually don’t end up as wandering minstrels or street performers. Instead, some bards use their magical abilities to unearth ancient lore, while others use their interpersonal skills and song music to advance their careers as spies, ambassadors, diplomats, and chroniclers. As such, bards and skalds find employ as adventurers, as well as in governments and among the mercantile houses.</p>\n<p><strong>Skills: </strong>Athletics, Language, Lore, Performance, Persuasion, Taunt, Traditions</p>\n<p><strong>Background Edges: </strong>Arcane Background (Song Magic), Attractive, Very Attractive, Charismatic, Fame, Famous, Linguist, Luck, Great Luck</p>\n<p><strong>Leadership Edges:</strong> Any Leadership edges</p>\n<p><strong>Professional Edges:</strong> Acrobat, Entertainer, Femme Fatale/Ladykiller, Honey Tongue, Jack-of-all-Trades, Master Storyteller, Legendary Storyteller, Skald</p>\n<p><strong>Social Edges:</strong> Bolser, Command Bond, Connections, Humiliate, Rabble-Rouse, Reliable, Streetwise, Work the Room, Work the Crowd <strong> </strong></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.V9GkKOtKpcThuSbb"},"cf":{"id":"temp_pkglbsbzxv","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/1. Character Creation#/CF_SEP/1.2. Character Concepts","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"x2alqHrzYZRpQJ4j","name":"3 Activation","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n  <h1 class=\"wide\">Activation</h1>\n  <p>\n    A character activates a power by picking a target within @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range} and making an\n    arcane skill roll. Failure means the power doesn’t activate. The caster spends one @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Point} \n    regardless of any Edges such as @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Channeling]{Channeling}, unless the ability specifically says it reduces the minimum cost to 0.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Success means the power activates and consumes all the Power Points\n    allocated to it, even if it misses the target (such as with <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>),\n    or the defender resists. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} has additional effects noted in the\n    particular power description.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Backlash:</strong> A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} when activating a power is\n    called @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Backlash]{Backlash}. It causes a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} and all currently active\n    powers instantly terminate.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Casting Requirements</h3>\n  <p>\n    A character must be able to see his target and cannot be\n    \n    <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound}</strong> or silenced.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Maintaining Powers</h3>\n  <p>\n    When a power ends, the caster can spend one @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Point} \n    to extend it by its base @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Duration]{Duration}. If a power’s Duration is five rounds, for example, it can be\n    maintained for another five rounds for 1 Power Point.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Maintenance is per target but ignores other @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}, \n    so renewing<em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost Trait}</em> on three allies costs 3 Power Points and\n    extends the effect of each another five rounds.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Unless a power says otherwise, the caster can terminate it as a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Stacking Powers</h3>\n  <p>\n    Powers don't stack beyond their maximum benefit or drawback. This\n    includes effects from magic items that specifically use those powers. A ring\n    that simply says it increases Strength a die type does so even if the\n    wearer's Strength is currently increased by\n    <em>boost Trait</em>(Strength), for example. If the same ring said it\n    boosts Strength a die type, however, it would only stack with the actual\n    spell or other items up to the power's maximum (two die types).\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Powers that target different Traits or abilities, such as\n    <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost/lower Trait}</em>, are considered separate powers in this context.\n    Strength may only be increased up to two die types by <em>boost Trait</em>,\n    for example, but Strength and Fighting could both be boosted up to two die\n    types as each one is a separate Trait. Similarly, a sorcerer could cast\n    <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}</em> (melee) on an ally who's already benefiting from a\n    ring of <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Ring of Protection, Minor]{protection}</em> (ranged).\n  </p>\n  <h3>Recharging</h3>\n  <p>A character recovers 5 @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} per hour spent resting.</p>\n  <p>\n    What constitutes rest is up to the GM, but generally, it means sitting,\n    eating, tending wounds, sleeping, and avoiding any strenuous activity.\n    Walking or riding a horse isn’t usually restful, but riding in a cushioned\n    carriage might be.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    A few interruptions don’t stop a character from resting— standing watch,\n    planning, sharpening weapons, and so on (GM’s call).\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    An arcane hero can also spend a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bennies]{Benny} to regain five Power Points. This is a\n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Powers As Multi-Actions</h3>\n  <p>\n    Each power activated is its own action, and the same or dif­ferent\n    powers may be cast multiple times as a <strong>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Action}</strong>. \n    A wizard might start combat by invoking <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}</em> and\n    <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{deflection}</em>, for example, or a priest might attempt to\n    <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{banish}</em> a spirit while invoking <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em> on his mace.\n  </p>\n  <h3>Shorting</h3>\n  <p>\n    A character may cast a power with <em>fewer</em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points}\n    than required (whether she has them or not) by increasing the difficulty of her arcane\n    skill roll (If there is no skill roll, as with Mystic Powers, the character\n    cannot short the power).\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    For every Power Point a character shorts, she suffers a −1 penalty to the\n    roll. Casting a 3-point <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> with 0 Power Points, for example,\n    inflicts a −3 penalty.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shorting]{Shorting} is risky. If a character fails a shorted arcane skill roll, it’s\n    consid­ered a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure!}\n  </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_vv8zdhdw0l","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.iKwTYsvj7DfBZR9y"}}}
{"_id":"xATNEaRpoy6q5ltP","name":"Cantrips","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Cantrips</h1>\n<p><img class=\"right table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/changeling-artificer.webp\" width=\"285\" height=\"500\" /></p>\n<p>A mage sets a broom to sweeping his floor. A priest lights a candle with the grace of her god. A bard tells an animated story in the night air, illuminated with the dancing cinders of a campfire. Such minor orisons (prayers) or lesser magicks are collectively called “cantrips.”</p>\n<p>In Savage Eberron, any character with an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Background} can cast cantrips.</p>\n<h2>ACTIVATION</h2>\n<p>A character may cast a cantrip by making an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll. This is an action, and the effect must be based on one of the character’s existing powers. A sorcerer could use <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> with a fire @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trappings]{Trapping} to light a campfire, for example. A druid could use <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> to make vines dance to entertain a group of children. A wizard can use <em>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{sound}</em> to ring a bell calling a servant to his study.</p>\n<p>Success means the desired effect occurs. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} has an additional narrative impact of some kind—the candle glows brightly, the vines dance in perfect synchronicity, or the bell rings loud and pure.</p>\n<p>Failure causes the spell to fail without effect. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} causes the spell to backfire, which requires the caster to lose 1 Power Point (or suffer @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} if the caster has no Power Points). @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} also causes an embarrassment or minor mishap of some sort—an animated broom carelessly knocks a jar of ink onto the floor, a conjured flame lights a book on fire, or the power makes an embarrassing sound or smell.</p>\n<p>A successfully cast cantrip’s Duration is the same as the power it’s based on and may be maintained by spending Power Points as usual.</p>\n<p>The DM has the final say on what a cantrip can do, but the effect must not replace a power or cause damage (at least directly). It can be used to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}, or grant a +1 bonus on a subsequent roll in the same encounter. For example, if the bard uses a cantrip to impress the children of Sharn, the DM might give him +1 to a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll later on if he talks to their parents or someone else who witnessed the kindness.</p>\n<h2 class=\"toc-columns-title\">Magic and Powers</h2>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Using Magic]{Using Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Activation]{Activation}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers Summary List]{Powers Summary list}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cantrips]{Cantrips}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Schools of Magic]{Schools of Magic}</h3>\n<h3>@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</h3>\n</div>\n<div class=\"toc-columns\">\n<h3> </h3>\n</div>\n</div>\n","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/icons/sweb-logo.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_fsjso9rnq9","path":"Savage Eberron Rules#/CF_SEP/5. Powers#/CF_SEP/4.1. Using Magic","color":"#000000"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.swade-core-rules.swade-rules.6SGCG8rZNklN3U6w"},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":9},"journal-links":{"references":{}}}}
